window.CONTENT["4870"] = {"meta":{"id":"4870","code":"COMP 4870","name":"Intranet Planning and Development","exam":"2026-04-24T10:30:00-07:00","room":"SE12-327","format":"60 MCQ + 10 match-two-columns + 1 coding · 80 marks · 60 min","cheatsheet_allowed":true,"instructor":"Medhat Elmasry","notes_html":"\u003cp\u003eCoverage: weeks 7–13 of the syllabus.\nTopic weights (marks): AI 13 · ML.NET 12 · Cache/Redis 8 · File-based apps 8 · gRPC 7 · TDD 6 · Aspire 5 · Localization 4 · Tag Helpers 3 · Blazor 2 · Excel/PDF/Chart 2 · coding question 10.\nYou may bring one hand-written 8.5&quot; × 11&quot; cheat sheet, both sides.\u003c/p\u003e"},"modules":[{"id":"module-1-ai-in-dotnet","name":"AI in .NET","topics":[{"id":"ai-agent-framework","name":"Microsoft Agent Framework (MAF) + tool calling","tags":["ai","maf","agent","tools","function-calling"],"prose":"Microsoft Agent Framework (MAF) wraps an `IChatClient` into a `ChatClientAgent` via\n`.AsAIAgent()`, registers C# delegates or lambdas as `AITool` values through\n`AIFunctionFactory.Create`, and drives turns with `RunAsync` or `RunStreamingAsync`.\nMulti-turn state lives in an `AgentSession` from `await agent.CreateSessionAsync()`,\nnot in a manual `ChatHistory`. Common exam traps: `.AsAgent()`, `agent.Invoke()`,\nand `AITool.Register()` do not exist.\n","cards":[{"id":"maf-base-package","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","source":"research-ai.md §NuGet Packages to Add","explanation":"The base package ships separately from the OpenAI integration. Both require --prerelease because MAF is not GA. Exam distractors swap the name to 'Microsoft.AgentFramework' or drop --prerelease.","example":"dotnet add package Microsoft.Agents.AI --prerelease","prompt":"The base NuGet package for MAF is {{Microsoft.Agents.AI}}, installed with the {{--prerelease}} flag.","answer":"Microsoft.Agents.AI --prerelease"},{"id":"maf-openai-package","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","source":"research-ai.md §NuGet Packages to Add","explanation":"The `.OpenAI` suffix is what pulls in the `ChatClient` type used for OpenAI-compatible endpoints. Missing this package means `.AsAIAgent()` compiles but nothing at the OpenAI layer does.","example":"dotnet add package Microsoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI --prerelease","prompt":"To get the OpenAI-compatible `ChatClient` integration (GitHub Models, Azure OpenAI), install {{Microsoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI}} with {{--prerelease}}.","answer":"Microsoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI --prerelease"},{"id":"maf-as-ai-agent-method","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"research-ai.md §Create MAF Agent (Basic); flashcard #3","explanation":"The extension lives on `IChatClient` and accepts `name`, `instructions`, and `tools`. `.AsAgent()` is a common distractor and does not compile.","example":"var agent = chatClient.AsAIAgent(instructions: \"You are a chef.\", name: \"RecipeAgent\");","prompt":"Name the extension method that wraps an `IChatClient` into a `ChatClientAgent`.","answer":".AsAIAgent()"},{"id":"maf-register-tool","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"research-ai.md §Create MAF Agent with Tools; flashcard #2","explanation":"`AIFunctionFactory.Create` takes a delegate plus `name:` and `description:`. The description is the natural-language string the LLM reads to decide when to call the tool. `AITool.Register` and `AIFunction.Create` are distractors.","example":"AITool weatherTool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(\n    WeatherService.GetWeatherAsync,\n    name: \"GetWeather\",\n    description: \"Get the weather details of a location using city name\");\n","prompt":"Name the factory call that turns a C# method into an `AITool` for an MAF agent.","answer":"AIFunctionFactory.Create"},{"id":"maf-session-for-multiturn","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"research-ai.md §MAF Agent with Session (Multi-Turn); flashcard #6","explanation":"`ChatHistory` is a manual `List\u003cChatMessage\u003e` for raw `IChatClient` loops. MAF agents manage history and tool-call state inside an `AgentSession`. Passing both duplicates state.","example":"var session = await agent.CreateSessionAsync();\nvar reply = await agent.RunAsync(\"What did I ask first?\", session);\n","prompt":"You need conversation memory across five `RunAsync` calls against one MAF agent. Do you build a `ChatHistory` list or an `AgentSession`, and how do you get it?","answer":"`AgentSession`, via `var session = await agent.CreateSessionAsync();` — pass it into every `RunAsync` call."},{"id":"maf-run-method-name","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","source":"research-ai.md §Create MAF Agent (Basic); flashcard #18","explanation":"`RunAsync` returns the full response after all tool round-trips complete. `Invoke` is a Semantic Kernel verb and a standard distractor on MAF questions.","example":"var response = await agent.RunAsync(\"A dessert for a rainy Tuesday.\");","prompt":"To execute an MAF agent turn and get the assembled reply, call {{agent.RunAsync(input)}} — not `agent.Invoke(input)`.","answer":"agent.RunAsync(input)"},{"id":"maf-streaming-method","type":"cloze","bloom":"apply","source":"research-ai.md §MAF Agent with Streaming; flashcard #9","explanation":"`RunStreamingAsync` yields updates as the model produces them. Swap it in for `RunAsync` when you want incremental output to the console or UI.","example":"await foreach (var update in agent.RunStreamingAsync(\"Which planet is closest to the sun?\")) {\n    Console.Write(update);\n}\n","prompt":"To stream tokens from an MAF agent, `await foreach` over {{agent.RunStreamingAsync(input)}}.","answer":"agent.RunStreamingAsync(input)"},{"id":"maf-lambda-tool","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"research-ai.md §Tool Registration from Async Lambda","explanation":"`AIFunctionFactory.Create` accepts delegates, including async lambdas. The lambda parameters become the tool's parameter schema sent to the LLM.","example":"AITool poemTool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(\n    async (string city, string weather) =\u003e (await chatClient.GetResponseAsync($\"Poem for {city}, {weather}\")).Text,\n    name: \"WriteShortPoem\",\n    description: \"Write a short funny poem about clothes to wear based on city and weather\");\n","prompt":"You have an async lambda `(string city, string weather) =\u003e Task\u003cstring\u003e` that builds a prompt and calls `chatClient.GetResponseAsync`. How do you expose it as a tool to an MAF agent?","answer":"Wrap it with `AIFunctionFactory.Create(lambda, name: \"...\", description: \"...\")` and pass the result in the `tools:` array of `.AsAIAgent(...)`."},{"id":"maf-fake-method-as-agent","type":"name","bloom":"analyze","source":"research-ai.md §Fake Method Names in MCQ","explanation":"`.AsAgent()` is a documented exam trap — it resembles the real API and compiles if you define your own extension. MAF ships `.AsAIAgent()` only.","example":"var agent = chatClient.AsAIAgent(name: \"Bot\", instructions: \"...\");","prompt":"A multiple-choice option shows `chatClient.AsAgent(instructions: \"...\")`. Correct or distractor?","answer":"Distractor. The real method is `.AsAIAgent()`."},{"id":"maf-fake-method-register","type":"name","bloom":"analyze","source":"research-ai.md §Fake Method Names in MCQ; MCQ #1","explanation":"MAF has no `AITool.Register`. All native and lambda tools flow through `AIFunctionFactory.Create`, which returns an `AITool` you pass in the `tools:` array.","example":"AITool tool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(\n    WeatherService.GetWeather,\n    name: \"Weather\",\n    description: \"Get weather\");\n","prompt":"A choice reads `AITool.Register(WeatherService.GetWeather, \"Weather\", \"Get weather\");`. Real or distractor?","answer":"Distractor. Use `AIFunctionFactory.Create(WeatherService.GetWeather, name: \"Weather\", description: \"Get weather\");`."},{"id":"maf-agent-reasoning-behavior","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"research-ai.md §MAF Stack; MCQ #6","explanation":"MAF agents are agentic — tool selection is implicit in the LLM's output. Tools execute only when the model emits a tool-call for them. Sequential execution of every registered tool is a distractor.","example":"Input 'What should I wear in Vancouver?' triggers GetWeather only if the model decides it needs weather data.","prompt":"When you call `agent.RunAsync(input, session)` on an MAF agent with three registered tools, what actually runs?","answer":"The LLM reads input and tool descriptions, decides which (if any) tools to call, MAF invokes those, tool results feed back into the LLM, and the final assistant message is returned. Not all tools run."},{"id":"maf-vs-sk-verbs","type":"name","bloom":"analyze","source":"research-ai.md §Semantic Kernel vs. MAF Differences","explanation":"MAF and SK are sibling SDKs with different vocabularies. Mixing `kernel.InvokeAsync` with `agent.RunAsync` on the same object is a classic exam trap — they do not interop directly.","example":"// SK\nkernel.ImportPluginFromType\u003cWeatherPlugin\u003e();\nawait kernel.InvokeAsync(plugin[\"GetWeather\"], new(\"Vancouver\"));\n// MAF\nAITool t = AIFunctionFactory.Create(WeatherPlugin.GetWeather, name: \"GetWeather\", description: \"...\");\nawait agent.RunAsync(\"Weather in Vancouver?\", session);\n","prompt":"Sketch the verb mapping: for (a) tool registration, (b) turn execution, which method belongs to Semantic Kernel and which to MAF?","answer":"Registration — SK: `kernel.ImportPluginFromType\u003cT\u003e()`; MAF: `AIFunctionFactory.Create(method, name, description)`.\nExecution  — SK: `kernel.InvokeAsync(function, args)`; MAF: `agent.RunAsync(input, session)`.\n"}],"source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx; research-ai.md §MAF"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow","name":"ML.NET pipeline workflow — Load → Transform → Concatenate → Train → Evaluate → Predict","tags":["ml-net","pipeline"],"prose":"The canonical ML.NET program chains seven steps: create MLContext, load data into an IDataView, rename the target column to \"Label\", one-hot-encode categoricals, Concatenate features into a column named \"Features\", pick a trainer, and call Fit to get back an ITransformer. These cards drill the return types, magic column names, and trap answers the exam reuses.","cards":[{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-01","type":"cloze","source":"research-mlnet.md §MLContext; card #2, #14","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`MLContext` exposes `Data`, `Transforms`, `Regression`, `MulticlassClassification`, and `Model`. Passing `seed: 0` pins the random-number generator so identical inputs produce identical models.","example":"`MLContext mlContext = new MLContext(seed: 0);` — every subsequent call starts `mlContext.Something`.","prompt":"The root object for every ML.NET program is `{{MLContext}}`, constructed with `new MLContext(seed: 0)` to make training {{deterministic}}.","answer":"`MLContext` / deterministic"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-02","type":"cloze","source":"research-mlnet.md §IDataView; card #3","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The load call is lazy: rows are not pulled into memory until a downstream transform or `Fit` asks for them. The generic `T` carries `[LoadColumn(N)]` attributes that map CSV indices to fields.","example":"`IDataView trainingData = mlContext.Data.LoadFromTextFile\u003cTaxiTrip\u003e(\"taxi-fare-train.csv\", hasHeader: true, separatorChar: ',');`","prompt":"`mlContext.Data.LoadFromTextFile\u003cT\u003e(path, hasHeader: true, separatorChar: ',')` returns an `{{IDataView}}` — an immutable, streaming view over tabular data.","answer":"`IDataView`"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-03","type":"name","source":"research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps #3; card #4; MCQ Q3","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`Fit` runs every transform and trains the final algorithm. It does not return `IDataView` (that is what `Transform` returns), not metrics, not a `PredictionEngine`. This is the single most common MCQ distractor.","example":"`ITransformer model = pipeline.Fit(trainingData);` — never `IDataView model = pipeline.Fit(…)`.","prompt":"What does `pipeline.Fit(trainingData)` return?","answer":"`ITransformer` — the trained, stateless, serializable model."},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-04","type":"cloze","source":"research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps #5; §Top 5 Exam Mistakes #2","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Trainers search the `IDataView` schema for a column named `\"Label\"`. If you leave `FareAmount` as the target name, the trainer cannot find it and `Fit` throws a \"column not found\" error.","example":"`mlContext.Transforms.CopyColumns(outputColumnName: \"Label\", inputColumnName: \"FareAmount\")`","prompt":"The first step in a trainer pipeline renames the target column to the literal name `{{\"Label\"}}` using the `{{CopyColumns}}` transform.","answer":"`\"Label\"` / `CopyColumns`"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-05","type":"cloze","source":"research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps #6; card #7","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Trainers look up their input by the hard-coded name `\"Features\"`. `Concatenate` packs the encoded columns into one vector under that name so the trainer can consume it as a single numeric input.","example":"`.Append(mlContext.Transforms.Concatenate(\"Features\", \"VendorIdEncoded\", \"TripDistance\"))`","prompt":"`Concatenate` must produce a single vector column named exactly `{{\"Features\"}}` — trainers refuse to run if the column is called `\"Input\"` or `\"X\"`.","answer":"`\"Features\"`"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-06","type":"cloze","source":"research-mlnet.md card #6; MCQ Q5","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Trainers accept only numeric input. `OneHotEncoding` expands a categorical column into one indicator column per distinct value — `\"VTS\"` becomes `[1,0]`, `\"CMT\"` becomes `[0,1]`.","example":"`.Append(mlContext.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(outputColumnName: \"VendorIdEncoded\", inputColumnName: \"VendorId\"))`","prompt":"To convert categorical text columns such as `\"VTS\"` or `\"CMT\"` into numeric binary vectors, apply the `{{OneHotEncoding}}` transform before `Concatenate`.","answer":"`OneHotEncoding`"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-07","type":"name","source":"research-mlnet.md §Algorithms; card #9","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`FastTree` is the default regression trainer for numeric prediction. Regression namespace matters: using `mlContext.MulticlassClassification.Trainers.…` for a regression task produces wrong metrics or compile errors.","example":"`.Append(mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree());`","prompt":"Which trainer call sits at the end of a regression pipeline in the taxi-fare example, and which namespace does it come from?","answer":"`mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree()` — gradient-boosted decision trees from `Microsoft.ML.FastTree`."},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-08","type":"cloze","source":"research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps #7","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`LoadColumn` takes a numeric index, not a header string. The index matches the CSV column position starting at zero; header names are ignored by this attribute.","example":"`[LoadColumn(0)] public string VendorId;` maps to the first CSV column.","prompt":"`[LoadColumn({{0}})]` on a field maps it to the CSV column at {{0-based}} index — `[LoadColumn(6)]` reads the seventh column.","answer":"0 / 0-based"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-09","type":"name","source":"research-mlnet.md §Complete Workflow Step 6; card #10","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`Transform` applies the pipeline to new data and adds the `\"Score\"` column. `Regression.Evaluate` reads `\"Label\"` and `\"Score\"` to produce a `RegressionMetrics` with `RSquared`, `RootMeanSquaredError`, and `MeanAbsoluteError`.","example":"`Console.WriteLine($\"RSquared: {metrics.RSquared:0.##}\");`","prompt":"After `Fit`, how do you compute regression quality metrics on a test `IDataView`?","answer":"`var predictions = model.Transform(testData); var metrics = mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\");`"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-10","type":"cloze","source":"research-mlnet.md §PredictionEngine; card #5; MCQ Q8","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`PredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` handles one example at a time. For batch inference use `model.Transform(batch)` instead — calling `Predict` in a tight loop is the single-row API.","example":"`var engine = mlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction\u003e(model); var fare = engine.Predict(newTrip).FareAmount;`","prompt":"For single-row inference at runtime, wrap the trained model in a `{{PredictionEngine}}` via `mlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTInput, TOutput\u003e(model)`, then call `.Predict(example)`.","answer":"`PredictionEngine`"},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-11","type":"name","source":"research-mlnet.md §Quick Reference Cheat Sheet","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"Every ML.NET program follows this shape. The order matters: rename to `\"Label\"` before any transforms that touch features; encode categoricals before `Concatenate`; `Concatenate` must come before the trainer.","example":"Taxi-fare pipeline: load CSV → copy `FareAmount` to `\"Label\"` → one-hot `VendorId` → concatenate into `\"Features\"` → `FastTree` → `Fit` → `Evaluate` → predict.","prompt":"Name the seven canonical steps of an ML.NET training program in order.","answer":"1. `new MLContext(seed: 0)` — 2. `LoadFromTextFile\u003cT\u003e` into `IDataView` — 3. `CopyColumns(\"Label\", target)` — 4. `OneHotEncoding` for categoricals — 5. `Concatenate(\"Features\", …)` — 6. append a trainer (`FastTree` etc.) — 7. `Fit` returns an `ITransformer`, then `Evaluate` or `CreatePredictionEngine`."},{"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow-card-12","type":"cloze","source":"research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps #4; §Top 5 Exam Mistakes #3","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"The trainer namespace and the evaluator namespace must match the task. Using `BinaryClassification` or `MulticlassClassification` for a numeric-prediction problem yields classification metrics or a compilation error.","example":"Taxi-fare (numeric target) uses `mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree()` and `mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(...)`.","prompt":"Calling `mlContext.{{Regression}}.Evaluate` on a regression pipeline returns `RSquared` and `RMSE`; calling `mlContext.{{MulticlassClassification}}.Evaluate` instead returns accuracy metrics — picking the wrong namespace is an exam trap.","answer":"`Regression` / `MulticlassClassification`"}],"source":"slides/ML.NET.pptx; notes/ML.NET_VSCODE_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md §Complete ML.NET Workflow"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel","name":"Semantic Kernel SDK","tags":["ai","orchestration","plugins"],"prose":"Semantic Kernel is Microsoft's orchestration SDK for LLMs in .NET. A Kernel — built by KernelBuilder — holds an IChatCompletionService and plugins. A plugin is a collection of callable functions: either a native C# class whose methods carry [KernelFunction] + [Description], or a prompt directory containing skprompt.txt with {{$variable}} placeholders. Invoke everything through kernel.InvokeAsync(). The core NuGet is Microsoft.SemanticKernel; add-on packages live under Microsoft.SemanticKernel.Plugins.*. Do not confuse with Microsoft Agent Framework — agent.RunAsync() and AIFunctionFactory.Create() belong to MAF, not Semantic Kernel.","cards":[{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-01","type":"name","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`KernelBuilder` configures services (LLM backend, logging) and constructs the `Kernel` via `Build()`. Variant `Kernel.Builder` does not exist.","example":"`var kernel = new KernelBuilder().AddOpenAIChatCompletion(\"gpt-4o\", apiKey).Build();`","source":"research-ai.md §Register Semantic Kernel in Program.cs","prompt":"Which class builds a Semantic Kernel `Kernel` instance fluently?","answer":"`KernelBuilder`"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-02","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`InvokeAsync` is the one call that runs any plugin function through the kernel. `kernel.Execute()` is a fake method that appears in distractors.","example":"`await kernel.InvokeAsync(plugin[\"RecipeGenerator\"], new(\"chocolate cake\"));`","source":"research-ai.md §Kernel, §Add Plugin to Kernel (Prompt-Based)","prompt":"To execute a Semantic Kernel function, call `kernel.{{InvokeAsync}}()`.","answer":"InvokeAsync"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-03","type":"name","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`[KernelFunction]` tags the method for kernel discovery; pair it with `[Description]` so the LLM can choose it during tool selection. `[SkillFunction]` is a distractor.","example":"`[KernelFunction(\"DescribeWeather\")] [Description(\"Get weather for a city\")] public static string GetWeatherDescription(string city) =\u003e ...;`","source":"research-ai.md flashcard #8, §Add Plugin to Kernel (Native C# Class)","prompt":"Which attribute marks a C# method as a Semantic Kernel function?","answer":"`[KernelFunction]`"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-04","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","explanation":"The kernel substitutes each `{{$var}}` with the argument passed to `InvokeAsync` before sending the rendered prompt to the LLM.","example":"`skprompt.txt`: `Identify the city in this input: {{$input}}` — called with `input = \"weather in Tokyo\"`.","source":"research-ai.md §skprompt.txt Template, flashcard #11","prompt":"In a Semantic Kernel prompt template, the placeholder syntax is `{{{{$variableName}}}}`.","answer":"{{$variableName}}"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-05","type":"name","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`IChatCompletionService` lets you swap OpenAI, Azure OpenAI, or Ollama backends without changing calling code. Implementations register via extension methods on `KernelBuilder` like `AddOpenAIChatCompletion`.","example":"`kernelBuilder.AddOpenAIChatCompletion(\"phi3\", new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434\"));` registers an Ollama-backed `IChatCompletionService`.","source":"research-ai.md §IChatCompletionService, flashcard #15","prompt":"Which interface abstracts the LLM backend in Semantic Kernel?","answer":"`IChatCompletionService`"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-06","type":"cloze","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`ImportPluginFromType\u003cT\u003e()` reflects over `T`, finds every `[KernelFunction]` method, and registers them. Use `ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory()` instead for directories containing `skprompt.txt`.","example":"`kernel.ImportPluginFromType\u003cWeatherPlugin\u003e();` makes `WeatherPlugin.GetWeatherDescription` callable via `kernel.InvokeAsync`.","source":"research-ai.md §Add Plugin to Kernel (Native C# Class)","prompt":"To load a native C# plugin class `WeatherPlugin`, call `kernel.{{ImportPluginFromType}}\u003cWeatherPlugin\u003e()`.","answer":"ImportPluginFromType"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-07","type":"name","bloom":"understand","explanation":"A prompt-directory plugin is a folder containing `skprompt.txt` — the template with `{{$var}}` placeholders — and optional config. `ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory()` reads this layout.","example":"`Plugins/CakeRecipe/skprompt.txt` contains `Write a recipe for {{$input}}.`; the kernel renders it at invoke time.","source":"research-ai.md §skprompt.txt Template, flashcard #10","prompt":"What file name identifies a prompt-based Semantic Kernel plugin inside its directory?","answer":"`skprompt.txt`"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-08","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","explanation":"`ChatHistory` carries prior turns so the LLM has context on each call. It is distinct from Microsoft Agent Framework's `AgentSession`.","example":"`var history = new ChatHistory(); history.AddUserMessage(\"hi\"); history.AddAssistantMessage(\"hello\");`","source":"research-ai.md §ChatHistory, §Kernel → ChatHistory Flow","prompt":"The ordered list tracking multi-turn conversation state in Semantic Kernel is `{{ChatHistory}}` — a list of `ChatMessage` objects with a `ChatRole` (User, Assistant, System).","answer":"ChatHistory"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-09","type":"name","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory(path)` scans the directory for prompt templates and registers them as functions. `SkillFactory.Create()` is a distractor — it does not exist.","example":"`kernel.ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory(Path.Combine(pluginDir, \"CakeRecipe\"));`","source":"research-ai.md §Add Plugin to Kernel (Prompt-Based)","prompt":"Which Semantic Kernel method loads a plugin from a directory of `skprompt.txt` files?","answer":"`ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory()`"},{"id":"ai-semantic-kernel-card-10","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Install the core package first; add individual `Microsoft.SemanticKernel.Plugins.*` packages only when you need their integrations. The MAF package `Microsoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI` is a separate SDK.","example":"`dotnet add package Microsoft.SemanticKernel` brings in `Kernel`, `KernelBuilder`, `[KernelFunction]`.","source":"research-ai.md §NuGet Packages to Add, §Package Naming Confusion","prompt":"The core Semantic Kernel NuGet package is `{{Microsoft.SemanticKernel}}`; add-on plugin packages live under `Microsoft.SemanticKernel.Plugins.*`.","answer":"Microsoft.SemanticKernel"}],"source":"slides/CSharp_Meets_AI.pptx; notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx; research-ai.md §Semantic Kernel"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms","name":"ML.NET data transforms","tags":["ml-net","feature-eng"],"prose":"Trainers in ML.NET consume two specific columns: a scalar named `\"Label\"` and a vector named `\"Features\"`. Three transforms produce them. `CopyColumns` renames your target to `\"Label\"`. `OneHotEncoding` converts each categorical text column into a numeric indicator vector under a name you choose. `Concatenate` stitches the surviving numeric columns — including every encoded output — into the single `\"Features\"` vector. Skip any step, misname a column, or forget an encoded column in the concatenate list and training breaks or silently loses a feature.","cards":[{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-01","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","prompt":"Trainers look up the target column by the literal name `\"{{Label}}\"` and the feature vector by the literal name `\"{{Features}}\"`.","answer":"Label","explanation":"Both names are hardcoded in ML.NET trainer lookups. Renaming either one breaks `Fit()` at runtime.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-02","type":"name","bloom":"understand","prompt":"What does `mlContext.Transforms.CopyColumns(outputColumnName: \"Label\", inputColumnName: \"FareAmount\")` do, and why is it required?","answer":"It duplicates the `FareAmount` column under the name `\"Label\"`.","explanation":"It duplicates the `FareAmount` column under the name `\"Label\"`. Regression trainers look for a column named exactly `\"Label\"` as their target; without this rename, training fails.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-03","type":"name","bloom":"understand","prompt":"Why can't a regression trainer consume a raw `VendorId` column containing strings like `\"CMT\"` and `\"VTS\"` directly?","answer":"Trainers operate on numeric vectors.","explanation":"Trainers operate on numeric vectors. `OneHotEncoding` performs categorical encoding: each distinct text value becomes a slot in a binary-indicator vector (e.g. `\"VTS\"` → `[0, 1]`), which the trainer can then process.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-04","type":"cloze","bloom":"apply","prompt":"In `mlContext.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(outputColumnName: \"VendorIdEncoded\", inputColumnName: \"VendorId\")`, the name `\"VendorIdEncoded\"` is {{chosen by you}}, but whatever you pick must then appear in the {{`Concatenate` input list}}.","answer":"chosen by you","explanation":"Output names are arbitrary — `\"VendorIdOH\"` works equally well. The only hard constraint is matching that exact string when you reference the encoded column downstream.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-05","type":"name","bloom":"apply","prompt":"A pipeline calls `OneHotEncoding` on `VendorId`, `RateCode`, and `PaymentType`, then `Concatenate(\"Features\", \"VendorIdEncoded\", \"PassengerCount\", \"TripDistance\")`. What silent bug exists?","answer":"`RateCodeEncoded` and `PaymentTypeEncoded` are encoded but never listed in `Concatenate`, so they are dropped from …","explanation":"`RateCodeEncoded` and `PaymentTypeEncoded` are encoded but never listed in `Concatenate`, so they are dropped from the `\"Features\"` vector. The pipeline compiles and trains, but on fewer features than intended.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-06","type":"cloze","bloom":"apply","prompt":"When predicting taxi fare, you must exclude `TripTime` from the feature list to prevent {{data leakage}}, because trip duration is unknown at {{prediction time}}.","answer":"data leakage","explanation":"Time-dependent columns known only after the event you're predicting leak future information into training. The model learns an unrealistic shortcut and fails on real inputs.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-07","type":"name","bloom":"apply","prompt":"Order these pipeline steps correctly: trainer `FastTree()`, `OneHotEncoding` calls, `CopyColumns(\"Label\", \"FareAmount\")`, `Concatenate(\"Features\", …)`.","answer":"`CopyColumns(\"Label\", \"FareAmount\")` → `OneHotEncoding` calls → `Concatenate(\"Features\", …)` → `FastTree()`.","explanation":"`CopyColumns(\"Label\", \"FareAmount\")` → `OneHotEncoding` calls → `Concatenate(\"Features\", …)` → `FastTree()`. Label rename and encoded-column setup must both occur before the trainer.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-08","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","prompt":"The `[LoadColumn(0)]` attribute uses a {{0-based}} CSV index, whereas ClosedXML cells are {{1-based}} — don't carry one convention into the other.","answer":"0-based","explanation":"ML.NET CSV column attributes start at 0 for the first column. ClosedXML's `Cell(1, 1)` addresses row 1, column 1. Mixing them causes off-by-one column mismatches.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-data-transforms-card-09","type":"name","bloom":"understand","prompt":"What does `NormalizeMinMax` do, and how does it differ in purpose from `OneHotEncoding`?","answer":"`NormalizeMinMax` scales numeric features to the `[0, 1]` range.","explanation":"`NormalizeMinMax` scales numeric features to the `[0, 1]` range. `OneHotEncoding` converts text categories into numeric indicator vectors. Normalization rescales existing numbers; one-hot encoding creates numbers from text.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"}],"source":"slides/ML.NET.pptx; notes/ML.NET_VSCODE_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md §Key Transform Classes"},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation","name":"ML.NET regression evaluation — FastTree, RMSE, R²","tags":["ml-net","regression","metrics"],"prose":"Regression trainers live on mlContext.Regression.Trainers; FastTree (gradient-boosted trees in Microsoft.ML.FastTree) is the default. You split an IDataView with mlContext.Data.TrainTestSplit(data, testFraction: 0.2) or average across folds with mlContext.Regression.CrossValidate. Evaluation runs through mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\"), which returns a RegressionMetrics object. Read metrics.RSquared (variance explained, 0–1, unitless), metrics.RootMeanSquaredError (average error in the label's original units, lower is better), and metrics.MeanAbsoluteError (absolute error, more robust to outliers). The namespace must match the task: Regression.Evaluate produces regression metrics, MulticlassClassification.Evaluate does not. The score argument names the prediction column; FastTree writes to \"Score\".","cards":[{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-01","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"research-mlnet.md §Regression Trainers; card #9","explanation":"FastTree is the default choice for general regression. Its output column is named \"Score\". SdcaRegression and LightGbmRegression are alternatives; LightGbm additionally requires Microsoft.ML.LightGbm.","example":".Append(mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree())","prompt":"The default gradient-boosted-trees regression trainer is created with ___ and ships in the ___ package.","answer":"mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree() ; Microsoft.ML.FastTree"},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-02","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"research-mlnet.md §TrainTestSplit; card #15","explanation":"TrainTestSplit sits on mlContext.Data, not mlContext.Regression. You fit the pipeline on TrainSet and evaluate predictions from TestSet.","example":"var split = mlContext.Data.TrainTestSplit(dataView, testFraction: 0.2);\nITransformer model = pipeline.Fit(split.TrainSet);\nvar predictions = model.Transform(split.TestSet);\n","prompt":"Which call partitions an IDataView into 80% training and 20% test subsets?","answer":"mlContext.Data.TrainTestSplit(dataView, testFraction: 0.2)  — returns a DataOperationsCatalog.TrainTestData with TrainSet and TestSet."},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-03","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"research-mlnet.md §CrossValidate","explanation":"CrossValidate gives a tighter performance estimate than a single TrainTestSplit because every row serves as test data in exactly one fold.","example":"var cv = mlContext.Regression.CrossValidate(pipeline, data, numberOfFolds: 5);","prompt":"Call ___ to run k-fold cross-validation: it trains k models, each on (k-1) folds, and reports ___ metrics across all folds.","answer":"mlContext.Regression.CrossValidate(pipeline, data, numberOfFolds: 5) ; averaged"},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-04","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"research-mlnet.md §Evaluation Metrics; card #10","explanation":"The first string is the label column (you renamed the target to \"Label\" via CopyColumns). The second is the score column — FastTree writes its prediction to \"Score\". Mismatched names break Evaluate.","example":"IDataView predictions = model.Transform(split.TestSet);\nvar metrics = mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\");\nConsole.WriteLine($\"R²: {metrics.RSquared:0.##}\");\n","prompt":"Which line evaluates a regression model and returns a RegressionMetrics object?","answer":"var metrics = mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\");"},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-05","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"research-mlnet.md §Regression Metrics","explanation":"R² = 1 − (SS_residual / SS_total). It is unitless. 0.89 means the model explains 89% of the label's variance, not that it is 89% accurate.","example":"Console.WriteLine($\"RSquared: {metrics.RSquared:0.##}\");","prompt":"R² is exposed as ___ on RegressionMetrics, ranges from ___ to ___, and reports the fraction of ___ the model explains.","answer":"metrics.RSquared ; 0 ; 1 ; variance"},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-06","type":"name","bloom":"evaluate","source":"research-mlnet.md §Regression Metrics example; MCQ #4","explanation":"RMSE inherits the label's units (dollars here). R² is unitless variance-explained. Distractors conflate the two — \"89% accurate with 3.3% error\" is wrong on both counts.","example":"metrics.RSquared = 0.89 ; metrics.RootMeanSquaredError = 3.30 ; label column = FareAmount (USD)","prompt":"A taxi-fare model reports RSquared = 0.89 and RootMeanSquaredError = 3.3 on the test set. What do those numbers mean?","answer":"The model explains 89% of variance in FareAmount, and predicted fares miss the actual fare by about $3.30 on average."},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-07","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"research-mlnet.md §Evaluation Metrics; §Exam Traps","explanation":"A uses the wrong namespace — MulticlassClassification returns accuracy metrics, not RSquared. B passes the wrong score-column name; FastTree emits \"Score\". D is not a real method — Evaluate lives on the task catalog (Regression), not on Trainers.","example":"var metrics = mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\");","prompt":"You trained a regression model and want to print R² and RMSE on a held-out test set. Which snippet is correct?\n\nA) var metrics = mlContext.MulticlassClassification.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\");\nB) var metrics = mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Prediction\");\nC) var metrics = mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\");\nD) var metrics = mlContext.Regression.Trainers.Evaluate(predictions);\n","answer":"C"},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-08","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"research-mlnet.md §Regression Metrics","explanation":"RMSE = √(Σ(predicted − actual)² / n). It punishes large errors more than MeanAbsoluteError does. MAE is the robust-to-outliers alternative.","example":"RSquared = 0.89 (89% variance explained) ; RMSE = 3.30 (≈ $3.30 average miss)","prompt":"Why is RootMeanSquaredError a better reality check than RSquared when a stakeholder asks \"how far off are predictions?\"","answer":"RMSE is in the label's original units (dollars for fare, seconds for duration) so it answers the question directly. RSquared is unitless variance-explained and says nothing about the size of an individual miss."},{"id":"ml-regression-evaluation-card-09","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"research-mlnet.md §Regression Metrics; §Exam Traps","explanation":"Claiming \"RMSE = 3.3%\" or \"RSquared is in dollars\" swaps the two. RMSE inherits units; R² never does.","example":"metrics.RootMeanSquaredError = 3.30   // dollars, because FareAmount is in USD","prompt":"RootMeanSquaredError measures error in the label's ___ units, while RSquared is ___ and ranges 0 to 1.","answer":"original (e.g. dollars for fare) ; unitless"}],"source":"slides/ML.NET.pptx; notes/ML.NET_VSCODE_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md §Evaluation Metrics"},{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption","module":"AI in .NET","tags":["ml-net","inference"],"cards":[{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption-card-01","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","prompt":"`pipeline.Fit(trainingData)` returns an instance of `{{ITransformer}}`, not an `IDataView`.","answer":"ITransformer","explanation":"`Fit` trains the pipeline and hands back the stateless, serializable trained model — the `ITransformer`. The `IDataView` is the input, not the output.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption-card-02","type":"name","bloom":"understand","prompt":"You need to score one new `TaxiTrip` at inference time. Which ML.NET type do you create, and from which factory?","answer":"Create a `PredictionEngine\u003cTaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction\u003e` via `mlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e(model)`, then call `Predict(trip)`.","explanation":"Create a `PredictionEngine\u003cTaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction\u003e` via `mlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e(model)`, then call `Predict(trip)`. It is the single-row inference wrapper around an `ITransformer`.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption-card-03","type":"cloze","bloom":"remember","prompt":"The prediction field on an ML.NET regression output class is decorated with `[ColumnName(\"{{Score}}\")]`.","answer":"Score","explanation":"Regression trainers write their output into a column literally named `Score`. Using `[ColumnName(\"Prediction\")]` leaves the field at its default value because the binding misses.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption-card-04","type":"name","bloom":"apply","prompt":"Write the two-line C# to persist `model` (an `ITransformer`) to `model.zip` using `trainingData`'s schema.","answer":"```csharp mlContext.Model.Save(model, trainingData.Schema, \"model.zip\"); ``` One call.","explanation":"```csharp\nmlContext.Model.Save(model, trainingData.Schema, \"model.zip\");\n```\nOne call. Pass the model, the training `DataViewSchema`, and the path. Omitting the schema produces a zip that won't load correctly.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption-card-05","type":"name","bloom":"apply","prompt":"You have `model.zip` on disk. Load it back into an `ITransformer` and capture its schema.","answer":"```csharp DataViewSchema schema; ITransformer loaded = mlContext.Model.Load(\"model.zip\", out schema); ``` `Load` returns the transformer; the …","explanation":"```csharp\nDataViewSchema schema;\nITransformer loaded = mlContext.Model.Load(\"model.zip\", out schema);\n```\n`Load` returns the transformer; the schema comes back through the `out` parameter.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption-card-06","type":"cloze","bloom":"understand","prompt":"For batch inference on an entire `IDataView`, call `model.{{Transform}}(dataView)` — not `CreatePredictionEngine`.","answer":"Transform","explanation":"`PredictionEngine` is the single-row path. `Transform` is the batch path: it returns a new `IDataView` with the `Score` column appended.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption-card-07","type":"name","bloom":"understand","prompt":"Why is sharing one `PredictionEngine` across threads a bug, and what is the recommended fix for a web API?","answer":"`PredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` is not thread-safe — concurrent `Predict` calls corrupt its internal buffers.","explanation":"`PredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` is not thread-safe — concurrent `Predict` calls corrupt its internal buffers. Use `PredictionEnginePool\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` from `Microsoft.Extensions.ML`, or give each thread its own engine.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-prediction-consumption-card-08","type":"name","bloom":"apply","prompt":"A teammate writes `mlContext.Model.Save(model, null, \"model.zip\")` and the code compiles. What breaks, and when?","answer":"It breaks at load time.","explanation":"It breaks at load time. Without the `DataViewSchema`, the saved zip lacks the column-name and type metadata ML.NET needs to reconstruct inputs, so `Load` returns a transformer that can't be bound to a `PredictionEngine` correctly. Always pass `trainingData.Schema`.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"}],"name":"ML.NET inference and model persistence","source":"notes/ML.NET_VS2022_SCRIPT.docx; notes/ML.NET_VSCODE_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md §PredictionEngine, §Save & Load","prose":"Cards for the ML.NET inference and model persistence topic."},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local","name":"Chat completion with Ollama + SLMs","tags":["ai","slm","ollama","streaming"],"prose":"Ollama runs Small Language Models locally on port 11434 over HTTP. The OllamaSharp NuGet package exposes OllamaApiClient, which implements IChatClient from Microsoft.Extensions.AI. You feed it a List\u003cChatMessage\u003e (each message is a ChatRole plus content) and call GetStreamingResponseAsync for token-by-token output or GetResponseAsync for a buffered reply. No cloud, no API key, no internet after the initial ollama pull.","cards":[{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-01","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"research-ai.md §Ollama; §Endpoint URL Pitfalls","explanation":"Port 11434 on localhost, HTTP only. HTTPS is the GitHub Models endpoint; port 1143 is a one-digit typo trap.","example":"new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\")","prompt":"Ollama listens on the endpoint ___ using the ___ protocol.","answer":"http://localhost:11434/ ; HTTP (not HTTPS)"},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-02","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"research-ai.md §Call Ollama via OllamaSharp; SLM.docx Demo #1","explanation":"OllamaApiClient takes a Uri and a model-id string. The returned object implements IChatClient from Microsoft.Extensions.AI.","example":"IChatClient chatClient = new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\");","prompt":"Which constructor call creates an OllamaSharp client for a local Phi-3 model?","answer":"new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\")"},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-03","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"research-ai.md §Ollama Setup Commands; flashcard #19","explanation":"pull downloads weights. list/show inspect what is installed. run opens an interactive REPL against a model.","example":"ollama pull phi3:latest","prompt":"What command downloads a model into Ollama so it can be served locally?","answer":"ollama pull \u003cmodel\u003e  (e.g. ollama pull phi3:latest)"},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-04","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"research-ai.md §Chat Completion; flashcard #16; MCQ #?","explanation":"Every ChatMessage carries a ChatRole plus content. A List\u003cChatMessage\u003e is the conversation history re-sent on each call.","example":"chatHistory.Add(new ChatMessage(ChatRole.User, userPrompt));","prompt":"The ChatMessage constructor takes two arguments: a ___ enum value (User, Assistant, or System) and the message ___.","answer":"ChatRole ; content (string or structured data)"},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-05","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"research-ai.md §Call Ollama via OllamaSharp; glossary §streaming","explanation":"GetStreamingResponseAsync yields ChatResponseUpdate items incrementally; GetResponseAsync blocks until the full response is ready.","example":"await foreach (ChatResponseUpdate item in\n    chatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync(chatHistory))\n{\n    Console.Write(item.Text);\n}\n","prompt":"Which IChatClient method streams the reply as ChatResponseUpdate fragments instead of returning one buffered response?","answer":"GetStreamingResponseAsync(chatHistory)  — iterate with await foreach"},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-06","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"research-ai.md §Local vs Cloud SLM; MCQ #7","explanation":"GitHub Models and Azure OpenAI both require cloud credentials. Ollama serves a pulled SLM from localhost with no auth.","example":"IChatClient client = new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\");","prompt":"You want a chatbot that runs with no cloud dependency and no API key. Which setup fits?","answer":"Use Ollama locally: new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\")"},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-07","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"research-ai.md §Endpoint URL Pitfalls; MCQ #2","explanation":"A drops a digit (1143 vs 11434). B and C wrongly use HTTPS; /inference is the GitHub Models path. E invents a port. Only D matches the canonical course pattern.","example":"new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\")","prompt":"Which endpoint URL correctly connects OllamaSharp to a local Ollama server?\n\nA) http://localhost:1143/\nB) https://api.ollama.com\nC) https://localhost:11434/inference\nD) http://localhost:11434/\nE) http://localhost:5000/ollama\n","answer":"D"},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-08","type":"name","bloom":"understand","source":"research-ai.md §Local vs Cloud SLM trap row","explanation":"After pull, the daemon loads weights from disk and serves requests from localhost. Airplane-mode demos are a common lecture point.","example":"ollama pull phi3:latest   # only this step needs the internet","prompt":"True or false: Ollama requires an internet connection to answer prompts.","answer":"False. Internet is needed only for ollama pull to download the model; inference is fully local."},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-09","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"research-ai.md §Endpoint URL Pitfalls (package confusion)","explanation":"The exam may test which name is the C# package. OllamaSharp = NuGet. ollama = the command-line binary you run to pull, list, or serve models.","example":"dotnet add package OllamaSharp","prompt":"The third-party NuGet package for the .NET Ollama client is ___ ; the CLI binary and daemon is ___ .","answer":"OllamaSharp ; ollama"},{"id":"ai-chat-completion-local-card-10","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"research-ai.md §appsettings.json for Ollama; §Call Ollama via ChatClient (Direct)","explanation":"Keeping URL and model id in config lets you switch SLMs without recompiling. The constructor signature is (Uri, string).","example":"string url = config[\"OllamaUrl\"];\nstring modelId = config[\"ModelId\"];\nIChatClient client = new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(url), modelId);\n","prompt":"Given OllamaUrl and ModelId in appsettings.json, what two values does the OllamaApiClient constructor consume?","answer":"A Uri built from OllamaUrl (\"http://localhost:11434/\") and the ModelId string (e.g. \"phi3:latest\")."}],"source":"slides/SLM.pptx; notes/SLM.docx; research-ai.md §Ollama, §Chat Completion"},{"id":"ai-cloud-models","name":"GitHub Models + Azure OpenAI endpoints","tags":["ai","cloud","auth"],"prose":"Wiring a hosted chat endpoint in .NET reduces to three knobs: endpoint URL,\ncredential object, and model name. GitHub Models uses\n`https://models.github.ai/inference` with a GitHub PAT wrapped in\n`AzureKeyCredential`, plus a vendor-prefixed model id like\n`openai/gpt-4o-mini`. Azure OpenAI uses your resource URL and a deployment\nname. Both reuse the same credential class despite the misleading name.\n","cards":[{"id":"ai-cloud-models-card-01","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx","prompt":"What is the GitHub Models inference endpoint URL?","answer":"https://models.github.ai/inference","explanation":"HTTPS, and the `/inference` path is required. Dropping the path breaks routing.","example":"```json\n\"ApiEndpoint\": \"https://models.github.ai/inference\"\n```\n"},{"id":"ai-cloud-models-card-02","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx","prompt":"Which credential class authenticates GitHub Models calls from the OpenAI SDK?","answer":"`AzureKeyCredential(token)`","explanation":"Despite the `Azure` prefix, this class wraps any bearer token. No `GithubCredential` type exists in the SDK.","example":"```csharp\nnew AzureKeyCredential(config[\"GitHub:Token\"]!)\n```\n"},{"id":"ai-cloud-models-card-03","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx","prompt":"Which credential type does a GitHub Models `ChatClient` require?","answer":"`AzureKeyCredential(token)`","explanation":"`AzureKeyCredential` is reused for GitHub PATs. The other three are distractors — none exist in this SDK context.","example":"```csharp\nIChatClient chatClient = new ChatClient(\n    model,\n    new AzureKeyCredential(apiKey!),\n    new OpenAIClientOptions { Endpoint = new Uri(endpoint) }\n).AsIChatClient();\n```\n"},{"id":"ai-cloud-models-card-04","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx","prompt":"Complete the `ChatClient` wiring for GitHub Models: `new ChatClient(model, new ___(apiKey!), new OpenAIClientOptions { Endpoint = new Uri(endpoint) }).___();`","answer":"`AzureKeyCredential`; `AsIChatClient`","explanation":"`AzureKeyCredential` carries the PAT. `.AsIChatClient()` adapts the OpenAI `ChatClient` to `Microsoft.Extensions.AI`'s `IChatClient` so MAF can consume it.","example":"```csharp\nIChatClient chatClient = new ChatClient(\n    \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\",\n    new AzureKeyCredential(token),\n    new OpenAIClientOptions { Endpoint = new Uri(\"https://models.github.ai/inference\") }\n).AsIChatClient();\n```\n"},{"id":"ai-cloud-models-card-05","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx","prompt":"Which model-id string is correctly formatted for GitHub Models?","answer":"`openai/gpt-4o-mini`","explanation":"GitHub Models routes through vendor-prefixed ids. `openai/` identifies the publisher; the bare name gets rejected.","example":"```json\n\"Model\": \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"\n```\n"},{"id":"ai-cloud-models-card-06","type":"name","bloom":"remember","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx","prompt":"Which `appsettings.json` keys store the GitHub Models configuration?","answer":"`GitHub:Token`, `GitHub:ApiEndpoint`, `GitHub:Model`","explanation":"The PAT lives under `GitHub:Token`. Endpoint and model id live alongside it so `config[...]` binding stays tidy.","example":"```json\n{\n  \"GitHub\": {\n    \"Token\": \"PUT-GITHUB-PERSONAL-ACCESS-TOKEN-HERE\",\n    \"ApiEndpoint\": \"https://models.github.ai/inference\",\n    \"Model\": \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"\n  }\n}\n```\n"},{"id":"ai-cloud-models-card-07","type":"name","bloom":"apply","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx; slides/CSharp_Meets_AI.pptx","prompt":"You need to differentiate a GitHub Models endpoint from a local Ollama endpoint in code review. Which pair is correct?","answer":"GitHub: `https://models.github.ai/inference`; Ollama: `http://localhost:11434/`","explanation":"GitHub is HTTPS with `/inference`. Ollama is HTTP on port `11434` with no path. Common traps: dropping `/inference`, typoing `1143` for `11434`, or swapping protocols.","example":"```csharp\n// GitHub Models\nnew Uri(\"https://models.github.ai/inference\");\n// Ollama (local)\nnew Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\");\n```\n"}],"source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx; research-ai.md §Call GitHub Models, §Call Azure OpenAI"},{"id":"ml-automl-cli","cards":[{"id":"ml-automl-cli-card-01","type":"cloze","tags":["ml-net","automl","naming"],"prompt":"The ML.NET AutoML command-line tool is named {{`mlnet`}} (lowercase, no dot); the framework it targets is written {{`ML.NET`}} (uppercase, dotted).","answer":"mlnet","explanation":"The CLI and the framework have different casing. `mlnet` is installed via `dotnet tool install -g mlnet-win-x64` (swap the suffix for `osx-x64` or `linux-x64`).","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-automl-cli-card-02","type":"name","tags":["ml-net","automl","cli"],"prompt":"What does this command do? `mlnet regression --dataset taxi-fare-train.csv --label-col 6 --train-time 60 --has-header true`","answer":"Runs AutoML for a regression task on `taxi-fare-train.csv`, predicts the column at index 6, explores …","explanation":"Runs AutoML for a regression task on `taxi-fare-train.csv`, predicts the column at index 6, explores 40+ algorithm/hyperparameter combinations for 60 seconds, and emits a console project wired to the best model. `--has-header true` says the CSV starts with a header row.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-automl-cli-card-03","type":"cloze","tags":["ml-net","automl","flags"],"prompt":"The `--label-col` flag accepts either a 0-based {{index}} (e.g. `6`) or a column {{name}} (e.g. `FareAmount`).","answer":"index","explanation":"Use the index when the header text is uncertain or missing — passing a name that does not match the CSV header causes silent failure.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-automl-cli-card-04","type":"name","tags":["ml-net","automl","flags"],"prompt":"Which `mlnet` flag sets the exploration budget, and what are its units?","answer":"`--train-time`, in seconds.","explanation":"`--train-time`, in seconds. A larger value generally surfaces better models, but returns diminish — doubling from 60 to 120 seconds rarely doubles RSquared.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-automl-cli-card-05","type":"name","tags":["ml-net","automl","output"],"prompt":"After `mlnet regression` finishes, what artifact does it emit?","answer":"A full console project — source files, a `.csproj`, and a `.zip` model — wired …","explanation":"A full console project — source files, a `.csproj`, and a `.zip` model — wired to the winning pipeline. You run it with `dotnet run`. The CLI does not emit a bare model file on its own.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"},{"id":"ml-automl-cli-card-06","type":"cloze","tags":["ml-net","automl","pitfall"],"prompt":"AutoML explores {{40+}} regression variants within the `--train-time` budget and ranks them; the ``top-5`` list is {{not guaranteed to be globally optimal}}.","answer":"40+","explanation":"AutoML searches the algorithm + hyperparameter space it has time to reach. Larger `--train-time` explores more combinations, but the winner is only the best model AutoML happened to try.","example":"\u003c!-- example: Stage 5 enrichment --\u003e"}],"name":"Ml Automl Cli","source":"notes/ML.NET_vscode_automl_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md §AutoML CLI","prose":"Cards for the Ml Automl Cli topic.","tags":[]}]},{"id":"module-2-distributed-services","name":"Distributed Services & Orchestration","topics":[{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts","name":"gRPC .proto contracts","tags":["grpc","protobuf","contract-first"],"source":"slides/gRPC.pptx; notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx; research-grpc.md","prose":"These cards drill the proto3 syntax you must read and write on the exam — keywords, field-tag rules, and the defaults that trip students up.","cards":[{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"In a `.proto` file, the `{{1}}` keyword declares a gRPC service and each `{{2}}` keyword inside declares one callable method.","answer":"service; rpc","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The generator walks every `rpc` line inside a `service` block to emit one C# method per RPC on both the server base class and the client stub.","example":"service StudentRemote {\n  rpc GetStudentInfo (StudentLookupModel) returns (StudentModel);\n}"},{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"Proto field tags `1` through `{{1}}` encode in one byte; tags `{{2}}` and higher take two bytes.","answer":"15; 16","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Protobuf packs the wire-type and tag number into a varint. Values below 16 fit in the first byte's 4 available tag bits, so frequently-sent fields should live in the 1–15 range.","example":"message Person {\n  int32 id = 1;      // 1-byte tag\n  string bio = 16;   // 2-byte tag\n}"},{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"What is the default value of an unset `string` field in proto3?","answer":"The empty string \"\".","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Proto3 removed the `null` / `HasField` concept for scalars. The server cannot distinguish 'client sent nothing' from 'client sent an empty string' on a plain `string` field.","example":"message Reply { string result = 1; }  // unset Result is \"\""},{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"The `{{1}}` keyword in a `message` definition maps to a `List\u003cT\u003e` in the generated C# code.","answer":"repeated","bloom":"understand","explanation":"`repeated` marks a field as a zero-or-more collection. `protoc` emits a `RepeatedField\u003cT\u003e` property that implements `IList\u003cT\u003e`, which is how you iterate or add items in C#.","example":"message StudentList {\n  repeated StudentModel items = 1;\n}"},{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"You delete the field `string school = 4;` from a deployed `.proto`. Can you safely reuse tag `4` for a new `int32 gradeLevel = 4;`?","answer":"No — reusing a tag number is forbidden. Old clients still sending tag 4 as a string will be misdecoded as the new `int32`.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"Field tags are the immutable binary wire identifier. Changing a tag's type without changing its number silently corrupts any already-deployed client. Either pick a fresh tag or mark the old one `reserved`.","example":"message Student {\n  reserved 4;             // protect old tag\n  int32 gradeLevel = 5;   // new field, new tag\n}"},{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-06","type":"predict","prompt":"Given this proto, what does the generated C# class for `StudentLookupModel` expose, and what is the default value of `StudentId` on a freshly-constructed instance?","lang":"proto","code":"message StudentLookupModel {\n  int32 studentId = 1;\n}\n","answer":"A C# class `StudentLookupModel` with a public `int StudentId { get; set; }` property. A `new StudentLookupModel()` has `StudentId == 0` because proto3 unset `int32` defaults to zero.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`protoc` PascalCases proto field names for C#, so `studentId` becomes `StudentId`. Proto3 scalar defaults are 0 / \"\" / false — there is no null option for plain scalars.","example":"var req = new StudentLookupModel();\n// req.StudentId == 0"},{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"In a `.csproj`, `\u003cProtobuf Include=\"Protos\\x.proto\" GrpcServices=\"{{1}}\" /\u003e` generates the abstract base class your service implementation inherits from.","answer":"Server","bloom":"understand","explanation":"The `GrpcServices` attribute controls which half of the contract `protoc` emits. `Server` yields the `ServiceNameBase` class; `Client` yields the `ServiceNameClient` stub; `Both` yields both.","example":"\u003cProtobuf Include=\"Protos\\students.proto\" GrpcServices=\"Server\" /\u003e"},{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"What does `option csharp_namespace = \"GrpcStudentsServer\";` do in a `.proto` file?","answer":"It sets the C# namespace that `protoc` wraps around every generated class for this `.proto`.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Without this option, `protoc` derives the namespace from the `package` directive, which may not match your C# project's conventions. The option lets the proto and C# namespaces diverge.","example":"option csharp_namespace = \"GrpcStudentsServer\";\npackage greet;"},{"id":"grpc-proto-contracts-card-09","type":"predict","prompt":"A client sends this proto message with `studentId` left unset. What does the server see?","lang":"proto","code":"message StudentLookupModel {\n  int32 studentId = 1;\n}\n","answer":"The server reads `request.StudentId == 0`. Proto3 cannot distinguish 'unset' from 'explicit zero' for a plain `int32` — both serialize identically on the wire.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"This is the proto3-no-null trap. If you need to tell 'missing' from 'zero', wrap the field in a singleton `message` or use a `google.protobuf.Int32Value` wrapper, which does carry presence information.","example":"if (request.StudentId == 0) {\n  // could mean unset OR id = 0\n}"}]},{"id":"grpc-server-implementation","name":"gRPC server implementation","tags":["grpc","server","asp-net-core"],"source":"notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx; Labs/W09 gRPC/; research-grpc.md","prose":"A gRPC server inherits from the auto-generated `[Service].[Service]Base` class and overrides one method per `rpc`. Each override takes the request type plus `ServerCallContext` and returns `Task\u003cResponse\u003e`. Services are registered with `AddGrpc()` and routed with `MapGrpcService\u003cT\u003e()`.","cards":[{"id":"grpc-server-implementation-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"A gRPC service class inherits from `{{StudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase}}` — the pattern is `[ServiceName].[ServiceName]{{Base}}`.","answer":"StudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase; Base","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`Grpc.Tools` generates the base at build time. Inheriting from it is the only way to get your methods matched to the wire-level service dispatch.","example":"public class StudentsService : StudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase { … }"},{"id":"grpc-server-implementation-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Every gRPC server-side method takes two parameters. Name them in order for a unary call.","answer":"The request message type, then ServerCallContext.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The `ServerCallContext` carries cancellation tokens, deadlines, metadata, and peer info. Omitting it is a compile error because the `override` target requires it.","example":"public override Task\u003cStudentModel\u003e GetStudentInfo(StudentLookupModel request, ServerCallContext context) { ... }"},{"id":"grpc-server-implementation-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"Server-side unary methods return `{{Task\u003cResponse\u003e}}`. Wrap a synchronous value with `{{Task.FromResult}}(value)`.","answer":"Task\u003cResponse\u003e; Task.FromResult","bloom":"apply","explanation":"gRPC methods are always asynchronous on the wire. Even when your implementation is synchronous, you must return a `Task` — `Task.FromResult` wraps the value cheaply.","example":"return Task.FromResult(new StudentModel { StudentId = 3 });"},{"id":"grpc-server-implementation-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"Which two calls register gRPC services in `Program.cs`?","answer":"`builder.Services.AddGrpc()` plus `app.MapGrpcService\u003cYourService\u003e()`.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`AddGrpc` registers framework types (serialization, interceptors, resilience). `MapGrpcService\u003cT\u003e` wires routing so HTTP/2 requests reach your class.","example":"builder.Services.AddGrpc(); … app.MapGrpcService\u003cStudentsService\u003e();"},{"id":"grpc-server-implementation-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Forgetting the `{{override}}` keyword on a method shadows the base-class method. The server compiles, but client calls get back `RpcException: {{UNIMPLEMENTED}}`.","answer":"override; UNIMPLEMENTED","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"Without `override`, your method is unrelated to the base class virtual method. The framework dispatches to the base's default, which throws UNIMPLEMENTED.","example":"public override Task\u003cStudentModel\u003e GetStudentInfo(... — the override keyword is non-optional."},{"id":"grpc-server-implementation-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"How does a server-streaming method signature differ from a unary method?","answer":"It returns `Task` (not `Task\u003cT\u003e`) and takes `IServerStreamWriter\u003cT\u003e` as a third parameter.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Streaming methods write each message via `responseStream.WriteAsync(...)` and return when the loop finishes. There is no single response object, so no `Task\u003cT\u003e` return.","example":"public override async Task RetrieveAllStudents(Empty r, IServerStreamWriter\u003cStudentModel\u003e stream, ServerCallContext ctx) { … }"},{"id":"grpc-server-implementation-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"To inject an EF Core DbContext into a gRPC service, register it with `{{builder.Services.AddDbContext}}\u003cT\u003e` in `Program.cs`, then accept it in the service constructor.","answer":"builder.Services.AddDbContext","bloom":"apply","explanation":"gRPC services use standard ASP.NET Core DI. Any service registered in the container can be constructor-injected, and gRPC services are instantiated per-request by default.","example":"public StudentsService(SchoolDbContext context) =\u003e _context = context;"},{"id":"grpc-server-implementation-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"What does the `ServerCallContext` parameter carry that you might use inside an override?","answer":"Cancellation tokens, deadlines, request metadata, and peer (client) info.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Use `context.CancellationToken` to short-circuit expensive work if the client disconnects. `context.Deadline` tells you when the client will time out. `context.RequestHeaders` carries metadata like auth tokens.","example":"if (context.CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested) return Task.FromResult(new Reply { IsOk = false });"}]},{"id":"grpc-client-consumption","name":"gRPC client consumption","tags":["grpc","client","di","asp-net-core"],"source":"notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx; Labs/W09 gRPC/; research-grpc.md","prose":"A gRPC client project shares the `.proto` file with the server but sets `GrpcServices=\"Client\"` in its `.csproj`. Clients are constructed from a long-lived `GrpcChannel.ForAddress(url)` or registered via `AddGrpcClient\u003cT\u003e()` for DI. Blazor pages awaiting gRPC calls must use `@rendermode InteractiveServer`.","cards":[{"id":"grpc-client-consumption-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"To generate only the client-side stub from a shared `.proto`, the `.csproj` entry is `\u003cProtobuf Include=\"…\" GrpcServices=\"{{Client}}\" /\u003e`.","answer":"Client","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`GrpcServices` chooses which code `Grpc.Tools` emits. `Server` produces the base class; `Client` produces the stub; `Both` produces both and is rarely needed.","example":"\u003cProtobuf Include=\"Protos\\students.proto\" GrpcServices=\"Client\" /\u003e"},{"id":"grpc-client-consumption-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which method constructs a long-lived gRPC connection given a URL?","answer":"GrpcChannel.ForAddress(url)","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The channel holds the HTTP/2 connection. Creating one is expensive; reuse across many client stubs. Client stubs themselves are cheap throwaway objects bound to a channel.","example":"using var channel = GrpcChannel.ForAddress(\"http://localhost:5099\");"},{"id":"grpc-client-consumption-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"For DI-based client registration in ASP.NET Core, use `builder.Services.{{AddGrpcClient}}\u003cStudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient\u003e(opts =\u003e opts.Address = new Uri(\"http://localhost:5099\"))` after adding the {{Grpc.Net.ClientFactory}} NuGet package.","answer":"AddGrpcClient; Grpc.Net.ClientFactory","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`AddGrpcClient` wires the client into the DI container with channel pooling, resilience handlers, and OpenTelemetry. Plain `new GrpcChannel` in Program.cs loses all those benefits.","example":"builder.Services.AddGrpcClient\u003cStudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient\u003e(o =\u003e o.Address = new Uri(\"http://backend\"));"},{"id":"grpc-client-consumption-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What render mode must a Blazor page use so it can `await` a gRPC client call inside `OnInitializedAsync`?","answer":"`@rendermode InteractiveServer` (or `InteractiveWebAssembly` / `InteractiveAuto`).","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Static server rendering completes before asynchronous work resolves. An interactive mode keeps the component alive and re-renders when the awaited task finishes.","example":"@page \"/students\"\n@rendermode InteractiveServer\n@inject StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient _g"},{"id":"grpc-client-consumption-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"gRPC client methods are exposed in two forms: a blocking `{{Xxx}}(...)` and an asynchronous `{{XxxAsync}}(...)` that returns a `Task\u003cT\u003e` you await.","answer":"Xxx; XxxAsync","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Protocol Buffers generate both forms. The Async form is what you almost always call from managed code — the blocking form can deadlock in sync contexts.","example":"var reply = await client.GetStudentInfoAsync(request); // not client.GetStudentInfo(request)"},{"id":"grpc-client-consumption-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"A Blazor client gets `ConnectionRefused` every time it calls the gRPC server. What is the first thing to check?","answer":"That the client's Uri matches the server's `launchSettings.json` applicationUrl (including port and http vs https).","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"Port drift between server launch profile and client config is the single most common cause. Aspire service discovery via `http://backend/` eliminates this class of bug entirely.","example":"Server listens on https://localhost:7001. Client Uri must be exactly that URL — not http://localhost:5001."},{"id":"grpc-client-consumption-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"Once registered with `AddGrpcClient\u003cT\u003e()`, inject the stub anywhere with `{{@inject}}` (Razor) or constructor injection (plain C# services).","answer":"@inject","bloom":"apply","explanation":"DI-registered gRPC clients are transient by default. Each request gets a fresh stub bound to a pooled channel.","example":"@inject StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient _grpcClient"}]},{"id":"aspire-apphost","name":".NET Aspire AppHost","tags":["aspire","orchestration","apphost"],"source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; Labs/W09 gRPC/; research-aspire.md","prose":"The Aspire AppHost is a separate project whose `Program.cs` builds a `DistributedApplication`. Four calls do the work: `CreateBuilder`, `AddProject\u003cProjects.X\u003e(name)`, `.WithReference(other)` for config injection, and `.WaitFor(other)` for startup ordering.","cards":[{"id":"aspire-apphost-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The Aspire orchestrator builder is created with `DistributedApplication.{{CreateBuilder}}(args)`, and the app runs with `builder.Build().{{Run}}()`.","answer":"CreateBuilder; Run","bloom":"remember","explanation":"AppHost `Program.cs` follows the same pattern as any other .NET host: builder → configure → build → run. The only difference is the type is `DistributedApplication`, not `WebApplication`.","example":"var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args); … builder.Build().Run();"},{"id":"aspire-apphost-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What does `builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.StudentsGrpcApi\u003e(\"backend\")` do?","answer":"Registers the StudentsGrpcApi project as a service under the logical name \"backend\".","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Logical names (e.g. \"backend\") become the service-discovery identity. Consumers reach the service via `http://backend/` instead of a hardcoded localhost URL.","example":"var backend = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.StudentsGrpcApi\u003e(\"backend\");"},{"id":"aspire-apphost-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"To make the frontend aware of the backend's URL, call `.{{WithReference}}(backend)`. To delay the frontend's startup until the backend is healthy, also call `.{{WaitFor}}(backend)`.","answer":"WithReference; WaitFor","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`WithReference` injects env-vars with connection info. `WaitFor` adds a health-gated startup order. Pair them when the consumer cannot recover from a cold dependency.","example":"builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Frontend\u003e(\"frontend\").WithReference(backend).WaitFor(backend);"},{"id":"aspire-apphost-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"In an AppHost, how do you add a containerized SQL Server resource with one database called `cms`?","answer":"`builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\")`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`AddSqlServer(\"sql\")` registers the server resource; `.AddDatabase(\"cms\")` chains a named database onto it. The service then `WithReference`s that database and gets `ConnectionStrings__cms` injected automatically.","example":"var cms = builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\"); api.WithReference(cms);"},{"id":"aspire-apphost-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Services reach each other via their logical name — `http://{{backend}}/` resolves to the actual host:port at runtime. This is called {{service discovery}}.","answer":"backend; service discovery","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Aspire's service-discovery protocol handler intercepts URLs whose host matches a registered logical name and swaps in the real address. This keeps client code identical across local dev, Docker, and cloud.","example":"In the Blazor app: `public const string ApiBaseUrl = \"http://backend/\";`"},{"id":"aspire-apphost-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Where does `AddServiceDefaults()` belong — in the AppHost's `Program.cs`, or in each service's `Program.cs`?","answer":"In each service's Program.cs, never in the AppHost's.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"AppHost is the orchestrator — it shouldn't register service-side concerns like OpenTelemetry or health checks on itself. Putting `AddServiceDefaults` in AppHost breaks boot.","example":"Service project: builder.AddServiceDefaults();  // in WebApi/Program.cs, NOT AppHost/Program.cs"},{"id":"aspire-apphost-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"The AppHost project must have a `\u003cProjectReference\u003e` to each service project — run `{{dotnet add reference}}` from the AppHost `.csproj` to each service.","answer":"dotnet add reference","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The `Projects.X` namespace used in `AddProject\u003cProjects.X\u003e` is generated from referenced projects. Without the reference, the type doesn't exist and the AppHost won't compile.","example":"dotnet add ./Cms.AppHost reference ./Cms.WebApi/Cms.WebApi.csproj"},{"id":"aspire-apphost-card-08","type":"name","prompt":"Which command runs the whole Aspire stack during development?","answer":"`dotnet watch` (or `dotnet run`) from the AppHost project directory.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The AppHost owns orchestration, so running it starts every declared service, database, and container. Other projects are not launched directly during dev.","example":"cd Cms.AppHost && dotnet watch"}]},{"id":"aspire-service-defaults","name":".NET Aspire ServiceDefaults","tags":["aspire","observability","health-checks"],"source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; research-aspire.md","prose":"Every Aspire service calls `builder.AddServiceDefaults()` at configure time and `app.MapDefaultEndpoints()` at map time. Together they install service discovery, OpenTelemetry, `/health` + `/alive` endpoints, and HttpClient resilience.","cards":[{"id":"aspire-service-defaults-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Every Aspire service's `Program.cs` calls `builder.{{AddServiceDefaults}}()` and `app.{{MapDefaultEndpoints}}()`.","answer":"AddServiceDefaults; MapDefaultEndpoints","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`AddServiceDefaults` registers services (discovery, OTel, health checks, resilience). `MapDefaultEndpoints` exposes the HTTP endpoints (`/health`, `/alive`). Both are required.","example":"builder.AddServiceDefaults(); … app.MapDefaultEndpoints();"},{"id":"aspire-service-defaults-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What four capabilities does `AddServiceDefaults()` install?","answer":"Service discovery, OpenTelemetry, default health checks, HttpClient resilience.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"These are the four Aspire primitives that every service is expected to have. Registering them manually in each service would produce dozens of lines; the extension consolidates them.","example":"ConfigureOpenTelemetry + AddDefaultHealthChecks + AddServiceDiscovery + ConfigureHttpClientDefaults(AddStandardResilienceHandler)"},{"id":"aspire-service-defaults-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"Aspire exposes two health endpoints: `{{/health}}` for readiness (all checks pass) and `{{/alive}}` for liveness (checks tagged \"live\" only).","answer":"/health; /alive","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Readiness gates traffic routing; liveness gates container restarts. Kubernetes maps them to `readinessProbe` and `livenessProbe` respectively.","example":"curl http://backend/health → 200 when ready; curl http://backend/alive → 200 when the process is alive."},{"id":"aspire-service-defaults-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"Which `.csproj` change connects a service to its ServiceDefaults library?","answer":"A `\u003cProjectReference\u003e` to the ServiceDefaults project (add via `dotnet add reference`).","bloom":"apply","explanation":"ServiceDefaults is a separate class library project in the solution. Each service project references it so the `AddServiceDefaults` extension method is available.","example":"dotnet add ./Cms.WebApi reference ./Cms.ServiceDefaults/Cms.ServiceDefaults.csproj"},{"id":"aspire-service-defaults-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"`AddServiceDefaults()` belongs in {{each service's}} `Program.cs`, NOT in the {{AppHost's}} `Program.cs`.","answer":"each service's; AppHost's","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"AppHost is the orchestrator — it shouldn't register service-side concerns. Putting `AddServiceDefaults` there makes the orchestrator try to configure telemetry on itself and breaks boot.","example":"AppHost/Program.cs: DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder + AddProject calls only. WebApi/Program.cs: AddServiceDefaults here."},{"id":"aspire-service-defaults-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"A new service appears red in the Aspire Dashboard. What is the single most likely cause?","answer":"The service is missing `builder.AddServiceDefaults()` so it has no `/health` endpoint.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"The dashboard polls `/health` for every registered project. Without default health checks, the endpoint returns 404 and the dashboard flags it red.","example":"Add builder.AddServiceDefaults(); and app.MapDefaultEndpoints(); to fix."},{"id":"aspire-service-defaults-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"`AddServiceDefaults` also configures HttpClientFactory: every `HttpClient` created through DI inherits {{AddStandardResilienceHandler}} and {{AddServiceDiscovery}}.","answer":"AddStandardResilienceHandler; AddServiceDiscovery","bloom":"understand","explanation":"This is why `HttpClient` calls to `http://backend/` work without per-client setup. The factory applies both resilience policies and name resolution globally.","example":"builder.Services.ConfigureHttpClientDefaults(http =\u003e { http.AddStandardResilienceHandler(); http.AddServiceDiscovery(); });"}]},{"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources","name":".NET Aspire orchestrated resources","tags":["aspire","sql-server","redis","orchestration"],"source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; research-aspire.md","prose":"AppHost declares infrastructure resources with `AddSqlServer`, `AddRedis`, `AddPostgres`, etc. under logical names. `.WithReference(resource)` injects the resource's connection info into consuming services as environment variables. Services consume it via typed helpers like `AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cT\u003e(name)`.","cards":[{"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"To register a SQL Server container with one database called `cms`: `builder.{{AddSqlServer}}(\"sql\").{{AddDatabase}}(\"cms\")`.","answer":"AddSqlServer; AddDatabase","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`AddSqlServer` registers the server resource under a logical name. `.AddDatabase` chains a named database onto it. The returned resource handle is what services `WithReference` to.","example":"var db = builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\");"},{"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"How does a consuming service receive the connection string for an Aspire-managed SQL Server database named `cms`?","answer":"Aspire injects `ConnectionStrings__cms` as an environment variable when the service process launches.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"The double-underscore is .NET's hierarchical-config convention — `ConnectionStrings__cms` equals `builder.Configuration.GetConnectionString(\"cms\")`. Aspire writes it; the service reads it.","example":"builder.AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cCmsDbContext\u003e(\"cms\"); // reads ConnectionStrings__cms automatically"},{"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"A consuming service only receives a resource's connection info if the AppHost chains `.{{WithReference}}(resource)` onto `AddProject\u003c\u003e(...)`.","answer":"WithReference","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`AddProject` alone launches the service but shares no resource info. `WithReference` is the bridge that translates resource declarations into env-vars on the consumer.","example":"builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Api\u003e(\"api\").WithReference(db);"},{"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"In a service's `Program.cs`, how do you wire EF Core to an Aspire-managed SQL Server database named `cms`?","answer":"`builder.AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cCmsDbContext\u003e(\"cms\")`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"This helper ships in `Aspire.Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer`. It reads `ConnectionStrings__cms` automatically and configures `DbContextOptions`.","example":"builder.AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cCmsDbContext\u003e(\"cms\"); // that's the only setup needed"},{"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"How do you register a Redis cache resource in the AppHost?","answer":"`var cache = builder.AddRedis(\"cache\");`","bloom":"remember","explanation":"No `.AddDatabase` chain — Redis is a single key-value store per resource. Services consume it with `builder.AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\")`.","example":"AppHost: var cache = builder.AddRedis(\"cache\"); api.WithReference(cache);\nService: builder.AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\");"},{"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"To pass an arbitrary env-var from AppHost to one specific service, use `.{{WithEnvironment}}(key, value)`.","answer":"WithEnvironment","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Scoped to that one project's process. Prefer this over leaking values globally. The service reads it via `IConfiguration` or `Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable`.","example":"api.WithEnvironment(\"FeatureFlags__NewCheckout\", \"true\");"},{"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"Your service throws \"connection string not found\" at runtime even though AppHost has `AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\")`. What's the most likely omission?","answer":"The consuming service's `AddProject\u003c\u003e(...)` call is missing `.WithReference(db)`.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"Declaring the resource is not enough. Without `WithReference`, Aspire never injects the connection string into the target service's environment.","example":"builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Api\u003e(\"api\").WithReference(db).WaitFor(db);"}]}]},{"id":"module-3-performance-caching","name":"Performance & Caching","topics":[{"id":"cache-abstractions","name":"IMemoryCache vs IDistributedCache","tags":["cache","architecture"],"source":"notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §1-2","prose":"`IMemoryCache` lives per-process and fails in web farms — each server holds its own copy. `IDistributedCache` lives across the network (Redis is the canonical backend) and is the only choice for load-balanced deployments.","cards":[{"id":"cache-abstractions-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"`{{IMemoryCache}}` stores entries in-process; `{{IDistributedCache}}` stores entries across the network, typically in Redis.","answer":"IMemoryCache; IDistributedCache","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The interface you register decides where entries live. In-process is microseconds-fast but per-server. Distributed is milliseconds-fast but shared across every app instance.","example":"builder.Services.AddMemoryCache();  // vs  builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(...)"},{"id":"cache-abstractions-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Why does `IMemoryCache` produce inconsistent data in a load-balanced web farm?","answer":"Each server instance holds its own separate cache — writes on Server A are invisible to Server B.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"In-process memory is not shared across app instances. Request 1 on Server A caches X; Request 2 on Server B finds no cache and refetches from DB. Users see different data depending on routing.","example":"Two pods behind a k8s service → two separate IMemoryCache instances → cache writes diverge."},{"id":"cache-abstractions-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"Two fixes for `IMemoryCache` in a multi-server deployment are: switch to `{{IDistributedCache}}` (e.g. Redis) or configure {{sticky sessions}} to route each client to the same server.","answer":"IDistributedCache; sticky sessions","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Redis is the clean fix — one cache, all servers see it. Sticky sessions are the lazy fix — they work until the pinned server restarts or becomes unbalanced.","example":"k8s sessionAffinity: ClientIP gives sticky sessions; Redis gives a proper shared cache."},{"id":"cache-abstractions-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"When is `IMemoryCache` still appropriate?","answer":"Per-process, ephemeral caching — single-server dev environments, precomputed lookup tables inside one app instance, data that does not need to survive a restart.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"For values that only need to be visible within one process, IMemoryCache wins on latency (microseconds) and simplicity (no container, no serialization). The rule: cross-request-cross-server = distributed; within-process = memory.","example":"Parsing appsettings.json once on boot and reusing the parsed object — IMemoryCache."},{"id":"cache-abstractions-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Does `IMemoryCache` data survive an app restart? {{No}}. Does Redis-backed `IDistributedCache` survive? {{Yes}} (when Redis has AOF or RDB persistence enabled).","answer":"No; Yes","bloom":"remember","explanation":"IMemoryCache is RAM inside the app process — the restart wipes it. Redis runs as a separate process/container with configurable persistence, so it can survive app restarts and redeployments.","example":"A pod redeployment wipes IMemoryCache; the Redis container keeps serving entries across the swap."},{"id":"cache-abstractions-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Which one-liner registers an in-memory cache in `Program.cs`?","answer":"`builder.Services.AddMemoryCache();`","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`AddMemoryCache` wires `IMemoryCache` into DI. No options required for a basic setup.","example":"builder.Services.AddMemoryCache();"},{"id":"cache-abstractions-card-07","type":"name","prompt":"Which one-liner registers a Redis-backed distributed cache in `Program.cs`?","answer":"`builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(opts =\u003e opts.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\");`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The helper reads from `Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis` and registers `IDistributedCache`. Any service can then inject `IDistributedCache`.","example":"builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(o =\u003e o.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\");"}]},{"id":"cache-expiration","name":"Cache expiration — Absolute, Sliding, Priority","tags":["cache","ttl","expiration"],"source":"notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §2, §4","prose":"`MemoryCacheEntryOptions` exposes `AbsoluteExpiration` (hard deadline), `SlidingExpiration` (idle timeout that resets on access), and `Priority` (eviction order under memory pressure). Combining absolute + sliding gives a capped-and-refreshing window.","cards":[{"id":"cache-expiration-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"`AbsoluteExpiration` is a {{hard}} deadline; `SlidingExpiration` resets on each {{access}}.","answer":"hard; access","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Absolute kills the entry at a wall-clock moment regardless of traffic. Sliding keeps hot entries alive while aging out idle ones.","example":"Absolute: expires at 10:00 AM. Sliding: expires 5 minutes after last read/write."},{"id":"cache-expiration-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"When `AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = 50s` and `SlidingExpiration = 20s` are BOTH set and the entry is accessed at t=15s, when does it expire?","answer":"At t=50s, because Absolute is a hard ceiling that wins over the reset Sliding window.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Sliding resets the idle timer to run until t=35s when the access happens at t=15s. Absolute deadline at t=50s is still binding and farther out, so Absolute fires first. Without the access, the entry would have expired at t=20s from sliding.","example":"Access at 15s → sliding resets to 35s deadline → absolute 50s deadline fires first → entry dies at 50s."},{"id":"cache-expiration-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"`CacheItemPriority` controls {{eviction order}} under memory pressure — NOT the entry's expiration time.","answer":"eviction order","bloom":"understand","explanation":"A Low-priority entry with a 1-hour Absolute still lives 1 hour unless memory pressure forces eviction. A High-priority entry with a 30-second Absolute still expires at 30 seconds.","example":"Priority = Low does NOT mean 'expires sooner.' It means 'dropped first when the cache is over its size limit.'"},{"id":"cache-expiration-card-04","type":"cloze","prompt":"The four `CacheItemPriority` levels are `{{NeverRemove}}`, `{{High}}`, `{{Normal}}`, and `{{Low}}`.","answer":"NeverRemove; High; Normal; Low","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`NeverRemove` excludes an entry from automatic eviction (only explicit `Remove` or time-based expiration can free it). Use sparingly — it converts the cache into persistent state.","example":"_cache.Set(\"config\", cfg, new MemoryCacheEntryOptions { Priority = CacheItemPriority.NeverRemove });"},{"id":"cache-expiration-card-05","type":"name","prompt":"Which `MemoryCacheEntryOptions` setting is best for session-like data that should time out when the user goes idle?","answer":"`SlidingExpiration`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Sliding resets on each access, so active users stay in cache and idle ones age out. Pair with a loose Absolute ceiling if you want a hard refresh guarantee.","example":"new MemoryCacheEntryOptions { SlidingExpiration = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(15) };"},{"id":"cache-expiration-card-06","type":"cloze","prompt":"On `IDistributedCache`, the options type is `{{DistributedCacheEntryOptions}}` and you use the fluent setters `{{SetAbsoluteExpiration}}` and `{{SetSlidingExpiration}}`.","answer":"DistributedCacheEntryOptions; SetAbsoluteExpiration; SetSlidingExpiration","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The shape differs between IMemoryCache (property-bag) and IDistributedCache (fluent). Semantics are identical — absolute is a hard deadline; sliding resets on access.","example":"new DistributedCacheEntryOptions().SetAbsoluteExpiration(TimeSpan.FromHours(1)).SetSlidingExpiration(TimeSpan.FromMinutes(30));"}]},{"id":"cache-aside-pattern","name":"Cache-aside pattern","tags":["cache","pattern","getorset","invalidation"],"source":"notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; notes/redis_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §3","prose":"Cache-aside: check cache, on miss fetch from source, store result, return. `GetOrCreateAsync` on `IMemoryCache` and `GetOrSetAsync\u003cT\u003e` extension on `IDistributedCache` give a one-line form. Writers must invalidate affected keys via `Remove(key)`.","cards":[{"id":"cache-aside-pattern-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The three steps of cache-aside are: (1) {{look up}} in the cache, (2) on {{hit}} return cached, (3) on {{miss}} fetch, store, return.","answer":"look up; hit; miss","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The same sequence at every call site: check, hit/miss branch, store-and-return on miss. Wrappers like GetOrCreateAsync collapse this into one call.","example":"if (!cache.TryGetValue(k, out v)) { v = fetch(); cache.Set(k, v, opts); } return v;"},{"id":"cache-aside-pattern-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which single `IMemoryCache` method checks the cache, runs a factory on miss, stores the result, and returns it?","answer":"`GetOrCreateAsync` (or `GetOrCreate` for synchronous factories).","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The factory runs only on cache miss. This is the idiomatic .NET helper — prefer it over hand-rolled TryGetValue + Set pairs for readability.","example":"var p = await cache.GetOrCreateAsync(\"key\", entry =\u003e { entry.AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5); return FetchAsync(); });"},{"id":"cache-aside-pattern-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"`IDistributedCache` works in raw {{byte arrays}}, so consumers typically wrap it with extension methods that serialize to {{JSON}}.","answer":"byte arrays; JSON","bloom":"understand","explanation":"The interface has Get/Set on byte[]. A JSON extension (SetAsync\u003cT\u003e, TryGetValue\u003cT\u003e, GetOrSetAsync\u003cT\u003e) hides serialization and matches the IMemoryCache ergonomics.","example":"bytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(JsonSerializer.Serialize(value));"},{"id":"cache-aside-pattern-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"After an `AddGame` write to the DB, what must you call on the cache to prevent stale reads?","answer":"`_cache.Remove(key)` for every affected cached key.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Cache-aside doesn't know when the source changes. The writer is responsible for invalidating affected keys after SaveChangesAsync — otherwise reads serve stale data until the TTL fires.","example":"await _db.SaveChangesAsync(); _cache.Remove(\"games\"); _cache.Remove($\"games:country:{game.Country}\");"},{"id":"cache-aside-pattern-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"`TryGetValue\u003cT\u003e` takes an `{{out}}` parameter: `if (cache.TryGetValue\u003cProduct\u003e(\"key\", out var product)) { ... }`.","answer":"out","bloom":"apply","explanation":"TryGetValue returns bool; the value is set via the out parameter. `if (cache.TryGetValue(\"key\", product))` is wrong — the compiler requires `out var`.","example":"if (cache.TryGetValue\u003cProduct\u003e(\"key\", out var product)) return product!;"},{"id":"cache-aside-pattern-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Why does JSON-round-tripping through `IDistributedCache` lose polymorphic type information by default?","answer":"System.Text.Json omits the runtime type — deserializing to a base type strips derived-type properties.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"A List\u003cDog\u003e : Animal cached as JSON and read back as List\u003cAnimal\u003e keeps only Animal properties. Fix: cache the concrete type, use a discriminator property, or enable TypeInfoResolver settings.","example":"Cache: new List\u003cDog\u003e{...} → JSON → read as List\u003cAnimal\u003e → breeds lost. Fix: keep the concrete type explicit in the cache signature."},{"id":"cache-aside-pattern-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"The helper `GetOrSetAsync\u003cT\u003e` defaults, in the course's example, to `{{SetAbsoluteExpiration(TimeSpan.FromHours(1))}}` combined with `{{SetSlidingExpiration(TimeSpan.FromMinutes(30))}}`.","answer":"SetAbsoluteExpiration(TimeSpan.FromHours(1)); SetSlidingExpiration(TimeSpan.FromMinutes(30))","bloom":"remember","explanation":"A 1-hour hard ceiling with a 30-minute idle window — sensible defaults for most read-heavy data. Override with your own `DistributedCacheEntryOptions` when finer control is needed.","example":"opts ??= new DistributedCacheEntryOptions().SetAbsoluteExpiration(TimeSpan.FromHours(1)).SetSlidingExpiration(TimeSpan.FromMinutes(30));"}]},{"id":"redis-configuration","name":"Redis configuration — Docker, StackExchange.Redis","tags":["redis","docker","stackexchange-redis"],"source":"slides/redis.pptx; notes/redis_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §6","prose":"Start Redis with `docker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis`. Wire it to ASP.NET Core with `builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(opts =\u003e opts.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\")` after adding the `Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis` NuGet package.","cards":[{"id":"redis-configuration-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Redis's default port is {{6379}}. The conventional Docker invocation is `docker run --name redis -d -p {{6379}}:{{6379}} redis`.","answer":"6379; 6379; 6379","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Every Redis example in the course assumes 6379. `-d` runs detached; `-p host:container` maps the port; `redis` is the official Docker Hub image.","example":"docker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis"},{"id":"redis-configuration-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which NuGet package provides the `AddStackExchangeRedisCache` extension?","answer":"`Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis`","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Without this package, the extension method doesn't compile. `StackExchange.Redis` is the underlying client library; the `Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.*` package wraps it for `IDistributedCache`.","example":"dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis"},{"id":"redis-configuration-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"In the Redis CLI, `{{SETEX}} destination 10 \"Tokyo\"` sets the key with a {{10-second}} expiration.","answer":"SETEX; 10-second","bloom":"remember","explanation":"SETEX = SET + EXpiration (seconds). Sub-second precision needs PSETEX, which takes milliseconds.","example":"SETEX greeting 60 \"hello for a minute\""},{"id":"redis-configuration-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What does `AbortOnConnectFail = true` do when Redis is unreachable at startup?","answer":"It causes the app to fail fast at startup instead of silently running with a no-op cache.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"In production you want the orchestrator to notice and restart the pod. `false` (the default) silently retries in the background — fine for dev, hazardous for prod.","example":"new StackExchange.Redis.ConfigurationOptions { AbortOnConnectFail = true, EndPoints = { \"localhost:6379\" } };"},{"id":"redis-configuration-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Under .NET Aspire, you skip the connection string and use `builder.{{AddRedisDistributedCache}}(\"cache\")` in the service's `Program.cs`; AppHost declares the resource with `builder.{{AddRedis}}(\"cache\")`.","answer":"AddRedisDistributedCache; AddRedis","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Aspire registers the Redis container resource and injects the connection string via environment variables. The typed helper reads the injected string automatically — no `opts.Configuration` literal needed.","example":"AppHost: var cache = builder.AddRedis(\"cache\"); api.WithReference(cache);\nApi: builder.AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\");"},{"id":"redis-configuration-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Name five Redis data structures.","answer":"String, Hash, List, Set, Sorted Set.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Recognition-level only — `IDistributedCache` just does byte-keyed `Get`/`Set`, which maps to the String type. The other types appear in Redis CLI usage and Redis-native C# clients.","example":"SET user:1 \"Alice\"  | HSET user:1 name Alice age 30  |  LPUSH feed p1 p2  |  SADD tags x y  |  ZADD board 100 alice"}]},{"id":"cache-tag-helper","name":"Cache Tag Helper","tags":["cache","razor","tag-helper"],"source":"notes/Cache_Tag_Helper_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §5","prose":"`\u003ccache\u003e` is the built-in Razor Tag Helper for fragment caching. Attributes `expires-after`, `expires-on`, `expires-sliding` control TTL; `vary-by-user`, `vary-by-route`, `vary-by-query`, `vary-by-cookie`, `vary-by-header`, `vary-by` create per-dimension cache keys. Backs onto `IMemoryCache`, so the web-farm problem applies.","cards":[{"id":"cache-tag-helper-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"`\u003ccache expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)\"\u003e…\u003c/cache\u003e` caches the enclosed fragment for {{10}} minutes as an {{absolute}} TTL.","answer":"10; absolute","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`expires-after` is absolute-from-now. Use `expires-sliding` for a reset-on-access window, `expires-on` for a specific wall-clock deadline.","example":"\u003ccache expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)\"\u003e\u003cp\u003e@DateTime.Now\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/cache\u003e"},{"id":"cache-tag-helper-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which `vary-by-*` attribute gives each logged-in user their own cached fragment?","answer":"`vary-by-user=\"true\"`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Without vary-by-user, the first visitor's personalized content leaks to every subsequent viewer until the TTL fires. `vary-by-user` keys the cache by authenticated identity.","example":"\u003ccache vary-by-user=\"true\"\u003e\u003cp\u003eHello, @User.Identity?.Name\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/cache\u003e"},{"id":"cache-tag-helper-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"`\u003ccache\u003e` uses `{{IMemoryCache}}` under the hood, so it has the same {{web-farm}} problem as raw in-memory caching.","answer":"IMemoryCache; web-farm","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"Each server caches its own rendered HTML. Users routed round-robin across servers see diverging cached content. Workarounds: sticky sessions, short TTLs, or output caching middleware / CDN.","example":"Three pods → three separate \u003ccache\u003e fragments → same URL, three different HTML outputs depending on routing."},{"id":"cache-tag-helper-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"List three `vary-by-*` attributes beyond `vary-by-user`.","answer":"`vary-by-route`, `vary-by-query`, `vary-by-cookie`, `vary-by-header` (any three).","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Each varies the cache key by a different request dimension. Combine freely — e.g. `vary-by-user + vary-by-route` produces one fragment per (user, route).","example":"\u003ccache vary-by-user=\"true\" vary-by-route=\"id\" expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5)\"\u003e...\u003c/cache\u003e"},{"id":"cache-tag-helper-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"To disable a `\u003ccache\u003e` block without deleting the markup, set `{{enabled}}=\"false\"` on the element.","answer":"enabled","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The `enabled` attribute short-circuits the caching behavior — the fragment re-renders on every request. Useful for toggling caching behind a feature flag.","example":"\u003ccache enabled=\"@cachingEnabled\" expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5)\"\u003e…\u003c/cache\u003e"},{"id":"cache-tag-helper-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"You want to cache a product detail view per user AND per product id, with a 10-minute absolute ceiling and a 2-minute sliding window. Write the tag.","answer":"`\u003ccache vary-by-user=\"true\" vary-by-route=\"id\" expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)\" expires-sliding=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2)\"\u003e…\u003c/cache\u003e`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Combine vary-by dimensions and both expiration modes on one tag. Sliding keeps hot fragments alive; absolute guarantees a refresh within the ceiling.","example":"Same as answer."}]},{"id":"taghelper-authoring","name":"Tag Helper authoring","tags":["tag-helper","razor","asp-net-core"],"source":"notes/TagHelpers_SCRIPT.docx; research-taghelpers-blazor.md","prose":"A custom Tag Helper inherits from `TagHelper`, is decorated with `[HtmlTargetElement(\"tag-name\")]`, and overrides `ProcessAsync(context, output)` (or `Process` for sync bodies). PascalCase C# properties bind to kebab-case HTML attributes.","cards":[{"id":"taghelper-authoring-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"A custom Tag Helper inherits from the `{{TagHelper}}` base class and is decorated with `[{{HtmlTargetElement}}(\"tag-name\")]`.","answer":"TagHelper; HtmlTargetElement","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Both pieces are non-optional. Without the base class, the framework won't recognize the type. Without the attribute, Razor has no tag binding.","example":"[HtmlTargetElement(\"toon\")] public class ToonTagHelper : TagHelper { … }"},{"id":"taghelper-authoring-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which override do you use when the Tag Helper body performs async I/O?","answer":"`ProcessAsync(TagHelperContext, TagHelperOutput)`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Overriding `Process` and calling `.Result` or `Task.Run` blocks the render thread and can deadlock. `ProcessAsync` lets the framework await without blocking.","example":"public override async Task ProcessAsync(TagHelperContext context, TagHelperOutput output) { var data = await FetchAsync(); … }"},{"id":"taghelper-authoring-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"A C# property named `{{FontFamily}}` binds to the HTML attribute `{{font-family}}` — PascalCase → kebab-case is the Razor convention.","answer":"FontFamily; font-family","bloom":"understand","explanation":"The mapping is automatic, not configurable. `ForegroundColor` becomes `foreground-color`; `DataTestId` becomes `data-test-id`. Never use underscores in the HTML attribute.","example":"public string? FontFamily { get; set; }  →  \u003ctoon font-family=\"arial\"\u003e"},{"id":"taghelper-authoring-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"Which `TagHelperOutput` call replaces the rendered tag's name?","answer":"`output.TagName = \"div\"` (set to `null` to suppress the element entirely).","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`TagName` is the rendered-element name. Setting `null` renders only the inner content without wrapping tag — useful for conditional wrappers.","example":"output.TagName = \"span\";  // \u003cmy-tag\u003e → \u003cspan\u003e"},{"id":"taghelper-authoring-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"`output.Content.{{SetHtmlContent}}(\"\u003cp\u003eHi\u003c/p\u003e\")` replaces the inner content, while `output.Content.{{AppendHtmlContent}}(\"\u003cp\u003eMore\u003c/p\u003e\")` preserves the existing inner content.","answer":"SetHtmlContent; AppendHtmlContent","bloom":"apply","explanation":"SetHtmlContent wipes what the page author wrote between the open and close tags. AppendHtmlContent keeps it and adds after.","example":"output.Content.AppendHtmlContent(\"\u003cp\u003eFooter\u003c/p\u003e\");  // keeps original inner"},{"id":"taghelper-authoring-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"How do you bind a Tag Helper to an existing `\u003cdiv\u003e` only when a specific attribute is present?","answer":"`[HtmlTargetElement(\"div\", Attributes = \"toonie\")]`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The Attributes selector restricts binding to elements carrying the named attribute. You can stack multiple [HtmlTargetElement] attributes on one class to bind several patterns.","example":"[HtmlTargetElement(\"div\", Attributes = \"toonie\")] public class DivToonTagHelper : TagHelper { … }"},{"id":"taghelper-authoring-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"Use `output.{{SuppressOutput}}()` to render nothing at all from a Tag Helper — handy when a condition says the element should not appear.","answer":"SuppressOutput","bloom":"apply","explanation":"SuppressOutput removes both the wrapping tag and its content from the rendered HTML. A feature-flag helper often does this when the flag is off.","example":"if (!_flags.IsEnabled(Flag!)) output.SuppressOutput();"}]},{"id":"taghelper-output-registration","name":"Tag Helper output + _ViewImports registration","tags":["tag-helper","razor","view-imports"],"source":"notes/TagHelpers_SCRIPT.docx; research-taghelpers-blazor.md","prose":"Tag Helpers are registered globally in `_ViewImports.cshtml` via `@addTagHelper *, AssemblyName`. In the helper's `Process`/`ProcessAsync`, the `TagHelperOutput` exposes `TagName`, `Content`, `PreContent`, `PostContent`, `Attributes`, and `SuppressOutput`.","cards":[{"id":"taghelper-output-registration-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Tag Helpers are registered in `{{_ViewImports.cshtml}}` with the directive `@addTagHelper *, {{AssemblyName}}`.","answer":"_ViewImports.cshtml; AssemblyName","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The `*` glob imports every Tag Helper in the assembly. Swap `*` for a fully qualified type name when you want to register only one.","example":"@addTagHelper *, Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers\n@addTagHelper *, MyApp"},{"id":"taghelper-output-registration-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Where should you register a Tag Helper assembly — in each .cshtml file, or in `_ViewImports.cshtml`?","answer":"In `_ViewImports.cshtml`. Individual .cshtml files inherit the registrations.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Registration is hierarchical — `_ViewImports.cshtml` in a subdirectory adds to the registrations from ancestor directories. Per-page registration is not the convention.","example":"Pages/_ViewImports.cshtml registers once; Pages/Admin/Dashboard.cshtml inherits automatically."},{"id":"taghelper-output-registration-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"To scope a Tag Helper registration to pages under `Pages/Admin/` only, drop a `_ViewImports.cshtml` into `{{Pages/Admin/}}` with the `@addTagHelper` directive.","answer":"Pages/Admin/","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Sub-folder _ViewImports.cshtml files extend their parent. The admin page picks up both registrations; pages outside `Admin/` see only the root set.","example":"Pages/Admin/_ViewImports.cshtml: @addTagHelper *, MyApp.AdminHelpers"},{"id":"taghelper-output-registration-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"Which `TagHelperOutput` method renders nothing at all from a helper?","answer":"`output.SuppressOutput()`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Suppresses both the tag and its content. Use when a condition says the element should not appear (feature gate, empty model, etc.).","example":"if (!_flags.IsEnabled(Flag!)) output.SuppressOutput();"},{"id":"taghelper-output-registration-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Given `\u003cmytag\u003eexisting\u003c/mytag\u003e` plus `output.PreContent.SetHtmlContent(\"[pre]\"); output.Content.AppendHtmlContent(\"[appended]\");` the rendered inner block reads `{{[pre]existing[appended]}}`.","answer":"[pre]existing[appended]","bloom":"apply","explanation":"PreContent injects HTML at the start of the inner area. Content.AppendHtmlContent adds after existing content. PostContent goes at the end. PreElement / PostElement (not shown) inject OUTSIDE the tag.","example":"output.PreContent + output.Content + output.PostContent ordered inside the rendered element."},{"id":"taghelper-output-registration-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Which call removes an HTML attribute the page author wrote on the tag?","answer":"`output.Attributes.RemoveAll(\"attribute-name\")`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"RemoveAll strips every attribute matching the name (supports case-insensitive match). SetAttribute replaces; this one deletes.","example":"output.Attributes.RemoveAll(\"data-legacy\");"},{"id":"taghelper-output-registration-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"To disable a globally-registered Tag Helper in one Razor file, use the directive `@{{removeTagHelper}} \"FullType, AssemblyName\"`.","answer":"removeTagHelper","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Rarely used but handy when a third-party package adds helpers you want to opt out of for specific pages. Pair @addTagHelper with @removeTagHelper at different scopes.","example":"@removeTagHelper \"Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers.CacheTagHelper, Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers\""}]}]},{"id":"module-4-i18n-ui","name":"Internationalization & Modern UI","topics":[{"id":"localization-resources-cultures","name":"Localization resources + cultures","tags":["i18n","culture","resx"],"source":"notes/razor_pages_localization_SCRIPT.docx; research-localization.md §2","prose":"Resource files live at `Resources/\u003cfolder\u003e/\u003cClassName\u003e.\u003cculture\u003e.resx` — the subfolder mirrors the class's project location. `CurrentCulture` controls formatting; `CurrentUICulture` controls which .resx loads. Culture providers run QueryString → Cookie → Accept-Language, first match wins.","cards":[{"id":"localization-resources-cultures-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The French resource file for `Pages/Index.cshtml.cs` (class `IndexModel`) lives at `Resources/{{Pages}}/IndexModel.{{fr}}.resx`.","answer":"Pages; fr","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Directory structure under `Resources/` mirrors the class location. The filename is `\u003cClassName\u003e.\u003cculture\u003e.resx` — not `\u003cPageName\u003e` and not flat.","example":"Pages/Courses.cshtml.cs (class CoursesModel) → Resources/Pages/CoursesModel.fr.resx"},{"id":"localization-resources-cultures-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What is the difference between `Thread.CurrentCulture` and `Thread.CurrentUICulture`?","answer":"CurrentCulture controls date/number/currency formatting; CurrentUICulture controls which .resx file IStringLocalizer loads.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Setting only one produces a half-translated page — numbers in the right locale but strings in the wrong one, or vice versa. UseRequestLocalization sets both together.","example":"CurrentCulture=fr-FR → decimal '3,14'; CurrentUICulture=fr-FR → IndexModel.fr.resx selected."},{"id":"localization-resources-cultures-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"The three default culture providers run in this order: `{{QueryString}}` → `{{Cookie}}` → `{{AcceptLanguageHeader}}`. First match wins.","answer":"QueryString; Cookie; AcceptLanguageHeader","bloom":"remember","explanation":"QueryString beats cookie (useful for testing / deep links). Cookie beats header (persistent user selection overrides browser default). Order is configurable via options.RequestCultureProviders.","example":"?culture=fr in the URL overrides a stored cookie or a browser Accept-Language: en-US header."},{"id":"localization-resources-cultures-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"If a resource key has no match in any .resx file for the current culture, what does `IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e[\"Key\"]` return?","answer":"The key itself, as a string.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"The indexer returns a `LocalizedString` whose `Name` equals `Value` equals the key, with `ResourceNotFound = true`. This makes it easy to stub a site in English before any .resx files exist.","example":"_localizer[\"Welcome\"] where no .resx has \"Welcome\" → string \"Welcome\"."},{"id":"localization-resources-cultures-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Fallback chain: a request for `{{fr-CA}}` falls back to `{{fr}}`, which falls back to the un-suffixed default `.resx` if one exists.","answer":"fr-CA; fr","bloom":"understand","explanation":"ASP.NET Core walks the parent culture chain. Ship a generic `fr.resx` and you can omit region-specific `.fr-CA.resx` unless you actually need Canadian-specific translations.","example":"Resources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx alone covers both fr-CA and fr-FR users."},{"id":"localization-resources-cultures-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Which culture provider persists a user's language choice across sessions?","answer":"CookieRequestCultureProvider (reads the `.AspNetCore.Culture` cookie).","bloom":"apply","explanation":"QueryString doesn't persist; Accept-Language reflects browser settings but not in-app selection. Only a cookie survives a browser restart and identifies the returning user.","example":"Response.Cookies.Append(CookieRequestCultureProvider.DefaultCookieName, CookieRequestCultureProvider.MakeCookieValue(new RequestCulture(\"fr\")), new CookieOptions { Expires = ... });"}]},{"id":"localization-setup","name":"Localization setup — AddLocalization + UseRequestLocalization","tags":["i18n","middleware","program-cs"],"source":"notes/razor_pages_localization_SCRIPT.docx; research-localization.md §3","prose":"Register services with `AddLocalization(opts =\u003e opts.ResourcesPath = \"Resources\")`, declare supported cultures via `Configure\u003cRequestLocalizationOptions\u003e`, add `AddViewLocalization()` to the MVC/Razor builder, and — critically — call `app.UseRequestLocalization()` middleware.","cards":[{"id":"localization-setup-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The service registration for localization is `builder.Services.{{AddLocalization}}(opts =\u003e opts.ResourcesPath = \"{{Resources}}\")`.","answer":"AddLocalization; Resources","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`AddLocalization` registers IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e, IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e, and the factory. ResourcesPath points at the root folder where .resx files live.","example":"builder.Services.AddLocalization(opts =\u003e opts.ResourcesPath = \"Resources\");"},{"id":"localization-setup-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which middleware call applies the detected culture to each incoming request?","answer":"`app.UseRequestLocalization()`","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Without the middleware call, no culture provider ever runs, so CurrentCulture / CurrentUICulture stay at defaults. This is the #1 silent-failure cause for 'my app never translates anything.'","example":"app.UseRequestLocalization();   // must run early in the pipeline"},{"id":"localization-setup-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"Inside `RequestLocalizationOptions`, `{{SupportedCultures}}` controls the allowed `CurrentCulture` values (formatting); `{{SupportedUICultures}}` controls the allowed `CurrentUICulture` values (.resx selection).","answer":"SupportedCultures; SupportedUICultures","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Two separate lists because in theory an app could format dates as en-US while showing French UI. In practice, set both to the same list.","example":"opts.SupportedCultures = opts.SupportedUICultures = new[] { new CultureInfo(\"en\"), new CultureInfo(\"fr\") };"},{"id":"localization-setup-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What does `builder.Services.AddMvc().AddViewLocalization()` enable?","answer":"`IViewLocalizer` injection directly in `.cshtml` files via `@inject`.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"AddLocalization alone gives you IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e in code-behind. AddViewLocalization adds the view-scoped IViewLocalizer used by @inject in Razor markup.","example":"builder.Services.AddRazorPages().AddViewLocalization();   // @inject IViewLocalizer Localizer now works"},{"id":"localization-setup-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"`UseRequestLocalization` must run {{before}} any endpoint routing / handler in the pipeline — typically just after `CreateBuilder().Build()`.","answer":"before","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Middleware runs in registration order. Put UseRequestLocalization after UseRouting and endpoint handlers run with the default culture even when the user's preferred culture could have been detected.","example":"app.UseRequestLocalization(); app.UseStaticFiles(); app.UseRouting(); ..."},{"id":"localization-setup-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What's the single most likely missing line if services are registered but language never changes at runtime?","answer":"`app.UseRequestLocalization()` middleware call.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"Without the middleware, no request-culture provider executes. Every request uses DefaultRequestCulture. Adding the line at the top of the pipeline usually fixes it immediately.","example":"Add `app.UseRequestLocalization();` after `var app = builder.Build();`."}]},{"id":"localization-injection","name":"Localizer injection — IStringLocalizer, IHtmlLocalizer, IViewLocalizer","tags":["i18n","di"],"source":"notes/razor_pages_localization_SCRIPT.docx; research-localization.md §2, §5","prose":"`IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` for code-behind plain text; `IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` for code-behind HTML content that should NOT be encoded; `IViewLocalizer` for direct `.cshtml` use via `@inject`. Shared app-wide strings use a marker `SharedResource` class plus `IStringLocalizerFactory.Create`.","cards":[{"id":"localization-injection-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"In a Razor view (`.cshtml`), inject the view-scoped localizer with `@inject {{IViewLocalizer}} Localizer`.","answer":"IViewLocalizer","bloom":"remember","explanation":"IViewLocalizer picks up the resource file matching the view's generated class. IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e and IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e are for code-behind injection.","example":"@inject IViewLocalizer Localizer\n\u003ch1\u003e@Localizer[\"Welcome\"]\u003c/h1\u003e"},{"id":"localization-injection-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"When should you use `IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` instead of `IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e`?","answer":"When the translated string contains HTML markup that must render as HTML, not HTML-encoded text.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"IStringLocalizer returns a plain string that Razor HTML-encodes. IHtmlLocalizer returns IHtmlContent which Razor passes through verbatim. Use it for translations containing \u003ca\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003e, etc.","example":".resx value: \"Read \u003ca href=\\\"/docs\\\"\u003ethe docs\u003c/a\u003e\" → use IHtmlLocalizer so the anchor renders as a link."},{"id":"localization-injection-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"A PageModel localizes plain text by constructor-injecting `{{IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e}}` and accessing values via the indexer: `_localizer[\"{{Key}}\"]`.","answer":"IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e; Key","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The generic parameter drives both DI resolution and the resource-file name mapping. The indexer returns a LocalizedString that implicitly converts to string.","example":"public IndexModel(IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e localizer) =\u003e _localizer = localizer; ... ViewData[\"Msg\"] = _localizer[\"Welcome\"];"},{"id":"localization-injection-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"How do you implement app-wide shared strings used by many pages?","answer":"Create an empty marker class `SharedResource`, build a service using `IStringLocalizerFactory.Create(nameof(SharedResource), assemblyName)`, register it as a singleton, and inject where needed.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"This avoids duplicating the same translations across every per-class .resx. Pair with `Resources/SharedResource.\u003cculture\u003e.resx` files. DataAnnotations localization often targets this shared class too.","example":"builder.Services.AddSingleton\u003cSharedLocalizer\u003e(); ... @inject SharedLocalizer S ... @S.Get(\"CompanyName\")"},{"id":"localization-injection-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Localizers accept positional format arguments: `_localizer[\"{{GreetUser}}\", userName]` with a .resx value of `\"Hello, {0}!\"`.","answer":"GreetUser","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Positional args let translators reorder placeholders in languages with different word order. Prefer this over string concatenation which cannot express reorderings.","example":"_localizer[\"ItemsCount\", 3] with .resx \"{0} items\" → \"3 items\" (en) / \"3 articles\" (fr)"},{"id":"localization-injection-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What error do you get if you use `@inject IViewLocalizer` without calling `AddViewLocalization()` in Program.cs?","answer":"A runtime exception: 'No service for type IViewLocalizer has been registered.'","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"AddLocalization registers IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e and IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e; it does NOT register IViewLocalizer. The view-scoped localizer requires AddViewLocalization() on the MVC/Razor Pages builder.","example":"builder.Services.AddRazorPages().AddViewLocalization();   // enables IViewLocalizer"}]},{"id":"blazor-quickgrid","name":"Blazor QuickGrid","tags":["blazor","ui","quickgrid"],"source":"notes/BlazorServer_QuickGrid.docx; notes/BlazorWasm_QuickGrid.docx; Labs/W07 QuickGrid/; research-taghelpers-blazor.md","prose":"`\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"IQueryable\u003cT\u003e\" Pagination=\"PaginationState\"\u003e` plus `\u003cPropertyColumn\u003e` for simple bindings and `\u003cTemplateColumn\u003e` with `SortBy` for custom markup. Live filter via `\u003cinput @bind @bind:event=\"oninput\"\u003e` + computed IQueryable. Host page needs an interactive render mode.","cards":[{"id":"blazor-quickgrid-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"A `QuickGrid` binds to an `{{IQueryable\u003cT\u003e}}` via `Items=\"@...\"`, with paging controlled by a `{{PaginationState}}` declared in `@code`.","answer":"IQueryable\u003cT\u003e; PaginationState","bloom":"apply","explanation":"IQueryable lets EF Core translate filtering / paging to SQL. PaginationState's `ItemsPerPage` decides page size; a sibling `\u003cPaginator State=\"@state\"\u003e` component renders the controls.","example":"private PaginationState _p = new() { ItemsPerPage = 10 };"},{"id":"blazor-quickgrid-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"How do you make a `PropertyColumn` sortable?","answer":"Add the `Sortable=\"true\"` attribute.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"PropertyColumn already knows which property to sort by — setting Sortable=\"true\" is sufficient. TemplateColumn needs an explicit SortBy because it has no implicit sort key.","example":"\u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e"},{"id":"blazor-quickgrid-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"A `TemplateColumn` needs `{{SortBy}}` to be sortable; `Sortable=\"true\"` alone does nothing on a TemplateColumn.","answer":"SortBy","bloom":"apply","explanation":"TemplateColumn's render fragment might touch many properties, so QuickGrid can't infer a single sort key. SortBy takes a GridSort\u003cT\u003e you build fluently.","example":"\u003cTemplateColumn Title=\"Name\" SortBy=\"@GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e.ByAscending(s =\u003e s.LastName)\"\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e@context.FirstName @context.LastName\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/TemplateColumn\u003e"},{"id":"blazor-quickgrid-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"How do you build a multi-key sort expression for a `TemplateColumn`?","answer":"`GridSort\u003cT\u003e.ByAscending(x =\u003e x.First).ThenAscending(x =\u003e x.Second)` (or `.ThenDescending(...)`).","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Chain as many .ThenAscending / .ThenDescending calls as you need. Each one tie-breaks equal rows from the previous key.","example":"GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e.ByAscending(s =\u003e s.FirstName).ThenAscending(s =\u003e s.LastName);"},{"id":"blazor-quickgrid-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"For a live-filter input, use `@bind=\"_filter\" @bind:event=\"{{oninput}}\"` — not the default onchange — so the filter updates on every keystroke.","answer":"oninput","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The default @bind event is onchange, which fires only when the input loses focus. Users typing in a search box expect instant filtering — oninput fires per keystroke.","example":"\u003cinput @bind=\"_filter\" @bind:event=\"oninput\" /\u003e"},{"id":"blazor-quickgrid-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What render-mode directive must a page hosting a QuickGrid declare for sorting / paging / filtering to work?","answer":"`@rendermode InteractiveServer` (or `InteractiveWebAssembly` / `InteractiveAuto`).","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Static server rendering produces initial HTML but no client-side runtime. Interactive modes keep the component alive so clicks and input events trigger re-renders.","example":"@page \"/students\"\n@rendermode InteractiveServer"},{"id":"blazor-quickgrid-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"Calling `{{.ToList()}}` on your data source before binding to QuickGrid breaks server-side SQL translation — keep the expression as `IQueryable\u003cT\u003e` all the way to the grid.","answer":".ToList()","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"ToList() materializes the entire result set into memory, after which filtering / paging happens in .NET. For large tables this wrecks performance. Let the grid see an IQueryable and EF Core builds an efficient SQL query per page.","example":"// wrong: _students.Where(...).ToList()\n// right: _students.Where(...)"}]}]},{"id":"module-5-dotnet10-reporting","name":".NET 10 Scripts & Reporting","topics":[{"id":"file-based-app-basics","name":"File-based .NET apps — basics","tags":["dotnet-10","scripting","file-based"],"source":"slides/file-based-apps.pptx; notes/file-based-apps.docx; research-file-based.md","prose":".NET 10 lets you run a single `.cs` file with `dotnet run file.cs` — no `.csproj`, no `bin/`, no `obj/`. Top-level statements replace `Main`. Implicit usings include System, System.Linq, System.Collections.Generic, System.Text, System.Threading.Tasks.","cards":[{"id":"file-based-app-basics-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"A .NET 10 file-based app runs with `{{dotnet run}} filename.cs` — no `.csproj`, no `bin/`, no `obj/` directory.","answer":"dotnet run","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The CLI detects the .cs argument, creates an implicit project context, compiles in memory, and caches artifacts under `~/.dotnet/runfile/`.","example":"dotnet run greet.cs"},{"id":"file-based-app-basics-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"To pass command-line args to a file-based script, what separator must you use?","answer":"`--` (double-dash). Everything after it becomes `args` inside the script.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Without `--`, the CLI interprets trailing tokens as its own flags. `dotnet run greet.cs Kevin` gives you nothing; `dotnet run greet.cs -- Kevin` makes `args[0] == \"Kevin\"`.","example":"dotnet run greet.cs -- Kevin   // args[0] == \"Kevin\""},{"id":"file-based-app-basics-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"File-based apps use {{top-level statements}}, so no `Program` class or `Main` method is needed; the file body executes as if it were inside `Main`.","answer":"top-level statements","bloom":"understand","explanation":"C# 9+ top-level statements let you write `Console.WriteLine(\"Hi\");` as the first line of a file. File-based apps rely on this feature exclusively.","example":"// greet.cs\\nConsole.WriteLine(\"Hello!\");"},{"id":"file-based-app-basics-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"List three of the namespaces automatically imported in a file-based app.","answer":"System, System.Collections.Generic, System.Linq (also System.Text and System.Threading.Tasks).","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Implicit usings cover the most common BCL namespaces so short scripts don't need `using` directives. Others still require explicit `using`.","example":"No `using System.Linq;` needed: arr.Where(x =\u003e x \u003e 0) just works."},{"id":"file-based-app-basics-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Compiled file-based-app binaries are cached under `~/.dotnet/{{runfile}}/` on macOS/Linux and `%USERPROFILE%\\.dotnet\\{{runfile}}\\` on Windows, keyed by filename + content hash.","answer":"runfile; runfile","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The cache makes subsequent runs fast. Edit the .cs file and a new hash triggers a fresh compile; other files stay cached.","example":"~/.dotnet/runfile/greet-3faf7380.../bin/debug/greet.dll"},{"id":"file-based-app-basics-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Which command converts a file-based app into a traditional .NET project with a .csproj?","answer":"`dotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Use when the single-file form outgrows its use case (multi-file, tests, deployment). The command preserves `#:` directives as the equivalent MSBuild settings.","example":"dotnet project convert api.cs -o ApiProject"},{"id":"file-based-app-basics-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"File-based apps require .NET version {{10}} or higher; earlier SDKs either error or require a separate shim.","answer":"10","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The `dotnet run file.cs` flow was finalized in .NET 10. On .NET 8/9 the command fails; verify with `dotnet --version` if a script mysteriously refuses to run.","example":"dotnet --version   // should report 10.x.x or later"}]},{"id":"file-based-app-directives","name":"File-based app #: directives","tags":["dotnet-10","scripting","directives"],"source":"notes/file-based-apps.docx; research-file-based.md §2.4","prose":"Four directives put build metadata into a file-based `.cs` — `#:package` for NuGet, `#:property` for MSBuild properties, `#:sdk` for SDK selection, `#:project` for project references. No space after the colon.","cards":[{"id":"file-based-app-directives-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The NuGet-package directive is `#:{{package}} PackageName@Version` — note: no space after the {{colon}}.","answer":"package; colon","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1` is legal; `#: package Spectre.Console@0.49.1` is not. The spaced form is a classic exam distractor.","example":"#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1"},{"id":"file-based-app-directives-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which directive switches the file's SDK to support ASP.NET Core minimal APIs?","answer":"`#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The default SDK (`Microsoft.NET.Sdk`) is console-only. `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` adds `WebApplication`, routing, middleware, etc.","example":"#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\\nvar app = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build();"},{"id":"file-based-app-directives-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"To set an MSBuild property like the target framework, use `#:{{property}} TargetFramework={{net10.0}}`.","answer":"property; net10.0","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Stack multiple #:property directives for more settings (LangVersion, Nullable, etc.). The `=` has no spaces around it.","example":"#:property TargetFramework=net10.0\\n#:property Nullable=enable"},{"id":"file-based-app-directives-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"How do you reference a local .csproj from a file-based .cs?","answer":"`#:project ./Relative/Path/Lib.csproj`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The path is resolved relative to the file-based .cs's location. Useful when a one-off script consumes types from a shared library.","example":"#:project ./MyLibrary/MyLibrary.csproj\\nusing MyLibrary;\\nvar p = new Person();"},{"id":"file-based-app-directives-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"The four `#:` directives are: `#:{{package}}`, `#:{{property}}`, `#:{{sdk}}`, and `#:{{project}}`. Each has NO space after the colon.","answer":"package; property; sdk; project","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Each directive targets one build-configuration concern. Stack as many as needed; each must sit on its own line.","example":"#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\\n#:package Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@10.0.0\\n#:property Nullable=enable"},{"id":"file-based-app-directives-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Is `#: sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` (with a space after the colon) valid?","answer":"No. Directive names sit flush against `#:` with no whitespace between.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"The spaced form is the most common distractor in exams because it reads naturally. Always proofread for the zero-space rule.","example":"#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web   (correct)\\n#: sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web  (invalid)"}]},{"id":"file-based-app-web","name":"File-based web apps — #:sdk + minimal API","tags":["dotnet-10","scripting","web","minimal-api"],"source":"notes/file-based-apps.docx; research-file-based.md","prose":"`#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` switches a file-based app from console mode to ASP.NET Core. `WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build()` plus `app.MapGet/Post/Put/Delete` gives a complete minimal-API web server in one file.","cards":[{"id":"file-based-app-web-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"To write a file-based web API, the first line is `#:sdk {{Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web}}` — without it, `WebApplication` is not resolvable.","answer":"Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The default file-based SDK is console-only. Switching to the Web SDK pulls in ASP.NET Core's implicit references so minimal-API types are available.","example":"#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\\nvar app = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build();\\napp.MapGet(\"/\", () =\u003e \"Hi\");\\napp.Run();"},{"id":"file-based-app-web-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What runtime type does `WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build()` return?","answer":"`WebApplication` — which you then use to call `MapGet`, `MapPost`, etc., and `Run()`.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`WebApplication` is the minimal-API host. It replaces the historical `IHost` + `IApplicationBuilder` split with a single object exposing routing + lifecycle methods.","example":"var app = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build();"},{"id":"file-based-app-web-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"A GET endpoint mapping in a file-based web app reads `app.{{MapGet}}(\"/route\", () =\u003e result)`.","answer":"MapGet","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Map methods take a route template and a handler delegate. Delegates can be lambdas, method references, or typed handlers with DI via parameter injection.","example":"app.MapGet(\"/widgets\", (AppDb db) =\u003e db.Widgets.ToList());"},{"id":"file-based-app-web-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"How do you include an additional NuGet package in a file-based web app?","answer":"Add a `#:package PackageName@Version` directive at the top of the file.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Directives stack: the SDK swap plus any number of package directives, all at the file's top. Each on its own line.","example":"#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\\n#:package Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@10.0.0"},{"id":"file-based-app-web-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"The error `The name 'WebApplication' does not exist in the current context` on a file-based `.cs` almost always means the `{{#:sdk}}` directive is missing.","answer":"#:sdk","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"WebApplication lives in ASP.NET Core types that the default console SDK does not reference. Adding `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` fixes the resolution.","example":"Add `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` as the first line of the file."},{"id":"file-based-app-web-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"When should you convert a file-based web app to a proper .NET project?","answer":"When you need multiple files, test projects, complex deployment, or CI pipelines that expect a .csproj.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Single-file form is great for demos and one-off utilities. Anything requiring structure graduates via `dotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder`.","example":"dotnet project convert api.cs -o ApiProject"}]},{"id":"excel-export","name":"Excel export with ClosedXML","tags":["excel","closedxml","report"],"source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/; research-excel-pdf-chart.md §3","prose":"Create `XLWorkbook`, add a worksheet, write cells with 1-based indexing, save to a `MemoryStream`, return a `FileResult` with MIME type `application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet`.","cards":[{"id":"excel-export-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"ClosedXML cell indexing is {{1-based}}: `sheet.Cell(1, 1)` is the top-left cell (A1), not `Cell(0, 0)`.","answer":"1-based","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The 1-based convention matches Excel's UI (row 1, column A = A1). Mixing it with C# arrays causes off-by-one bugs, especially when data loops start at row 2 (header in row 1).","example":"sheet.Cell(1, 1).Value = \"Name\"; sheet.Cell(2, 1).Value = \"Alice\";"},{"id":"excel-export-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"What MIME type identifies an .xlsx file download?","answer":"`application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet`","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Long but precise — this is the OpenXML spreadsheet MIME. `application/excel` and `application/vnd.ms-excel` refer to older or incorrect formats.","example":"return File(bytes, \"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet\", \"Report.xlsx\");"},{"id":"excel-export-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"In ClosedXML, save the workbook to a `{{MemoryStream}}` with `workbook.SaveAs(stream)`, then call `stream.{{ToArray}}()` to get bytes for `File(...)`.","answer":"MemoryStream; ToArray","bloom":"apply","explanation":"The byte array form works with `File(byte[], mime, name)` which returns `FileContentResult`. For very large exports, return `FileStreamResult` and remember to rewind the stream — but `ToArray` is simpler for typical report sizes.","example":"using var ms = new MemoryStream(); workbook.SaveAs(ms); return File(ms.ToArray(), mime, name);"},{"id":"excel-export-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"How do you style all cells in a header range (rows 1, columns 1-3) with a background fill?","answer":"`sheet.Range(sheet.Cell(1,1).Address, sheet.Cell(1,3).Address).Style.Fill.SetBackgroundColor(XLColor.Almond);`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"IXLRange applies styles to all cells in the rectangular region. Single-cell styling works via `.Style` directly on `Cell(r, c)`.","example":"sheet.Range(sheet.Cell(1,1).Address, sheet.Cell(1,3).Address).Style.Font.Bold = true;"},{"id":"excel-export-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"After populating data, call `sheet.Columns().{{AdjustToContents}}()` to auto-fit every column's width before saving.","answer":"AdjustToContents","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Without autofit, users open your export and see all columns at the default ~8-character width. Call it once after all cells are written.","example":"sheet.Columns().AdjustToContents();  // before workbook.SaveAs(stream)"},{"id":"excel-export-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What ASP.NET Core return type does an Excel-export handler typically produce?","answer":"`FileResult` — specifically constructed via `File(bytes, mime, filename)`.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"`File(...)` is a controller/PageModel helper that creates a `FileContentResult` (or `FileStreamResult` when streaming). Both inherit from `FileResult`.","example":"public FileResult OnGet() =\u003e File(bytes, mime, \"Report.xlsx\");"}]},{"id":"pdf-export","name":"PDF export with iText 7","tags":["pdf","itext7","report"],"source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/; research-excel-pdf-chart.md §3","prose":"iText 7 plus `itext.bouncy-castle-adapter` are both required. Pipeline: `MemoryStream` → `PdfWriter` → `PdfDocument` → `Document`. Call `writer.SetCloseStream(false)` to keep the stream open for `FileStreamResult`, and reset `ms.Position = 0` before returning.","cards":[{"id":"pdf-export-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"iText 7 requires two NuGet packages: `{{itext7}}` and `{{itext.bouncy-castle-adapter}}` — the adapter is a runtime crypto dependency, not optional.","answer":"itext7; itext.bouncy-castle-adapter","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Installing just itext7 compiles fine but crashes at runtime when iText attempts hashing or signing. Add both packages together to avoid the late failure.","example":"\u003cPackageReference Include=\"itext7\" Version=\"9.6.0\" /\u003e\\n\u003cPackageReference Include=\"itext.bouncy-castle-adapter\" Version=\"9.6.0\" /\u003e"},{"id":"pdf-export-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Order the four iText 7 types you construct top-to-bottom in a PDF pipeline.","answer":"MemoryStream → PdfWriter(stream) → PdfDocument(writer) → Document(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false)","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Each layer wraps the previous. MemoryStream is the byte sink; PdfWriter writes PDF-shaped bytes; PdfDocument owns PDF file structure (pages, xref); Document is the layout engine that accepts Paragraphs and Tables.","example":"var ms = new MemoryStream(); var writer = new PdfWriter(ms); var pdfDoc = new PdfDocument(writer); var doc = new Document(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false);"},{"id":"pdf-export-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"Call `writer.{{SetCloseStream}}(false)` so `document.Close()` does NOT close the underlying `MemoryStream` — you still need to read from it when returning the response.","answer":"SetCloseStream","bloom":"apply","explanation":"By default, closing the Document cascades and closes the writer + stream. Flipping the flag keeps the MemoryStream open for `FileStreamResult`. An alternative is returning `File(ms.ToArray(), ...)` which materializes bytes and doesn't care about the stream state.","example":"writer.SetCloseStream(false);"},{"id":"pdf-export-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"What line do you need before returning a `FileStreamResult` wrapping your PDF `MemoryStream`?","answer":"`ms.Position = 0;`","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"After writing, the MemoryStream's position is at the end. FileStreamResult reads from current position, finds nothing, and serves an empty file. Rewinding to 0 fixes this.","example":"document.Close(); ms.Position = 0; return new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\");"},{"id":"pdf-export-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"In iText, page numbering is added AFTER layout by looping over `pdfDoc.{{GetNumberOfPages}}()` and calling `document.ShowTextAligned(...)` per page.","answer":"GetNumberOfPages","bloom":"apply","explanation":"You can't know the total page count until content is laid out. Loop from 1 to GetNumberOfPages() and add a page-N-of-total paragraph to each page.","example":"for (int i = 1; i \u003c= pdfDoc.GetNumberOfPages(); i++) document.ShowTextAligned(new Paragraph($\"Page {i} of {pdfDoc.GetNumberOfPages()}\"), 559, 806, i, TextAlignment.RIGHT, VerticalAlignment.TOP, 0);"},{"id":"pdf-export-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Which MIME type identifies a PDF download?","answer":"`application/pdf`","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Standard MIME — browsers recognize it and either render in a built-in viewer or save to disk. `FileStreamResult` takes it as a constructor argument.","example":"return new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\") { FileDownloadName = \"Report.pdf\" };"},{"id":"pdf-export-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"A simpler alternative to `FileStreamResult` + `ms.Position = 0` is `return {{File}}(ms.ToArray(), \"application/pdf\", \"name.pdf\")` — the `ToArray()` is position-insensitive.","answer":"File","bloom":"apply","explanation":"File(byte[], mime, name) materializes the bytes, bypassing the stream-position trap. Trade-off: materializing into memory uses more RAM for large PDFs.","example":"return File(ms.ToArray(), \"application/pdf\", \"Report.pdf\");"}]},{"id":"chart-rendering","name":"Chart.js in Razor — CDN + Razor data injection","tags":["chart","chart-js","razor"],"source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/; research-excel-pdf-chart.md §3","prose":"Chart.js is a client-side library loaded from a CDN. A Razor page exposes a `\u003ccanvas\u003e` element, builds JS data arrays by `@:` directives in a `\u003cscript\u003e` block, and calls `new Chart(ctx, { type, data })` to render.","cards":[{"id":"chart-rendering-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"Chart.js renders on a `\u003c{{canvas}}\u003e` element identified by `id`. In the script, grab it via `document.getElementById('pie-chart')` and pass it to `new Chart(ctx, config)`.","answer":"canvas","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Chart.js draws 2D graphics using the canvas's 2D context. The canvas has to be in the DOM when the script runs, so typically the \u003cscript\u003e block appears after the canvas element.","example":"\u003ccanvas id=\"pie-chart\" width=\"400\" height=\"400\"\u003e\u003c/canvas\u003e"},{"id":"chart-rendering-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"Which Razor directive injects a JavaScript line per loop iteration inside a `\u003cscript\u003e` block?","answer":"`@:` (at-colon) at the start of each JS line.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"`@:` tells Razor \"treat this line as mixed content with @-expression substitutions.\" Without it, Razor may misparse the JS or produce malformed output.","example":"@foreach (var x in Model.Data) { @:labels.push('@x.Name'); }"},{"id":"chart-rendering-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"The Chart.js constructor takes two arguments: `new Chart({{ctx}}, {{config}})` — the canvas element (or its 2D context) and a config object with `type`, `data`, and optional `options`.","answer":"ctx; config","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Config.type picks the chart shape ('pie', 'bar', 'line', 'doughnut', etc.). Config.data has labels and datasets arrays. Options tune axes, legend, tooltips.","example":"new Chart(canvas, { type: 'pie', data: { labels, datasets: [{ data, backgroundColor }] } });"},{"id":"chart-rendering-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"How do you load Chart.js into a Razor page?","answer":"Add `\u003cscript src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js\"\u003e\u003c/script\u003e` to the page.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The library is distributed via CDN; no NuGet package is involved because the chart runs client-side. Pin a version (e.g. @3.9.1) so updates don't silently change behavior.","example":"\u003cscript src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js\"\u003e\u003c/script\u003e"},{"id":"chart-rendering-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"For a pie chart, the dataset's `{{backgroundColor}}` is an array of colors — one entry per slice.","answer":"backgroundColor","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Unlike bar/line charts which typically use a single color across the dataset, pie slices want distinct colors. Pass an array aligned with the data array.","example":"datasets: [{ data: [10, 20, 30], backgroundColor: ['red', 'blue', 'green'] }]"},{"id":"chart-rendering-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"Can Chart.js render a chart at the server and include the PNG in a PDF export?","answer":"No. Chart.js runs only in the browser. Server-side chart rendering requires a different library (e.g. SkiaSharp, System.Drawing).","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"The chart lives in a browser \u003ccanvas\u003e. PDFs generated by iText 7 on the server cannot include a Chart.js-rendered image unless you first export the canvas from the browser (e.g. toDataURL) and POST it back to the server for embedding.","example":"Use SkiaSharp or ScottPlot for server-rendered images if you need charts embedded in PDFs."}]}]},{"id":"module-6-testing","name":"Testing Discipline","topics":[{"id":"tdd-cycle","name":"TDD cycle — Red, Green, Refactor + Three Laws","tags":["tdd","discipline"],"source":"slides/TDD_xunit.pptx; notes/TDD_xunit_SCRIPT.docx; research-tdd.md","prose":"TDD is a loop: write a failing test (Red), write the minimum code to make it pass (Green), then clean up without breaking the test (Refactor). Robert C. Martin's Three Laws enforce test-first discipline.","cards":[{"id":"tdd-cycle-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"The TDD cycle has three phases: `{{Red}}` (failing test), `{{Green}}` (minimum code to pass), `{{Refactor}}` (clean up without breaking the test).","answer":"Red; Green; Refactor","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Each phase has a single job. Skipping any phase defeats the purpose — no Red means you might be writing a tautological test; no Refactor means technical debt compounds.","example":"Red → Write Assert.Equal(4, calc.Add(2, 2));  // fails because Calculator doesn't exist\\nGreen → class Calculator { public int Add(int a, int b) =\u003e a + b; }\\nRefactor → rename, extract, simplify"},{"id":"tdd-cycle-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"State Robert C. Martin's First Law of TDD.","answer":"You are not allowed to write any production code unless it is to make a failing test pass.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The First Law defines the relationship: production code exists to satisfy failing tests. Writing code without a failing test in hand breaks the TDD discipline.","example":"Failing test on table → you may write production code. No failing test → you may not."},{"id":"tdd-cycle-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"During the {{Green}} phase, you write the {{minimum}} code necessary to make the failing test pass — not more, not less.","answer":"Green; minimum","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Resisting the urge to add 'just in case' logic is the hardest discipline. Extra code has no test backing it and accumulates as unverified complexity.","example":"Test expects Add(2, 2) → 4. Green code could be `return 4;` (passes the one test). Add more tests to force more general logic."},{"id":"tdd-cycle-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"Why is writing the test first (the Red phase) important — what does it prove that a test written after the code cannot?","answer":"It proves the test can fail when the feature is missing, confirming the test's assertion is valid and the test framework can detect the failure.","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"A test written after the code might be tautological — it may check something the code trivially satisfies without you knowing. Watching it fail first eliminates that false-confidence.","example":"If you watch the test fail, then see it pass after implementing, you've proved: (a) the test detects absence, (b) your code fixes it."},{"id":"tdd-cycle-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"In the Refactor phase, you clean up code while {{re-running tests}} after each change to ensure nothing breaks.","answer":"re-running tests","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Refactor happens under the safety net of green tests. Every structural change should leave all tests green. If a refactor breaks a test, undo and try a smaller step.","example":"Rename variable → run tests → still green → commit. Extract method → run tests → still green → commit."},{"id":"tdd-cycle-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"When is TDD a poor fit?","answer":"Exploratory spikes, UI prototyping, research code — situations where the goal is learning, not regression-proof production code.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Test-first requires you to know what the test should check; exploratory work is about discovering what you don't know. After the spike, rewrite production-worthy parts with TDD.","example":"Prototyping 'does ML.NET support this feature?' — write code first, test viable outputs later."},{"id":"tdd-cycle-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"Robert Martin's Third Law: you are not allowed to write any more production code than is sufficient to make the {{currently failing test}} pass.","answer":"currently failing test","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Keeps production code tied to test coverage. Adding logic beyond the current failing test introduces untested behavior — exactly what TDD exists to prevent.","example":"Test: Divide(10, 2) → 5. Green body: `return 5;` — not `return a / b;`. The next test (Divide(6, 2) → 3) forces generalization."}]},{"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions","name":"xUnit attributes, assertions, AAA","tags":["tdd","xunit","assert"],"source":"slides/TDD_xunit.pptx; notes/TDD_xunit_SCRIPT.docx; research-tdd.md","prose":"xUnit uses `[Fact]` for single-scenario tests and `[Theory]` + `[InlineData]` for parameterized tests. Arrange/Act/Assert organizes the body. `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` argument order is expected-first, and `Assert.Throws\u003cT\u003e(() =\u003e action())` is the exception matcher.","cards":[{"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"A single-scenario xUnit test is marked `[{{Fact}}]`; a parameterized test is marked `[{{Theory}}]` and paired with one or more `[{{InlineData}}]` rows.","answer":"Fact; Theory; InlineData","bloom":"remember","explanation":"Each [InlineData(...)] produces one test execution. Four [InlineData] rows = four runs of the same [Theory] method body. Individual failures are reported per-row.","example":"[Theory]\\n[InlineData(1, 2, 3)]\\n[InlineData(0, 0, 0)]\\npublic void Add(int a, int b, int expected) =\u003e Assert.Equal(expected, calc.Add(a, b));"},{"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions-card-02","type":"cloze","prompt":"The canonical test body structure is {{Arrange}} / {{Act}} / {{Assert}} — setup, the operation under test, then the verification.","answer":"Arrange; Act; Assert","bloom":"understand","explanation":"AAA keeps tests readable and makes failures diagnosable — a stack trace points to Arrange, Act, or Assert and you know immediately whether setup, behavior, or expectations broke.","example":"// Arrange\\nvar calc = new Calculator();\\n// Act\\nint r = calc.Add(2, 3);\\n// Assert\\nAssert.Equal(5, r);"},{"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions-card-03","type":"name","prompt":"What's the argument order for `Assert.Equal`?","answer":"Expected first, actual second: `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)`.","bloom":"remember","explanation":"The compiler doesn't enforce order. Reversing produces failure messages that lie — the Expected/Actual labels in the message will be swapped, and you'll chase the wrong value.","example":"Assert.Equal(5, calc.Add(2, 3));  // expected 5, actual is the result of Add"},{"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"How do you test that a method throws `ArgumentException`?","answer":"`Assert.Throws\u003cArgumentException\u003e(() =\u003e method(args));`","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Assert.Throws runs the lambda and asserts a specific exception type was thrown. It returns the exception instance so you can also assert on Message or custom properties.","example":"var ex = Assert.Throws\u003cArgumentException\u003e(() =\u003e _service.DoThing(null));\\nAssert.Contains(\"cannot be null\", ex.Message);"},{"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"When multiple derived exception types could match, use `Assert.{{ThrowsAny}}\u003cT\u003e(() =\u003e action())` to accept any subtype of `T`.","answer":"ThrowsAny","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Assert.Throws\u003cT\u003e matches T EXACTLY — a derived type fails the test. Assert.ThrowsAny\u003cT\u003e accepts T or any subclass. Use the strict form when the exact type matters; the any form when it doesn't.","example":"Assert.ThrowsAny\u003cArgumentException\u003e(() =\u003e action());  // ArgumentNullException and ArgumentOutOfRangeException both pass"},{"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"What xUnit assertion compares two references for being the same object (not just value-equal)?","answer":"`Assert.Same(expected, actual)` (its negation: `Assert.NotSame`).","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Same compares by reference identity; Equal compares by value. For value types Equal is almost always what you want; for reference types, choose based on whether you care about identity or content.","example":"Assert.Same(obj, service.GetCached());  // must be the literal same instance"},{"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions-card-07","type":"cloze","prompt":"`[Theory]` tests require at least one data attribute. Common choices: `[{{InlineData}}(...)]` for literals, `[{{MemberData}}(nameof(Method))]` for computed data, `[{{ClassData}}(typeof(Cls))]` for typed data providers.","answer":"InlineData; MemberData; ClassData","bloom":"remember","explanation":"[InlineData] is simplest for small literal values. [MemberData] when data requires computation or doesn't fit in an attribute. [ClassData] when data provider needs its own class with complex logic.","example":"[Theory]\\n[MemberData(nameof(GetSamples))]\\npublic void RoundTrip(string json) { /* ... */ }\\npublic static IEnumerable\u003cobject[]\u003e GetSamples() { yield return new object[] { \"{}\" }; }"}]},{"id":"xunit-fixtures-lifecycle","name":"xUnit fixtures and lifecycle","tags":["tdd","xunit","fixture","lifecycle"],"source":"notes/TDD_xunit_SCRIPT.docx; research-tdd.md","prose":"xUnit creates a fresh test-class instance per test. Constructor runs before each test; `IDisposable.Dispose` runs after each test. `IClassFixture\u003cT\u003e` shares one instance across all tests in a class; `ICollectionFixture\u003cT\u003e` + `[CollectionDefinition]` + `[Collection(\"Name\")]` shares across multiple classes.","cards":[{"id":"xunit-fixtures-lifecycle-card-01","type":"cloze","prompt":"In xUnit, the test class's {{constructor}} runs before each test, and `{{IDisposable.Dispose}}` runs after — replacing older frameworks' `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` attributes.","answer":"constructor; IDisposable.Dispose","bloom":"remember","explanation":"xUnit uses standard C# object lifecycle instead of framework-specific attributes. Every [Fact] or [Theory] run gets a fresh test class instance, so state doesn't leak between tests.","example":"public class MyTests : IDisposable { public MyTests() { /* setup */ } public void Dispose() { /* cleanup */ } }"},{"id":"xunit-fixtures-lifecycle-card-02","type":"name","prompt":"How do you share an expensive setup (e.g. a seeded DbContext) across all tests in one test class?","answer":"Implement the setup as a fixture class and have the test class implement `IClassFixture\u003cTFixture\u003e`. xUnit injects the shared fixture via the test class constructor.","bloom":"apply","explanation":"IClassFixture\u003cT\u003e creates one fixture instance per test class, shared across all tests in that class. The test class's own lifetime (constructor/Dispose per test) is unchanged.","example":"public class MyTests : IClassFixture\u003cDbFixture\u003e { public MyTests(DbFixture fx) { _fx = fx; } }"},{"id":"xunit-fixtures-lifecycle-card-03","type":"cloze","prompt":"To share a fixture across multiple test classes, define `{{ICollectionFixture\u003cT\u003e}}` inside a `[{{CollectionDefinition}}(\"Name\")]` class, and decorate each participating test class with `[{{Collection}}(\"Name\")]`.","answer":"ICollectionFixture\u003cT\u003e; CollectionDefinition; Collection","bloom":"apply","explanation":"Three pieces: definition class declares the fixture, test classes join by [Collection(\"Name\")]. Tests within the collection run serially; the fixture is instantiated once per collection.","example":"[CollectionDefinition(\"Db\")] public class DbColl : ICollectionFixture\u003cDbFixture\u003e {}\\n[Collection(\"Db\")] public class UserTests { /* ... */ }\\n[Collection(\"Db\")] public class OrderTests { /* ... */ }"},{"id":"xunit-fixtures-lifecycle-card-04","type":"name","prompt":"By default, does xUnit run tests in the same class in parallel or serially?","answer":"Serially. Tests in one class run one at a time; different test classes run in parallel.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"This default prevents shared-fixture races within a class. Parallelism happens at the class level, so IClassFixture-shared state is safe (no two tests touch it concurrently). Opt into full parallelization via [assembly: CollectionBehavior(...)] if needed.","example":"TestsInClassA: serialized. TestsInClassB: serialized. ClassA vs ClassB: parallel."},{"id":"xunit-fixtures-lifecycle-card-05","type":"cloze","prompt":"Fixtures are {{not safe}} for tests that mutate the fixture's state — xUnit doesn't guarantee test ordering within a class, so one test's writes may or may not be visible to another.","answer":"not safe","bloom":"analyze","explanation":"If tests need to mutate shared state, either reset in the test class's own Dispose, or switch to fresh-per-test state (no fixture). IClassFixture is intended for read-only / idempotent setup.","example":"Bad: TestA adds a user, TestB counts users, result depends on execution order.\\nFix: each test manages its own state, or reset in Dispose."},{"id":"xunit-fixtures-lifecycle-card-06","type":"name","prompt":"When should you NOT use a fixture?","answer":"When setup is cheap (in-memory list, simple object graph). Fixtures add indirection; plain constructors are simpler for tests that don't need expensive shared setup.","bloom":"understand","explanation":"Fixtures trade test isolation for performance. For a few-line setup there's no perf benefit; fixture overhead (an extra class, [Collection] attribute for cross-class sharing) is net negative.","example":"`new Calculator()` in the constructor — no fixture needed. `new MyDbContext(...)` with seed data — fixture pays off."}]}]}],"mockExam":{"duration_seconds":3600,"pass_mark":0.5,"questions":[{"id":"mq-ai-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Microsoft Agent Framework","marks":1,"question":"Which extension method wraps an `IChatClient` into a Microsoft Agent Framework agent?","choices":[".AsAgent()",".AsAIAgent()",".ToAgent()",".CreateAgent()"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`.AsAIAgent()` is the only real method. `.AsAgent()` is the single most common exam distractor — it does not exist in MAF. `.ToAgent()` and `.CreateAgent()` are also fabrications meant to confuse learners who remember \"something starts with As\" or \"something ends with Agent\". MAF's API is deliberately specific: the `AI` prefix distinguishes it from other agent frameworks in the ecosystem.","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx; research-ai.md §MAF","bloom":"remember","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-ai-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"MAF tool registration","marks":1,"question":"What does `AIFunctionFactory.Create(methodRef, name: \"X\", description: \"Y\")` return?","choices":["A `ChatClientAgent`","An `AITool` ready to register on an agent","A `ChatMessage`","A `KernelFunction`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The factory produces an `AITool` — MAF's runtime representation of a callable function. Option A confuses the output with the container that consumes it (agents hold lists of AITools). Option C confuses it with a conversation-turn type. Option D confuses MAF with Semantic Kernel, which uses `KernelFunction`/`[KernelFunction]` instead — the two SDKs do not interop at the type level.","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx §Demo #3","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-ai-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Ollama endpoint","marks":1,"question":"Which URL is correct for an OllamaSharp client connecting to a locally-running Ollama daemon?","choices":["https://localhost:11434","http://localhost:1143","http://localhost:11434/","http://ollama.local/inference"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Ollama listens on port 11434 (not 1143 — off-by-one on the port number is a common typo trap) over HTTP, not HTTPS. Option A is wrong on the protocol — the local daemon doesn't serve TLS by default. Option D confuses Ollama's local-URL format with GitHub Models' `https://models.github.ai/inference`. Only option C matches what `OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), model)` expects.","source":"slides/SLM.pptx; research-ai.md §Ollama","bloom":"remember","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-ai-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"GitHub Models authentication","marks":1,"question":"Which credential type authenticates a `ChatClient` configured for GitHub Models?","choices":["`BearerTokenCredential(token)`","`AzureKeyCredential(token)`","`GithubCredential(token)`","`OAuthCredential(token)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Despite the Azure prefix, `AzureKeyCredential` wraps any bearer token and is what the OpenAI SDK uses for GitHub Models. `BearerTokenCredential` does not exist in this SDK context. `GithubCredential` is entirely fabricated — there is no type by that name. `OAuthCredential` refers to an interactive OAuth flow, not the simple PAT-based auth GitHub Models uses.","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx §Demo #2","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-ai-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"Semantic Kernel plugin loading","marks":1,"question":"Which Semantic Kernel method loads a plugin from a directory of `skprompt.txt` files?","choices":["`kernel.LoadSkillFromDirectory(path)`","`kernel.ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory(path)`","`kernel.AddPlugin(path)`","`kernel.RegisterSkill(path)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory` is the actual SK method name — it walks the directory, loads every `skprompt.txt`, and registers them under the plugin name. Option A uses the legacy SK-v0 terminology (\"Skill\") which SK-v1 renamed to \"Plugin\". Options C and D are fabrications that sound reasonable but don't exist in the SK API. Writing \"LoadSkill\" or \"AddPlugin\" compiles with nothing.","source":"research-ai.md §Add Plugin to Kernel","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-ai-06","type":"MCQ","topic":"Semantic Kernel function attribute","marks":1,"question":"Which attribute exposes a C# method as a callable function inside a Semantic Kernel plugin?","choices":["`[SkillFunction]`","`[KernelFunction]`","`[SKFunction]`","`[AIFunction]`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`[KernelFunction]` is the SK-v1 attribute. `[SkillFunction]` and `[SKFunction]` were earlier-version names; mixing versions produces a compile error because the attribute isn't found in the current namespace. `[AIFunction]` belongs to Microsoft Agent Framework (MAF), which uses a different registration pattern entirely — `AIFunctionFactory.Create` instead of attribute-driven discovery.","source":"research-ai.md §Plugins (Native C# class)","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-ai-07","type":"MCQ","topic":"MAF multi-turn state","marks":1,"question":"You want your MAF agent to maintain conversation context across multiple `RunAsync` calls. Which object do you create?","choices":["A new `ChatHistory`","An `AgentSession` via `await agent.CreateSessionAsync()`","A `ConversationContext`","Nothing — MAF agents remember automatically"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`AgentSession` is MAF's managed multi-turn state object, created via `CreateSessionAsync()` and passed to subsequent `RunAsync(input, session)` calls. Option A (`ChatHistory`) is raw — it works for `IChatClient` directly but bypasses agent-managed state. `ConversationContext` is not a real MAF type. Option D is false — agents need an explicit session to carry history; otherwise each `RunAsync` starts fresh.","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx §Demo #3","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-ai-08","type":"MCQ","topic":"Prompt template syntax","marks":1,"question":"In a Semantic Kernel `skprompt.txt` file, how do you substitute the variable `cityName` into the prompt?","choices":["`{cityName}`","`${cityName}`","`{{$cityName}}`","`\u003c%= cityName %\u003e`"],"correct":2,"rationale":"SK's double-brace template syntax uses `{{$varName}}` — the leading `$` distinguishes variable references from plain template commands. Option A uses C# string interpolation syntax, which SK does not parse. Option B is shell-style, also not recognized. Option D is Razor/classic-ASP syntax, inappropriate for a prompt-template DSL.","source":"research-ai.md §skprompt.txt Template","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-ai-09","type":"MCQ","topic":"MAF tool invocation semantics","marks":1,"question":"An MAF agent has three registered tools. When you call `agent.RunAsync(input, session)`, what happens?","choices":["All three tools execute in sequence","The LLM decides which tools (if any) to invoke and combines their outputs","The first registered tool always runs first","The framework invokes only tools whose name appears in the input"],"correct":1,"rationale":"MAF agents are agentic — the underlying LLM reasons about the user input and decides which tools, if any, to call. Option A would make tools meaningless (why register more than one?). Option C misses that the LLM decides order based on the task. Option D describes keyword matching, which is not what MAF does — the description metadata is passed to the LLM so it can match on semantic intent, not literal tool names in user input.","source":"research-ai.md §MAF MCQ #6","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-ai-10","type":"MCQ","topic":"Ollama offline capability","marks":1,"question":"Which statement about Ollama is TRUE?","choices":["Ollama requires a persistent internet connection during inference","Ollama serves an OpenAI-compatible API on localhost after `ollama pull` downloads the model","Ollama requires an API key stored in `appsettings.json`","Ollama only supports Microsoft-authored models"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Ollama exposes an OpenAI-compatible API at `http://localhost:11434/` and runs fully offline after the one-time `ollama pull` to download the model. Option A is false — the whole point of Ollama is local inference. Option C is false — there is no auth on the local daemon. Option D is false — Ollama distributes Phi-3 (Microsoft), Llama (Meta), Qwen (Alibaba), and many others.","source":"slides/SLM.pptx; research-ai.md §Ollama","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-ai-11","type":"MCQ","topic":"MAF streaming","marks":1,"question":"Which method streams an MAF agent's response as tokens arrive?","choices":["`agent.GetStreamAsync(input)`","`agent.RunStreamingAsync(input)`","`agent.StreamResponseAsync(input)`","`agent.RunAsync(input, stream: true)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`RunStreamingAsync` returns an `IAsyncEnumerable` you iterate with `await foreach`. Option A is a fabrication. Option C sounds reasonable but isn't the real method name. Option D tries to toggle streaming via a bool parameter on `RunAsync` — MAF does not overload `RunAsync` this way; it has separate sync and streaming methods to keep return types distinct (`Task\u003cT\u003e` vs `IAsyncEnumerable\u003cT\u003e`).","source":"research-ai.md §MAF Agent with Streaming","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-ai-12","type":"MCQ","topic":"Cross-SDK method confusion","marks":1,"question":"Which of the following method names is REAL (not a fabrication)?","choices":["`kernel.Execute(promptTemplate)`","`kernel.InvokeAsync(plugin[\"FuncName\"], arguments)`","`agent.Invoke(input)`","`AITool.Register(method, name, description)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`kernel.InvokeAsync` is Semantic Kernel's actual method for executing a function. Option A (`Execute`) is a fabrication — the real method is `InvokeAsync`. Option C confuses MAF with SK — MAF uses `agent.RunAsync`, not `Invoke`. Option D fabricates a static `Register` method; the real API is `AIFunctionFactory.Create`.","source":"research-ai.md §Exam Traps (Fake Method Names)","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET Fit() return type","marks":1,"question":"What does `pipeline.Fit(trainingData)` return?","choices":["`IDataView`","`ITransformer`","`TrainingMetrics`","`MLContext`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`Fit` produces the trained model as an `ITransformer` — stateless, serializable, and ready to either evaluate or wrap in a `PredictionEngine`. Option A is the type of the INPUT (training data), not the output. Option C is what `Regression.Evaluate` returns, not `Fit`. Option D is the root container you create at step 1, not what `Fit` returns. This argument-type confusion is one of the most-tested traps.","source":"slides/ML.NET.pptx; research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps","bloom":"remember","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-mlnet-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET Features column name","marks":1,"question":"Why does `mlContext.Transforms.Concatenate(outputColumnName: \"Inputs\", ...)` cause regression trainers to fail?","choices":["The column `Inputs` is too short — names must be at least 6 characters","ML.NET trainers look up the input vector by the literal name `\"Features\"` — any other name breaks the lookup","Concatenate requires the output column name to match the first input column","`\"Inputs\"` is a reserved keyword in ML.NET"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`\"Features\"` is the hardcoded name regression and classification trainers look up at `Fit()` time. The same convention applies to the label column (`\"Label\"`). Option A invents a length rule that doesn't exist. Option C invents a matching rule — Concatenate names are entirely your choice except that the OUTPUT must be `\"Features\"`. Option D calls `\"Inputs\"` reserved, which is not true.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps trap 6","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET pipeline ordering","marks":1,"question":"Your pipeline is: `FastTree()` → `OneHotEncoding(...)` → `Concatenate(\"Features\", ...)` → `CopyColumns(\"Label\", \"FareAmount\")`. Why does training fail?","choices":["`FastTree()` must be the last step; it's at the beginning","`CopyColumns` is not a valid ML.NET transform","The pipeline missing `hasHeader: true`","FastTree doesn't support regression"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Pipelines execute in order, and the trainer (FastTree here) always sits at the end because it consumes the `Features` and `Label` columns that earlier transforms produce. Putting it first means no features exist when it runs. Option B is false — `CopyColumns` is real and is how you typically name the target column `\"Label\"`. Option C names an argument to `LoadFromTextFile`, not a pipeline step. Option D is false — FastTree is the default regression trainer.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Training Pipeline Anatomy","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET one-hot encoding","marks":1,"question":"You apply `OneHotEncoding` to three text columns: `VendorId`, `RateCode`, `PaymentType`. Then your `Concatenate(\"Features\", ...)` lists only `VendorIdEncoded`, `PassengerCount`, and `TripDistance`. What's the effect?","choices":["The pipeline fails to compile","`RateCode` and `PaymentType` never reach the trainer — they're silently dropped","The trainer auto-includes the missing encoded columns","The pipeline defaults to using the raw text columns instead"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Concatenate picks exactly the inputs you list. Encoded outputs that aren't in the list simply don't reach the trainer — the pipeline compiles and trains, just on fewer features. This is a silent-bug class: the model looks reasonable but has less signal than you expected. Option A is wrong — no compile error. Option C is wrong — ML.NET does no auto-include. Option D is wrong — raw text columns never reach the trainer because they weren't concatenated either.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET metrics","marks":1,"question":"A regression model reports `RSquared = 0.89` and `RootMeanSquaredError = 3.3`. How do you interpret these for predicting taxi fare in dollars?","choices":["The model is 89% accurate with an average error of 3.3%","The model explains 89% of variance in fares, with average prediction error around $3.30","The model has 89% precision and 3.3% recall","The model needs retraining because RMSE is above 1"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RSquared is the fraction of variance explained (unitless, 0-1). RMSE is in the label's original units — dollars here, because `FareAmount` is in dollars. Option A conflates RSquared with accuracy (which is a classification metric) and misinterprets RMSE as a percentage. Option C is classification-only terminology. Option D invents an absolute threshold; RMSE meaning depends on the scale of the data (3.3 dollars is fine for fare amounts that average ~$15).","source":"research-mlnet.md §Evaluation Metrics MCQ #4","bloom":"understand","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-mlnet-06","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET PredictionEngine","marks":1,"question":"You loaded a saved model and want to predict the fare for one new `TaxiTrip`. Which call is correct?","choices":["`model.Predict(trip)`","`var engine = mlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction\u003e(model); var p = engine.Predict(trip);`","`mlContext.Regression.Predict(model, trip)`","`model.Transform(trip)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`ITransformer` has no `Predict` method — you wrap it in a `PredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` for single-row inference. Option A is a fabrication. Option C fabricates a static Predict on the regression catalog, which doesn't exist. Option D (`Transform`) takes an `IDataView` (collection), not a single object — wrong for per-row inference. For batch inference you'd use `model.Transform(dataView)`, returning an `IDataView` with prediction columns appended.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Code Patterns","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-07","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET AutoML CLI","marks":1,"question":"What does `mlnet regression --dataset train.csv --label-col 6 --train-time 60` do?","choices":["Trains exactly one model using FastTree for 60 seconds","Converts the CSV into a binary ML.NET model file","Explores dozens of regression algorithms and hyperparameter combinations for 60 seconds, returning top-5 models","Starts a web service on port 6000"],"correct":2,"rationale":"AutoML's CLI tries many algorithm/hyperparameter combinations within the time budget and ranks the results. Option A describes manual training, not AutoML. Option B invents CSV-to-model conversion — the CLI emits a full console project plus model. Option D confuses the `--train-time` flag (seconds) with a port number. The flag's unit is seconds; larger values explore more combinations at diminishing returns.","source":"notes/ML.NET_vscode_automl_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md §AutoML","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-08","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET Label column","marks":1,"question":"What is the purpose of `mlContext.Transforms.CopyColumns(outputColumnName: \"Label\", inputColumnName: \"FareAmount\")` at the start of a regression pipeline?","choices":["To validate the CSV column count","To rename the target column to `\"Label\"` — the name regression trainers look for","To remove the target column from the feature set","To convert numeric data to categorical"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Regression trainers look up the target column by the literal name `\"Label\"`. If your CSV class has the target as `FareAmount`, you must rename it first — CopyColumns is the tool. Option A invents a validation role. Option C describes the inverse effect — CopyColumns leaves both columns present; it's actually Concatenate's job to pick which ones become features. Option D confuses CopyColumns with OneHotEncoding.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Complete ML.NET Workflow","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-09","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET column indexing","marks":1,"question":"Your CSV has columns `VendorId`, `PassengerCount`, `Distance`, `FareAmount` in that order. Which attribute marks `FareAmount` correctly for loading?","choices":["`[LoadColumn(\"FareAmount\")]`","`[LoadColumn(3)]`","`[LoadColumn(4)]`","`[Column(3)]`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`[LoadColumn(N)]` is 0-based — `FareAmount` is the 4th column, index 3. Option A fabricates a string-named overload; `LoadColumn` takes a 0-based integer index (or a range). Option C is off-by-one (treating the columns as 1-based). Option D uses `[Column]`, which is a different older attribute with incompatible semantics.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Column Mapping","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-10","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET Save / Load schema","marks":1,"question":"A teammate writes `mlContext.Model.Save(model, null, \"model.zip\")`. The call compiles. What breaks and when?","choices":["Compilation fails — `null` isn't allowed","Loading fails at runtime — the saved model is missing its schema and `PredictionEngine` cannot bind inputs","Saving succeeds; no downstream effects","The file is encrypted and unreadable"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The `DataViewSchema` argument carries column-name and type metadata. Passing `null` skips that, so the saved ZIP has the weights but no shape info. `Load` succeeds but the returned ITransformer can't be bound to a `PredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` correctly because the column-name mapping is lost. Option A is false — the compiler accepts null. Option C is the dangerous misconception — the save appears to work. Option D invents encryption behavior.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Persistence","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-mlnet-11","type":"MCQ","topic":"ML.NET namespace selection","marks":1,"question":"You want to evaluate a regression model. Which namespace's `Evaluate` method do you call?","choices":["`mlContext.BinaryClassification.Evaluate(...)`","`mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(...)`","`mlContext.MulticlassClassification.Evaluate(...)`","`mlContext.Clustering.Evaluate(...)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Each ML task has its own Evaluate that returns task-specific metrics (`RegressionMetrics`, `BinaryClassificationMetrics`, etc.). Using the wrong one either throws or returns metrics that don't match your problem (e.g. Classification returns `Accuracy`, which is meaningless for regression). Regression has RSquared and RMSE; BinaryClassification has Accuracy/Precision/Recall; MulticlassClassification has MacroAccuracy and Log-Loss; Clustering has Davies-Bouldin Index. Pick based on the task.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Exam Traps trap 4","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-cache-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"IMemoryCache vs IDistributedCache","marks":1,"question":"An ASP.NET Core app caches product data with `IMemoryCache`. After scaling from 1 to 3 servers behind a load balancer, users report seeing different product lists. Why?","choices":["IMemoryCache uses weak references","The load balancer corrupts cache keys","Each server holds its own separate in-memory cache — data isn't shared","IMemoryCache caches everything with the same key"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`IMemoryCache` is per-process. Three servers = three separate caches. A write on Server A is invisible to Server B. Option A invents weak-reference behavior (IMemoryCache uses strong references with optional Size-based eviction). Option B is nonsense — load balancers pass requests through unchanged. Option D is false — cache keys are user-supplied and distinct. Fix: switch to `IDistributedCache` backed by Redis, or configure sticky sessions.","source":"notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md MCQ #1","bloom":"analyze","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-cache-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Cache expiration combination","marks":1,"question":"A cache entry has `AbsoluteExpiration = now + 50s` and `SlidingExpiration = 20s`. At t=15s the entry is accessed. When does it expire (assuming no further access)?","choices":["At t=50s (absolute deadline)","At t=35s (15s + 20s sliding window from the access)","At t=65s (50s absolute + 20s extension)","Never — sliding access resets it"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The combined expiration is `min(absolute, idle-since-last-access + sliding)`. Last access at t=15 resets the sliding timer to fire at t=35. Absolute fires at t=50. Min is t=35, so the entry dies then. If an ADDITIONAL access happened later — say at t=25, extending sliding to t=45 — absolute at t=50 would then be the binding constraint. Option A ignores the sliding timer entirely. Option C adds the two windows (wrong mental model). Option D misses that absolute is a hard ceiling.","source":"notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §4","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-cache-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"CacheItemPriority semantics","marks":1,"question":"What does `CacheItemPriority.Low` on a cache entry mean?","choices":["The entry expires 5 minutes sooner than `Normal`","The entry is evicted first when the cache is under memory pressure","The entry is stored with lower compression","The entry is only cached when the server is idle"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Priority controls eviction order, not expiration. A Low-priority entry with a 1-hour absolute expiration still lives 1 hour unless memory pressure forces eviction. `NeverRemove` excludes from auto-eviction entirely; `High` is kept longer under pressure. Option A invents a time-based effect. Option C invents compression behavior. Option D invents scheduling behavior.","source":"research-cache.md §Exam Traps trap 7","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-cache-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"TryGetValue syntax","marks":1,"question":"Which is the correct syntax to check for a cache entry and receive it into `product`?","choices":["`if (_cache.TryGetValue(\"key\", product)) { ... }`","`if (_cache.TryGetValue\u003cProduct\u003e(\"key\", out var product)) { ... }`","`var product = _cache.TryGetValue\u003cProduct\u003e(\"key\");`","`if (_cache.ContainsKey(\"key\")) { var product = _cache[\"key\"]; }`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`TryGetValue` returns `bool` and takes an `out` parameter. Option A misses `out`. Option C treats it as returning the value directly — it returns `bool`. Option D invents a `ContainsKey` method (it's common on Dictionary, not on IMemoryCache) plus indexer access, which doesn't exist either. The `out var` pattern introduces the variable with inferred type in the same line.","source":"research-cache.md §Exam Traps trap 2","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-cache-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"Redis Docker port","marks":1,"question":"Which Docker command starts a Redis container listening on its conventional port?","choices":["`docker run --name redis -d -p 6380:6379 redis`","`docker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis`","`docker run --name redis -p 11434:11434 redis`","`docker run redis:latest --detached --port 6379`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Redis's standard port is 6379. `-p 6379:6379` maps host port to container port, both 6379. Option A remaps the host port to 6380, which means clients configured for 6379 won't find it. Option C uses Ollama's port (11434) — wrong service. Option D uses non-existent flag names (`--detached --port`); the real flags are `-d` and `-p host:container`.","source":"notes/redis_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §6","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-cache-06","type":"MCQ","topic":"Redis SETEX","marks":1,"question":"In the Redis CLI, `SETEX temp 10 \"hello\"` does what?","choices":["Sets `temp` to `hello` with a 10-byte size limit","Sets `temp` to `hello` and schedules deletion in 10 seconds","Sets `temp` to `hello` and schedules deletion in 10 minutes","Sets `temp` only if it doesn't exist, with key named `10`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`SETEX` = `SET` + `EXpiration` in seconds. The number argument is always seconds, not minutes or milliseconds. Sub-second precision requires `PSETEX` which takes milliseconds. Option A invents a size limit. Option C uses the wrong unit — seconds, not minutes. Option D describes `SETNX` (set-if-not-exists) and mis-parses the arguments.","source":"notes/redis_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §6","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-cache-07","type":"MCQ","topic":"Cache-aside invalidation","marks":1,"question":"You cache a list at key `\"games\"`. A user adds a new game via an API. Why might the UI continue showing the old list?","choices":["The cache is corrupted","The write-handler didn't call `_cache.Remove(\"games\")` after saving to the database","Redis can only hold 1 MB per key","The API writes to a different Redis instance"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Cache-aside requires the writer to invalidate affected keys. Adding a game persists to the DB, but the cache still holds the old list until someone calls `Remove`. The TTL will eventually refresh it, but in the meantime the UI looks stale. Option A is rarely the real cause; corruption would throw. Option C invents a size limit (512 MB is the default per-value cap in Redis, not 1 MB). Option D confuses multi-instance topology with ordinary cache staleness.","source":"notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §3","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-cache-08","type":"MCQ","topic":"AddStackExchangeRedisCache NuGet","marks":1,"question":"Which NuGet package do you install to use `builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(...)`?","choices":["`StackExchange.Redis` alone","`Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis`","`Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.Redis`","`Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.Memory`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The adapter package is `Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis`. Option A is the underlying client library — it ships with the adapter but doesn't expose the `AddStackExchangeRedisCache` extension. Option C is the older (deprecated) Redis caching package that predates StackExchange.Redis integration. Option D is the in-memory cache package, unrelated. Getting the exact package name matters because NuGet won't resolve the extension method otherwise.","source":"notes/redis_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-fb-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"#:package directive syntax","marks":1,"question":"Which directive line is valid in a .NET 10 file-based app?","choices":["`#: package Spectre.Console@0.49.1`","`#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1`","`#:Package Spectre.Console@0.49.1`","`#package Spectre.Console@0.49.1`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`#:package` — no space after the colon, lowercase directive name, package+version in `Name@Version` form. Option A has a space after `:` (syntax error — the most common exam distractor). Option C uppercases `Package` (directive names are case-sensitive lowercase). Option D drops the colon entirely. All three fail the parser.","source":"research-file-based.md §2.4","bloom":"remember","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-fb-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"File-based app SDK switch","marks":1,"question":"You want to write a minimal web API as a single `.cs` file. Which directive must appear at the top?","choices":["`#:web`","`#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web`","`#:framework aspnetcore`","`#:runtime Microsoft.AspNetCore.App`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The `#:sdk` directive selects the SDK at compilation. `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` pulls in ASP.NET Core's implicit references, making `WebApplication`, routing, and middleware available. Option A is a fabricated shorthand. Option C invents a `#:framework` directive that doesn't exist. Option D invents a `#:runtime` directive; runtime selection happens via `TargetFramework` not a separate directive.","source":"research-file-based.md §2.4","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-fb-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"File-based app command-line args","marks":1,"question":"You want to pass the keyword `alice` to your script `filter.cs`. Which invocation is correct?","choices":["`dotnet run filter.cs alice`","`dotnet run filter.cs -- alice`","`dotnet run filter.cs --arg alice`","`dotnet run filter.cs args=alice`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`--` separates `dotnet run` arguments from the script's own args. Without it, `dotnet` interprets `alice` as its own flag (and ignores/rejects it). Option A omits the separator. Option C invents an `--arg` flag syntax. Option D uses `key=value` syntax, which the CLI doesn't parse.","source":"research-file-based.md §2.2","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-fb-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"File-based app directives available","marks":1,"question":"Which of the following is NOT a valid file-based-app directive?","choices":["`#:package`","`#:property`","`#:sdk`","`#:using`"],"correct":3,"rationale":"The four real directives are `#:package`, `#:property`, `#:sdk`, and `#:project`. `#:using` doesn't exist — C# `using` directives go in the file body as normal (`using System.Text.Json;`). Implicit usings cover common namespaces automatically. The trap here is that `#:using` sounds plausible by analogy to `using` in C#, but the directive language is strictly limited to the four named.","source":"research-file-based.md §2.4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-fb-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"File-based app implicit usings","marks":1,"question":"Which namespace is NOT implicitly imported in a .NET 10 file-based app?","choices":["`System`","`System.Linq`","`System.Text.Json`","`System.Collections.Generic`"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`System.Text.Json` requires an explicit `using` — it's not in the implicit set. Implicit usings cover `System`, `System.Linq`, `System.Collections.Generic`, `System.Text`, and `System.Threading.Tasks`. Anything outside that small list needs a normal `using` directive. This is a high-value question because tooling hints about \"unresolved types\" often point here — the fix is usually one `using` line.","source":"research-file-based.md §2.3","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-fb-06","type":"MCQ","topic":"File-based app project conversion","marks":1,"question":"Which command converts a file-based app `api.cs` into a traditional .NET project in a folder `ApiProject`?","choices":["`dotnet project convert api.cs -o ApiProject`","`dotnet convert api.cs --project ApiProject`","`dotnet new console -n ApiProject --from api.cs`","`dotnet migrate api.cs ApiProject`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"`dotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder` is the real command. It creates the folder, generates a `.csproj`, and moves the `.cs` body into `Program.cs`, preserving `#:` directives as MSBuild settings. Option B inverts the flag position and uses the wrong flag name. Option C uses `dotnet new`, which creates a fresh project (no conversion). Option D invents `dotnet migrate` (an older command, unrelated to file-based apps).","source":"research-file-based.md","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-fb-07","type":"MCQ","topic":"File-based app cache location","marks":1,"question":"Where does the .NET CLI cache compiled binaries for file-based apps on macOS/Linux?","choices":["In the directory where the `.cs` file lives","`~/.dotnet/runfile/`","`/tmp/dotnet/`","`$HOME/Library/Caches/dotnet/`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`~/.dotnet/runfile/` is the cache root; per-file subdirectories are named with a content hash so edits trigger fresh compiles. Option A would produce `bin/` folders next to scripts — file-based apps deliberately avoid this. Option C is a generic temp-dir guess; dotnet uses `~/.dotnet/` instead to survive reboots. Option D is macOS-specific system cache, not what dotnet uses.","source":"research-file-based.md §2.1","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-fb-08","type":"MCQ","topic":"File-based app top-level statements","marks":1,"question":"In `greet.cs`, where does `Console.WriteLine(\"Hi\");` go?","choices":["Inside `static void Main(string[] args)` in a `Program` class","At the top level of the file, before any type declarations","Inside a `public class Program` but outside `Main`","In a `[Entry]`-attributed method"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Top-level statements go at file scope; the compiler synthesizes an implicit `Main` around them. Type declarations (classes, records, etc.) come AFTER the top-level statements. Option A is the traditional form that file-based apps replace. Option C would be invalid (code outside a method doesn't compile in traditional classes). Option D invents an `[Entry]` attribute that doesn't exist in C#.","source":"research-file-based.md §2.2","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-grpc-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"gRPC proto field tags","marks":1,"question":"A live service ships `message Person { string name = 1; int32 age = 2; }`. You want to drop `age` and add `string email`. What's the safe rewrite?","choices":["`message Person { string name = 1; string email = 2; }`","`message Person { string name = 1; reserved 2; string email = 3; }`","`message Person { string name = 1; int32 age = 0; string email = 2; }`","`message Person { string name = 1; string email = 2; int32 age = 2; }`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Tag 2 was int32 in deployed clients. Reusing it for `email` (a string) corrupts the wire format — deployed consumers still interpret tag 2 bytes as int32. `reserved 2;` marks the old tag as off-limits; `email = 3` allocates a fresh tag. Option A reuses tag 2 for email — the forbidden move. Option C attempts tag 0 which is invalid (proto tags start at 1). Option D duplicates tag 2, which the compiler rejects.","source":"slides/gRPC.pptx; research-grpc.md","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-grpc-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"gRPC server method signature","marks":1,"question":"Given `rpc GetStudent (StudentLookup) returns (Student);` in the proto, which C# method signature is correct for the server implementation?","choices":["`public Student GetStudent(StudentLookup request)`","`public override Task\u003cStudent\u003e GetStudent(StudentLookup request, ServerCallContext context)`","`public async Student GetStudent(StudentLookup request)`","`public override Student GetStudent(StudentLookup request, CallContext context)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"gRPC server methods must be `override`, take the request type plus `ServerCallContext`, and return `Task\u003cTResponse\u003e`. Option A misses `override`, `Task\u003c\u003e`, and `ServerCallContext` — the service class wouldn't replace the base method. Option C uses `async Student` (not a valid return type). Option D uses `CallContext` (fabricated name) and drops the `Task\u003c\u003e` wrapper.","source":"notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx; research-grpc.md","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-grpc-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"gRPC proto file types","marks":1,"question":"In a `.proto` file, which keyword declares a data structure?","choices":["`class`","`struct`","`message`","`record`"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`message` is proto's keyword for structured data. The other three are C# keywords that don't appear in proto files. `protoc` generates C# classes from `message` blocks — but the declaration keyword on the proto side is always `message`, regardless of target language.","source":"slides/gRPC.pptx; research-grpc.md","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-grpc-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"gRPC .csproj Protobuf GrpcServices","marks":1,"question":"In a Blazor client project, your `.csproj` has `\u003cProtobuf Include=\"Protos\\students.proto\" GrpcServices=\"Server\" /\u003e`. The build fails with \"type or namespace name 'StudentRemoteClient' could not be found\". Why?","choices":["The client needs a different .proto file than the server","`GrpcServices=\"Server\"` only generates the server-side base class; set it to `\"Client\"` (or `\"Both\"`) for client stubs","Blazor can't consume gRPC","The `.proto` file must be in `Clients\\` not `Protos\\`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`GrpcServices` chooses which side's code `Grpc.Tools` emits. `Server` produces only the abstract base class; `Client` produces only the stub; `Both` produces both. A client project with `Server` selected gets no client stub. Option A is wrong — the same .proto works for both sides. Option C is false — Blazor apps routinely call gRPC. Option D invents a folder-naming rule; the path is your choice.","source":"notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-grpc-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"gRPC HTTP version","marks":1,"question":"Which transport protocol does gRPC require?","choices":["HTTP/1.1","HTTP/2","WebSocket","TCP directly"],"correct":1,"rationale":"gRPC relies on HTTP/2's multiplexing and binary framing. A server configured only for HTTP/1.1 rejects gRPC calls with a protocol error. Option A is what REST typically uses. Option C (WebSocket) is a different real-time protocol used by SignalR. Option D skips the HTTP framing entirely; gRPC is built on HTTP/2, not raw TCP.","source":"slides/gRPC.pptx; research-grpc.md","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-grpc-06","type":"MCQ","topic":"gRPC client factory registration","marks":1,"question":"Which call registers a typed gRPC client in ASP.NET Core DI?","choices":["`builder.Services.AddGrpcClient\u003cStudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient\u003e(o =\u003e o.Address = new Uri(url))`","`builder.Services.AddSingleton(new GrpcChannel(url))`","`builder.Services.AddGrpc\u003cStudentRemoteClient\u003e()`","`builder.Services.RegisterGrpcClient\u003cT\u003e(url)`"],"correct":0,"rationale":"`AddGrpcClient\u003cT\u003e` comes from `Grpc.Net.ClientFactory` NuGet and wires channel pooling + resilience + service discovery. Option B registers a raw channel via singleton, bypassing the factory's benefits. Option C confuses client-side registration with server-side `AddGrpc()`. Option D invents a `RegisterGrpcClient` method that doesn't exist.","source":"notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-grpc-07","type":"MCQ","topic":"gRPC call types","marks":1,"question":"Which gRPC call type sends one request and receives a stream of responses?","choices":["Unary RPC","Server streaming RPC","Client streaming RPC","Bidirectional streaming RPC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Server streaming: 1 → N, client sends one request, server replies with multiple messages. Option A (Unary) is 1 → 1. Option C (Client streaming) is N → 1 (client sends multiple, server replies once). Option D (Bidirectional) is N ↔ N. In the .proto, server streaming is declared as `rpc List (Request) returns (stream Response);`.","source":"research-grpc.md","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-tdd-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"TDD cycle","marks":1,"question":"Which phase sequence describes one TDD iteration?","choices":["Design → Implement → Test","Red → Green → Refactor","Plan → Code → Ship","Test → Debug → Deploy"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Red (failing test first), Green (minimum code to pass), Refactor (clean up while keeping tests green) is the canonical TDD loop. Option A is traditional waterfall order — write code first, then test. Option C is a shipping cadence, not a development method. Option D is a debug workflow, not TDD's test-first ordering.","source":"slides/TDD_xunit.pptx; research-tdd.md","bloom":"remember","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-tdd-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"xUnit test attribute","marks":1,"question":"Which attribute marks a single-scenario xUnit test method?","choices":["`[Test]`","`[TestMethod]`","`[Fact]`","`[Scenario]`"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`[Fact]` is xUnit's single-scenario test attribute. Option A (`[Test]`) is NUnit. Option B (`[TestMethod]`) is MSTest. Option D is fabricated. Different frameworks intentionally use different attribute names to avoid accidental runtime coupling; know which framework you're in.","source":"slides/TDD_xunit.pptx","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-tdd-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"xUnit parameterized test","marks":1,"question":"You want one test method that runs with three different input sets. Which combination is correct?","choices":["`[Fact]` plus three `[Data(...)]` attributes","`[Theory]` plus three `[InlineData(...)]` attributes","`[TestCase(...)]` three times","`[ParameterizedTest]` with an array parameter"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`[Theory]` marks a parameterized test, and data attributes (`[InlineData]`, `[MemberData]`, `[ClassData]`) supply arguments per execution. One `[Theory]` + three `[InlineData]` = three runs. Option A mixes `[Fact]` (wrong — takes no data) with `[Data]` (not a real xUnit attribute). Option C is NUnit syntax. Option D is a fabrication.","source":"research-tdd.md §Key Concepts","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-tdd-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"Assert.Equal argument order","marks":1,"question":"Which is the correct call order for asserting that `calc.Add(2, 3)` returns 5?","choices":["`Assert.Equal(calc.Add(2, 3), 5)`","`Assert.Equal(5, calc.Add(2, 3))`","`Assert.Equal(actual: calc.Add(2, 3), expected: 5)` — named args make order irrelevant","Both options A and B are equivalent in practice"],"correct":1,"rationale":"xUnit's convention is expected first, actual second. The framework reports \"Expected: X, Actual: Y\" in failure messages based on that order — reversing produces misleading messages. Option A has arguments swapped; the test still passes or fails correctly (the comparison is symmetric), but the failure diagnostics lie. Option C is technically true for named args but relies on naming discipline every time. Option D is dangerous complacency — the underlying comparison is symmetric, but the DIAGNOSTIC output is not.","source":"research-tdd.md","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-tdd-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"xUnit lifecycle","marks":1,"question":"In xUnit, how do you run setup code before each test in a class?","choices":["Attribute a method with `[Setup]`","Attribute a method with `[BeforeEach]`","Put the code in the test class's constructor","Override an inherited `Initialize` method"],"correct":2,"rationale":"xUnit instantiates the test class fresh for EACH test. The constructor runs before every test. No `[Setup]` / `[BeforeEach]` attributes exist in xUnit — those are NUnit/MSTest conventions. Option D fabricates an inherited method. The design relies on standard C# object lifecycle: constructor = setup, `IDisposable.Dispose` = teardown.","source":"research-tdd.md","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-tdd-06","type":"MCQ","topic":"TDD Third Law","marks":1,"question":"Under Robert Martin's Three Laws of TDD, a developer writes `public int Add(int a, int b) =\u003e a + b;` as the Green-phase response to a single test asserting `Add(2, 3) == 5`. What's the issue?","choices":["The code is fine — this is standard TDD","This violates the Third Law by writing more production code than the failing test demands; `return 5;` would be minimal","The code should use `a - b` first, then refactor","The test should use `int.TryAdd` instead of `+`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Strict TDD says production code should be just enough to pass the current test. A single test `Add(2, 3) == 5` can be satisfied by `return 5;`. The more general `a + b` is added only when a second test (e.g. `Add(4, 5) == 9`) forces it. This enforces that every generalization is test-backed. Option A misses the strict interpretation. Option C is nonsense. Option D invents a method and misses the point entirely.","source":"research-tdd.md §Robert C. Martin's 3 Laws","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-aspire-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Aspire AppHost builder","marks":1,"question":"Which call creates the orchestrator builder in an Aspire AppHost's `Program.cs`?","choices":["`WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args)`","`DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args)`","`Host.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)`","`AppHostBuilder.Create(args)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"AppHost's entry point is `DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args)`. Option A is for ordinary ASP.NET Core web apps, not the orchestrator. Option C is generic-host creation. Option D fabricates `AppHostBuilder`. The distinct type (`DistributedApplication`) distinguishes the orchestrator from the services it orchestrates.","source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; research-aspire.md","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-aspire-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"AddServiceDefaults placement","marks":1,"question":"Where does `builder.AddServiceDefaults()` belong?","choices":["In the AppHost's `Program.cs`","In each individual service project's `Program.cs`","In the `ServiceDefaults.csproj` entry point","In `appsettings.json`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`AddServiceDefaults` registers service-discovery, OpenTelemetry, health checks, and resilience on the current service. AppHost is the orchestrator and doesn't need these. Option A is the single most common misconfiguration — putting it in AppHost makes the orchestrator try to register telemetry on itself and breaks boot. Option C is false — ServiceDefaults is a library, not an entry point. Option D is false — appsettings holds config, not extension-method calls.","source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; research-aspire.md","bloom":"apply","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-aspire-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Aspire logical names + service discovery","marks":1,"question":"In the AppHost: `builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Api\u003e(\"backend\")`. How should the frontend call the backend?","choices":["`http://localhost:5099`","`http://backend`","`http://192.168.1.5:8080`","`https://backend.prod.company.com`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Logical names replace hardcoded URLs. `http://backend/` is resolved by Aspire's service-discovery protocol handler at runtime. Option A hardcodes a local port (works in one-env dev but breaks under Aspire's dynamic port allocation). Option C hardcodes an IP (breaks on container restart). Option D hardcodes prod DNS (breaks in dev). The logical-name approach works identically across all environments — dev, CI, prod.","source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; research-aspire.md","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-aspire-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"Aspire database orchestration","marks":1,"question":"Which AppHost code registers a SQL Server container with a database named `cms`?","choices":["`builder.AddDatabase(\"cms\", provider: \"SqlServer\")`","`builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\")`","`builder.Services.AddDbContext\u003cCmsDb\u003e()`","`builder.AddSqlServer(\"cms\")`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`AddSqlServer` registers the server resource; `.AddDatabase` chains a database on it. Option A inverts the relationship and fabricates a top-level `AddDatabase`. Option C is EF Core DI registration — belongs in the service's Program.cs, not the AppHost. Option D names the server as `cms` — not quite wrong but doesn't create a named database resource the service can `WithReference` to.","source":"research-aspire.md","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-aspire-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"Aspire dependency ordering","marks":1,"question":"You want `frontend` to start only after `backend` reports healthy. Which AppHost chain does that?","choices":["`builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Frontend\u003e(\"frontend\").WithReference(backend)`","`builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Frontend\u003e(\"frontend\").WithReference(backend).WaitFor(backend)`","`builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Frontend\u003e(\"frontend\").After(backend)`","`builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Frontend\u003e(\"frontend\").DependsOn(backend)`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`WithReference` injects the config; `WaitFor` gates startup on health. Option A only wires config — the frontend can start before the backend is healthy. Option C fabricates `.After(...)`. Option D fabricates `.DependsOn(...)`. The pair `WithReference` + `WaitFor` is the canonical recipe for \"frontend depends on backend.\"","source":"research-aspire.md","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-loc-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Resource file location","marks":1,"question":"Your page is `Pages/Index.cshtml.cs` (class `IndexModel`). Where does the French resource file go?","choices":["`Resources/IndexModel.fr.resx`","`Resources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx`","`Resources/Pages/Index.fr.resx`","`Localization/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Directory structure under `Resources/` must mirror the class's project location. Option A misses the `Pages/` subfolder — the file exists but isn't found. Option C uses the page name `Index` instead of the class name `IndexModel` — wrong. Option D uses `Localization/` instead of `Resources/` (the latter is the convention; change only if you configure `ResourcesPath` differently).","source":"research-localization.md MCQ #2","bloom":"apply","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-loc-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"CurrentCulture vs CurrentUICulture","marks":1,"question":"Setting only `Thread.CurrentCulture = new CultureInfo(\"fr-FR\")` (and not `CurrentUICulture`) produces what behavior?","choices":["Everything localizes normally","Numbers and dates render in French format, but UI strings stay in the default language","UI strings translate to French, but numbers stay in default format","An exception on the next request"],"correct":1,"rationale":"CurrentCulture controls formatting (ToString on dates/numbers). CurrentUICulture controls which .resx loads. Set only the first and your numbers are French but your labels are English. `UseRequestLocalization()` middleware normally sets both from the detected culture. Option A misses the half-configuration failure. Option C reverses the two properties. Option D invents an exception that doesn't occur.","source":"research-localization.md §2","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-loc-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"Culture provider order","marks":1,"question":"In which order do the default culture providers run?","choices":["AcceptLanguageHeader → Cookie → QueryString","QueryString → Cookie → AcceptLanguageHeader","Cookie → QueryString → AcceptLanguageHeader","All providers run in parallel; the response of the slowest one wins"],"correct":1,"rationale":"QueryString first (highest priority; useful for testing and deep links), then Cookie (persistent user selection), then AcceptLanguageHeader (browser default). First match wins. Option A inverts the order — the header would dominate, defeating in-app selectors. Option C swaps the first two. Option D fabricates parallelism; middleware runs providers serially, first match wins.","source":"research-localization.md §4","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-loc-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"IViewLocalizer registration","marks":1,"question":"`@inject IViewLocalizer Localizer` in `Index.cshtml` fails at runtime with \"No service registered.\" `AddLocalization` is called. What's missing?","choices":["A `[Localized]` attribute on the page","`builder.Services.AddMvc().AddViewLocalization()` (or the equivalent on `AddRazorPages()`)","A corresponding `.resx` file","An explicit `Resources/` folder in the project root"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`AddLocalization` registers `IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` and `IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` but NOT `IViewLocalizer`. The view-scoped localizer requires `AddViewLocalization()` on the MVC or Razor Pages builder. Option A invents an attribute. Option C is false — a missing .resx doesn't throw; it returns the key itself. Option D is false — the folder comes from `ResourcesPath`, with a default value that works regardless of whether the folder exists.","source":"research-localization.md §Exam Trap 5","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-th-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Tag Helper attribute naming","marks":1,"question":"A Tag Helper has `public string? FontFamily { get; set; }`. The page author writes `\u003ctoon fontfamily=\"arial\"\u003e`. What happens?","choices":["The `FontFamily` property is set to `\"arial\"`","The `FontFamily` property stays null; Razor expects `font-family=\"arial\"` (kebab-case)","A runtime exception is thrown","The attribute is passed through unchanged to the rendered HTML"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Razor auto-translates PascalCase C# properties to kebab-case HTML attributes. `FontFamily` → `font-family`. The `fontfamily` (all lowercase, no hyphen) doesn't match, so the property stays at its default (null for string). No exception; the Tag Helper simply runs with an unset property. Option A is the common misconception — `fontfamily` \"looks close enough\" but the kebab-case rule is strict.","source":"research-taghelpers-blazor.md","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-th-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"Tag Helper registration location","marks":1,"question":"Where do you register a custom Tag Helper so it's available to every Razor page in your app?","choices":["In each `.cshtml` page via `@taghelper`","In `Program.cs` via `builder.Services.AddTagHelpers\u003cT\u003e()`","In `_ViewImports.cshtml` via `@addTagHelper *, AssemblyName`","In `appsettings.json` under `TagHelpers:*`"],"correct":2,"rationale":"`_ViewImports.cshtml` is the central file Razor reads for per-directory Tag Helper registration. `@addTagHelper *, AssemblyName` imports every Tag Helper from the assembly. Option A would work if `@taghelper` were a real directive; it isn't. Option B fabricates an `AddTagHelpers` method. Option D invents a config section; Tag Helpers are not DI-registered, they're Razor-registered via the view-imports file.","source":"research-taghelpers-blazor.md","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-th-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"ProcessAsync vs Process","marks":1,"question":"Your Tag Helper fetches data from an HTTP API. Which override do you use?","choices":["`public override void Process(TagHelperContext context, TagHelperOutput output)` with `.Result` on the task","`public override async Task ProcessAsync(TagHelperContext context, TagHelperOutput output)` with `await`","`public override string Render(TagHelperContext context)` returning the HTML","Either works identically"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Override `ProcessAsync` for any Tag Helper that awaits. Option A blocks on `.Result`, which can deadlock in the Razor render pipeline and kills performance under load. Option C fabricates a `Render` method; the real output mechanism is mutating `output` inside the override. Option D is dangerous — sync `.Result` in Razor can deadlock, so the two forms are not interchangeable when async work is involved.","source":"notes/TagHelpers_SCRIPT.docx; research-taghelpers-blazor.md","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-blazor-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"TemplateColumn sorting","marks":1,"question":"`\u003cTemplateColumn Title=\"Name\" Sortable=\"true\"\u003e` renders correctly but the header doesn't sort when clicked. Why?","choices":["`TemplateColumn` is not a valid QuickGrid component","`TemplateColumn` ignores `Sortable`; you must supply `SortBy=\"@someGridSort\"` instead","Sorting requires the page to be `@rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly`","QuickGrid doesn't support sorting on computed columns"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`PropertyColumn` infers the sort key from its `Property` expression, so `Sortable=\"true\"` is enough. `TemplateColumn` renders arbitrary markup — QuickGrid cannot guess what to sort by. You must supply `SortBy=\"@GridSort\u003cT\u003e.ByAscending(x =\u003e x.Field)\"`. Option A is false. Option C is false — InteractiveServer also sorts fine. Option D is false — QuickGrid supports sort on any expression you provide.","source":"research-taghelpers-blazor.md","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-blazor-02","type":"MCQ","topic":"QuickGrid live filter binding","marks":1,"question":"An input `\u003cinput @bind=\"_filter\" /\u003e` tied to a computed `IQueryable` filter appears not to update the grid until the user tabs out of the input. What's the minimal fix?","choices":["Add `@onkeyup=\"StateHasChanged\"`","Add `@bind:event=\"oninput\"`","Call `InvokeAsync(StateHasChanged)` manually","Wrap the grid in a `\u003cCascadingValue\u003e`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The default `@bind` event is `onchange`, which fires on focus loss. `@bind:event=\"oninput\"` changes it to fire per keystroke. Option A adds an extra handler that works but is redundant — `@bind` already triggers a re-render. Option C is also redundant; @bind's round-trip already calls StateHasChanged. Option D is unrelated — CascadingValue shares state across components, not the issue here.","source":"notes/BlazorServer_QuickGrid.docx","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-excel-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"ClosedXML indexing","marks":1,"question":"In ClosedXML, which call addresses the top-left cell A1?","choices":["`worksheet.Cell(0, 0)`","`worksheet.Cell(1, 1)`","`worksheet.Cell(\"A\", 1)`","`worksheet.Cell[0][0]`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ClosedXML cells are 1-based, matching Excel's UI (row 1, column A). Option A treats cells as 0-based like C# arrays — produces either an exception or silent no-op depending on the version. Option C invents a string-based overload. Option D is indexer syntax that ClosedXML doesn't expose. If your data loop starts at row 2 (row 1 is headers), your counter starts at 2, not 0 or 1.","source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail; research-excel-pdf-chart.md","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-pdf-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"iText MemoryStream position","marks":1,"question":"Your PDF handler writes into a `MemoryStream`, then returns `new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\")`. The download is a 0-byte file. What's the fix?","choices":["Change the MIME type to `application/octet-stream`","Set `ms.Position = 0` before constructing the FileStreamResult","Call `ms.Flush()` before returning","Use `new MemoryStream(ms.ToArray())` to copy the buffer"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After writing, MemoryStream's position sits at the end. FileStreamResult reads from current position, finds zero bytes, delivers an empty file. Rewinding fixes it. Option A changes the MIME but still streams zero bytes. Option C (`Flush`) is a no-op for MemoryStream. Option D would work (materializes bytes at position 0) but allocates twice; simpler to rewind. Alternative: `return File(ms.ToArray(), mime, name)` is position-insensitive.","source":"research-excel-pdf-chart.md","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-chart-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Razor @: directive","marks":1,"question":"Inside a Razor `\u003cscript\u003e` block iterating `Model.ChartData`, how do you emit a JavaScript `push` call per iteration?","choices":["`@foreach (var x in Model.ChartData) { labels.push('@x.Name'); }`","`@foreach (var x in Model.ChartData) { @:labels.push('@x.Name'); }`","`@foreach (var x in Model.ChartData) { Html.Raw(\"labels.push('\" + x.Name + \"');\") }`","`\u003c@foreach (var x in Model.ChartData)\u003elabels.push('@x.Name');\u003c/foreach\u003e`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The `@:` directive tells Razor to treat a line as literal output with `@`-expression substitutions. Without it, Razor tries to parse the whole line as C# and errors or produces malformed JS. Option A writes C# that calls a JS method — nonsense at compile time. Option C uses `Html.Raw` but stacks too much ceremony; `@:` is idiomatic. Option D invents XML-like Razor syntax that doesn't exist.","source":"research-excel-pdf-chart.md §Chart.js","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-xcut-01","type":"MCQ","topic":"Cheat-sheet permission","marks":1,"question":"The final exam allows which cheat sheet?","choices":["No cheat sheet — closed book","One hand-written 8.5\" × 11\" sheet, both sides","Unlimited printed material","A laptop with PDF notes open"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The instructor's explicit note: one hand-written, 8.5\" × 11\", both sides. Printed material is not allowed. A laptop is not allowed. Plan your sheet deliberately — high-value content is exact method names, NuGet packages, and CLI shapes. Prose is a waste of space.","source":"courses/COMP4870/4870 final exam details.txt","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-xcut-02","type":"SHORT","topic":"ML.NET pipeline skeleton","marks":1,"question":"Name the five pipeline steps in correct order for an ML.NET regression on a CSV with categorical features (use short names: Load, CopyLabel, OneHot, Concat, Train).","correct":"Load → CopyLabel → OneHot → Concat → Train","rationale":"The canonical order is Load (LoadFromTextFile), CopyLabel (CopyColumns renames target to \"Label\"), OneHot (encode each categorical column), Concat (combine into \"Features\"), Train (FastTree or similar). Reversing any of the middle three breaks because each step consumes the output of the previous. The trainer always goes last because it reads from \"Features\" and \"Label\" that earlier steps produced.","source":"research-mlnet.md §Training Pipeline Anatomy","bloom":"remember","tags":["pretest"]},{"id":"mq-xcut-03","type":"MCQ","topic":"MCP transport","marks":1,"question":"The Model Context Protocol (MCP) defines two transports. Which transport is synchronous, process-spawned, and uses stdin/stdout pipes?","choices":["SSE (Server-Sent Events)","stdio","WebSocket","HTTP/2"],"correct":1,"rationale":"MCP's two transports are `stdio` (synchronous, process-spawned, stdin/stdout — low overhead, good for local tools) and SSE (asynchronous, HTTP-based, good for remote servers). Option A is the other transport — asynchronous. Option C (WebSocket) is not an MCP transport. Option D is a generic HTTP version, not an MCP transport name.","source":"research-ai.md §MCP","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-xcut-04","type":"MCQ","topic":"NuGet package names","marks":1,"question":"Which package is required IN ADDITION TO `itext7` for full PDF generation?","choices":["`itext7.bouncycastle`","`itext.bouncy-castle-adapter`","`System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates`","No additional package needed"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The package is `itext.bouncy-castle-adapter` (exact NuGet casing and hyphenation). Option A is close but uses `itext7.bouncycastle` (wrong name — mixing the version in and missing the hyphens). Option C is a BCL assembly, not a NuGet requirement for iText. Option D is the most dangerous — installing only itext7 compiles fine but crashes at runtime when iText needs crypto.","source":"research-excel-pdf-chart.md","bloom":"remember"},{"id":"mq-xcut-05","type":"MCQ","topic":"MAF + SK interop","marks":1,"question":"Can you call `kernel.InvokeAsync(...)` inside an MAF agent's tool handler to reuse a Semantic Kernel function?","choices":["Yes — MAF and SK share the same kernel","Not directly — they are separate SDKs with different entry points, though you can wrap an SK-driven method as an AITool","Only if you set `MafKernelBridge = true`","Only in ASP.NET Core apps"],"correct":1,"rationale":"MAF and SK are separate SDKs. `kernel.InvokeAsync` is SK; `agent.RunAsync` is MAF. They don't share an object graph, but you can write a plain C# method that uses SK internally and register it as an MAF `AITool` via `AIFunctionFactory.Create`. Option A confuses the two. Option C invents a flag. Option D invents a platform constraint.","source":"research-ai.md §Traps","bloom":"analyze"},{"id":"mq-xcut-06","type":"MCQ","topic":"xUnit data attribute variety","marks":1,"question":"For a `[Theory]` test whose data requires computation or doesn't fit in an attribute, which data attribute is best?","choices":["`[InlineData(...)]`","`[MemberData(nameof(DataProvider))]`","`[HugeData]`","`[RandomData]`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"`[MemberData]` references a static member (property, field, or method) that returns `IEnumerable\u003cobject[]\u003e` — allowing computed or complex data. `[ClassData]` is similar but uses a dedicated class. `[InlineData]` only takes literal arguments. Options C and D are fabrications.","source":"research-tdd.md","bloom":"understand"},{"id":"mq-xcut-07","type":"MCQ","topic":"Aspire Redis + service integration","marks":1,"question":"Under Aspire, how does a service consume a Redis resource registered as `builder.AddRedis(\"cache\")`?","choices":["Hardcode `opts.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\"` in the service","The service calls `builder.AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\")`; Aspire injects the connection string automatically","The service reads `appsettings.json` for `ConnectionStrings:Redis`","Aspire doesn't support Redis"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Aspire's `AddRedisDistributedCache(name)` helper reads the injected connection string by logical name (`cache`). The AppHost's `WithReference(cache)` is what actually injects it. Option A hardcodes and bypasses every Aspire benefit (dynamic ports, service discovery). Option C requires manual config that Aspire is designed to eliminate. Option D is false — `AddRedis` and `AddRedisDistributedCache` are both first-class Aspire integrations.","source":"research-aspire.md","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-xcut-08","type":"MCQ","topic":"File-based web app minimal boot","marks":1,"question":"The minimal code to write a file-based web API with one GET endpoint is approximately:","choices":["One line, no directives needed","Three lines plus `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` at the top","Requires 10+ lines of middleware setup","Requires a separate launchSettings.json file"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A minimal web API is literally `var app = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build(); app.MapGet(\"/\", () =\u003e \"Hi\"); app.Run();` plus the `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` directive. Option A omits the SDK switch — won't find WebApplication. Option C is true only for complex apps with auth/middleware. Option D is false — file-based apps need no launchSettings.json.","source":"research-file-based.md","bloom":"apply"},{"id":"mq-xcut-09","type":"MCQ","topic":"Blazor rendermode interactive","marks":1,"question":"Your Blazor page shows a gRPC result on initial load but the page's click handlers do nothing. Which directive at the top of the .razor file is likely missing?","choices":["`@page \"/students\"`","`@rendermode InteractiveServer`","`@using Grpc.Net.Client`","`@inject HttpClient Http`"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Without an interactive render mode (`InteractiveServer` or `InteractiveWebAssembly` or `InteractiveAuto`), Blazor renders statically — the initial HTML is fine, but clicks and events have no runtime behind them. Option A is required for the page to route at all but doesn't affect interactivity. Option C imports a namespace but doesn't enable interactivity. Option D injects an HttpClient but doesn't alter rendering mode.","source":"Labs/W09 gRPC/","bloom":"analyze"}]},"lessons":[{"n":0,"id":"4870-exam-strategy","title":"Exam strategy and pitfalls","hook":"Time allocation, top pitfalls, when to skip.","tags":["strategy","exam-prep"],"module":"Exam prep","kind":"strategy","source":"courses/COMP4870/4870 final exam details.txt + materials/past-exams/midterm_exam_questions.md + materials/notes/* + generated/exam-study/research-*.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The exam in one sentence","text":"The exam in one sentence"},{"kind":"p","html":"80 marks, 60 minutes, single room (SE12-327), Friday 2026-04-24 10:30–11:30 AM. Bring one hand-written 8.5&quot; × 11&quot; cheat sheet — both sides fair game.","text":"80 marks, 60 minutes, single room (SE12-327), Friday 2026-04-24 10:30–11:30 AM. Bring one hand-written 8.5\" × 11\" cheat sheet — both sides fair game."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Format and marks","text":"Format and marks"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSection\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth align=\"right\"\u003eCount\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth align=\"right\"\u003eMarks each\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth align=\"right\"\u003eSection marks\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth align=\"right\"\u003eTime budget\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMultiple choice\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e60\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e60\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e~40 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMatch two columns\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e10\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e10\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e~5 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCoding question\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e10\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e10\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e~12 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReview / skipped\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e~3 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTotal\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e71\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e80\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd align=\"right\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e60 min\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The MCQ + match pool covers 11 pre-announced topics. The coding question&#39;s topic is not announced — assume it comes from one of the heavy buckets (AI, ML.NET, Cache/Redis, File-based apps, or gRPC).","text":"The MCQ + match pool covers 11 pre-announced topics. The coding question's topic is not announced — assume it comes from one of the heavy buckets (AI, ML.NET, Cache/Redis, File-based apps, or gRPC)."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Topic weights — where the marks live","text":"Topic weights — where the marks live"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"AI ................ 13 marks (16%)   ← heaviest; MAF + Semantic Kernel + SLM/Ollama\nML.NET ............ 12 marks (15%)   ← pipeline + metrics\nCache/Redis ....... 8 marks  (10%)\nFile-based apps ... 8 marks  (10%)\ngRPC .............. 7 marks  (9%)\nTDD ............... 6 marks  (8%)\nAspire ............ 5 marks  (6%)\nLocalization ...... 4 marks  (5%)\nTag Helpers ....... 3 marks  (4%)\nBlazor (QuickGrid)  2 marks  (3%)\nExcel/PDF/Chart ... 2 marks  (3%)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Study proportionally. If the cheat sheet is 8.5&quot; × 11&quot; double-sided, AI + ML.NET + Cache/Redis together deserve ~40% of the real estate.","text":"Study proportionally. If the cheat sheet is 8.5\" × 11\" double-sided, AI + ML.NET + Cache/Redis together deserve ~40% of the real estate."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Time allocation per question","text":"Time allocation per question"},{"kind":"p","html":"The 60-minute clock breaks down as 45 seconds per mark. In practice, not every mark burns 45 seconds — MCQ/match questions average ~40 seconds; the coding question gets the remaining block.","text":"The 60-minute clock breaks down as 45 seconds per mark. In practice, not every mark burns 45 seconds — MCQ/match questions average ~40 seconds; the coding question gets the remaining block."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMCQ rhythm.\u003c/strong\u003e Read the stem twice. If the answer leaps out within 15 seconds, commit and move on. If not, eliminate the two most obviously wrong choices, mark the remaining two with a dot on the paper, and move on. Come back to dotted questions in the review pass.","text":"**MCQ rhythm.** Read the stem twice. If the answer leaps out within 15 seconds, commit and move on. If not, eliminate the two most obviously wrong choices, mark the remaining two with a dot on the paper, and move on. Come back to dotted questions in the review pass."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMatch rhythm.\u003c/strong\u003e Scan all 10 pairs before committing to any. Start with pairs where one side is unique jargon (e.g. a specific CLI command, a specific NuGet package). Work from certainty outward.","text":"**Match rhythm.** Scan all 10 pairs before committing to any. Start with pairs where one side is unique jargon (e.g. a specific CLI command, a specific NuGet package). Work from certainty outward."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eCoding rhythm.\u003c/strong\u003e Read the prompt fully before touching the pen. Sketch the signature, write the body, then cross-check edge cases. Twelve minutes is tight — don&#39;t aim for the most elegant solution, aim for the most correct one.","text":"**Coding rhythm.** Read the prompt fully before touching the pen. Sketch the signature, write the body, then cross-check edge cases. Twelve minutes is tight — don't aim for the most elegant solution, aim for the most correct one."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When to skip and return","text":"When to skip and return"},{"kind":"p","html":"Skip any question that:","text":"Skip any question that:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBurns more than 90 seconds without a clear path. Two skipped questions cost ~90 seconds; two wrong-but-committed questions cost 2 marks. Skipping is cheaper.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHinges on a term you genuinely don&#39;t recognize. Distractors target confusion; without a foothold, guessing among five options is a 20% hit rate.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUses a code-fence stem longer than five lines. These are traps dressed as tests — come back when your head is fresh.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Burns more than 90 seconds without a clear path. Two skipped questions cost ~90 seconds; two wrong-but-committed questions cost 2 marks. Skipping is cheaper.\n- Hinges on a term you genuinely don't recognize. Distractors target confusion; without a foothold, guessing among five options is a 20% hit rate.\n- Uses a code-fence stem longer than five lines. These are traps dressed as tests — come back when your head is fresh."},{"kind":"p","html":"Mark skips with a single dot in the margin. At minute 45, do a focused review pass on dotted questions only.","text":"Mark skips with a single dot in the margin. At minute 45, do a focused review pass on dotted questions only."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Top pitfalls — by topic","text":"Top pitfalls — by topic"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every pitfall below is sourced from lecture scripts, research notes, or the midterm&#39;s distractor patterns. No invented hazards.","text":"Every pitfall below is sourced from lecture scripts, research notes, or the midterm's distractor patterns. No invented hazards."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall 1 — \u003ccode\u003e#:package\u003c/code\u003e has no space after the colon.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003e#: package Spectre.Console@0.49.1\u003c/code\u003e is a syntax error. The correct form is \u003ccode\u003e#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1\u003c/code\u003e. Expect at least one distractor option presenting the spaced form as plausible. Source: \u003ccode\u003enotes/file-based-apps.docx\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003eresearch-file-based.md §directives\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Pitfall 1 — `#:package` has no space after the colon.**\n`#: package Spectre.Console@0.49.1` is a syntax error. The correct form is `#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1`. Expect at least one distractor option presenting the spaced form as plausible. Source: `notes/file-based-apps.docx`; `research-file-based.md §directives`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall 2 — \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e does not survive a web farm.\u003c/strong\u003e\nWhen asked &quot;which cache abstraction works across multiple app servers behind a load balancer,&quot; the answer is \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e (backed by Redis), not \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e is per-process; each server holds its own copy, so data written on server A is invisible on server B. Source: \u003ccode\u003enotes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003eresearch-cache.md §architecture\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Pitfall 2 — `IMemoryCache` does not survive a web farm.**\nWhen asked \"which cache abstraction works across multiple app servers behind a load balancer,\" the answer is `IDistributedCache` (backed by Redis), not `IMemoryCache`. `IMemoryCache` is per-process; each server holds its own copy, so data written on server A is invisible on server B. Source: `notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx`; `research-cache.md §architecture`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall 3 — ML.NET trainers look for a column literally named \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003emlContext.Transforms.Concatenate(outputColumnName: &quot;Features&quot;, …)\u003c/code\u003e — the string \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e is not a convention, it&#39;s a contract. Rename it to \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Input&quot;\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e&quot;X&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eFastTree()\u003c/code\u003e cannot find the input. Same goes for \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e on the target side. Source: \u003ccode\u003eslides/ML.NET.pptx p.14\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003eresearch-mlnet.md §transforms\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Pitfall 3 — ML.NET trainers look for a column literally named `\"Features\"`.**\n`mlContext.Transforms.Concatenate(outputColumnName: \"Features\", …)` — the string `\"Features\"` is not a convention, it's a contract. Rename it to `\"Input\"` or `\"X\"` and `FastTree()` cannot find the input. Same goes for `\"Label\"` on the target side. Source: `slides/ML.NET.pptx p.14`; `research-mlnet.md §transforms`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall 4 — \u003ccode\u003eCurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e are not the same thing.\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003eCurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e drives date, number, and currency formatting. \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e drives which \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e file loads. Setting only one produces a page where numbers are translated but text is not (or vice versa). \u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e sets both when configured correctly; forgetting the middleware call leaves both at system default. Source: \u003ccode\u003enotes/razor_pages_localization_SCRIPT.docx\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003eresearch-localization.md\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Pitfall 4 — `CurrentCulture` and `CurrentUICulture` are not the same thing.**\n`CurrentCulture` drives date, number, and currency formatting. `CurrentUICulture` drives which `.resx` file loads. Setting only one produces a page where numbers are translated but text is not (or vice versa). `UseRequestLocalization()` sets both when configured correctly; forgetting the middleware call leaves both at system default. Source: `notes/razor_pages_localization_SCRIPT.docx`; `research-localization.md`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall 5 — \u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e belongs in each service&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e, NOT in the AppHost.\u003c/strong\u003e\nThe AppHost&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e calls \u003ccode\u003eDistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args)\u003c/code\u003e and then \u003ccode\u003e.AddProject&lt;&gt;()\u003c/code\u003e. Each individual service&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e calls \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.AddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e to pick up service discovery, OpenTelemetry, and health endpoints. Swapping these breaks the boot. Source: \u003ccode\u003enotes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003eresearch-aspire.md §defaults\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Pitfall 5 — `AddServiceDefaults()` belongs in each service's `Program.cs`, NOT in the AppHost.**\nThe AppHost's `Program.cs` calls `DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args)` and then `.AddProject\u003c\u003e()`. Each individual service's `Program.cs` calls `builder.AddServiceDefaults()` to pick up service discovery, OpenTelemetry, and health endpoints. Swapping these breaks the boot. Source: `notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx`; `research-aspire.md §defaults`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Domain-specific traps — beyond the top 5","text":"Domain-specific traps — beyond the top 5"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMemoryStream position.\u003c/strong\u003e When returning a \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e for a PDF or XLSX you just wrote into a \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e, set \u003ccode\u003ems.Position = 0\u003c/code\u003e before returning. Skip the reset and the client downloads an empty file. Source: \u003ccode\u003eresearch-excel-pdf-chart.md §pdf\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**MemoryStream position.** When returning a `FileStreamResult` for a PDF or XLSX you just wrote into a `MemoryStream`, set `ms.Position = 0` before returning. Skip the reset and the client downloads an empty file. Source: `research-excel-pdf-chart.md §pdf`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eiText7 + bouncy-castle-adapter.\u003c/strong\u003e iText7 alone won&#39;t run — you need both \u003ccode\u003eiText7\u003c/code\u003e AND \u003ccode\u003eitext.bouncy-castle-adapter\u003c/code\u003e NuGet packages. Forgetting the adapter produces a cryptic runtime error, not a build error. Source: \u003ccode\u003eresearch-excel-pdf-chart.md\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**iText7 + bouncy-castle-adapter.** iText7 alone won't run — you need both `iText7` AND `itext.bouncy-castle-adapter` NuGet packages. Forgetting the adapter produces a cryptic runtime error, not a build error. Source: `research-excel-pdf-chart.md`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003exUnit \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Equal(expected, actual)\u003c/code\u003e argument order.\u003c/strong\u003e Expected first, actual second. Reversing produces backwards error messages that waste debugging time. The argument order is not enforced by the compiler. Source: \u003ccode\u003eslides/TDD_xunit.pptx\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**xUnit `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` argument order.** Expected first, actual second. Reversing produces backwards error messages that waste debugging time. The argument order is not enforced by the compiler. Source: `slides/TDD_xunit.pptx`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eProtocol Buffer field tags are permanent.\u003c/strong\u003e Reusing a tag number for a different field breaks every deployed client that hasn&#39;t recompiled. Tags 1–15 are also special — they encode in one byte; tags 16+ take two. Source: \u003ccode\u003eresearch-grpc.md\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Protocol Buffer field tags are permanent.** Reusing a tag number for a different field breaks every deployed client that hasn't recompiled. Tags 1–15 are also special — they encode in one byte; tags 16+ take two. Source: `research-grpc.md`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eClosedXML cell indexing is 1-based.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eworksheet.Cell(1, 1)\u003c/code\u003e is the top-left cell. Not \u003ccode\u003e(0, 0)\u003c/code\u003e. Source: \u003ccode\u003eLabs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail.html\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**ClosedXML cell indexing is 1-based.** `worksheet.Cell(1, 1)` is the top-left cell. Not `(0, 0)`. Source: `Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail.html`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRoute attribute syntax uses parentheses, not brackets.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e[Route(&quot;api/[controller]&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e is correct. \u003ccode\u003e[Route[&quot;api/[controller]&quot;]]\u003c/code\u003e is a midterm distractor pattern (Q7) — it uses C# indexer syntax instead of method-call syntax. Carries forward into any final-exam routing question. Source: \u003ccode\u003ematerials/past-exams/midterm_exam_questions.md Q7\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Route attribute syntax uses parentheses, not brackets.** `[Route(\"api/[controller]\")]` is correct. `[Route[\"api/[controller]\"]]` is a midterm distractor pattern (Q7) — it uses C# indexer syntax instead of method-call syntax. Carries forward into any final-exam routing question. Source: `materials/past-exams/midterm_exam_questions.md Q7`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBlazor \u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e needs \u003ccode\u003eSortBy=\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003eSortable=\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ePropertyColumn\u003c/code\u003e accepts \u003ccode\u003eSortable=&quot;true&quot;\u003c/code\u003e directly. \u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e ignores \u003ccode\u003eSortable\u003c/code\u003e — you must supply \u003ccode\u003eSortBy=&quot;@GridSort&lt;T&gt;.ByAscending(x =&gt; x.Name)&quot;\u003c/code\u003e to make it sortable. Source: \u003ccode\u003enotes/BlazorServer_QuickGrid.docx\u003c/code\u003e; Labs/W07.","text":"**Blazor `TemplateColumn` needs `SortBy=`, not `Sortable=`.** `PropertyColumn` accepts `Sortable=\"true\"` directly. `TemplateColumn` ignores `Sortable` — you must supply `SortBy=\"@GridSort\u003cT\u003e.ByAscending(x =\u003e x.Name)\"` to make it sortable. Source: `notes/BlazorServer_QuickGrid.docx`; Labs/W07."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eAI endpoint confusion.\u003c/strong\u003e Ollama runs at \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:11434\u003c/code\u003e (HTTP, no path). GitHub Models runs at \u003ccode\u003ehttps://models.github.ai/inference\u003c/code\u003e (HTTPS, has \u003ccode\u003e/inference\u003c/code\u003e path). Azure OpenAI uses your deployment-specific URL plus a deployment name. Mixing these is a distractor gift. Source: \u003ccode\u003enotes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**AI endpoint confusion.** Ollama runs at `http://localhost:11434` (HTTP, no path). GitHub Models runs at `https://models.github.ai/inference` (HTTPS, has `/inference` path). Azure OpenAI uses your deployment-specific URL plus a deployment name. Mixing these is a distractor gift. Source: `notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.AsAIAgent()\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003e.AsAgent()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The MAF method to wrap an \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e into an agent is literally \u003ccode\u003e.AsAIAgent()\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e.AsAgent()\u003c/code\u003e doesn&#39;t exist. Source: \u003ccode\u003eresearch-ai.md §maf\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**`.AsAIAgent()`, not `.AsAgent()`.** The MAF method to wrap an `IChatClient` into an agent is literally `.AsAIAgent()`. `.AsAgent()` doesn't exist. Source: `research-ai.md §maf`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Off-by-one, unit, and ordering traps specific to this course","text":"Off-by-one, unit, and ordering traps specific to this course"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eClosedXML\u003c/code\u003e cells are 1-based\u003c/strong\u003e; C# arrays and \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e are 0-based. Mixing these breaks row/column math.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[LoadColumn(0)]\u003c/code\u003e on the first column\u003c/strong\u003e of a CSV in ML.NET is 0-based despite ClosedXML&#39;s opposite convention. Don&#39;t generalize across libraries.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProtobuf field tags start at 1\u003c/strong\u003e, not 0. Tag 0 is reserved.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePort 11434 for Ollama, 6379 for Redis, 1433 for SQL Server, 5432 for Postgres.\u003c/strong\u003e Aspire tends to pick ephemeral ports unless overridden — don&#39;t memorize ports for Aspire-managed services; memorize for stand-alone Docker runs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **`ClosedXML` cells are 1-based**; C# arrays and `List\u003cT\u003e` are 0-based. Mixing these breaks row/column math.\n- **`[LoadColumn(0)]` on the first column** of a CSV in ML.NET is 0-based despite ClosedXML's opposite convention. Don't generalize across libraries.\n- **Protobuf field tags start at 1**, not 0. Tag 0 is reserved.\n- **Port 11434 for Ollama, 6379 for Redis, 1433 for SQL Server, 5432 for Postgres.** Aspire tends to pick ephemeral ports unless overridden — don't memorize ports for Aspire-managed services; memorize for stand-alone Docker runs."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Cheat-sheet packing priorities","text":"Cheat-sheet packing priorities"},{"kind":"p","html":"Given one 8.5&quot; × 11&quot; page, two sides, prioritize this order. Items above the cut line are high-leverage per mark; below the cut line are nice-to-haves if space permits.","text":"Given one 8.5\" × 11\" page, two sides, prioritize this order. Items above the cut line are high-leverage per mark; below the cut line are nice-to-haves if space permits."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eML.NET pipeline skeleton\u003c/strong\u003e — every token of \u003ccode\u003eLoadFromTextFile → Concatenate(&quot;Features&quot;) → FastTree().Fit(data)\u003c/code\u003e. Boilerplate you shouldn&#39;t derive under time pressure.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMAF + Ollama 10-line boot snippet\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003eOllamaApiClient\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e.AsIChatClient()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eChatClientAgent\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e.RunAsync\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGetOrSetAsync\u003c/code\u003e signature + absolute/sliding expiration option object.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e file template\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003esyntax = &quot;proto3&quot;; service Foo { rpc Bar (X) returns (Y); } message X { int32 id = 1; }\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAspire AppHost skeleton\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003eCreateBuilder → AddProject&lt;&gt;(&quot;name&quot;) → WithReference → WaitFor\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[HtmlTargetElement]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync\u003c/code\u003e signature\u003c/strong\u003e for a tag helper.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLocalization setup three calls\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003eAddLocalization\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAddViewLocalization\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFile-based apps directive quick-reference\u003c/strong\u003e — four directive forms, no-space-after-colon reminder.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003exUnit attribute cheat row\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e[Fact]\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e[Theory]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[InlineData(...)]\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eQuickGrid column syntax\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003ePropertyColumn\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eSortBy\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eClosedXML \u003ccode\u003eworksheet.Cell(r, c).Value = x; wb.SaveAs(stream)\u003c/code\u003e one-liner.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eiText7 \u003ccode\u003ePdfWriter → PdfDocument → Document\u003c/code\u003e three-line open; \u003ccode\u003edoc.Close()\u003c/code\u003e close.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **ML.NET pipeline skeleton** — every token of `LoadFromTextFile → Concatenate(\"Features\") → FastTree().Fit(data)`. Boilerplate you shouldn't derive under time pressure.\n2. **MAF + Ollama 10-line boot snippet** — `OllamaApiClient` → `.AsIChatClient()` → `ChatClientAgent` → `.RunAsync`.\n3. **`GetOrSetAsync` signature + absolute/sliding expiration option object.**\n4. **`.proto` file template** — `syntax = \"proto3\"; service Foo { rpc Bar (X) returns (Y); } message X { int32 id = 1; }`.\n5. **Aspire AppHost skeleton** — `CreateBuilder → AddProject\u003c\u003e(\"name\") → WithReference → WaitFor`.\n6. **`[HtmlTargetElement]` + `ProcessAsync` signature** for a tag helper.\n7. **Localization setup three calls** — `AddLocalization`, `AddViewLocalization`, `UseRequestLocalization`.\n8. **File-based apps directive quick-reference** — four directive forms, no-space-after-colon reminder.\n9. **xUnit attribute cheat row** — `[Fact]`, `[Theory]` + `[InlineData(...)]`.\n10. **QuickGrid column syntax** — `PropertyColumn` vs `TemplateColumn` with `SortBy`.\n11. **ClosedXML `worksheet.Cell(r, c).Value = x; wb.SaveAs(stream)` one-liner.**\n12. **iText7 `PdfWriter → PdfDocument → Document` three-line open; `doc.Close()` close.**"},{"kind":"p","html":"Do NOT waste space on:","text":"Do NOT waste space on:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAnything you can reason about in under 30 seconds from a memorized concept (e.g. &quot;what&#39;s a Bloom filter&quot; — no, skip that, it&#39;s not on the exam anyway).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFull paragraphs of prose — the cheat sheet is for code skeletons and naming conventions, not textbook passages.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTopics from the midterm (Razor, MVC, EF foundations, Identity, JWT, SignalR) — they&#39;re \u003cstrong\u003eout of scope\u003c/strong\u003e for the final.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Anything you can reason about in under 30 seconds from a memorized concept (e.g. \"what's a Bloom filter\" — no, skip that, it's not on the exam anyway).\n- Full paragraphs of prose — the cheat sheet is for code skeletons and naming conventions, not textbook passages.\n- Topics from the midterm (Razor, MVC, EF foundations, Identity, JWT, SignalR) — they're **out of scope** for the final."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe midterm covered Razor Pages, MVC, Entity Framework foundations, Identity, JWT, and SignalR — none of those are on the final. If the cheat sheet you prepared for midterms is still in your head, consciously drop it. Re-studying midterm material costs time you need for AI + ML.NET.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The midterm covered Razor Pages, MVC, Entity Framework foundations, Identity, JWT, and SignalR — none of those are on the final. If the cheat sheet you prepared for midterms is still in your head, consciously drop it. Re-studying midterm material costs time you need for AI + ML.NET."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe final rewards \u003cem\u003especific\u003c/em\u003e recall of NuGet names, CLI shapes, and API method names. 70% of MCQ distractors are subtle renames of the correct answer. A cheat sheet that lists exact names and exact call signatures beats a cheat sheet that explains concepts. Teach yourself to flip to the sheet fast enough that the 60-second-per-question budget holds.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The final rewards *specific* recall of NuGet names, CLI shapes, and API method names. 70% of MCQ distractors are subtle renames of the correct answer. A cheat sheet that lists exact names and exact call signatures beats a cheat sheet that explains concepts. Teach yourself to flip to the sheet fast enough that the 60-second-per-question budget holds."}]},{"n":1,"id":"ai-agent-framework","title":"Microsoft Agent Framework (MAF) + tool calling","hook":"Wrap an `IChatClient` into an agent, register a C# method as a tool, and let the LLM decide when to call it.","tags":["ai","maf","agent","tools","function-calling"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx (Demos #2, #3); research-ai.md §maf","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The weather-poet agent","text":"The weather-poet agent"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have an \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e pointed at GitHub Models. You want it to answer &quot;What should I wear in Vancouver?&quot; by calling \u003ccode\u003eWeatherService.GetWeatherAsync(&quot;Vancouver&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e, reading the result, and writing a short poem. The Microsoft Agent Framework (MAF) turns that three-step pipeline into one \u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e call — the LLM picks the tool, MAF runs it, the LLM stitches the answer.","text":"You have an `IChatClient` pointed at GitHub Models. You want it to answer \"What should I wear in Vancouver?\" by calling `WeatherService.GetWeatherAsync(\"Vancouver\")`, reading the result, and writing a short poem. The Microsoft Agent Framework (MAF) turns that three-step pipeline into one `RunAsync` call — the LLM picks the tool, MAF runs it, the LLM stitches the answer."},{"kind":"p","html":"MAF (package \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e--prerelease\u003c/code\u003e) sits on top of \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e. It adds three things: agent wrapping, tool registration, and session state. You write one extension-method call, one factory call per tool, and one \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e per turn.","text":"MAF (package `Microsoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI`, `--prerelease`) sits on top of `IChatClient`. It adds three things: agent wrapping, tool registration, and session state. You write one extension-method call, one factory call per tool, and one `await` per turn."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Build a bare agent","text":"Build a bare agent"},{"kind":"p","html":"Start with an \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e. Wrap it into a \u003ccode\u003eChatClientAgent\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e.AsAIAgent()\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Start with an `IChatClient`. Wrap it into a `ChatClientAgent` with `.AsAIAgent()`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using Microsoft.Agents.AI;\n\nvar agent = chatClient.AsAIAgent(\n    instructions: \"You write short rhyming recipes.\",\n    name: \"CakeRecipeAgent\");\n\nvar response = await agent.RunAsync(\"A dessert for a rainy Tuesday.\");\nConsole.WriteLine(response);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAsAIAgent\u003c/code\u003e is an extension method on \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e returns the assembled assistant message. That is the full non-tool case — two method calls.","text":"`AsAIAgent` is an extension method on `IChatClient`. `RunAsync` returns the assembled assistant message. That is the full non-tool case — two method calls."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which extension method wraps an `IChatClient` into a `ChatClientAgent`?","a":"`.AsAIAgent()`. `.AsAgent()` does not exist — it is a common exam distractor."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Add a tool","text":"Add a tool"},{"kind":"p","html":"A tool is an \u003ccode\u003eAITool\u003c/code\u003e. You build one by handing a C# delegate to \u003ccode\u003eAIFunctionFactory.Create\u003c/code\u003e along with a name and a natural-language description. The LLM reads the description to decide when to call it.","text":"A tool is an `AITool`. You build one by handing a C# delegate to `AIFunctionFactory.Create` along with a name and a natural-language description. The LLM reads the description to decide when to call it."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using Microsoft.Extensions.AI;\nusing Microsoft.Agents.AI;\n\nAITool getCityNameTool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(\n    CityInfo.GetCityNameFromJson,\n    name: \"GetCityNameFromJson\",\n    description: \"Get the City Name from the given JSON string\");\n\nAITool getWeatherTool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(\n    WeatherService.GetWeatherAsync,\n    name: \"GetWeather\",\n    description: \"Get the weather details of a location using city name\");\n\nAIAgent agent = chatClient.AsAIAgent(\n    name: \"WeatherPoetAgent\",\n    instructions: \"You are a helpful assistant that detects cities and describes weather.\",\n    tools: [getCityNameTool, getWeatherTool]);"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003etools:\u003c/code\u003e parameter takes an array of \u003ccode\u003eAITool\u003c/code\u003e. The agent now has two callable functions. When you call \u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e, the LLM inspects the descriptions, decides which tools to call, calls them through MAF, reads the results, and answers.","text":"The `tools:` parameter takes an array of `AITool`. The agent now has two callable functions. When you call `RunAsync`, the LLM inspects the descriptions, decides which tools to call, calls them through MAF, reads the results, and answers."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eTrace the weather-poet turn.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUser input: \u003ccode\u003e&quot;What should I wear in Vancouver?&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLLM sees \u003ccode\u003eGetWeather\u003c/code\u003e description and emits a tool-call for \u003ccode\u003eGetWeather(&quot;Vancouver&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMAF invokes \u003ccode\u003eWeatherService.GetWeatherAsync(&quot;Vancouver&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e and returns the string \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Vancouver: 8C, rainy&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLLM receives the tool result as context and writes the final reply.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eagent.RunAsync(...)\u003c/code\u003e returns that final reply. The two tool round-trips happen inside one \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"Trace the weather-poet turn.\n1. User input: `\"What should I wear in Vancouver?\"`.\n2. LLM sees `GetWeather` description and emits a tool-call for `GetWeather(\"Vancouver\")`.\n3. MAF invokes `WeatherService.GetWeatherAsync(\"Vancouver\")` and returns the string `\"Vancouver: 8C, rainy\"`.\n4. LLM receives the tool result as context and writes the final reply.\n5. `agent.RunAsync(...)` returns that final reply. The two tool round-trips happen inside one `await`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Wrap a lambda as a tool","text":"Wrap a lambda as a tool"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAIFunctionFactory.Create\u003c/code\u003e also takes an async lambda. This is how you register a prompt-based step — load a template, substitute values, call \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient.GetResponseAsync\u003c/code\u003e, return the text.","text":"`AIFunctionFactory.Create` also takes an async lambda. This is how you register a prompt-based step — load a template, substitute values, call `IChatClient.GetResponseAsync`, return the text."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"string shortPoemTemplate = File.ReadAllText(templatePath);\n\nAITool writeShortPoemTool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(\n    async (string cityName, string weatherInput) =\u003e {\n        string prompt = shortPoemTemplate\n            .Replace(\"{{$CityName}}\", cityName)\n            .Replace(\"{{$WeatherInput}}\", weatherInput);\n        var result = await chatClient.GetResponseAsync(prompt);\n        return result.Text;\n    },\n    name: \"WriteShortPoem\",\n    description: \"Write a short funny poem about clothes to wear based on city and weather\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"The lambda parameters become the tool&#39;s parameter schema. Names and types travel to the LLM through the factory.","text":"The lambda parameters become the tool's parameter schema. Names and types travel to the LLM through the factory."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Keep state across turns","text":"Keep state across turns"},{"kind":"p","html":"For multi-turn chat, create an \u003ccode\u003eAgentSession\u003c/code\u003e once and pass it into every \u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e. The agent manages history and tool-call state inside the session — you do not build a \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;ChatMessage&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"For multi-turn chat, create an `AgentSession` once and pass it into every `RunAsync`. The agent manages history and tool-call state inside the session — you do not build a `List\u003cChatMessage\u003e`."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var session = await agent.CreateSessionAsync();\n\nwhile (true) {\n    Console.Write(\"User \u003e \");\n    string? input = Console.ReadLine();\n    if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(input)) continue;\n\n    var response = await agent.RunAsync(input, session);\n    Console.WriteLine(response.Text);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"For streaming, swap \u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e for \u003ccode\u003eRunStreamingAsync\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eawait foreach\u003c/code\u003e the updates:","text":"For streaming, swap `RunAsync` for `RunStreamingAsync` and `await foreach` the updates:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"await foreach (var update in agent.RunStreamingAsync(\"Which planet is closest to the sun?\")) {\n    Console.Write(update);\n}"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You want conversation memory across five `RunAsync` calls. Do you build a `ChatHistory` or an `AgentSession`?","a":"`AgentSession`, created via `await agent.CreateSessionAsync()`. `ChatHistory` is a manual `List\u003cChatMessage\u003e` — fine for raw `IChatClient` use, wrong for MAF agents."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eFour fake APIs that look right on a multiple-choice exam.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.AsAgent()\u003c/code\u003e — does not exist. Use \u003ccode\u003e.AsAIAgent()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eagent.Invoke()\u003c/code\u003e — does not exist. Use \u003ccode\u003eagent.RunAsync()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAITool.Register(method)\u003c/code\u003e — does not exist. Use \u003ccode\u003eAIFunctionFactory.Create(method, name: ..., description: ...)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ekernel.InvokeAsync()\u003c/code\u003e on an MAF agent — that is Semantic Kernel. MAF uses \u003ccode\u003eagent.RunAsync()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"Four fake APIs that look right on a multiple-choice exam.\n- `.AsAgent()` — does not exist. Use `.AsAIAgent()`.\n- `agent.Invoke()` — does not exist. Use `agent.RunAsync()`.\n- `AITool.Register(method)` — does not exist. Use `AIFunctionFactory.Create(method, name: ..., description: ...)`.\n- `kernel.InvokeAsync()` on an MAF agent — that is Semantic Kernel. MAF uses `agent.RunAsync()`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eDo not pass both a \u003ccode\u003eChatHistory\u003c/code\u003e and an \u003ccode\u003eAgentSession\u003c/code\u003e into the same agent run. \u003ccode\u003eChatHistory\u003c/code\u003e belongs to raw \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e code. \u003ccode\u003eAgentSession\u003c/code\u003e belongs to MAF agents. Mixing them duplicates state.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Do not pass both a `ChatHistory` and an `AgentSession` into the same agent run. `ChatHistory` belongs to raw `IChatClient` code. `AgentSession` belongs to MAF agents. Mixing them duplicates state."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003ePackage names ship separately and both need \u003ccode\u003e--prerelease\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Agents.AI\u003c/code\u003e is the base. \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI\u003c/code\u003e adds the OpenAI-compatible \u003ccode\u003eChatClient\u003c/code\u003e integration used by GitHub Models. Install the one that matches your backend.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Package names ship separately and both need `--prerelease`. `Microsoft.Agents.AI` is the base. `Microsoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI` adds the OpenAI-compatible `ChatClient` integration used by GitHub Models. Install the one that matches your backend."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eAn MAF agent is an \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e plus \u003ccode\u003e.AsAIAgent()\u003c/code\u003e, plus zero or more \u003ccode\u003eAITool\u003c/code\u003e values from \u003ccode\u003eAIFunctionFactory.Create\u003c/code\u003e, plus an optional \u003ccode\u003eAgentSession\u003c/code\u003e for multi-turn state. You drive it with \u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eRunStreamingAsync\u003c/code\u003e. Everything else — \u003ccode\u003e.AsAgent\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eInvoke\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAITool.Register\u003c/code\u003e — is a distractor.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"An MAF agent is an `IChatClient` plus `.AsAIAgent()`, plus zero or more `AITool` values from `AIFunctionFactory.Create`, plus an optional `AgentSession` for multi-turn state. You drive it with `RunAsync` or `RunStreamingAsync`. Everything else — `.AsAgent`, `Invoke`, `AITool.Register` — is a distractor."}]},{"n":2,"id":"ml-pipeline-workflow","title":"ML.NET pipeline — Load, Transform, Train, Evaluate, Predict","hook":"You have a CSV of taxi trips and you need to predict the fare. ML.NET turns that into seven lines of pipeline chaining.","tags":["ml-net","pipeline"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"slides/ML.NET.pptx; notes/ML.NET_VSCODE_SCRIPT.docx; notes/ML.NET_VS2022_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The taxi-fare problem","text":"The taxi-fare problem"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have \u003ccode\u003etaxi-fare-train.csv\u003c/code\u003e. Each row lists a vendor, rate code, passenger count, trip time, trip distance, payment type, and the fare charged. You want a model that predicts the fare from the other six columns. \u003ccode\u003eML.NET\u003c/code\u003e turns that job into a single chained pipeline.","text":"You have `taxi-fare-train.csv`. Each row lists a vendor, rate code, passenger count, trip time, trip distance, payment type, and the fare charged. You want a model that predicts the fare from the other six columns. `ML.NET` turns that job into a single chained pipeline."},{"kind":"p","html":"Every \u003ccode\u003eML.NET\u003c/code\u003e program follows the same seven steps:","text":"Every `ML.NET` program follows the same seven steps:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"MLContext → LoadFromTextFile → CopyColumns(\"Label\") → OneHotEncoding\n          → Concatenate(\"Features\") → Trainer → Fit → Evaluate → Predict"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each step has exactly one purpose. Miss one and training breaks.","text":"Each step has exactly one purpose. Miss one and training breaks."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 1: \u003ccode\u003eMLContext\u003c/code\u003e — the root object","text":"Step 1: `MLContext` — the root object"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using Microsoft.ML;\n\nMLContext mlContext = new MLContext(seed: 0);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eMLContext\u003c/code\u003e is the single entry point. From it you reach \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Data\u003c/code\u003e (loaders), \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Transforms\u003c/code\u003e (feature engineering), \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Regression\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003emlContext.MulticlassClassification\u003c/code\u003e (trainers + evaluators), and \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Model\u003c/code\u003e (save, load, prediction engines). The \u003ccode\u003eseed: 0\u003c/code\u003e argument pins the random-number generator so training is deterministic across runs — identical inputs produce identical models.","text":"`MLContext` is the single entry point. From it you reach `mlContext.Data` (loaders), `mlContext.Transforms` (feature engineering), `mlContext.Regression` or `mlContext.MulticlassClassification` (trainers + evaluators), and `mlContext.Model` (save, load, prediction engines). The `seed: 0` argument pins the random-number generator so training is deterministic across runs — identical inputs produce identical models."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 2: Load data into an \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Step 2: Load data into an `IDataView`"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"IDataView trainingData = mlContext.Data.LoadFromTextFile\u003cTaxiTrip\u003e(\n    trainDataPath,\n    hasHeader: true,\n    separatorChar: ',');"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eLoadFromTextFile&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e parses the CSV into an \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e — an immutable, streaming, lazy view over tabular data. Nothing is read into memory until a downstream operation pulls rows. The generic type \u003ccode\u003eTaxiTrip\u003c/code\u003e tells \u003ccode\u003eML.NET\u003c/code\u003e how CSV columns map to fields:","text":"`LoadFromTextFile\u003cT\u003e` parses the CSV into an `IDataView` — an immutable, streaming, lazy view over tabular data. Nothing is read into memory until a downstream operation pulls rows. The generic type `TaxiTrip` tells `ML.NET` how CSV columns map to fields:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class TaxiTrip\n{\n    [LoadColumn(0)] public string VendorId;\n    [LoadColumn(4)] public float TripDistance;\n    [LoadColumn(6)] public float FareAmount;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e[LoadColumn(0)]\u003c/code\u003e is zero-based and matches the CSV column index, not the header name.","text":"`[LoadColumn(0)]` is zero-based and matches the CSV column index, not the header name."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 3–5: Build the pipeline","text":"Step 3–5: Build the pipeline"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var pipeline = mlContext.Transforms\n    .CopyColumns(outputColumnName: \"Label\", inputColumnName: \"FareAmount\")\n    .Append(mlContext.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(\n        outputColumnName: \"VendorIdEncoded\", inputColumnName: \"VendorId\"))\n    .Append(mlContext.Transforms.Concatenate(\"Features\",\n        \"VendorIdEncoded\", \"TripDistance\"))\n    .Append(mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree());"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three rules govern the chain:","text":"Three rules govern the chain:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCopyColumns\u003c/code\u003e comes first\u003c/strong\u003e and renames the target column (\u003ccode\u003e&quot;FareAmount&quot;\u003c/code\u003e) to the literal name \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Trainers search for a column named \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e; rename it or training fails with a &quot;column not found&quot; error.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eOneHotEncoding\u003c/code\u003e expands categorical text\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003e&quot;VTS&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;CMT&quot;\u003c/code\u003e) into binary indicator vectors. Trainers only accept numeric input, so every string column must be encoded before it reaches \u003ccode\u003eConcatenate\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eConcatenate\u003c/code\u003e must output the literal name \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e It packs the encoded columns into a single vector column. Any other name (\u003ccode\u003e&quot;Input&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;X&quot;\u003c/code\u003e) and the trainer cannot find its input.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **`CopyColumns` comes first** and renames the target column (`\"FareAmount\"`) to the literal name `\"Label\"`. Trainers search for a column named `\"Label\"`; rename it or training fails with a \"column not found\" error.\n2. **`OneHotEncoding` expands categorical text** (`\"VTS\"`, `\"CMT\"`) into binary indicator vectors. Trainers only accept numeric input, so every string column must be encoded before it reaches `Concatenate`.\n3. **`Concatenate` must output the literal name `\"Features\"`.** It packs the encoded columns into a single vector column. Any other name (`\"Input\"`, `\"X\"`) and the trainer cannot find its input."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eFastTree\u003c/code\u003e is the default regression trainer — a gradient-boosted decision-tree ensemble shipped in \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.ML.FastTree\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`FastTree` is the default regression trainer — a gradient-boosted decision-tree ensemble shipped in `Microsoft.ML.FastTree`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 6: \u003ccode\u003eFit()\u003c/code\u003e returns an \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Step 6: `Fit()` returns an `ITransformer`"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"ITransformer model = pipeline.Fit(trainingData);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eFit()\u003c/code\u003e runs every transform, trains the algorithm on the resulting numeric vectors, and returns an \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e — the trained, stateless, serializable model. It does \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e return an \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e. Confusing the two is the single most common exam distractor.","text":"`Fit()` runs every transform, trains the algorithm on the resulting numeric vectors, and returns an `ITransformer` — the trained, stateless, serializable model. It does **not** return an `IDataView`. Confusing the two is the single most common exam distractor."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 7: Evaluate and predict","text":"Step 7: Evaluate and predict"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"IDataView predictions = model.Transform(testData);\nvar metrics = mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\");\nConsole.WriteLine($\"RSquared: {metrics.RSquared:0.##}\");\n\nvar engine = mlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction\u003e(model);\nvar result = engine.Predict(new TaxiTrip { VendorId = \"VTS\", TripDistance = 10.33f });"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003emodel.Transform\u003c/code\u003e applies the whole pipeline to a batch \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eEvaluate\u003c/code\u003e reads the \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Score&quot;\u003c/code\u003e columns and returns \u003ccode\u003eRegressionMetrics\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eCreatePredictionEngine\u003c/code\u003e wraps the model for one-row-at-a-time inference.","text":"`model.Transform` applies the whole pipeline to a batch `IDataView`. `Evaluate` reads the `\"Label\"` and `\"Score\"` columns and returns `RegressionMetrics`. `CreatePredictionEngine` wraps the model for one-row-at-a-time inference."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `pipeline.Fit(trainingData)` return?","a":"An `ITransformer` — the trained model. It is not an `IDataView`, not metrics, not a `PredictionEngine`. Pick `ITransformer` whenever the exam offers those four choices."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003etrace a three-column pipeline\nYou have columns \u003ccode\u003eVendorId\u003c/code\u003e (string), \u003ccode\u003eTripDistance\u003c/code\u003e (float), and \u003ccode\u003eFareAmount\u003c/code\u003e (float). Walk the data through:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLoad\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eLoadFromTextFile&lt;TaxiTrip&gt;\u003c/code\u003e produces an \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e with three columns.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCopyColumns(&quot;Label&quot;, &quot;FareAmount&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: adds a fourth column \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e holding fare values. Trainers now have a target.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eOneHotEncoding(&quot;VendorIdEncoded&quot;, &quot;VendorId&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: adds a vector column where \u003ccode\u003e&quot;VTS&quot;\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003e[1,0]\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;CMT&quot;\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003e[0,1]\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eConcatenate(&quot;Features&quot;, &quot;VendorIdEncoded&quot;, &quot;TripDistance&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: adds a single vector column combining the encoded vendor and the distance.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eFastTree()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: reads \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e as input and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e as target, trains the tree ensemble.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eFit()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: returns the \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eEvaluate\u003c/code\u003e then reads \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Score&quot;\u003c/code\u003e from the transformed output.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"trace a three-column pipeline\nYou have columns `VendorId` (string), `TripDistance` (float), and `FareAmount` (float). Walk the data through:\n1. **Load**: `LoadFromTextFile\u003cTaxiTrip\u003e` produces an `IDataView` with three columns.\n2. **`CopyColumns(\"Label\", \"FareAmount\")`**: adds a fourth column `\"Label\"` holding fare values. Trainers now have a target.\n3. **`OneHotEncoding(\"VendorIdEncoded\", \"VendorId\")`**: adds a vector column where `\"VTS\"` becomes `[1,0]` and `\"CMT\"` becomes `[0,1]`.\n4. **`Concatenate(\"Features\", \"VendorIdEncoded\", \"TripDistance\")`**: adds a single vector column combining the encoded vendor and the distance.\n5. **`FastTree()`**: reads `\"Features\"` as input and `\"Label\"` as target, trains the tree ensemble.\n6. **`Fit()`**: returns the `ITransformer`. `Evaluate` then reads `\"Label\"` and `\"Score\"` from the transformed output."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eWriting \u003ccode\u003eIDataView model = pipeline.Fit(trainingData);\u003c/code\u003e compiles-fails. \u003ccode\u003eFit\u003c/code\u003e produces an \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e. The same trap hides behind \u003ccode\u003eConcatenate(&quot;Input&quot;, …)\u003c/code\u003e — the trainer silently cannot locate \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and throws at runtime. Always type the two magic strings \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e verbatim.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Writing `IDataView model = pipeline.Fit(trainingData);` compiles-fails. `Fit` produces an `ITransformer`. The same trap hides behind `Concatenate(\"Input\", …)` — the trainer silently cannot locate `\"Features\"` and throws at runtime. Always type the two magic strings `\"Label\"` and `\"Features\"` verbatim."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eOne \u003ccode\u003eMLContext\u003c/code\u003e, one \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e, one pipeline with \u003ccode\u003eCopyColumns\u003c/code\u003e → encoders → \u003ccode\u003eConcatenate(&quot;Features&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e → trainer, then \u003ccode\u003eFit\u003c/code\u003e returns an \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e you evaluate or wrap in a \u003ccode\u003ePredictionEngine\u003c/code\u003e. Memorise those seven steps and the return type of \u003ccode\u003eFit\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"One `MLContext`, one `IDataView`, one pipeline with `CopyColumns` → encoders → `Concatenate(\"Features\")` → trainer, then `Fit` returns an `ITransformer` you evaluate or wrap in a `PredictionEngine`. Memorise those seven steps and the return type of `Fit`."}]},{"n":3,"id":"ai-semantic-kernel","title":"Semantic Kernel SDK","hook":"Wire a C# method to GPT-4o with one attribute and one line — that is Semantic Kernel.","tags":["ai","orchestration","plugins"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"courses/COMP4870/generated/exam-study/research-ai.md §Semantic Kernel, §Register Semantic Kernel in Program.cs, §Add Plugin to Kernel, §skprompt.txt Template; slides/CSharp_Meets_AI.pptx p.17–24; notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"From a C# method to an LLM tool in six lines","text":"From a C# method to an LLM tool in six lines"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have a \u003ccode\u003eGetWeatherDescription(string city)\u003c/code\u003e method. You want GPT-4o to call it when a user asks about weather. Semantic Kernel is Microsoft&#39;s orchestration SDK that makes this wiring a six-line job: build a \u003ccode\u003eKernel\u003c/code\u003e, attach an LLM service, import your class as a plugin, invoke.","text":"You have a `GetWeatherDescription(string city)` method. You want GPT-4o to call it when a user asks about weather. Semantic Kernel is Microsoft's orchestration SDK that makes this wiring a six-line job: build a `Kernel`, attach an LLM service, import your class as a plugin, invoke."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var kernelBuilder = new KernelBuilder();\nkernelBuilder.AddOpenAIChatCompletion(\"gpt-4o\", apiKey);\nvar kernel = kernelBuilder.Build();\nkernel.ImportPluginFromType\u003cWeatherPlugin\u003e();\nvar result = await kernel.InvokeAsync(\"WeatherPlugin\", \"DescribeWeather\",\n    new() { [\"city\"] = \"Vancouver\" });"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003eKernel\u003c/code\u003e is the runtime orchestrator. The \u003ccode\u003eKernelBuilder\u003c/code\u003e configures it fluently — register an \u003ccode\u003eIChatCompletionService\u003c/code\u003e implementation (OpenAI, Azure OpenAI, or Ollama), then call \u003ccode\u003eBuild()\u003c/code\u003e. Every invocation flows through that kernel: plugin lookup, prompt rendering, LLM call, response.","text":"The `Kernel` is the runtime orchestrator. The `KernelBuilder` configures it fluently — register an `IChatCompletionService` implementation (OpenAI, Azure OpenAI, or Ollama), then call `Build()`. Every invocation flows through that kernel: plugin lookup, prompt rendering, LLM call, response."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Plugins: native C# vs prompt-based","text":"Plugins: native C# vs prompt-based"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003eplugin\u003c/strong\u003e is a collection of callable functions loaded into a \u003ccode\u003eKernel\u003c/code\u003e. Semantic Kernel supports two flavours, and both register through the kernel&#39;s import methods.","text":"A **plugin** is a collection of callable functions loaded into a `Kernel`. Semantic Kernel supports two flavours, and both register through the kernel's import methods."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eNative plugin\u003c/strong\u003e — a C# class whose methods are decorated with \u003ccode\u003e[KernelFunction]\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e[Description]\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003e[Description]\u003c/code\u003e attribute is what the LLM reads when deciding which function fits the user&#39;s intent; skip it and tool selection gets guesswork.","text":"**Native plugin** — a C# class whose methods are decorated with `[KernelFunction]` and `[Description]`. The `[Description]` attribute is what the LLM reads when deciding which function fits the user's intent; skip it and tool selection gets guesswork."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"[KernelFunction(\"DescribeWeather\")]\n[Description(\"Get weather description for a city\")]\npublic static string GetWeatherDescription(\n    [Description(\"City name\")] string city)\n{\n    return $\"Weather in {city}: sunny\";\n}\n\nkernel.ImportPluginFromType\u003cWeatherPlugin\u003e();"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePrompt-based plugin\u003c/strong\u003e — a directory containing a \u003ccode\u003eskprompt.txt\u003c/code\u003e file. The template uses \u003ccode\u003e{{$variableName}}\u003c/code\u003e placeholders substituted at invoke time.","text":"**Prompt-based plugin** — a directory containing a `skprompt.txt` file. The template uses `{{$variableName}}` placeholders substituted at invoke time."},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"## Instructions\nIdentify and reply with the name of a city from a given user input.\nWhen you cannot identify a city name in the given input, reply with \"Unknown\".\n\n## User Input Format:\n{{$input}}"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"string pluginDirectory = Path.Combine(Directory.GetCurrentDirectory(), \"Plugins\");\nvar plugin = kernel.ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory(\n    Path.Combine(pluginDirectory, \"CakeRecipe\"));"},{"kind":"p","html":"Native functions give you compile-time safety and debugger breakpoints. Prompt directories let non-developers edit LLM behaviour without touching C#.","text":"Native functions give you compile-time safety and debugger breakpoints. Prompt directories let non-developers edit LLM behaviour without touching C#."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A user types \"weather in Tokyo\" and your kernel has a native `GetWeatherDescription` function plus a prompt-based `CityExtractor` plugin. Which attribute tells the LLM to pick the weather function first?","a":"`[Description(\"Get weather description for a city\")]`. The LLM reads description metadata on each registered function (and its parameters) to match user intent. Without `[Description]`, the method name alone steers tool selection — much weaker signal."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The invocation flow","text":"The invocation flow"},{"kind":"p","html":"When you call \u003ccode\u003ekernel.InvokeAsync(...)\u003c/code\u003e, a fixed pipeline runs: kernel looks up the function, renders any prompt template by substituting \u003ccode\u003e{{$var}}\u003c/code\u003e placeholders, forwards the rendered prompt to the configured \u003ccode\u003eIChatCompletionService\u003c/code\u003e, and returns the result. For multi-turn conversations the service maintains a \u003ccode\u003eChatHistory\u003c/code\u003e — an ordered list of \u003ccode\u003eChatMessage\u003c/code\u003e objects (User, Assistant, System roles) that carries context across calls.","text":"When you call `kernel.InvokeAsync(...)`, a fixed pipeline runs: kernel looks up the function, renders any prompt template by substituting `{{$var}}` placeholders, forwards the rendered prompt to the configured `IChatCompletionService`, and returns the result. For multi-turn conversations the service maintains a `ChatHistory` — an ordered list of `ChatMessage` objects (User, Assistant, System roles) that carries context across calls."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eRegistering the kernel in an ASP.NET Core \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate the builder: \u003ccode\u003evar kernelBuilder = new KernelBuilder();\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAdd an LLM service. For cloud: \u003ccode\u003ekernelBuilder.AddOpenAIChatCompletion(&quot;gpt-4o&quot;, apiKey);\u003c/code\u003e. For local Ollama: \u003ccode\u003ekernelBuilder.AddOpenAIChatCompletion(&quot;phi3&quot;, new Uri(&quot;http://localhost:11434&quot;));\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCall \u003ccode\u003eBuild()\u003c/code\u003e to get the \u003ccode\u003eKernel\u003c/code\u003e instance.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRegister it as a singleton: \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.Services.AddSingleton(kernel);\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eInject \u003ccode\u003eKernel\u003c/code\u003e into your controllers or services. Each request imports plugins and calls \u003ccode\u003eInvokeAsync\u003c/code\u003e.\nThe singleton matters — a \u003ccode\u003eKernel\u003c/code\u003e holds HTTP clients and plugin registrations; creating one per request wastes connections.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"Registering the kernel in an ASP.NET Core `Program.cs`:\n1. Create the builder: `var kernelBuilder = new KernelBuilder();`\n2. Add an LLM service. For cloud: `kernelBuilder.AddOpenAIChatCompletion(\"gpt-4o\", apiKey);`. For local Ollama: `kernelBuilder.AddOpenAIChatCompletion(\"phi3\", new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434\"));`.\n3. Call `Build()` to get the `Kernel` instance.\n4. Register it as a singleton: `builder.Services.AddSingleton(kernel);`.\n5. Inject `Kernel` into your controllers or services. Each request imports plugins and calls `InvokeAsync`.\nThe singleton matters — a `Kernel` holds HTTP clients and plugin registrations; creating one per request wastes connections."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eExam distractors love fake method names. \u003ccode\u003ekernel.Execute()\u003c/code\u003e does not exist — the method is \u003ccode\u003ekernel.InvokeAsync()\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eSkillFactory.Create()\u003c/code\u003e does not exist — use \u003ccode\u003eImportPluginFromPromptDirectory()\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eImportPluginFromType&lt;T&gt;()\u003c/code\u003e. The attribute is \u003ccode\u003e[KernelFunction]\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003e[SkillFunction]\u003c/code\u003e. And do not cross wires with Microsoft Agent Framework: \u003ccode\u003eagent.RunAsync()\u003c/code\u003e belongs to MAF, not Semantic Kernel.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Exam distractors love fake method names. `kernel.Execute()` does not exist — the method is `kernel.InvokeAsync()`. `SkillFactory.Create()` does not exist — use `ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory()` or `ImportPluginFromType\u003cT\u003e()`. The attribute is `[KernelFunction]`, not `[SkillFunction]`. And do not cross wires with Microsoft Agent Framework: `agent.RunAsync()` belongs to MAF, not Semantic Kernel."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Plugin, skill, tool — precise words","text":"Plugin, skill, tool — precise words"},{"kind":"p","html":"Vocabulary trips students. In Semantic Kernel, a \u003cstrong\u003eplugin\u003c/strong\u003e is the collection; a \u003cstrong\u003eskill\u003c/strong\u003e is the legacy term for a prompt-directory (\u003ccode\u003eskprompt.txt\u003c/code\u003e plus optional code); a \u003cstrong\u003enative function\u003c/strong\u003e is a C# method marked \u003ccode\u003e[KernelFunction]\u003c/code\u003e. Microsoft Agent Framework uses a different word — \u003ccode\u003eAITool\u003c/code\u003e — for the same idea, registered via \u003ccode\u003eAIFunctionFactory.Create()\u003c/code\u003e. If an exam question mixes \u003ccode\u003e[KernelFunction]\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eagent.RunAsync()\u003c/code\u003e, it is wrong by construction.","text":"Vocabulary trips students. In Semantic Kernel, a **plugin** is the collection; a **skill** is the legacy term for a prompt-directory (`skprompt.txt` plus optional code); a **native function** is a C# method marked `[KernelFunction]`. Microsoft Agent Framework uses a different word — `AITool` — for the same idea, registered via `AIFunctionFactory.Create()`. If an exam question mixes `[KernelFunction]` with `agent.RunAsync()`, it is wrong by construction."},{"kind":"p","html":"Package names follow the same discipline. \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.SemanticKernel\u003c/code\u003e is the core NuGet. Add-ons live under \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.SemanticKernel.Plugins.*\u003c/code\u003e. Nothing ships under \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.SK\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eSemanticKernel.Core\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Package names follow the same discipline. `Microsoft.SemanticKernel` is the core NuGet. Add-ons live under `Microsoft.SemanticKernel.Plugins.*`. Nothing ships under `Microsoft.SK` or `SemanticKernel.Core`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eSemantic Kernel orchestrates LLM calls through a \u003ccode\u003eKernel\u003c/code\u003e built by \u003ccode\u003eKernelBuilder\u003c/code\u003e, loaded with plugins — either native C# classes using \u003ccode\u003e[KernelFunction]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[Description]\u003c/code\u003e, or prompt directories with \u003ccode\u003eskprompt.txt\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e{{$var}}\u003c/code\u003e templates — and invoked through \u003ccode\u003ekernel.InvokeAsync()\u003c/code\u003e backed by an \u003ccode\u003eIChatCompletionService\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Semantic Kernel orchestrates LLM calls through a `Kernel` built by `KernelBuilder`, loaded with plugins — either native C# classes using `[KernelFunction]` + `[Description]`, or prompt directories with `skprompt.txt` and `{{$var}}` templates — and invoked through `kernel.InvokeAsync()` backed by an `IChatCompletionService`."}]},{"n":4,"id":"ml-data-transforms","title":"ML.NET data transforms","hook":"A trainer reads numbers from a column literally named \"Features\" and a target literally named \"Label\" — your pipeline's job is to produce both.","tags":["ml-net","feature-eng"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"slides/ML.NET.pptx p.11–18; research-mlnet.md §transforms","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Start with one raw row","text":"Start with one raw row"},{"kind":"p","html":"A CSV row arrives: \u003ccode\u003eVTS,1,1,430,10.33,CSH,15.5\u003c/code\u003e. Your \u003ccode\u003eTaxiTrip\u003c/code\u003e class reads it with \u003ccode\u003e[LoadColumn(0)]\u003c/code\u003e through \u003ccode\u003e[LoadColumn(6)]\u003c/code\u003e, pulling \u003ccode\u003eVendorId = &quot;VTS&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eTripDistance = 10.33f\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eFareAmount = 15.5f\u003c/code\u003e. A regression trainer cannot consume the string \u003ccode\u003e&quot;VTS&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and will not scan for a column called \u003ccode\u003eFareAmount\u003c/code\u003e. You must rewrite this row into two vectors the trainer recognizes: \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e (the target scalar) and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e (the input vector).","text":"A CSV row arrives: `VTS,1,1,430,10.33,CSH,15.5`. Your `TaxiTrip` class reads it with `[LoadColumn(0)]` through `[LoadColumn(6)]`, pulling `VendorId = \"VTS\"`, `TripDistance = 10.33f`, `FareAmount = 15.5f`. A regression trainer cannot consume the string `\"VTS\"` and will not scan for a column called `FareAmount`. You must rewrite this row into two vectors the trainer recognizes: `\"Label\"` (the target scalar) and `\"Features\"` (the input vector)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Three transforms do the rewriting: \u003ccode\u003eCopyColumns\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eOneHotEncoding\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eConcatenate\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Three transforms do the rewriting: `CopyColumns`, `OneHotEncoding`, and `Concatenate`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Rename your target to \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Rename your target to `\"Label\"`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eCopyColumns(outputColumnName: &quot;Label&quot;, inputColumnName: &quot;FareAmount&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e duplicates \u003ccode\u003eFareAmount\u003c/code\u003e under the name \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Trainers in \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Regression.Trainers\u003c/code\u003e look up the target by that exact name. The rename must come \u003cstrong\u003ebefore\u003c/strong\u003e the trainer step in the \u003ccode\u003e.Append(...)\u003c/code\u003e chain — append it later and the fit call fails to find \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`CopyColumns(outputColumnName: \"Label\", inputColumnName: \"FareAmount\")` duplicates `FareAmount` under the name `\"Label\"`. Trainers in `mlContext.Regression.Trainers` look up the target by that exact name. The rename must come **before** the trainer step in the `.Append(...)` chain — append it later and the fit call fails to find `\"Label\"`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-csharp\"\u003evar pipeline = mlContext.Transforms\n    .CopyColumns(outputColumnName: &quot;Label&quot;, inputColumnName: &quot;FareAmount&quot;)\n    .Append(/* encodings */)\n    .Append(/* concatenate */)\n    .Append(mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree());\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","text":"```csharp\nvar pipeline = mlContext.Transforms\n    .CopyColumns(outputColumnName: \"Label\", inputColumnName: \"FareAmount\")\n    .Append(/* encodings */)\n    .Append(/* concatenate */)\n    .Append(mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree());\n```"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Turn text categories into numbers with \u003ccode\u003eOneHotEncoding\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Turn text categories into numbers with `OneHotEncoding`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eVendorId\u003c/code\u003e holds strings like \u003ccode\u003e&quot;CMT&quot;\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e&quot;VTS&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Trainers need numbers. \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(outputColumnName: &quot;VendorIdEncoded&quot;, inputColumnName: &quot;VendorId&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e expands each distinct value into a binary-indicator slot. \u003ccode\u003e&quot;VTS&quot;\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003e[0, 1]\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003e&quot;CMT&quot;\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003e[1, 0]\u003c/code\u003e. This is \u003cstrong\u003ecategorical encoding\u003c/strong\u003e.","text":"`VendorId` holds strings like `\"CMT\"` or `\"VTS\"`. Trainers need numbers. `mlContext.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(outputColumnName: \"VendorIdEncoded\", inputColumnName: \"VendorId\")` expands each distinct value into a binary-indicator slot. `\"VTS\"` becomes `[0, 1]`; `\"CMT\"` becomes `[1, 0]`. This is **categorical encoding**."},{"kind":"p","html":"You pick the output name. \u003ccode\u003e&quot;VendorIdEncoded&quot;\u003c/code\u003e is a convention; \u003ccode\u003e&quot;VendorId_OH&quot;\u003c/code\u003e works equally well. The name only matters because the next step references it by string.","text":"You pick the output name. `\"VendorIdEncoded\"` is a convention; `\"VendorId_OH\"` works equally well. The name only matters because the next step references it by string."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your raw data has three text columns — `VendorId`, `RateCode`, `PaymentType`. How many `OneHotEncoding` calls does the pipeline need, and what names do their outputs carry?","a":"Three calls — one per categorical column. Output names are your choice (e.g. `\"VendorIdEncoded\"`, `\"RateCodeEncoded\"`, `\"PaymentTypeEncoded\"`); every name you pick must then appear in the `Concatenate` input list."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Assemble one \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e vector with \u003ccode\u003eConcatenate\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Assemble one `\"Features\"` vector with `Concatenate`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eConcatenate(outputColumnName: &quot;Features&quot;, …inputColumnNames)\u003c/code\u003e stitches the surviving numeric columns into a single vector. The output name \u003cstrong\u003emust\u003c/strong\u003e be the literal string \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e — trainers hardcode that lookup. Rename it to \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Inputs&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and the fit call throws.","text":"`Concatenate(outputColumnName: \"Features\", …inputColumnNames)` stitches the surviving numeric columns into a single vector. The output name **must** be the literal string `\"Features\"` — trainers hardcode that lookup. Rename it to `\"Inputs\"` and the fit call throws."},{"kind":"p","html":"Every column the trainer should see belongs in the input list: each encoded output plus each raw numeric feature you kept.","text":"Every column the trainer should see belongs in the input list: each encoded output plus each raw numeric feature you kept."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":".Append(mlContext.Transforms.Concatenate(\"Features\",\n    \"VendorIdEncoded\", \"RateCodeEncoded\",\n    \"PassengerCount\", \"TripDistance\", \"PaymentTypeEncoded\"))"},{"kind":"p","html":"Notice what is \u003cstrong\u003emissing\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eTripTime\u003c/code\u003e. You predict fare before the trip ends, so trip time is not known at prediction time. Including it causes data leakage — the model &quot;cheats&quot; during training and performs badly on real trips.","text":"Notice what is **missing**: `TripTime`. You predict fare before the trip ends, so trip time is not known at prediction time. Including it causes data leakage — the model \"cheats\" during training and performs badly on real trips."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Full pipeline shape","text":"Full pipeline shape"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var pipeline = mlContext.Transforms.CopyColumns(\"Label\", \"FareAmount\")\n    .Append(mlContext.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(\"VendorIdEncoded\", \"VendorId\"))\n    .Append(mlContext.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(\"RateCodeEncoded\", \"RateCode\"))\n    .Append(mlContext.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(\"PaymentTypeEncoded\", \"PaymentType\"))\n    .Append(mlContext.Transforms.Concatenate(\"Features\",\n        \"VendorIdEncoded\", \"RateCodeEncoded\",\n        \"PassengerCount\", \"TripDistance\", \"PaymentTypeEncoded\"))\n    .Append(mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree());"},{"kind":"p","html":"Read top-to-bottom: rename target, encode three text columns, concatenate into \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, train.","text":"Read top-to-bottom: rename target, encode three text columns, concatenate into `\"Features\"`, train."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You add a fourth categorical column `StoreAndFwdFlag` and call `OneHotEncoding(\"StoreAndFwdFlagEncoded\", \"StoreAndFwdFlag\")`. The pipeline compiles and trains without error. Why might your model still perform identically to before?","a":"The `Concatenate` call determines which columns feed the trainer. If `\"StoreAndFwdFlagEncoded\"` is not added to the `Concatenate` input list, the encoded column exists in the schema but never reaches `FastTree`. Always cross-check: every encoded output must appear as a `Concatenate` input."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eEncoding a column and then forgetting to list it in \u003ccode\u003eConcatenate\u003c/code\u003e silently drops it from the feature vector. The pipeline still compiles and trains — just on fewer features. Always cross-check: every \u003ccode\u003eOneHotEncoding\u003c/code\u003e output name appears in the \u003ccode\u003eConcatenate\u003c/code\u003e input list.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Encoding a column and then forgetting to list it in `Concatenate` silently drops it from the feature vector. The pipeline still compiles and trains — just on fewer features. Always cross-check: every `OneHotEncoding` output name appears in the `Concatenate` input list."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[LoadColumn(0)]\u003c/code\u003e is 0-based (first CSV column is index 0). ClosedXML cell indexes are 1-based. Copy-pasting between an Excel reader and an ML.NET schema is where off-by-one errors live.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`[LoadColumn(0)]` is 0-based (first CSV column is index 0). ClosedXML cell indexes are 1-based. Copy-pasting between an Excel reader and an ML.NET schema is where off-by-one errors live."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThree transforms, three jobs: \u003ccode\u003eCopyColumns\u003c/code\u003e names your target \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eOneHotEncoding\u003c/code\u003e numerifies each text column under a name you choose, \u003ccode\u003eConcatenate\u003c/code\u003e bundles everything into the single \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e vector the trainer expects.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Three transforms, three jobs: `CopyColumns` names your target `\"Label\"`, `OneHotEncoding` numerifies each text column under a name you choose, `Concatenate` bundles everything into the single `\"Features\"` vector the trainer expects."}]},{"n":5,"id":"ml-regression-evaluation","title":"ML.NET regression evaluation — FastTree, RMSE, R²","hook":"Your taxi-fare model reports RSquared 0.89 and RootMeanSquaredError 3.3. Is that good? What do the numbers mean, and in what units?","tags":["ml-net","regression","metrics"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"slides/ML.NET.pptx p.20–27; research-mlnet.md §Algorithms & Trainers, §Regression Trainers, §Evaluation Metrics, §Regression Metrics, §TrainTestSplit, §CrossValidate; cards #9–10; MCQ #4","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Reading a trained model&#39;s report card","text":"Reading a trained model's report card"},{"kind":"p","html":"You trained a taxi-fare regressor on \u003ccode\u003etaxi-fare-train.csv\u003c/code\u003e. The evaluator prints:","text":"You trained a taxi-fare regressor on `taxi-fare-train.csv`. The evaluator prints:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"RSquared:              0.89\nRootMeanSquaredError:  3.30\nMeanAbsoluteError:     2.10"},{"kind":"p","html":"You need three facts to read that report. First, the trainer used to produce it. Second, the split that gave you a fair test set. Third, what each metric actually measures — because the exam sets up distractors that sound right and are wrong.","text":"You need three facts to read that report. First, the trainer used to produce it. Second, the split that gave you a fair test set. Third, what each metric actually measures — because the exam sets up distractors that sound right and are wrong."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 1: Pick a regression trainer","text":"Step 1: Pick a regression trainer"},{"kind":"p","html":"Trainers hang off \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Regression.Trainers\u003c/code\u003e. The three you must recognise:","text":"Trainers hang off `mlContext.Regression.Trainers`. The three you must recognise:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree()           // default\nmlContext.Regression.Trainers.Sdca()               // linear, small data\nmlContext.Regression.Trainers.LightGbm()           // needs Microsoft.ML.LightGbm"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eFastTree\u003c/code\u003e is a gradient-boosted-trees ensemble shipped in \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.ML.FastTree\u003c/code\u003e. It is the default choice for general regression and the trainer AutoML picked for taxi-fare (all top-5 models were \u003ccode\u003eFastTree\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eFastForest\u003c/code\u003e variants). \u003ccode\u003eSdcaRegression\u003c/code\u003e is stochastic dual coordinate ascent — a fast linear trainer suited to small datasets with linear relationships. \u003ccode\u003eLightGbmRegression\u003c/code\u003e is Microsoft&#39;s LightGBM gradient-boosting trainer; it needs the extra \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.ML.LightGbm\u003c/code\u003e package before the line compiles.","text":"`FastTree` is a gradient-boosted-trees ensemble shipped in `Microsoft.ML.FastTree`. It is the default choice for general regression and the trainer AutoML picked for taxi-fare (all top-5 models were `FastTree` or `FastForest` variants). `SdcaRegression` is stochastic dual coordinate ascent — a fast linear trainer suited to small datasets with linear relationships. `LightGbmRegression` is Microsoft's LightGBM gradient-boosting trainer; it needs the extra `Microsoft.ML.LightGbm` package before the line compiles."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 2: Hold out a test set","text":"Step 2: Hold out a test set"},{"kind":"p","html":"Training accuracy lies. You need unseen rows. \u003ccode\u003eTrainTestSplit\u003c/code\u003e partitions an \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e into two subsets:","text":"Training accuracy lies. You need unseen rows. `TrainTestSplit` partitions an `IDataView` into two subsets:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var split = mlContext.Data.TrainTestSplit(dataView, testFraction: 0.2);\nITransformer model = pipeline.Fit(split.TrainSet);\nIDataView predictions = model.Transform(split.TestSet);"},{"kind":"p","html":"That is 80% for training, 20% for evaluation. The model never sees \u003ccode\u003eTestSet\u003c/code\u003e rows during \u003ccode\u003eFit\u003c/code\u003e, so metrics on \u003ccode\u003eTestSet\u003c/code\u003e measure generalisation rather than memorisation.","text":"That is 80% for training, 20% for evaluation. The model never sees `TestSet` rows during `Fit`, so metrics on `TestSet` measure generalisation rather than memorisation."},{"kind":"p","html":"For a tighter estimate, use k-fold cross-validation:","text":"For a tighter estimate, use k-fold cross-validation:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var cvResults = mlContext.Regression.CrossValidate(\n    pipeline, data, numberOfFolds: 5);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eCrossValidate\u003c/code\u003e trains five models. Each is trained on four folds and tested on the remaining fold. It reports metrics averaged across all five runs — a better performance estimate than any single split.","text":"`CrossValidate` trains five models. Each is trained on four folds and tested on the remaining fold. It reports metrics averaged across all five runs — a better performance estimate than any single split."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why split at all? Why not evaluate on the training data directly?","a":"A tree ensemble can memorise training rows and score near-perfect `RSquared` on them while failing on new trips. The test set is the only honest estimate of how the model behaves in production."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 3: Call \u003ccode\u003eEvaluate\u003c/code\u003e in the right namespace","text":"Step 3: Call `Evaluate` in the right namespace"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var metrics = mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\");\nConsole.WriteLine($\"RSquared: {metrics.RSquared:0.##}\");\nConsole.WriteLine($\"RMSE:     {metrics.RootMeanSquaredError:0.##}\");\nConsole.WriteLine($\"MAE:      {metrics.MeanAbsoluteError:0.##}\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three details decide whether the call works:","text":"Three details decide whether the call works:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe namespace must match the task.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Regression.Evaluate\u003c/code\u003e returns a \u003ccode\u003eRegressionMetrics\u003c/code\u003e object with \u003ccode\u003eRSquared\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eRootMeanSquaredError\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eMeanAbsoluteError\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003emlContext.MulticlassClassification.Evaluate\u003c/code\u003e returns accuracy-style metrics for a classifier — wrong shape for regression.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe label argument names the target column.\u003c/strong\u003e You renamed it to \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eCopyColumns\u003c/code\u003e in the pipeline, so pass \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe score argument names the prediction column.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eFastTree\u003c/code\u003e writes its output to a column called \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Score&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Your prediction class must expose it as \u003ccode\u003e[ColumnName(&quot;Score&quot;)] public float FareAmount;\u003c/code\u003e. Pass any other string and \u003ccode\u003eEvaluate\u003c/code\u003e cannot find the predictions.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **The namespace must match the task.** `mlContext.Regression.Evaluate` returns a `RegressionMetrics` object with `RSquared`, `RootMeanSquaredError`, `MeanAbsoluteError`. `mlContext.MulticlassClassification.Evaluate` returns accuracy-style metrics for a classifier — wrong shape for regression.\n2. **The label argument names the target column.** You renamed it to `\"Label\"` with `CopyColumns` in the pipeline, so pass `\"Label\"`.\n3. **The score argument names the prediction column.** `FastTree` writes its output to a column called `\"Score\"`. Your prediction class must expose it as `[ColumnName(\"Score\")] public float FareAmount;`. Pass any other string and `Evaluate` cannot find the predictions."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Step 4: Read the three regression metrics","text":"Step 4: Read the three regression metrics"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMetric\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eProperty\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRange\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat it tells you\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eR²\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003emetrics.RSquared\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e0 to 1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFraction of variance the model explains. Closer to 1 is better. Unitless.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRMSE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003emetrics.RootMeanSquaredError\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e≥ 0\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAverage prediction error in the label&#39;s original units. Lower is better.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMAE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003emetrics.MeanAbsoluteError\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e≥ 0\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAverage absolute error. Same units as RMSE, more robust to outliers.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"R² is computed as \u003ccode\u003e1 - (SS_residual / SS_total)\u003c/code\u003e. An R² of 0.89 means the model explains 89% of the variation in fare amounts — the remaining 11% is noise or unmodelled effects. RMSE squares each error before averaging, so it punishes large misses more than MAE does; MAE simply averages absolute errors and shrugs off a few extreme outliers.","text":"R² is computed as `1 - (SS_residual / SS_total)`. An R² of 0.89 means the model explains 89% of the variation in fare amounts — the remaining 11% is noise or unmodelled effects. RMSE squares each error before averaging, so it punishes large misses more than MAE does; MAE simply averages absolute errors and shrugs off a few extreme outliers."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003einterpret \u003ccode\u003eRSquared = 0.89, RMSE = 3.30\u003c/code\u003e on taxi fare\nThe label column is \u003ccode\u003eFareAmount\u003c/code\u003e in US dollars, so:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRSquared = 0.89\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — the model explains 89% of fare variance. For real-world taxi data this is a strong fit.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRMSE = 3.30\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — on average, a predicted fare misses the actual fare by about \u003cstrong\u003e$3.30\u003c/strong\u003e. RMSE inherits the label&#39;s units; dollars in, dollars out.\nThe wrong reading is &quot;the model is 89% accurate with 3.3% error.&quot; R² is not accuracy, and RMSE is not a percentage. It is a dollar amount attached to a regression task.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"interpret `RSquared = 0.89, RMSE = 3.30` on taxi fare\nThe label column is `FareAmount` in US dollars, so:\n- **`RSquared = 0.89`** — the model explains 89% of fare variance. For real-world taxi data this is a strong fit.\n- **`RMSE = 3.30`** — on average, a predicted fare misses the actual fare by about **$3.30**. RMSE inherits the label's units; dollars in, dollars out.\nThe wrong reading is \"the model is 89% accurate with 3.3% error.\" R² is not accuracy, and RMSE is not a percentage. It is a dollar amount attached to a regression task."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe four interchangeable-looking mistakes the exam exploits:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003emlContext.MulticlassClassification.Evaluate\u003c/code\u003e on a regression model — the wrong namespace yields the wrong metric class; \u003ccode\u003eRSquared\u003c/code\u003e is not even a member.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePassing the wrong score-column name, e.g. \u003ccode\u003eEvaluate(predictions, &quot;Label&quot;, &quot;Prediction&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003eFastTree\u003c/code\u003e emits \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Score&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, so mismatched names break evaluation.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTreating \u003ccode\u003eRSquared = 0.89\u003c/code\u003e as &quot;89% accurate.&quot; \u003ccode\u003eAccuracy\u003c/code\u003e is a classification metric and does not exist on \u003ccode\u003eRegressionMetrics\u003c/code\u003e. R² is unitless variance-explained.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClaiming RMSE is a percentage. RMSE is in the label&#39;s original units — dollars for fare, seconds for trip time, square metres for area.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"The four interchangeable-looking mistakes the exam exploits:\n1. Calling `mlContext.MulticlassClassification.Evaluate` on a regression model — the wrong namespace yields the wrong metric class; `RSquared` is not even a member.\n2. Passing the wrong score-column name, e.g. `Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Prediction\")` — `FastTree` emits `\"Score\"`, so mismatched names break evaluation.\n3. Treating `RSquared = 0.89` as \"89% accurate.\" `Accuracy` is a classification metric and does not exist on `RegressionMetrics`. R² is unitless variance-explained.\n4. Claiming RMSE is a percentage. RMSE is in the label's original units — dollars for fare, seconds for trip time, square metres for area."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eTrain with \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree()\u003c/code\u003e, hold out 20% via \u003ccode\u003eTrainTestSplit\u003c/code\u003e or average across folds with \u003ccode\u003eCrossValidate\u003c/code\u003e, then call \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, &quot;Label&quot;, &quot;Score&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e and read \u003ccode\u003eRSquared\u003c/code\u003e (variance explained, 0–1), \u003ccode\u003eRootMeanSquaredError\u003c/code\u003e (label units, lower is better), and \u003ccode\u003eMeanAbsoluteError\u003c/code\u003e. Match the namespace to the task, type \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Score&quot;\u003c/code\u003e exactly, and never call R² &quot;accuracy.&quot;\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Train with `mlContext.Regression.Trainers.FastTree()`, hold out 20% via `TrainTestSplit` or average across folds with `CrossValidate`, then call `mlContext.Regression.Evaluate(predictions, \"Label\", \"Score\")` and read `RSquared` (variance explained, 0–1), `RootMeanSquaredError` (label units, lower is better), and `MeanAbsoluteError`. Match the namespace to the task, type `\"Label\"` and `\"Score\"` exactly, and never call R² \"accuracy.\""}]},{"n":6,"id":"ml-prediction-consumption","title":"ML.NET inference and model persistence","hook":"You have a trained taxi-fare model and one new trip. Turn the model into a price.","tags":["ml-net","inference"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"notes/ML.NET_VS2022_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md §consume","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"From trained model to predicted fare","text":"From trained model to predicted fare"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have an \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e returned by \u003ccode\u003epipeline.Fit(trainingData)\u003c/code\u003e. You also have one \u003ccode\u003eTaxiTrip\u003c/code\u003e object describing a new ride. Your job: produce a single fare.","text":"You have an `ITransformer` returned by `pipeline.Fit(trainingData)`. You also have one `TaxiTrip` object describing a new ride. Your job: produce a single fare."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eFit()\u003c/code\u003e hands back an \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e — the trained, stateless, serializable model. It is not an \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e. Keep that distinction sharp; the exam leans on it.","text":"`Fit()` hands back an `ITransformer` — the trained, stateless, serializable model. It is not an `IDataView`. Keep that distinction sharp; the exam leans on it."},{"kind":"p","html":"To score one row, wrap the transformer in a \u003ccode\u003ePredictionEngine&lt;TInput, TOutput&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Create it through \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine&lt;TaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction&gt;(model)\u003c/code\u003e, then call \u003ccode\u003ePredict(taxiTrip)\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"To score one row, wrap the transformer in a `PredictionEngine\u003cTInput, TOutput\u003e`. Create it through `mlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction\u003e(model)`, then call `Predict(taxiTrip)`."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Retrieval checkpoint","text":"Retrieval checkpoint"},{"kind":"p","html":"Close your eyes. What type does \u003ccode\u003eFit()\u003c/code\u003e return? Which factory builds a single-row predictor? What attribute decorates the prediction field on your output class?","text":"Close your eyes. What type does `Fit()` return? Which factory builds a single-row predictor? What attribute decorates the prediction field on your output class?"},{"kind":"p","html":"Answers: \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine&lt;TIn, TOut&gt;\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003e[ColumnName(&quot;Score&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Answers: `ITransformer`; `mlContext.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e`; `[ColumnName(\"Score\")]`."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The output class","text":"The output class"},{"kind":"p","html":"Your output type carries one field per prediction, tagged with the score column name:","text":"Your output type carries one field per prediction, tagged with the score column name:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class TaxiTripFarePrediction\n{\n    [ColumnName(\"Score\")] public float FareAmount;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Regression trainers write their prediction into a column named \u003ccode\u003eScore\u003c/code\u003e. Marking the field \u003ccode\u003e[ColumnName(&quot;Prediction&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e leaves \u003ccode\u003eFareAmount\u003c/code\u003e at zero — the binding fails silently.","text":"Regression trainers write their prediction into a column named `Score`. Marking the field `[ColumnName(\"Prediction\")]` leaves `FareAmount` at zero — the binding fails silently."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your web API hosts one `PredictionEngine\u003cTaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction\u003e` as a singleton service. Under concurrent load, predictions occasionally return garbage values. What is the root cause and what is the fix?","a":"`PredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` is not thread-safe — concurrent `Predict` calls corrupt its internal buffers. Fix: use `PredictionEnginePool\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` from `Microsoft.Extensions.ML`, or give each request thread its own engine. `ITransformer` itself is thread-safe; only the engine wrapper is not."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003escore a single trip\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-csharp\"\u003evar predictionEngine = mlContext.Model\n    .CreatePredictionEngine&lt;TaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction&gt;(model);\nvar trip = new TaxiTrip\n{\n    VendorId = &quot;VTS&quot;,\n    RateCode = &quot;1&quot;,\n    PassengerCount = 1,\n    TripDistance = 10.33f,\n    PaymentType = &quot;CSH&quot;,\n    FareAmount = 0          // placeholder; this is what you predict\n};\nvar prediction = predictionEngine.Predict(trip);\nConsole.WriteLine($&quot;Predicted fare: {prediction.FareAmount:0.####}&quot;);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","text":"score a single trip\n```csharp\nvar predictionEngine = mlContext.Model\n    .CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTaxiTrip, TaxiTripFarePrediction\u003e(model);\nvar trip = new TaxiTrip\n{\n    VendorId = \"VTS\",\n    RateCode = \"1\",\n    PassengerCount = 1,\n    TripDistance = 10.33f,\n    PaymentType = \"CSH\",\n    FareAmount = 0          // placeholder; this is what you predict\n};\nvar prediction = predictionEngine.Predict(trip);\nConsole.WriteLine($\"Predicted fare: {prediction.FareAmount:0.####}\");\n```"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Batch inference: skip the engine","text":"Batch inference: skip the engine"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ePredictionEngine\u003c/code\u003e is a single-row wrapper. For many rows at once, feed an \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e straight into the transformer:","text":"`PredictionEngine` is a single-row wrapper. For many rows at once, feed an `IDataView` straight into the transformer:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"IDataView scored = model.Transform(batchDataView);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eTransform\u003c/code\u003e returns a new \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e with the \u003ccode\u003eScore\u003c/code\u003e column appended. Use this path when you already have rows in tabular form.","text":"`Transform` returns a new `IDataView` with the `Score` column appended. Use this path when you already have rows in tabular form."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Save and load","text":"Save and load"},{"kind":"p","html":"A trained model outlives its process. Serialize it with the training schema and reload later:","text":"A trained model outlives its process. Serialize it with the training schema and reload later:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// Save — pass the schema from the data you trained on\nmlContext.Model.Save(model, trainingData.Schema, \"model.zip\");\n\n// Load — receive the schema back through the out parameter\nDataViewSchema modelSchema;\nITransformer loadedModel = mlContext.Model.Load(\"model.zip\", out modelSchema);"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003eDataViewSchema\u003c/code\u003e carries column names and types. Without it, \u003ccode\u003eSave\u003c/code\u003e produces a zip that won&#39;t rehydrate into a working pipeline.","text":"The `DataViewSchema` carries column names and types. Without it, `Save` produces a zip that won't rehydrate into a working pipeline."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCreatePredictionEngine\u003c/code\u003e is not thread-safe. Creating one per request under load works but wastes allocations. For concurrent inference, use \u003ccode\u003ePredictionEnginePool&lt;TIn, TOut&gt;\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Extensions.ML\u003c/code\u003e, or give each thread its own engine.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`CreatePredictionEngine` is not thread-safe. Creating one per request under load works but wastes allocations. For concurrent inference, use `PredictionEnginePool\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e` from `Microsoft.Extensions.ML`, or give each thread its own engine."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003esaving without the schema. \u003ccode\u003emlContext.Model.Save(model, null, &quot;model.zip&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e compiles but strips the metadata ML.NET needs to reconstruct input columns. Always pass \u003ccode\u003etrainingData.Schema\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"saving without the schema. `mlContext.Model.Save(model, null, \"model.zip\")` compiles but strips the metadata ML.NET needs to reconstruct input columns. Always pass `trainingData.Schema`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eFit()\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e. Wrap it in a \u003ccode\u003ePredictionEngine\u003c/code\u003e for single rows, call \u003ccode\u003eTransform\u003c/code\u003e for batches, and persist it with \u003ccode\u003eSave(model, schema, path)\u003c/code\u003e so the trained weights survive a restart.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`Fit()` returns `ITransformer`. Wrap it in a `PredictionEngine` for single rows, call `Transform` for batches, and persist it with `Save(model, schema, path)` so the trained weights survive a restart."}]},{"n":7,"id":"ai-chat-completion-local","title":"Chat completion with Ollama + SLMs","hook":"Run Phi-3 on your laptop, stream tokens into a console loop, and never touch a cloud API key.","tags":["ai","slm","ollama","streaming"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"slides/SLM.pptx; notes/SLM.docx; notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx; research-ai.md §Ollama, §Chat Completion, §Call Ollama via OllamaSharp, §Ollama Setup Commands, §Endpoint URL Pitfalls","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Open concrete","text":"Open concrete"},{"kind":"p","html":"You open a terminal, run \u003ccode\u003eollama pull phi3:latest\u003c/code\u003e, and a few gigabytes later a Small Language Model (SLM) sits on disk. A second command, \u003ccode\u003eollama run phi3:latest\u003c/code\u003e, hands you a REPL. The same daemon now listens on \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:11434/\u003c/code\u003e, and your C# console app can talk to it with four lines of \u003ccode\u003eOllamaSharp\u003c/code\u003e code. No API key, no cloud, no rate limit.","text":"You open a terminal, run `ollama pull phi3:latest`, and a few gigabytes later a Small Language Model (SLM) sits on disk. A second command, `ollama run phi3:latest`, hands you a REPL. The same daemon now listens on `http://localhost:11434/`, and your C# console app can talk to it with four lines of `OllamaSharp` code. No API key, no cloud, no rate limit."},{"kind":"p","html":"This lesson wires that daemon to a \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e in .NET, sends a \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;ChatMessage&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, and streams the reply token-by-token.","text":"This lesson wires that daemon to a `IChatClient` in .NET, sends a `List\u003cChatMessage\u003e`, and streams the reply token-by-token."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Ollama: the local runtime","text":"Ollama: the local runtime"},{"kind":"p","html":"Ollama is a local LLM/SLM runtime. It downloads a model, loads it into memory, and exposes an OpenAI-compatible HTTP API on port \u003ccode\u003e11434\u003c/code\u003e. Everything runs on your machine after the initial pull.","text":"Ollama is a local LLM/SLM runtime. It downloads a model, loads it into memory, and exposes an OpenAI-compatible HTTP API on port `11434`. Everything runs on your machine after the initial pull."},{"kind":"p","html":"The four commands you need:","text":"The four commands you need:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"ollama pull phi3:latest\nollama list\nollama show phi3:latest\nollama run phi3:latest"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003epull\u003c/code\u003e downloads; \u003ccode\u003elist\u003c/code\u003e shows what you have; \u003ccode\u003eshow\u003c/code\u003e prints model metadata; \u003ccode\u003erun\u003c/code\u003e opens an interactive chat in the terminal (useful for smoke-testing before you touch C#).","text":"`pull` downloads; `list` shows what you have; `show` prints model metadata; `run` opens an interactive chat in the terminal (useful for smoke-testing before you touch C#)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Typical SLMs the course uses: Phi-3 (Microsoft, ~3.8B params), Llava (vision-capable), Llama3.2-1B (tiny). All fit under 5 GB.","text":"Typical SLMs the course uses: Phi-3 (Microsoft, ~3.8B params), Llava (vision-capable), Llama3.2-1B (tiny). All fit under 5 GB."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Does Ollama need an internet connection at inference time?","a":"No. Internet is required only for `ollama pull` to download the model. After that the daemon and model are fully local."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Configure the endpoint from \u003ccode\u003eappsettings.json\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Configure the endpoint from `appsettings.json`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Keep the URL and model id out of code:","text":"Keep the URL and model id out of code:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"json","code":"{\n  \"OllamaUrl\": \"http://localhost:11434/\",\n  \"ModelId\": \"phi3:latest\"\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Read these at startup, hand them to the client constructor. Changing models becomes a config edit, not a recompile.","text":"Read these at startup, hand them to the client constructor. Changing models becomes a config edit, not a recompile."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Call Ollama from C# with \u003ccode\u003eOllamaSharp\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Call Ollama from C# with `OllamaSharp`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Add the packages:","text":"Add the packages:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"dotnet add package OllamaSharp\ndotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.AI -v 10.4.0"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eOllamaSharp\u003c/code\u003e is the third-party NuGet package providing \u003ccode\u003eOllamaApiClient\u003c/code\u003e, which implements \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Extensions.AI\u003c/code\u003e. The abstraction lets you swap in cloud backends later without rewriting the caller.","text":"`OllamaSharp` is the third-party NuGet package providing `OllamaApiClient`, which implements `IChatClient` from `Microsoft.Extensions.AI`. The abstraction lets you swap in cloud backends later without rewriting the caller."},{"kind":"p","html":"The canonical chat-completion loop (from \u003ccode\u003eSLM.docx\u003c/code\u003e Demo #1):","text":"The canonical chat-completion loop (from `SLM.docx` Demo #1):"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using Microsoft.Extensions.AI;\nusing OllamaSharp;\n\nIChatClient chatClient =\n    new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\");\n\nList\u003cChatMessage\u003e chatHistory = new();\nchatHistory.Add(new ChatMessage(ChatRole.User, userPrompt));\n\nawait foreach (ChatResponseUpdate item in\n    chatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync(chatHistory))\n{\n    Console.Write(item.Text);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Four moving parts:","text":"Four moving parts:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eOllamaApiClient(uri, modelId)\u003c/code\u003e — constructor takes a \u003ccode\u003eUri\u003c/code\u003e and a model id string. The returned object implements \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eChatMessage(ChatRole.User, content)\u003c/code\u003e — one entry in the conversation. \u003ccode\u003eChatRole\u003c/code\u003e is the enum \u003ccode\u003eUser\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAssistant\u003c/code\u003e, or \u003ccode\u003eSystem\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eList&lt;ChatMessage&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — acts as your \u003ccode\u003eChatHistory\u003c/code\u003e. Append each turn in order; the full list is re-sent on every call.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGetStreamingResponseAsync\u003c/code\u003e — returns \u003ccode\u003eIAsyncEnumerable&lt;ChatResponseUpdate&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Each update carries a \u003ccode\u003eText\u003c/code\u003e fragment. You print as tokens arrive instead of waiting for the full response.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. `OllamaApiClient(uri, modelId)` — constructor takes a `Uri` and a model id string. The returned object implements `IChatClient`.\n2. `ChatMessage(ChatRole.User, content)` — one entry in the conversation. `ChatRole` is the enum `User`, `Assistant`, or `System`.\n3. `List\u003cChatMessage\u003e` — acts as your `ChatHistory`. Append each turn in order; the full list is re-sent on every call.\n4. `GetStreamingResponseAsync` — returns `IAsyncEnumerable\u003cChatResponseUpdate\u003e`. Each update carries a `Text` fragment. You print as tokens arrive instead of waiting for the full response."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eBuffered vs streaming. If you call \u003ccode\u003eawait chatClient.GetResponseAsync(chatHistory)\u003c/code\u003e instead, you get one \u003ccode\u003eChatResponse\u003c/code\u003e object back once the model finishes. That is simpler but feels slow on long replies. \u003ccode\u003eGetStreamingResponseAsync\u003c/code\u003e trades a few more lines for immediate feedback — the right default for interactive UIs.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Buffered vs streaming. If you call `await chatClient.GetResponseAsync(chatHistory)` instead, you get one `ChatResponse` object back once the model finishes. That is simpler but feels slow on long replies. `GetStreamingResponseAsync` trades a few more lines for immediate feedback — the right default for interactive UIs."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Using the ChatClient directly (no streaming)","text":"Using the ChatClient directly (no streaming)"},{"kind":"p","html":"When you only need the final text, the shape collapses:","text":"When you only need the final text, the shape collapses:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"string ollamaUrl = \"http://localhost:11434/\";\nstring modelId = \"llava:7b\";\nIChatClient ollamaClient = new OllamaApiClient(ollamaUrl, modelId);\n\nvar response = await ollamaClient.GetResponseAsync(chatHistory);\nConsole.WriteLine(response.Text);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Same client, different method. \u003ccode\u003eGetResponseAsync\u003c/code\u003e returns a full \u003ccode\u003eChatResponse\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003eGetStreamingResponseAsync\u003c/code\u003e yields \u003ccode\u003eChatResponseUpdate\u003c/code\u003e items incrementally.","text":"Same client, different method. `GetResponseAsync` returns a full `ChatResponse`; `GetStreamingResponseAsync` yields `ChatResponseUpdate` items incrementally."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Multi-turn conversations","text":"Multi-turn conversations"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eList&lt;ChatMessage&gt;\u003c/code\u003e is the conversation. To keep context across turns, append the user&#39;s new message and the model&#39;s reply to the same list, then call the client again:","text":"`List\u003cChatMessage\u003e` is the conversation. To keep context across turns, append the user's new message and the model's reply to the same list, then call the client again:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"chatHistory.Add(new ChatMessage(ChatRole.User, \"What is its moon?\"));\nvar reply = await chatClient.GetResponseAsync(chatHistory);\nchatHistory.Add(new ChatMessage(ChatRole.Assistant, reply.Text));"},{"kind":"p","html":"The SLM has no memory of its own. Every call re-sends the whole history. Trim oldest entries when you hit the context window.","text":"The SLM has no memory of its own. Every call re-sends the whole history. Trim oldest entries when you hit the context window."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003ePort typo and protocol traps.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWrong port: \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:1143\u003c/code\u003e has four digits, not five. The daemon listens on \u003ccode\u003e11434\u003c/code\u003e. A single dropped digit silently fails to connect.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWrong protocol: Ollama is \u003ccode\u003ehttp://\u003c/code\u003e. GitHub Models is \u003ccode\u003ehttps://\u003c/code\u003e with the path \u003ccode\u003e/inference\u003c/code\u003e. Mixing them — e.g. \u003ccode\u003ehttps://localhost:11434/inference\u003c/code\u003e — is a classic exam distractor.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e&quot;Ollama requires internet&quot; is FALSE. It is fully local after \u003ccode\u003eollama pull\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePackage vs binary: \u003ccode\u003eOllamaSharp\u003c/code\u003e is the NuGet C# client. \u003ccode\u003eollama\u003c/code\u003e is the CLI binary and daemon. The exam may ask which name is the .NET package — answer: \u003ccode\u003eOllamaSharp\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"Port typo and protocol traps.\n- Wrong port: `http://localhost:1143` has four digits, not five. The daemon listens on `11434`. A single dropped digit silently fails to connect.\n- Wrong protocol: Ollama is `http://`. GitHub Models is `https://` with the path `/inference`. Mixing them — e.g. `https://localhost:11434/inference` — is a classic exam distractor.\n- \"Ollama requires internet\" is FALSE. It is fully local after `ollama pull`.\n- Package vs binary: `OllamaSharp` is the NuGet C# client. `ollama` is the CLI binary and daemon. The exam may ask which name is the .NET package — answer: `OllamaSharp`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"How the pieces sit","text":"How the pieces sit"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Your C# app\n    |\nOllamaApiClient(\"http://localhost:11434/\", \"phi3\")  implements IChatClient\n    |  HTTP POST, OpenAI-compatible JSON\nOllama daemon  (listens on port 11434)\n    |\nLoaded SLM (Phi-3 weights in RAM)\n    |\nTokens stream back as ChatResponseUpdate fragments"},{"kind":"p","html":"Nothing leaves your machine. The daemon is the only process that touches the model; your app only speaks HTTP to \u003ccode\u003elocalhost\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Nothing leaves your machine. The daemon is the only process that touches the model; your app only speaks HTTP to `localhost`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eOllamaApiClient(new Uri(&quot;http://localhost:11434/&quot;), &quot;phi3&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e is the full setup for local chat completion. Build a \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;ChatMessage&gt;\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eChatRole\u003c/code\u003e + content, call \u003ccode\u003eGetStreamingResponseAsync\u003c/code\u003e for token-by-token output or \u003ccode\u003eGetResponseAsync\u003c/code\u003e for one buffered reply, and remember: HTTP, port 11434, no internet needed after \u003ccode\u003eollama pull\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\")` is the full setup for local chat completion. Build a `List\u003cChatMessage\u003e` with `ChatRole` + content, call `GetStreamingResponseAsync` for token-by-token output or `GetResponseAsync` for one buffered reply, and remember: HTTP, port 11434, no internet needed after `ollama pull`."}]},{"n":8,"id":"ai-cloud-models","title":"GitHub Models + Azure OpenAI endpoints","hook":"Same SDK, two clouds — and the credential class has a misleading name.","tags":["ai","cloud","auth"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"notes/AI-Models_MAF_SCRIPT.docx; slides/CSharp_Meets_AI.pptx","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"GitHub Models and Azure OpenAI endpoints","text":"GitHub Models and Azure OpenAI endpoints"},{"kind":"p","html":"You point a \u003ccode\u003eChatClient\u003c/code\u003e at either GitHub Models or Azure OpenAI. Both clouds use the same \u003ccode\u003eAzureKeyCredential\u003c/code\u003e class for authentication. The endpoint URL and model-name format change — everything else stays identical.","text":"You point a `ChatClient` at either GitHub Models or Azure OpenAI. Both clouds use the same `AzureKeyCredential` class for authentication. The endpoint URL and model-name format change — everything else stays identical."},{"kind":"h3","html":"GitHub Models wiring","text":"GitHub Models wiring"},{"kind":"p","html":"GitHub Models hosts inference at \u003ccode\u003ehttps://models.github.ai/inference\u003c/code\u003e. You authenticate with a GitHub Personal Access Token, passed through \u003ccode\u003eAzureKeyCredential(token)\u003c/code\u003e. The model id requires a vendor prefix like \u003ccode\u003eopenai/gpt-4o-mini\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"GitHub Models hosts inference at `https://models.github.ai/inference`. You authenticate with a GitHub Personal Access Token, passed through `AzureKeyCredential(token)`. The model id requires a vendor prefix like `openai/gpt-4o-mini`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003econstruct a \u003ccode\u003eChatClient\u003c/code\u003e for GitHub Models:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-csharp\"\u003estring? apiKey = config[&quot;GitHub:Token&quot;];\nstring? endpoint = config[&quot;GitHub:ApiEndpoint&quot;];\nstring? model = config[&quot;GitHub:Model&quot;];\nIChatClient chatClient = new ChatClient(\n    model,\n    new AzureKeyCredential(apiKey!),\n    new OpenAIClientOptions\n    {\n        Endpoint = new Uri(endpoint)\n    }\n).AsIChatClient();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","text":"construct a `ChatClient` for GitHub Models:\n```csharp\nstring? apiKey = config[\"GitHub:Token\"];\nstring? endpoint = config[\"GitHub:ApiEndpoint\"];\nstring? model = config[\"GitHub:Model\"];\nIChatClient chatClient = new ChatClient(\n    model,\n    new AzureKeyCredential(apiKey!),\n    new OpenAIClientOptions\n    {\n        Endpoint = new Uri(endpoint)\n    }\n).AsIChatClient();\n```"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e.AsIChatClient()\u003c/code\u003e extension adapts the OpenAI \u003ccode\u003eChatClient\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Extensions.AI\u003c/code\u003e&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e. That lets the agent framework consume it.","text":"The `.AsIChatClient()` extension adapts the OpenAI `ChatClient` to `Microsoft.Extensions.AI`'s `IChatClient`. That lets the agent framework consume it."},{"kind":"h3","html":"appsettings.json contract","text":"appsettings.json contract"},{"kind":"p","html":"Store the token, endpoint, and model together so config binding stays clean.","text":"Store the token, endpoint, and model together so config binding stays clean."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eappsettings.json for GitHub Models:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-json\"\u003e{\n  &quot;GitHub&quot;: {\n    &quot;Token&quot;: &quot;PUT-GITHUB-PERSONAL-ACCESS-TOKEN-HERE&quot;,\n    &quot;ApiEndpoint&quot;: &quot;https://models.github.ai/inference&quot;,\n    &quot;Model&quot;: &quot;openai/gpt-4o-mini&quot;\n  }\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","text":"appsettings.json for GitHub Models:\n```json\n{\n  \"GitHub\": {\n    \"Token\": \"PUT-GITHUB-PERSONAL-ACCESS-TOKEN-HERE\",\n    \"ApiEndpoint\": \"https://models.github.ai/inference\",\n    \"Model\": \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"\n  }\n}\n```"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Azure OpenAI wiring","text":"Azure OpenAI wiring"},{"kind":"p","html":"Azure OpenAI swaps the endpoint for your resource URL and keys the call on a deployment name. You still pass \u003ccode\u003eAzureKeyCredential\u003c/code\u003e. The Semantic Kernel variant registers it through \u003ccode\u003eAddAzureOpenAIChatCompletion\u003c/code\u003e with three fields: deployment name, endpoint URL, and API key.","text":"Azure OpenAI swaps the endpoint for your resource URL and keys the call on a deployment name. You still pass `AzureKeyCredential`. The Semantic Kernel variant registers it through `AddAzureOpenAIChatCompletion` with three fields: deployment name, endpoint URL, and API key."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why does `AzureKeyCredential` authenticate GitHub Models despite the \"Azure\" prefix?","a":"The class wraps any bearer token. The OpenAI SDK reuses it for GitHub PATs — no `GithubCredential` type exists."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Distractor map","text":"Distractor map"},{"kind":"p","html":"The exam leans on fake credential classes and malformed endpoints.","text":"The exam leans on fake credential classes and malformed endpoints."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003ewrong credential types:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGithubCredential\u003c/code\u003e — does not exist.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eBearerTokenCredential\u003c/code\u003e — not in this SDK context.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eOAuthCredential\u003c/code\u003e — wrong auth flow entirely.\nAlways \u003ccode\u003eAzureKeyCredential(token)\u003c/code\u003e for both GitHub Models and Azure OpenAI.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"wrong credential types:\n- `GithubCredential` — does not exist.\n- `BearerTokenCredential` — not in this SDK context.\n- `OAuthCredential` — wrong auth flow entirely.\nAlways `AzureKeyCredential(token)` for both GitHub Models and Azure OpenAI."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eendpoint URL shape:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGitHub Models must be HTTPS and include \u003ccode\u003e/inference\u003c/code\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ehttps://models.github.ai/inference\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDrop the \u003ccode\u003e/inference\u003c/code\u003e path and the client fails.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDo not confuse with Ollama, which is HTTP on port \u003ccode\u003e11434\u003c/code\u003e and needs no path.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"endpoint URL shape:\n- GitHub Models must be HTTPS and include `/inference`: `https://models.github.ai/inference`.\n- Drop the `/inference` path and the client fails.\n- Do not confuse with Ollama, which is HTTP on port `11434` and needs no path."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003emodel-name prefix:\nGitHub Models requires a vendor prefix like \u003ccode\u003eopenai/gpt-4o-mini\u003c/code\u003e. Passing bare \u003ccode\u003egpt-4o-mini\u003c/code\u003e gets rejected by the router.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"model-name prefix:\nGitHub Models requires a vendor prefix like `openai/gpt-4o-mini`. Passing bare `gpt-4o-mini` gets rejected by the router."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eChatClient(model, new AzureKeyCredential(token), new OpenAIClientOptions { Endpoint = new Uri(&quot;https://models.github.ai/inference&quot;) })\u003c/code\u003e — HTTPS, \u003ccode\u003e/inference\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eopenai/\u003c/code\u003e prefix, \u003ccode\u003eAzureKeyCredential\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`ChatClient(model, new AzureKeyCredential(token), new OpenAIClientOptions { Endpoint = new Uri(\"https://models.github.ai/inference\") })` — HTTPS, `/inference`, `openai/` prefix, `AzureKeyCredential`."}]},{"n":9,"id":"ml-automl-cli","title":"ML.NET AutoML CLI","hook":"One terminal command explores 40+ regression models and emits a ready-to-run console project.","tags":["ml-net","automl"],"module":"AI in .NET","source":"notes/ML.NET_vscode_automl_SCRIPT.docx; research-mlnet.md §automl","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Run the CLI","text":"Run the CLI"},{"kind":"p","html":"Open a terminal in the folder holding your CSV and run:","text":"Open a terminal in the folder holding your CSV and run:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"mlnet regression --dataset taxi-fare-train.csv --label-col 6 --train-time 60 --has-header true"},{"kind":"p","html":"This tells \u003ccode\u003emlnet\u003c/code\u003e to treat the task as regression, read \u003ccode\u003etaxi-fare-train.csv\u003c/code\u003e, predict the column at index 6 (0-based), and spend 60 seconds exploring algorithm and hyperparameter combinations.","text":"This tells `mlnet` to treat the task as regression, read `taxi-fare-train.csv`, predict the column at index 6 (0-based), and spend 60 seconds exploring algorithm and hyperparameter combinations."},{"kind":"p","html":"Install the tool once per machine with:","text":"Install the tool once per machine with:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"dotnet tool install -g mlnet-win-x64"},{"kind":"p","html":"Swap in \u003ccode\u003emlnet-osx-x64\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003emlnet-linux-x64\u003c/code\u003e for the other platforms. The installed command is lowercase \u003ccode\u003emlnet\u003c/code\u003e, with no dot.","text":"Swap in `mlnet-osx-x64` or `mlnet-linux-x64` for the other platforms. The installed command is lowercase `mlnet`, with no dot."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What AutoML actually does","text":"What AutoML actually does"},{"kind":"p","html":"AutoML does not pick one algorithm. In the 60-second window it fits dozens of regression variants (FastTree, FastTreeTweedie, LightGbm, Sdca, FastForest, and more) across multiple hyperparameter settings, then ranks the results by metric.","text":"AutoML does not pick one algorithm. In the 60-second window it fits dozens of regression variants (FastTree, FastTreeTweedie, LightGbm, Sdca, FastForest, and more) across multiple hyperparameter settings, then ranks the results by metric."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-text\"\u003eExploration time: 60 seconds\nModels tested: 42\nTop 5 models (by RSquared):\n  1. FastTreeRegression         0.951\n  2. FastTreeTweedieRegression  0.944\n  3. LightGbmRegression         0.938\n  4. FastForestRegression       0.930\n  5. SdcaRegression             0.812\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe CLI keeps the winner at position 1 and writes a console project that trains and loads it.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"```text\nExploration time: 60 seconds\nModels tested: 42\nTop 5 models (by RSquared):\n  1. FastTreeRegression         0.951\n  2. FastTreeTweedieRegression  0.944\n  3. LightGbmRegression         0.938\n  4. FastForestRegression       0.930\n  5. SdcaRegression             0.812\n```\nThe CLI keeps the winner at position 1 and writes a console project that trains and loads it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Key flags","text":"Key flags"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e--dataset\u003c/code\u003e — path to the training CSV.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e--label-col\u003c/code\u003e — the column to predict. Accepts a 0-based INDEX (\u003ccode\u003e6\u003c/code\u003e) or a column NAME (\u003ccode\u003eFareAmount\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e--train-time\u003c/code\u003e — exploration budget in seconds.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e--has-header\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e if the CSV has a header row; otherwise \u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `--dataset` — path to the training CSV.\n- `--label-col` — the column to predict. Accepts a 0-based INDEX (`6`) or a column NAME (`FareAmount`).\n- `--train-time` — exploration budget in seconds.\n- `--has-header` — `true` if the CSV has a header row; otherwise `false`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which flag sets the exploration budget, and what unit does it use? Which flag chooses the target column, and what two forms does it accept?","a":"`--train-time` in seconds; `--label-col` takes a 0-based index (e.g. `6`) or a column name (e.g. `FareAmount`)."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What you get back","text":"What you get back"},{"kind":"p","html":"The CLI generates a full console project — source files, \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e, and a \u003ccode\u003e.zip\u003c/code\u003e model — wired to the winning pipeline. You \u003ccode\u003edotnet run\u003c/code\u003e it; you do not receive a bare model file.","text":"The CLI generates a full console project — source files, `.csproj`, and a `.zip` model — wired to the winning pipeline. You `dotnet run` it; you do not receive a bare model file."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003emlnet\u003c/code\u003e (lowercase, no dot) is the CLI tool. \u003ccode\u003eML.NET\u003c/code\u003e (uppercase, dotted) is the framework the tool targets. Mixing casing on the exam loses the mark. The CLI is also not a script generator — expect a console project, never a Python file or a standalone \u003ccode\u003e.zip\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`mlnet` (lowercase, no dot) is the CLI tool. `ML.NET` (uppercase, dotted) is the framework the tool targets. Mixing casing on the exam loses the mark. The CLI is also not a script generator — expect a console project, never a Python file or a standalone `.zip`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e--label-col FareAmount\u003c/code\u003e silently fails when your CSV header spells the column \u003ccode\u003efare_amount\u003c/code\u003e or lacks a header row entirely. Pass the 0-based index (\u003ccode\u003e6\u003c/code\u003e) whenever the exact header text is uncertain.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`--label-col FareAmount` silently fails when your CSV header spells the column `fare_amount` or lacks a header row entirely. Pass the 0-based index (`6`) whenever the exact header text is uncertain."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe top-5 list ranks only the models AutoML happened to try. A larger \u003ccode\u003e--train-time\u003c/code\u003e generally surfaces a better winner, but gains diminish — doubling from 60 to 120 seconds rarely doubles RSquared.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The top-5 list ranks only the models AutoML happened to try. A larger `--train-time` generally surfaces a better winner, but gains diminish — doubling from 60 to 120 seconds rarely doubles RSquared."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003emlnet regression --dataset &lt;csv&gt; --label-col &lt;index|name&gt; --train-time &lt;seconds&gt;\u003c/code\u003e explores 40+ regression variants in the given budget and emits a console project wired to the best model it found.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`mlnet regression --dataset \u003ccsv\u003e --label-col \u003cindex|name\u003e --train-time \u003cseconds\u003e` explores 40+ regression variants in the given budget and emits a console project wired to the best model it found."}]},{"n":10,"id":"grpc-proto-contracts","title":"gRPC .proto contracts — syntax, field tags, messages","hook":"Write the contract first; the code generates itself.","tags":["grpc","protobuf","contract-first"],"module":"Distributed Services & Orchestration","source":"slides/gRPC.pptx; notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx; research-grpc.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"One \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e file drives a whole service","text":"One `.proto` file drives a whole service"},{"kind":"p","html":"You want a student lookup service. Before you write a single line of C#, you author this:","text":"You want a student lookup service. Before you write a single line of C#, you author this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"proto","code":"syntax = \"proto3\";\n\noption csharp_namespace = \"GrpcStudentsServer\";\n\nservice StudentRemote {\n  rpc GetStudentInfo (StudentLookupModel) returns (StudentModel);\n  rpc InsertStudent  (StudentModel)      returns (Reply);\n}\n\nmessage StudentLookupModel {\n  int32 studentId = 1;\n}\n\nmessage StudentModel {\n  int32 studentId = 1;\n  string firstName = 2;\n  string lastName = 3;\n  string school = 4;\n}\n\nmessage Reply {\n  string result = 1;\n  bool   isOk   = 2;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"That single \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e file is the contract. \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Tools\u003c/code\u003e compiles it at build time into two C# classes per side: on the server, a base class your service inherits from; on the client, a ready-to-call stub. No manually written DTOs, no hand-rolled serialization.","text":"That single `.proto` file is the contract. `Grpc.Tools` compiles it at build time into two C# classes per side: on the server, a base class your service inherits from; on the client, a ready-to-call stub. No manually written DTOs, no hand-rolled serialization."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The four keywords you actually write","text":"The four keywords you actually write"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eKeyword\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esyntax = &quot;proto3&quot;;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePins the version. Proto3 is what the course targets.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eoption csharp_namespace = &quot;X&quot;;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSets the generated C# namespace. Without it, you get the \u003ccode\u003epackage\u003c/code\u003e name instead.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eservice\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeclares a gRPC service. Name it once; both sides use the same name.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003erpc\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeclares a single method. Shape: \u003ccode\u003erpc Name (Request) returns (Response);\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003emessage\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeclares a structured payload. Each field has a type, a name, and a \u003cstrong\u003etag\u003c/strong\u003e.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Field tags are contracts with the future","text":"Field tags are contracts with the future"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every field in a \u003ccode\u003emessage\u003c/code\u003e carries a number:","text":"Every field in a `message` carries a number:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"proto","code":"message StudentModel {\n  int32 studentId = 1;\n  string firstName = 2;\n  string lastName = 3;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Those numbers — the \u003cstrong\u003efield tags\u003c/strong\u003e — are what \u003ccode\u003eprotoc\u003c/code\u003e serializes to the wire. The text name is cosmetic; the tag is the ABI.","text":"Those numbers — the **field tags** — are what `protoc` serializes to the wire. The text name is cosmetic; the tag is the ABI."},{"kind":"p","html":"Two non-obvious rules:","text":"Two non-obvious rules:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTags are permanent.\u003c/strong\u003e Once a tag ships to a client, reusing it for a different field breaks every deployed consumer that hasn&#39;t recompiled. Delete the field but keep the tag reserved: \u003ccode\u003ereserved 2;\u003c/code\u003e tells future authors the slot is off-limits.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTags 1–15 encode in one byte; 16+ take two.\u003c/strong\u003e Put hot fields in the 1–15 range. On a per-message basis the difference is small; across millions of requests it adds up.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Tags are permanent.** Once a tag ships to a client, reusing it for a different field breaks every deployed consumer that hasn't recompiled. Delete the field but keep the tag reserved: `reserved 2;` tells future authors the slot is off-limits.\n2. **Tags 1–15 encode in one byte; 16+ take two.** Put hot fields in the 1–15 range. On a per-message basis the difference is small; across millions of requests it adds up."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A live service has `message Person { string name = 1; int32 age = 2; }` deployed. You want to drop `age` and add a new `string email` field. What is the safe rewrite?","a":"Reserve the old tag and allocate a fresh one: `message Person { string name = 1; reserved 2; string email = 3; }`. Never set `email = 2` — deployed clients still interpret tag 2 as an `int32`, and the wire bytes collide."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Proto3 defaults — there is no \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Proto3 defaults — there is no `null`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Unset scalar fields take zero-values: numbers are \u003ccode\u003e0\u003c/code\u003e, strings are \u003ccode\u003e&quot;&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, bools are \u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e, bytes are empty. This is a surprise coming from C#, where \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e is a valid state. If you need &quot;absent vs zero&quot; semantics on an integer field, wrap it in a nested message or use \u003ccode\u003egoogle.protobuf.Int32Value\u003c/code\u003e — not a bare \u003ccode\u003eint32\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Unset scalar fields take zero-values: numbers are `0`, strings are `\"\"`, bools are `false`, bytes are empty. This is a surprise coming from C#, where `null` is a valid state. If you need \"absent vs zero\" semantics on an integer field, wrap it in a nested message or use `google.protobuf.Int32Value` — not a bare `int32`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Empty requests use \u003ccode\u003emessage Empty {}\u003c/code\u003e — a declared zero-field message. This pattern appears often for &quot;list everything&quot; style methods.","text":"Empty requests use `message Empty {}` — a declared zero-field message. This pattern appears often for \"list everything\" style methods."},{"kind":"p","html":"Collections use \u003ccode\u003erepeated\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Collections use `repeated`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"proto","code":"message StudentList {\n  repeated StudentModel items = 1;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"On the C# side, \u003ccode\u003erepeated\u003c/code\u003e maps to a read-only \u003ccode\u003eRepeatedField&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e you populate with \u003ccode\u003e.Add(...)\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"On the C# side, `repeated` maps to a read-only `RepeatedField\u003cT\u003e` you populate with `.Add(...)`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e above generates (among others) a C# class \u003ccode\u003eStudentModel\u003c/code\u003e with properties \u003ccode\u003eStudentId\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSchool\u003c/code\u003e and a base class \u003ccode\u003eStudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase\u003c/code\u003e your service inherits from. The generated code is a build artifact — rebuild after every \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e edit or you consume stale stubs.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The `.proto` above generates (among others) a C# class `StudentModel` with properties `StudentId`, `FirstName`, `LastName`, `School` and a base class `StudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase` your service inherits from. The generated code is a build artifact — rebuild after every `.proto` edit or you consume stale stubs."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eField tags 1–15 encode in a single byte; tags 16+ take two. On a \u003ccode\u003eStudentModel\u003c/code\u003e that ships 6 million times a day, putting rare fields in low tags wastes bandwidth. Allocate low tags to the fields that ship on every call; park optional / rarely-set fields at 16+.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Field tags 1–15 encode in a single byte; tags 16+ take two. On a `StudentModel` that ships 6 million times a day, putting rare fields in low tags wastes bandwidth. Allocate low tags to the fields that ship on every call; park optional / rarely-set fields at 16+."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003egRPC requires HTTP/2. The framework enforces this — a client talking to a server that refuses HTTP/2 (because Kestrel was misconfigured to HTTP/1.1, or \u003ccode\u003elaunchSettings.json\u003c/code\u003e forced a legacy protocol) fails with a cryptic connection error, not a clear &quot;protocol mismatch&quot; message. If the first call of a brand-new gRPC service hangs or resets, check HTTP/2 settings first.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"gRPC requires HTTP/2. The framework enforces this — a client talking to a server that refuses HTTP/2 (because Kestrel was misconfigured to HTTP/1.1, or `launchSettings.json` forced a legacy protocol) fails with a cryptic connection error, not a clear \"protocol mismatch\" message. If the first call of a brand-new gRPC service hangs or resets, check HTTP/2 settings first."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e file is your single source of truth. \u003ccode\u003esyntax = &quot;proto3&quot;;\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eoption csharp_namespace = ...;\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eservice\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003erpc\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003emessage\u003c/code\u003e are the only keywords you need. Number every field starting at 1, never reuse a tag, put hot fields in 1–15, and remember that unset scalars are zero-values, not null.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The `.proto` file is your single source of truth. `syntax = \"proto3\";` + `option csharp_namespace = ...;` + `service` + `rpc` + `message` are the only keywords you need. Number every field starting at 1, never reuse a tag, put hot fields in 1–15, and remember that unset scalars are zero-values, not null."}]},{"n":11,"id":"grpc-server-implementation","title":"gRPC server implementation — override the generated base class","hook":"Inherit from the generated `ServiceBase`; override one async method per `rpc`.","tags":["grpc","server","asp-net-core"],"module":"Distributed Services & Orchestration","source":"notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx; Labs/W09 gRPC/; research-grpc.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"One class, one override per \u003ccode\u003erpc\u003c/code\u003e","text":"One class, one override per `rpc`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Given the \u003ccode\u003eStudentRemote\u003c/code\u003e service in your \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Tools\u003c/code\u003e generates an abstract base class named \u003ccode\u003eStudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase\u003c/code\u003e with one virtual method per \u003ccode\u003erpc\u003c/code\u003e. Your job as server author: inherit and override.","text":"Given the `StudentRemote` service in your `.proto`, `Grpc.Tools` generates an abstract base class named `StudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase` with one virtual method per `rpc`. Your job as server author: inherit and override."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class StudentsService : StudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase\n{\n    private readonly SchoolDbContext _context;\n\n    public StudentsService(SchoolDbContext context) =\u003e _context = context;\n\n    public override Task\u003cStudentModel\u003e GetStudentInfo(\n        StudentLookupModel request,\n        ServerCallContext context)\n    {\n        var student = _context.Students!.Find(request.StudentId);\n        if (student is null) return Task.FromResult(new StudentModel());\n\n        return Task.FromResult(new StudentModel\n        {\n            StudentId = student.StudentId,\n            FirstName = student.FirstName,\n            LastName  = student.LastName,\n            School    = student.School\n        });\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three non-negotiable shape rules:","text":"Three non-negotiable shape rules:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInherit from \u003ccode\u003e[Service].[Service]Base\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The name mirrors the \u003ccode\u003eservice\u003c/code\u003e keyword in \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e, plus \u003ccode\u003eBase\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEvery overridden method takes two parameters:\u003c/strong\u003e the request message type, then \u003ccode\u003eServerCallContext\u003c/code\u003e. The second parameter is not optional — it carries cancellation tokens, deadlines, metadata, and peer info.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe return type is \u003ccode\u003eTask&lt;Response&gt;\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eTask\u003c/code\u003e for streaming methods.\u003c/strong\u003e Use \u003ccode\u003eTask.FromResult(...)\u003c/code\u003e to wrap a synchronous result; use \u003ccode\u003easync/await\u003c/code\u003e when the body calls anything async (EF Core, HTTP, file I/O).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Inherit from `[Service].[Service]Base`.** The name mirrors the `service` keyword in `.proto`, plus `Base`.\n2. **Every overridden method takes two parameters:** the request message type, then `ServerCallContext`. The second parameter is not optional — it carries cancellation tokens, deadlines, metadata, and peer info.\n3. **The return type is `Task\u003cResponse\u003e` or `Task` for streaming methods.** Use `Task.FromResult(...)` to wrap a synchronous result; use `async/await` when the body calls anything async (EF Core, HTTP, file I/O)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Miss any of these and the C# compiler flags the method as not matching an \u003ccode\u003eoverride\u003c/code\u003e target.","text":"Miss any of these and the C# compiler flags the method as not matching an `override` target."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Wire the service in \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Wire the service in `Program.cs`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two calls matter:","text":"Two calls matter:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nbuilder.Services.AddGrpc();                           // 1. register gRPC stack\nbuilder.Services.AddDbContext\u003cSchoolDbContext\u003e(opts =\u003e\n    opts.UseSqlite(builder.Configuration.GetConnectionString(\"DefaultConnection\")!));\n\nvar app = builder.Build();\n\napp.MapGrpcService\u003cStudentsService\u003e();                // 2. route requests to your service\napp.Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAddGrpc()\u003c/code\u003e registers framework types. \u003ccode\u003eMapGrpcService&lt;T&gt;()\u003c/code\u003e tells ASP.NET Core routing: requests hitting this app whose HTTP/2 headers encode a \u003ccode\u003e/StudentRemote/...\u003c/code\u003e path land in your \u003ccode\u003eStudentsService\u003c/code\u003e. Register one \u003ccode\u003eMapGrpcService\u003c/code\u003e per service — the same app can host many.","text":"`AddGrpc()` registers framework types. `MapGrpcService\u003cT\u003e()` tells ASP.NET Core routing: requests hitting this app whose HTTP/2 headers encode a `/StudentRemote/...` path land in your `StudentsService`. Register one `MapGrpcService` per service — the same app can host many."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Streaming overrides look a little different","text":"Streaming overrides look a little different"},{"kind":"p","html":"For a server-streaming method (\u003ccode\u003erpc RetrieveAllStudents (Empty) returns (stream StudentModel);\u003c/code\u003e), the override signature changes:","text":"For a server-streaming method (`rpc RetrieveAllStudents (Empty) returns (stream StudentModel);`), the override signature changes:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public override async Task RetrieveAllStudents(\n    Empty request,\n    IServerStreamWriter\u003cStudentModel\u003e responseStream,\n    ServerCallContext context)\n{\n    foreach (var s in _context.Students!)\n    {\n        await responseStream.WriteAsync(new StudentModel { /* … */ });\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The return type drops to \u003ccode\u003eTask\u003c/code\u003e (no response object) and a third parameter \u003ccode\u003eIServerStreamWriter&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e takes its place. You write each message and the framework frames it on the wire.","text":"The return type drops to `Task` (no response object) and a third parameter `IServerStreamWriter\u003cT\u003e` takes its place. You write each message and the framework frames it on the wire."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your service compiles and runs, but the client times out on the first call. The Kestrel logs show \"HTTP/1.1 request rejected.\" What is the root cause?","a":"gRPC requires HTTP/2. Something in your Kestrel config (e.g. `launchSettings.json` forcing `http` endpoints without HTTP/2, or a legacy `HttpProtocols.Http1` registration) is refusing to negotiate HTTP/2. Fix: ensure your endpoint is declared with `HttpProtocols.Http2` or let .NET defaults apply."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA full CRUD override for \u003ccode\u003eInsertStudent\u003c/code\u003e, which persists via EF Core:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003epublic override async Task&lt;Reply&gt; InsertStudent(StudentModel request, ServerCallContext context)\n{\n    _context.Students!.Add(new Student\n    {\n        FirstName = request.FirstName,\n        LastName  = request.LastName,\n        School    = request.School\n    });\n    await _context.SaveChangesAsync();\n    return new Reply { Result = &quot;Inserted&quot;, IsOk = true };\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eNote the \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e/\u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003eTask.FromResult\u003c/code\u003e. Any override that awaits must be declared \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A full CRUD override for `InsertStudent`, which persists via EF Core:\n```cs\npublic override async Task\u003cReply\u003e InsertStudent(StudentModel request, ServerCallContext context)\n{\n    _context.Students!.Add(new Student\n    {\n        FirstName = request.FirstName,\n        LastName  = request.LastName,\n        School    = request.School\n    });\n    await _context.SaveChangesAsync();\n    return new Reply { Result = \"Inserted\", IsOk = true };\n}\n```\nNote the `async`/`await` instead of `Task.FromResult`. Any override that awaits must be declared `async`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eForgetting the \u003ccode\u003eoverride\u003c/code\u003e keyword on one of your methods silently shadows the base-class method instead of replacing it. The server compiles. The service starts. But client calls hit the generated base&#39;s default &quot;not implemented&quot; handler and get back \u003ccode\u003eRpcException: UNIMPLEMENTED\u003c/code\u003e. Always \u003ccode\u003eoverride\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Forgetting the `override` keyword on one of your methods silently shadows the base-class method instead of replacing it. The server compiles. The service starts. But client calls hit the generated base's default \"not implemented\" handler and get back `RpcException: UNIMPLEMENTED`. Always `override`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eInherit from \u003ccode\u003e[Service].[Service]Base\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eoverride\u003c/code\u003e one \u003ccode\u003eTask&lt;Response&gt;\u003c/code\u003e method per \u003ccode\u003erpc\u003c/code\u003e, always accept the \u003ccode\u003eServerCallContext\u003c/code\u003e parameter, register with \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.Services.AddGrpc()\u003c/code\u003e plus \u003ccode\u003eapp.MapGrpcService&lt;T&gt;()\u003c/code\u003e, and let Kestrel default to HTTP/2. For streaming methods, swap \u003ccode\u003eTask&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for \u003ccode\u003eTask\u003c/code\u003e plus an \u003ccode\u003eIServerStreamWriter&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e parameter.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Inherit from `[Service].[Service]Base`, `override` one `Task\u003cResponse\u003e` method per `rpc`, always accept the `ServerCallContext` parameter, register with `builder.Services.AddGrpc()` plus `app.MapGrpcService\u003cT\u003e()`, and let Kestrel default to HTTP/2. For streaming methods, swap `Task\u003cT\u003e` for `Task` plus an `IServerStreamWriter\u003cT\u003e` parameter."}]},{"n":12,"id":"grpc-client-consumption","title":"gRPC client consumption — GrpcChannel, DI, .csproj config","hook":"Share the `.proto`, flip the `GrpcServices` attribute, and call typed methods.","tags":["grpc","client","di","asp-net-core"],"module":"Distributed Services & Orchestration","source":"notes/gRPC_EF_SQLite_VSCode_SCRIPT.docx; Labs/W09 gRPC/gRPC ASP.NET Client1.html; research-grpc.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Start with the same \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Start with the same `.proto`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Your client project needs the exact same \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e file the server has. Copy it in, drop the server-side namespace (or pick a different \u003ccode\u003eoption csharp_namespace\u003c/code\u003e for client-generated types), and reference it in \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Your client project needs the exact same `.proto` file the server has. Copy it in, drop the server-side namespace (or pick a different `option csharp_namespace` for client-generated types), and reference it in `.csproj`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"xml","code":"\u003cItemGroup\u003e\n  \u003cProtobuf Include=\"Protos\\students.proto\" GrpcServices=\"Client\" /\u003e\n\u003c/ItemGroup\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two things matter. The \u003ccode\u003eInclude\u003c/code\u003e path is relative to the \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003eGrpcServices\u003c/code\u003e attribute tells \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Tools\u003c/code\u003e which side&#39;s code to generate: \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Client&quot;\u003c/code\u003e for clients, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Server&quot;\u003c/code\u003e for servers, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Both&quot;\u003c/code\u003e when one project does both (rare). Build the project and generated classes appear: among them is \u003ccode\u003eStudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient\u003c/code\u003e, your callable stub.","text":"Two things matter. The `Include` path is relative to the `.csproj`. The `GrpcServices` attribute tells `Grpc.Tools` which side's code to generate: `\"Client\"` for clients, `\"Server\"` for servers, `\"Both\"` when one project does both (rare). Build the project and generated classes appear: among them is `StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient`, your callable stub."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Two ways to construct the client","text":"Two ways to construct the client"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Raw: \u003ccode\u003eGrpcChannel\u003c/code\u003e + direct construction","text":"Raw: `GrpcChannel` + direct construction"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using var channel = GrpcChannel.ForAddress(\"http://localhost:5099\");\nvar client = new StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient(channel);\n\nvar reply = await client.GetStudentInfoAsync(\n    new StudentLookupModel { StudentId = 3 });\n\nConsole.WriteLine($\"{reply.FirstName} {reply.LastName}\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eGrpcChannel.ForAddress(url)\u003c/code\u003e opens a long-lived HTTP/2 connection. Reuse the channel across many client constructions — channels are expensive, client stubs are free. Each generated call exposes an async \u003ccode\u003eXxxAsync\u003c/code\u003e form you \u003ccode\u003eawait\u003c/code\u003e and a blocking \u003ccode\u003eXxx\u003c/code\u003e form you typically avoid.","text":"`GrpcChannel.ForAddress(url)` opens a long-lived HTTP/2 connection. Reuse the channel across many client constructions — channels are expensive, client stubs are free. Each generated call exposes an async `XxxAsync` form you `await` and a blocking `Xxx` form you typically avoid."},{"kind":"h3","html":"DI: \u003ccode\u003eAddGrpcClient&lt;T&gt;()\u003c/code\u003e","text":"DI: `AddGrpcClient\u003cT\u003e()`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Inside an ASP.NET Core app — MVC, Razor Pages, Blazor, or a Web API that talks to another gRPC service — register the client with the host&#39;s DI container:","text":"Inside an ASP.NET Core app — MVC, Razor Pages, Blazor, or a Web API that talks to another gRPC service — register the client with the host's DI container:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"builder.Services.AddGrpcClient\u003cStudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient\u003e(opts =\u003e\n{\n    opts.Address = new Uri(\"http://localhost:5099\");\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"You need the \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Net.ClientFactory\u003c/code\u003e NuGet package. Once registered, inject the client anywhere:","text":"You need the `Grpc.Net.ClientFactory` NuGet package. Once registered, inject the client anywhere:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"@inject StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient _grpcClient\n@rendermode InteractiveServer\n\n@code {\n    private StudentModel? _student;\n\n    protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()\n    {\n        _student = await _grpcClient.GetStudentInfoAsync(\n            new StudentLookupModel { StudentId = 3 });\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The factory pattern gives you resilience handlers, OpenTelemetry integration, and channel reuse for free — exactly what \u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e wires up when the client runs under Aspire.","text":"The factory pattern gives you resilience handlers, OpenTelemetry integration, and channel reuse for free — exactly what `AddServiceDefaults()` wires up when the client runs under Aspire."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Interactive render mode matters in Blazor","text":"Interactive render mode matters in Blazor"},{"kind":"p","html":"If your page calls a gRPC client from \u003ccode\u003eOnInitializedAsync\u003c/code\u003e, it must be interactive. \u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveServer\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly\u003c/code\u003e keeps the component alive long enough for an async call to complete. A static-server-rendered page cannot await anything after initial render.","text":"If your page calls a gRPC client from `OnInitializedAsync`, it must be interactive. `@rendermode InteractiveServer` or `@rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly` keeps the component alive long enough for an async call to complete. A static-server-rendered page cannot await anything after initial render."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your .csproj has `\u003cProtobuf Include=\"Protos\\greet.proto\" GrpcServices=\"Server\" /\u003e` inside a Blazor client project. You compile and get errors like \"the type or namespace name 'StudentRemoteClient' could not be found.\" Why?","a":"`GrpcServices=\"Server\"` generates only the server-side base class, not the client stub. Flip the attribute to `GrpcServices=\"Client\"`. Use `\"Both\"` only when the same project hosts both roles."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eMinimal DI-based client registration in \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003evar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.Services.AddGrpcClient&lt;StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient&gt;(opts =&gt;\n    opts.Address = new Uri(&quot;http://localhost:5099&quot;));\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorComponents()\n    .AddInteractiveServerComponents();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapRazorComponents&lt;App&gt;()\n   .AddInteractiveServerRenderMode();\napp.Run();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAny \u003ccode\u003e.razor\u003c/code\u003e component can now \u003ccode\u003e@inject StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient _grpcClient\u003c/code\u003e and call methods without constructing a \u003ccode\u003eGrpcChannel\u003c/code\u003e by hand.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Minimal DI-based client registration in `Program.cs`:\n```cs\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.Services.AddGrpcClient\u003cStudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient\u003e(opts =\u003e\n    opts.Address = new Uri(\"http://localhost:5099\"));\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorComponents()\n    .AddInteractiveServerComponents();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapRazorComponents\u003cApp\u003e()\n   .AddInteractiveServerRenderMode();\napp.Run();\n```\nAny `.razor` component can now `@inject StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient _grpcClient` and call methods without constructing a `GrpcChannel` by hand."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003ePort mismatch between \u003ccode\u003elaunchSettings.json\u003c/code\u003e (where the server declares its listening URL) and the \u003ccode\u003eUri\u003c/code\u003e you pass to the channel. Common case: the server&#39;s dev HTTPS URL is \u003ccode\u003ehttps://localhost:7001\u003c/code\u003e, the client hardcodes \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:5001\u003c/code\u003e, and every call fails with a connection error. Read the server&#39;s \u003ccode\u003elaunchSettings.json\u003c/code\u003e applicationUrl before typing the client URL — or, better, let Aspire&#39;s service discovery resolve \u003ccode\u003ehttp://backend/\u003c/code\u003e at runtime.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Port mismatch between `launchSettings.json` (where the server declares its listening URL) and the `Uri` you pass to the channel. Common case: the server's dev HTTPS URL is `https://localhost:7001`, the client hardcodes `http://localhost:5001`, and every call fails with a connection error. Read the server's `launchSettings.json` applicationUrl before typing the client URL — or, better, let Aspire's service discovery resolve `http://backend/` at runtime."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eCopy the \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e to the client project, set \u003ccode\u003eGrpcServices=&quot;Client&quot;\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e, reuse \u003ccode\u003eGrpcChannel.ForAddress(url)\u003c/code\u003e across calls, and for ASP.NET Core apps prefer \u003ccode\u003eAddGrpcClient&lt;T&gt;()\u003c/code\u003e + constructor/DI injection over hand-rolled channels. In Blazor, set \u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveServer\u003c/code\u003e on any page that awaits a gRPC client call.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Copy the `.proto` to the client project, set `GrpcServices=\"Client\"` in `.csproj`, reuse `GrpcChannel.ForAddress(url)` across calls, and for ASP.NET Core apps prefer `AddGrpcClient\u003cT\u003e()` + constructor/DI injection over hand-rolled channels. In Blazor, set `@rendermode InteractiveServer` on any page that awaits a gRPC client call."}]},{"n":13,"id":"aspire-apphost","title":".NET Aspire AppHost — the orchestration entry point","hook":"One project to declare every service, database, and connection in your stack.","tags":["aspire","orchestration","apphost"],"module":"Distributed Services & Orchestration","source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; Labs/W09 gRPC/; materials/assignments/4870-assignment-2_v0.docx; research-aspire.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The smallest AppHost that does anything","text":"The smallest AppHost that does anything"},{"kind":"p","html":"Given a solution with a gRPC backend and a Blazor frontend, the Aspire AppHost is a separate project whose entire \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e looks like this:","text":"Given a solution with a gRPC backend and a Blazor frontend, the Aspire AppHost is a separate project whose entire `Program.cs` looks like this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nvar backend  = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.StudentsGrpcApi\u003e(\"backend\");\nvar frontend = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.StudentsBlazor\u003e(\"frontend\")\n    .WithReference(backend)\n    .WaitFor(backend);\n\nbuilder.Build().Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Four API calls do the work:","text":"Four API calls do the work:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCall\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat it does\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreates the orchestrator builder.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddProject&lt;Projects.X&gt;(&quot;logical-name&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRegisters a .NET project as a named service.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.WithReference(other)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInjects the other service&#39;s connection info as environment variables.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.WaitFor(other)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDelays startup until the referenced resource reports healthy.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Run \u003ccode\u003edotnet run --project StudentsAppHost\u003c/code\u003e (or \u003ccode\u003edotnet watch\u003c/code\u003e in the AppHost directory) and Aspire launches every declared project, points each at its dependencies, and surfaces everything in the Aspire Dashboard on \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:15888\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Run `dotnet run --project StudentsAppHost` (or `dotnet watch` in the AppHost directory) and Aspire launches every declared project, points each at its dependencies, and surfaces everything in the Aspire Dashboard on `http://localhost:15888`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Logical names replace hardcoded URLs","text":"Logical names replace hardcoded URLs"},{"kind":"p","html":"The string you pass to \u003ccode\u003eAddProject&lt;&gt;(&quot;backend&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e is the service&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003elogical name\u003c/strong\u003e. Consumers reach it as \u003ccode\u003ehttp://backend/\u003c/code\u003e — not \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:5099\u003c/code\u003e. Aspire intercepts that URL at runtime and resolves it to whichever port the backend actually bound to (which may be picked dynamically on each run).","text":"The string you pass to `AddProject\u003c\u003e(\"backend\")` is the service's **logical name**. Consumers reach it as `http://backend/` — not `http://localhost:5099`. Aspire intercepts that URL at runtime and resolves it to whichever port the backend actually bound to (which may be picked dynamically on each run)."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is the whole point of Aspire&#39;s service discovery: your Blazor page says \u003ccode\u003ehttp://backend/api/students\u003c/code\u003e and it works identically in the Docker-containerized production environment and in a dev-box where the backend is running as a plain \u003ccode\u003edotnet run\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"This is the whole point of Aspire's service discovery: your Blazor page says `http://backend/api/students` and it works identically in the Docker-containerized production environment and in a dev-box where the backend is running as a plain `dotnet run`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Adding a database resource","text":"Adding a database resource"},{"kind":"p","html":"A database is just another resource you register on the builder:","text":"A database is just another resource you register on the builder:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nvar sqlDb = builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\")\n                   .AddDatabase(\"schooldata\");\n\nvar backend = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.StudentsGrpcApi\u003e(\"backend\")\n    .WithReference(sqlDb)\n    .WaitFor(sqlDb);\n\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.StudentsBlazor\u003e(\"frontend\")\n    .WithReference(backend)\n    .WaitFor(backend);\n\nbuilder.Build().Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServer(&quot;sql&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e spins up a containerized SQL Server instance under the logical name \u003ccode\u003esql\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e.AddDatabase(&quot;schooldata&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e chains a named database onto it. When the backend calls \u003ccode\u003eWithReference(sqlDb)\u003c/code\u003e, Aspire writes the connection string into the backend&#39;s environment as \u003ccode\u003eConnectionStrings__schooldata\u003c/code\u003e. Inside the backend&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.AddSqlServerDbContext&lt;SchoolDbContext&gt;(&quot;schooldata&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e picks it up automatically.","text":"`AddSqlServer(\"sql\")` spins up a containerized SQL Server instance under the logical name `sql`. `.AddDatabase(\"schooldata\")` chains a named database onto it. When the backend calls `WithReference(sqlDb)`, Aspire writes the connection string into the backend's environment as `ConnectionStrings__schooldata`. Inside the backend's `Program.cs`, `builder.AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cSchoolDbContext\u003e(\"schooldata\")` picks it up automatically."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You see `WithReference(backend)` and `WaitFor(backend)` written next to each other. What happens if you omit `WaitFor`?","a":"The frontend still learns the backend's address, but Aspire may start it before the backend is reporting healthy. First calls during boot fail with connection errors. `WaitFor` ties startup order to health checks; `WithReference` only wires configuration. Pair them whenever the frontend cannot survive a cold backend."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eAn A2-style AppHost orchestrating a WebAPI, a Server-Blazor admin site, and a Client-Blazor public site against one SQL Server:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003evar builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nvar sql = builder.AddSqlServer(&quot;sql&quot;).AddDatabase(&quot;cms&quot;);\nvar api = builder.AddProject&lt;Projects.Cms_Api&gt;(&quot;api&quot;)\n    .WithReference(sql).WaitFor(sql);\nbuilder.AddProject&lt;Projects.Cms_Admin&gt;(&quot;admin&quot;)\n    .WithReference(api).WaitFor(api);\nbuilder.AddProject&lt;Projects.Cms_Public&gt;(&quot;public&quot;)\n    .WithReference(api).WaitFor(api);\nbuilder.Build().Run();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThree projects talk to one API; the API talks to one database. The AppHost is under 10 lines and replaces a docker-compose file plus reams of connection-string config.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"An A2-style AppHost orchestrating a WebAPI, a Server-Blazor admin site, and a Client-Blazor public site against one SQL Server:\n```cs\nvar builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nvar sql = builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\");\nvar api = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Cms_Api\u003e(\"api\")\n    .WithReference(sql).WaitFor(sql);\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Cms_Admin\u003e(\"admin\")\n    .WithReference(api).WaitFor(api);\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Cms_Public\u003e(\"public\")\n    .WithReference(api).WaitFor(api);\nbuilder.Build().Run();\n```\nThree projects talk to one API; the API talks to one database. The AppHost is under 10 lines and replaces a docker-compose file plus reams of connection-string config."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e does NOT belong in the AppHost&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e. It belongs in every SERVICE project&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e. Putting it in the AppHost makes the orchestrator itself try to register OpenTelemetry + health checks as if it were a microservice — the app fails to start. Keep AppHost focused on \u003ccode\u003eAddProject\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eWithReference\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eWaitFor\u003c/code\u003e / resource registrations.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`AddServiceDefaults()` does NOT belong in the AppHost's `Program.cs`. It belongs in every SERVICE project's `Program.cs`. Putting it in the AppHost makes the orchestrator itself try to register OpenTelemetry + health checks as if it were a microservice — the app fails to start. Keep AppHost focused on `AddProject` / `WithReference` / `WaitFor` / resource registrations."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eAppHost cannot find a sibling service project on its own. You must run \u003ccode\u003edotnet add reference\u003c/code\u003e from the AppHost&#39;s \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e to each service project. Without that, \u003ccode\u003eAddProject&lt;Projects.X&gt;\u003c/code\u003e fails at compile time because \u003ccode\u003eProjects.X\u003c/code\u003e doesn&#39;t exist. The \u003ccode\u003eProjects\u003c/code\u003e namespace is generated from referenced projects.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"AppHost cannot find a sibling service project on its own. You must run `dotnet add reference` from the AppHost's `.csproj` to each service project. Without that, `AddProject\u003cProjects.X\u003e` fails at compile time because `Projects.X` doesn't exist. The `Projects` namespace is generated from referenced projects."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eAppHost = \u003ccode\u003eDistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args)\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eAddProject&lt;&gt;(&quot;name&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e per service + \u003ccode\u003eWithReference\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eWaitFor\u003c/code\u003e. Logical names replace hardcoded URLs. Add databases with \u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServer(&quot;sql&quot;).AddDatabase(&quot;name&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e; Aspire injects connection strings automatically. \u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e goes in each service, never in the AppHost. \u003ccode\u003edotnet add reference\u003c/code\u003e connects AppHost to service projects.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"AppHost = `DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args)` + `AddProject\u003c\u003e(\"name\")` per service + `WithReference` + `WaitFor`. Logical names replace hardcoded URLs. Add databases with `AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"name\")`; Aspire injects connection strings automatically. `AddServiceDefaults()` goes in each service, never in the AppHost. `dotnet add reference` connects AppHost to service projects."}]},{"n":14,"id":"aspire-service-defaults","title":".NET Aspire ServiceDefaults — health endpoints, OpenTelemetry, discovery","hook":"One extension method per service wires up everything Aspire expects.","tags":["aspire","observability","health-checks"],"module":"Distributed Services & Orchestration","source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; research-aspire.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Every service calls exactly two methods","text":"Every service calls exactly two methods"},{"kind":"p","html":"Given any service project in an Aspire solution — a Web API, a Razor Pages site, a Blazor Server app — your \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e contains these two lines:","text":"Given any service project in an Aspire solution — a Web API, a Razor Pages site, a Blazor Server app — your `Program.cs` contains these two lines:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nbuilder.AddServiceDefaults();           // 1. register discovery, OTel, health checks, resilience\n\nbuilder.Services.AddControllers();      // your usual registrations\nvar app = builder.Build();\n\napp.MapDefaultEndpoints();              // 2. expose /health and /alive\napp.MapControllers();\napp.Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e comes from the \u003ccode\u003eServiceDefaults\u003c/code\u003e class library — a sibling project every service references. \u003ccode\u003eMapDefaultEndpoints()\u003c/code\u003e lives in the same library. Together they install four capabilities without you writing any more code:","text":"`AddServiceDefaults()` comes from the `ServiceDefaults` class library — a sibling project every service references. `MapDefaultEndpoints()` lives in the same library. Together they install four capabilities without you writing any more code:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCapability\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat you get for free\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eService discovery\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ehttp://backend/\u003c/code\u003e resolves to the actual host:port at runtime.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOpenTelemetry\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTraces, metrics, and logs exported to the Aspire Dashboard.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHealth checks\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReadiness on \u003ccode\u003e/health\u003c/code\u003e; liveness on \u003ccode\u003e/alive\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eResilience\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDefault retry + timeout on outbound \u003ccode\u003eHttpClient\u003c/code\u003e calls.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"What \u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults\u003c/code\u003e actually registers","text":"What `AddServiceDefaults` actually registers"},{"kind":"p","html":"The typical \u003ccode\u003eServiceDefaults/Extensions.cs\u003c/code\u003e body:","text":"The typical `ServiceDefaults/Extensions.cs` body:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public static TBuilder AddServiceDefaults\u003cTBuilder\u003e(this TBuilder builder)\n    where TBuilder : IHostApplicationBuilder\n{\n    builder.ConfigureOpenTelemetry();\n    builder.AddDefaultHealthChecks();\n    builder.Services.AddServiceDiscovery();\n\n    builder.Services.ConfigureHttpClientDefaults(http =\u003e\n    {\n        http.AddStandardResilienceHandler();\n        http.AddServiceDiscovery();\n    });\n\n    return builder;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Four registrations. \u003ccode\u003eConfigureOpenTelemetry\u003c/code\u003e sets up OTel exporters aimed at the dashboard. \u003ccode\u003eAddDefaultHealthChecks\u003c/code\u003e wires up the default ping + dependency probes. \u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDiscovery\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eIServiceCollection\u003c/code\u003e makes the \u003ccode\u003ehttp+https://\u003c/code\u003e protocol handler available. The \u003ccode\u003eConfigureHttpClientDefaults\u003c/code\u003e block says every \u003ccode\u003eHttpClient\u003c/code\u003e created through \u003ccode\u003eIHttpClientFactory\u003c/code\u003e picks up standard resilience + service discovery automatically.","text":"Four registrations. `ConfigureOpenTelemetry` sets up OTel exporters aimed at the dashboard. `AddDefaultHealthChecks` wires up the default ping + dependency probes. `AddServiceDiscovery` on `IServiceCollection` makes the `http+https://` protocol handler available. The `ConfigureHttpClientDefaults` block says every `HttpClient` created through `IHttpClientFactory` picks up standard resilience + service discovery automatically."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e/health\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003e/alive\u003c/code\u003e","text":"`/health` vs `/alive`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Aspire distinguishes two health scenarios:","text":"Aspire distinguishes two health scenarios:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/health\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003cstrong\u003ereadiness.\u003c/strong\u003e Returns 200 only when every registered health check passes. Use this to decide whether traffic should be routed to the service.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/alive\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003cstrong\u003eliveness.\u003c/strong\u003e Returns 200 for the subset of checks tagged \u003ccode\u003e&quot;live&quot;\u003c/code\u003e — typically just the process-is-running probe. Use this to decide whether the container should be restarted.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **`/health`** — **readiness.** Returns 200 only when every registered health check passes. Use this to decide whether traffic should be routed to the service.\n- **`/alive`** — **liveness.** Returns 200 for the subset of checks tagged `\"live\"` — typically just the process-is-running probe. Use this to decide whether the container should be restarted."},{"kind":"p","html":"Kubernetes maps these directly to \u003ccode\u003ereadinessProbe\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003elivenessProbe\u003c/code\u003e. The Aspire Dashboard shows both.","text":"Kubernetes maps these directly to `readinessProbe` and `livenessProbe`. The Aspire Dashboard shows both."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You added a new Web API project to your Aspire solution. You see it in the dashboard but it's always red — failing health checks. The rest of your services are green. Where is the missing call?","a":"The new project probably isn't calling `builder.AddServiceDefaults()` in its `Program.cs`. Without it, there are no default health checks and no `/health` endpoint. The dashboard polls `/health`, gets 404, and flags the service red."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA minimal Web API \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e Aspire-ready from the first commit:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003evar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.AddServiceDefaults();                 // Aspire requirement\nbuilder.Services.AddControllers();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapDefaultEndpoints();                    // Aspire requirement\napp.MapControllers();\napp.Run();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTwo lines of ceremony and the service is discoverable, observable, and health-checked.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A minimal Web API `Program.cs` Aspire-ready from the first commit:\n```cs\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.AddServiceDefaults();                 // Aspire requirement\nbuilder.Services.AddControllers();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapDefaultEndpoints();                    // Aspire requirement\napp.MapControllers();\napp.Run();\n```\nTwo lines of ceremony and the service is discoverable, observable, and health-checked."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e lives in the service&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e, NEVER in the AppHost&#39;s. The AppHost is the orchestrator — adding service-side defaults there breaks boot because the orchestrator tries to register OpenTelemetry and health checks on itself, not on the managed services.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`AddServiceDefaults()` lives in the service's `Program.cs`, NEVER in the AppHost's. The AppHost is the orchestrator — adding service-side defaults there breaks boot because the orchestrator tries to register OpenTelemetry and health checks on itself, not on the managed services."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eForgetting \u003ccode\u003eMapDefaultEndpoints()\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults\u003c/code\u003e alone registers the health-check services but does not expose the HTTP endpoints. The dashboard sees no \u003ccode\u003e/health\u003c/code\u003e response and paints the service red. Both calls are required: one at builder time, one at app time.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Forgetting `MapDefaultEndpoints()` — `AddServiceDefaults` alone registers the health-check services but does not expose the HTTP endpoints. The dashboard sees no `/health` response and paints the service red. Both calls are required: one at builder time, one at app time."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eEvery Aspire-managed service calls \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.AddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e at configure time and \u003ccode\u003eapp.MapDefaultEndpoints()\u003c/code\u003e at map time. Together they wire service discovery, OpenTelemetry, \u003ccode\u003e/health\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e/alive\u003c/code\u003e endpoints, and HttpClient resilience — four Aspire capabilities with two lines. These calls belong in each service, never in the AppHost.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Every Aspire-managed service calls `builder.AddServiceDefaults()` at configure time and `app.MapDefaultEndpoints()` at map time. Together they wire service discovery, OpenTelemetry, `/health` + `/alive` endpoints, and HttpClient resilience — four Aspire capabilities with two lines. These calls belong in each service, never in the AppHost."}]},{"n":15,"id":"aspire-orchestrated-resources","title":".NET Aspire orchestrated resources — AddSqlServer, AddRedis, env-var injection","hook":"Declare a database in AppHost; consume it with a typed helper in the service.","tags":["aspire","sql-server","redis","orchestration"],"module":"Distributed Services & Orchestration","source":"notes/aspire_SCRIPT.docx; research-aspire.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Declare once in AppHost, consume by name in the service","text":"Declare once in AppHost, consume by name in the service"},{"kind":"p","html":"AppHost registers a SQL Server resource:","text":"AppHost registers a SQL Server resource:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nvar db = builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\")\n                .AddDatabase(\"cms\");\n\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Cms_Api\u003e(\"api\")\n    .WithReference(db)\n    .WaitFor(db);\n\nbuilder.Build().Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"The API&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e consumes it by name:","text":"The API's `Program.cs` consumes it by name:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nbuilder.AddServiceDefaults();\nbuilder.AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cCmsDbContext\u003e(\"cms\");  // ← the database's logical name\n\nbuilder.Services.AddControllers();\nvar app = builder.Build();\n// …\napp.Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Nothing else. No connection string in \u003ccode\u003eappsettings.json\u003c/code\u003e, no environment-variable lookup, no \u003ccode\u003eConfigureOptions\u003c/code\u003e. Aspire writes \u003ccode\u003eConnectionStrings__cms\u003c/code\u003e into the API&#39;s process env when it launches it; the \u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServerDbContext&lt;T&gt;(&quot;cms&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e helper reads that env-var and configures EF Core.","text":"Nothing else. No connection string in `appsettings.json`, no environment-variable lookup, no `ConfigureOptions`. Aspire writes `ConnectionStrings__cms` into the API's process env when it launches it; the `AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cT\u003e(\"cms\")` helper reads that env-var and configures EF Core."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The resource family","text":"The resource family"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServer\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAddRedis\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAddPostgres\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAddRabbitMQ\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAddMongoDB\u003c/code\u003e, and others follow the same pattern:","text":"`AddSqlServer`, `AddRedis`, `AddPostgres`, `AddRabbitMQ`, `AddMongoDB`, and others follow the same pattern:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var cache = builder.AddRedis(\"cache\");\nvar api   = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Api\u003e(\"api\").WithReference(cache);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Inside the API, \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.AddRedisDistributedCache(&quot;cache&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e reads the connection string automatically.","text":"Inside the API, `builder.AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\")` reads the connection string automatically."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAddDatabase(&quot;name&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e is chained specifically onto \u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServer\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eAddPostgres\u003c/code\u003e — the server resource hosts zero or more named databases. You don&#39;t need a separate \u003ccode\u003eAddDatabase\u003c/code\u003e for Redis; Redis is just a key-value store, no schema object to declare.","text":"`AddDatabase(\"name\")` is chained specifically onto `AddSqlServer` / `AddPostgres` — the server resource hosts zero or more named databases. You don't need a separate `AddDatabase` for Redis; Redis is just a key-value store, no schema object to declare."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Environment variables from AppHost to service","text":"Environment variables from AppHost to service"},{"kind":"p","html":"Beyond connection strings, you can inject arbitrary env-vars:","text":"Beyond connection strings, you can inject arbitrary env-vars:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Api\u003e(\"api\")\n    .WithEnvironment(\"ParentCompany\", builder.Configuration[\"Company\"])\n    .WithEnvironment(\"FeatureFlags__NewCheckout\", \"true\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eWithEnvironment\u003c/code\u003e takes a key and a value. The service reads them normally through \u003ccode\u003eIConfiguration\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eEnvironment.GetEnvironmentVariable\u003c/code\u003e. Scope env-vars to one project rather than leaking them to every service — a secret meant for the API should not appear in the frontend.","text":"`WithEnvironment` takes a key and a value. The service reads them normally through `IConfiguration` or `Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable`. Scope env-vars to one project rather than leaking them to every service — a secret meant for the API should not appear in the frontend."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Container image overrides","text":"Container image overrides"},{"kind":"p","html":"When you need a specific SQL Server version or image:","text":"When you need a specific SQL Server version or image:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\")\n    .WithImage(\"mssql/server\")\n    .WithImageRegistry(\"mcr.microsoft.com\")\n    .WithImageTag(\"2022-latest\")\n    .AddDatabase(\"cms\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"Default images come from Microsoft Container Registry. \u003ccode\u003eWithImage\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eWithImageRegistry\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eWithImageTag\u003c/code\u003e override any of the three parts. Useful when your dev environment needs the same image tag as your CI or production.","text":"Default images come from Microsoft Container Registry. `WithImage` / `WithImageRegistry` / `WithImageTag` override any of the three parts. Useful when your dev environment needs the same image tag as your CI or production."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your API has `builder.AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cCmsDbContext\u003e(\"cms\")` and AppHost has `builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\")`. But at runtime EF Core fails with \"connection string not found.\" What broke?","a":"The API is missing `.WithReference(db)` in AppHost. Without it, Aspire never injects `ConnectionStrings__cms` into the API's environment, so `AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cT\u003e(\"cms\")` looks for the connection string, finds nothing, and throws. `WithReference` is what bridges the resource declaration to the consuming service."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eFull AppHost + service pair with SQL Server and Redis:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e// AppHost\nvar db    = builder.AddSqlServer(&quot;sql&quot;).AddDatabase(&quot;cms&quot;);\nvar cache = builder.AddRedis(&quot;cache&quot;);\nbuilder.AddProject&lt;Projects.Api&gt;(&quot;api&quot;)\n    .WithReference(db)\n    .WithReference(cache)\n    .WaitFor(db)\n    .WaitFor(cache);\n// Api/Program.cs\nbuilder.AddServiceDefaults();\nbuilder.AddSqlServerDbContext&lt;CmsDbContext&gt;(&quot;cms&quot;);\nbuilder.AddRedisDistributedCache(&quot;cache&quot;);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe API gets both a typed DbContext and an \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e, each wired from its declared resource.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Full AppHost + service pair with SQL Server and Redis:\n```cs\n// AppHost\nvar db    = builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\");\nvar cache = builder.AddRedis(\"cache\");\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Api\u003e(\"api\")\n    .WithReference(db)\n    .WithReference(cache)\n    .WaitFor(db)\n    .WaitFor(cache);\n// Api/Program.cs\nbuilder.AddServiceDefaults();\nbuilder.AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cCmsDbContext\u003e(\"cms\");\nbuilder.AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\");\n```\nThe API gets both a typed DbContext and an `IDistributedCache`, each wired from its declared resource."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eHardcoding \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Server=localhost;Database=cms;Trusted_Connection=true;&quot;\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eappsettings.json\u003c/code\u003e while also using Aspire to manage the database. Both are set; Aspire&#39;s env-var wins at runtime, but your unit tests read \u003ccode\u003eappsettings.json\u003c/code\u003e&#39;s value, so tests hit a different database than dev runs. Either delete the \u003ccode\u003eappsettings.json\u003c/code\u003e connection string when Aspire is in charge, or make the test environment use the Aspire-managed port.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Hardcoding `\"Server=localhost;Database=cms;Trusted_Connection=true;\"` in `appsettings.json` while also using Aspire to manage the database. Both are set; Aspire's env-var wins at runtime, but your unit tests read `appsettings.json`'s value, so tests hit a different database than dev runs. Either delete the `appsettings.json` connection string when Aspire is in charge, or make the test environment use the Aspire-managed port."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003e.AddDatabase(&quot;cms&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e at the builder level instead of chained off \u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServer(...)\u003c/code\u003e. The builder has no top-level \u003ccode\u003eAddDatabase\u003c/code\u003e method — it exists only on the server-resource builder. The compile error is obvious; the mistake is still common because autocomplete is generous.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Calling `.AddDatabase(\"cms\")` at the builder level instead of chained off `AddSqlServer(...)`. The builder has no top-level `AddDatabase` method — it exists only on the server-resource builder. The compile error is obvious; the mistake is still common because autocomplete is generous."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eAppHost declares resources (\u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServer\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAddRedis\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAddPostgres\u003c/code\u003e) with logical names. \u003ccode\u003e.WithReference(resource)\u003c/code\u003e wires them to consuming services. Each service picks the injected connection string up through Aspire&#39;s typed helpers (\u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServerDbContext&lt;T&gt;(name)\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAddRedisDistributedCache(name)\u003c/code\u003e). Use \u003ccode\u003eWithEnvironment\u003c/code\u003e for arbitrary non-connection config scoped to a single project.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"AppHost declares resources (`AddSqlServer`, `AddRedis`, `AddPostgres`) with logical names. `.WithReference(resource)` wires them to consuming services. Each service picks the injected connection string up through Aspire's typed helpers (`AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cT\u003e(name)`, `AddRedisDistributedCache(name)`). Use `WithEnvironment` for arbitrary non-connection config scoped to a single project."}]},{"n":16,"id":"cache-abstractions","title":"IMemoryCache vs IDistributedCache — pick the right abstraction","hook":"`IMemoryCache` is fast and fails in web farms. `IDistributedCache` survives scale-out.","tags":["cache","architecture","idistributedcache"],"module":"Performance & Caching","source":"slides/redis.pptx; notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §1-2","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Two abstractions, one decision","text":"Two abstractions, one decision"},{"kind":"p","html":".NET ships two cache interfaces. Picking the wrong one silently breaks multi-server deployments.","text":".NET ships two cache interfaces. Picking the wrong one silently breaks multi-server deployments."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// Single-process, in-memory. Fast, ephemeral, per-server.\nbuilder.Services.AddMemoryCache();        // resolves IMemoryCache\n\n// Network-backed. Shared across servers, survives app restart (with Redis).\nbuilder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(opts =\u003e\n    opts.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\"); // resolves IDistributedCache"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e lives inside the app process. Lookups take microseconds. But every app instance owns a separate copy. \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e lives across the network in Redis (or SQL Server, or NCache, or any backend that implements the interface). Lookups take milliseconds and every app instance sees the same data.","text":"`IMemoryCache` lives inside the app process. Lookups take microseconds. But every app instance owns a separate copy. `IDistributedCache` lives across the network in Redis (or SQL Server, or NCache, or any backend that implements the interface). Lookups take milliseconds and every app instance sees the same data."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The web-farm problem","text":"The web-farm problem"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"     Load balancer\n         │\n  ┌──────┴──────┐\n  │             │\nServer A      Server B\n [cache]       [cache]   ← IMemoryCache: each server caches separately"},{"kind":"p","html":"Request 1 hits Server A → miss → fetch from DB → cache on Server A.\nRequest 2 hits Server B → miss (Server B cache is empty) → fetch from DB again.","text":"Request 1 hits Server A → miss → fetch from DB → cache on Server A.\nRequest 2 hits Server B → miss (Server B cache is empty) → fetch from DB again."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e in a load-balanced deployment means you cache 2× (or N×) instead of once, and users see different data depending on which server answered.","text":"`IMemoryCache` in a load-balanced deployment means you cache 2× (or N×) instead of once, and users see different data depending on which server answered."},{"kind":"p","html":"Two fixes:","text":"Two fixes:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSwitch to \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e One shared cache (Redis). Every server hits the same copy.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSticky sessions.\u003c/strong\u003e Route each client to the same server so they always hit the same process. Works, but scales poorly and breaks when the chosen server restarts.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Switch to `IDistributedCache`.** One shared cache (Redis). Every server hits the same copy.\n2. **Sticky sessions.** Route each client to the same server so they always hit the same process. Works, but scales poorly and breaks when the chosen server restarts."},{"kind":"p","html":"Redis is the standard move.","text":"Redis is the standard move."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e is still right","text":"When `IMemoryCache` is still right"},{"kind":"p","html":"For pure per-request optimization of expensive CPU work inside one process — parsing a config file once and reusing the result, or precomputing a lookup table on boot — \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e is ideal. The key question: &quot;does this value need to be visible to the next request, possibly on a different server?&quot; If no, \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e. If yes, \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"For pure per-request optimization of expensive CPU work inside one process — parsing a config file once and reusing the result, or precomputing a lookup table on boot — `IMemoryCache` is ideal. The key question: \"does this value need to be visible to the next request, possibly on a different server?\" If no, `IMemoryCache`. If yes, `IDistributedCache`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Development and single-server scenarios also favor \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e — no extra container, no connection string, no serialization cost.","text":"Development and single-server scenarios also favor `IMemoryCache` — no extra container, no connection string, no serialization cost."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Consuming either interface","text":"Consuming either interface"},{"kind":"p","html":"Constructor-inject whichever you registered:","text":"Constructor-inject whichever you registered:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class ProductService\n{\n    private readonly IMemoryCache _cache;    // or IDistributedCache\n\n    public ProductService(IMemoryCache cache) =\u003e _cache = cache;\n\n    public async Task\u003cProduct[]\u003e GetProductsAsync()\n    {\n        if (_cache.TryGetValue\u003cProduct[]\u003e(\"products\", out var cached))\n            return cached!;\n\n        var products = await FetchFromDbAsync();\n        _cache.Set(\"products\", products,\n            new MemoryCacheEntryOptions { AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5) });\n        return products;\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e has a similar API but works at the byte-array level — you typically wrap it in an extension method that serializes to JSON. See the cache-aside-pattern lesson for the canonical helper.","text":"`IDistributedCache` has a similar API but works at the byte-array level — you typically wrap it in an extension method that serializes to JSON. See the cache-aside-pattern lesson for the canonical helper."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your app caches product data with `IMemoryCache`. You scale from one server to three. Intermittently, users see stale products even when other users just updated them. What's the root cause and the fix?","a":"Each server has its own `IMemoryCache`. Writes on Server A don't propagate to Servers B and C — their caches stay stale for the full TTL. Fix: switch the registration to `AddStackExchangeRedisCache` and inject `IDistributedCache` instead. All three servers now hit one Redis container."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA health dashboard caches a 10-second snapshot of DB stats. Running on one server, \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eAbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10)\u003c/code\u003e is fine. The team scales to 5 Kubernetes pods; every pod runs its own cache, so the DB gets hit 5× per 10-second window instead of once. Migrating to \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e + Redis drops DB load back to ≤ 1× per window across the whole farm.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A health dashboard caches a 10-second snapshot of DB stats. Running on one server, `IMemoryCache` with `AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10)` is fine. The team scales to 5 Kubernetes pods; every pod runs its own cache, so the DB gets hit 5× per 10-second window instead of once. Migrating to `IDistributedCache` + Redis drops DB load back to ≤ 1× per window across the whole farm."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e data DOES NOT survive an app restart. A deployment, a crash, or a container rescheduled by Kubernetes all wipe the cache. If you were relying on cached data between restarts (e.g. expensive startup computation carried across recycles), you need \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e with a persistent backend — Redis with AOF or RDB enabled.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`IMemoryCache` data DOES NOT survive an app restart. A deployment, a crash, or a container rescheduled by Kubernetes all wipe the cache. If you were relying on cached data between restarts (e.g. expensive startup computation carried across recycles), you need `IDistributedCache` with a persistent backend — Redis with AOF or RDB enabled."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eUse \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e for per-process, ephemeral, within-one-server caching. Use \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e (backed by Redis) whenever the cache must span multiple servers, survive restarts, or power a load-balanced deployment. The choice is made once in \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e and baked into the injected interface.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Use `IMemoryCache` for per-process, ephemeral, within-one-server caching. Use `IDistributedCache` (backed by Redis) whenever the cache must span multiple servers, survive restarts, or power a load-balanced deployment. The choice is made once in `Program.cs` and baked into the injected interface."}]},{"n":17,"id":"cache-expiration","title":"Cache expiration — Absolute, Sliding, combined, Priority","hook":"Absolute is a hard deadline. Sliding resets on access. Priority decides who gets evicted first.","tags":["cache","ttl","expiration"],"module":"Performance & Caching","source":"notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §2, §4","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Three knobs on \u003ccode\u003eMemoryCacheEntryOptions\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Three knobs on `MemoryCacheEntryOptions`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every cache write can carry expiration policy. The shape is the same for \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e (the names differ slightly on the distributed variant; semantics are identical).","text":"Every cache write can carry expiration policy. The shape is the same for `IMemoryCache` and `IDistributedCache` (the names differ slightly on the distributed variant; semantics are identical)."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var options = new MemoryCacheEntryOptions\n{\n    AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10),\n    SlidingExpiration               = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2),\n    Priority                         = CacheItemPriority.High\n};\n\n_cache.Set(\"products\", products, options);"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eOption\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMeaning\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAbsoluteExpiration\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHard deadline at a wall-clock moment. Expires then, regardless of access.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSame, but computed as &quot;now + duration&quot; at set-time.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSlidingExpiration\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSoft deadline that resets to the full duration every time the entry is accessed.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePriority\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eNeverRemove\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eHigh\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eNormal\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eLow\u003c/code\u003e — eviction order when memory pressure hits.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Absolute vs Sliding — pick one, two, or both","text":"Absolute vs Sliding — pick one, two, or both"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eAbsolute alone.\u003c/strong\u003e Cache expires at T + duration regardless of traffic. Good for data that refreshes on a schedule (e.g. hourly reports). Predictable upper bound.","text":"**Absolute alone.** Cache expires at T + duration regardless of traffic. Good for data that refreshes on a schedule (e.g. hourly reports). Predictable upper bound."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSliding alone.\u003c/strong\u003e Cache expires after N minutes of idleness. Good for session-like data where hot entries should stay and idle entries should evict. Risk: a popular entry never expires, so you never refresh it.","text":"**Sliding alone.** Cache expires after N minutes of idleness. Good for session-like data where hot entries should stay and idle entries should evict. Risk: a popular entry never expires, so you never refresh it."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBoth, combined.\u003c/strong\u003e Sliding resets the idle timer, but absolute is a hard ceiling. The entry dies at \u003cstrong\u003emin(absolute deadline, idle-window end)\u003c/strong\u003e — whichever fires first.","text":"**Both, combined.** Sliding resets the idle timer, but absolute is a hard ceiling. The entry dies at **min(absolute deadline, idle-window end)** — whichever fires first."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"new MemoryCacheEntryOptions\n{\n    AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10),   // hard ceiling\n    SlidingExpiration               = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2)     // idle timeout\n};"},{"kind":"p","html":"This combination gives hot entries a 2-minute idle reset while still guaranteeing a fresh fetch every 10 minutes at the outside.","text":"This combination gives hot entries a 2-minute idle reset while still guaranteeing a fresh fetch every 10 minutes at the outside."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Priority is about eviction, not TTL","text":"Priority is about eviction, not TTL"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eCacheItemPriority.Low\u003c/code\u003e does NOT mean &quot;expires sooner.&quot; It means &quot;when the cache is under memory pressure and has to drop entries, drop me first.&quot; A \u003ccode\u003eLow\u003c/code\u003e-priority entry with a 1-hour absolute expiration still lives 1 hour unless memory pressure forces eviction.","text":"`CacheItemPriority.Low` does NOT mean \"expires sooner.\" It means \"when the cache is under memory pressure and has to drop entries, drop me first.\" A `Low`-priority entry with a 1-hour absolute expiration still lives 1 hour unless memory pressure forces eviction."},{"kind":"p","html":"The four levels:","text":"The four levels:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eNeverRemove\u003c/code\u003e — excluded from automatic eviction. Only removable via \u003ccode\u003eRemove(key)\u003c/code\u003e or time-based expiration.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eHigh\u003c/code\u003e — kept longer during pressure.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eNormal\u003c/code\u003e — default.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eLow\u003c/code\u003e — evicted first.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `NeverRemove` — excluded from automatic eviction. Only removable via `Remove(key)` or time-based expiration.\n- `High` — kept longer during pressure.\n- `Normal` — default.\n- `Low` — evicted first."},{"kind":"p","html":"Use \u003ccode\u003eNeverRemove\u003c/code\u003e sparingly. It converts your cache into persistent state that only the explicit \u003ccode\u003eRemove\u003c/code\u003e call can release — often a footgun.","text":"Use `NeverRemove` sparingly. It converts your cache into persistent state that only the explicit `Remove` call can release — often a footgun."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You set `AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = 50s` and `SlidingExpiration = 20s`. A user accesses the entry at t=15s. When does the cache expire?","a":"At t=50s, from the absolute deadline. The sliding access at t=15s resets the idle timer to run until t=35s, but the absolute deadline at t=50s is farther out, so absolute is still binding. If there were no further accesses, the cache would have expired at t=35s. Because another hit reset the timer, absolute wins at t=50s."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA &quot;top products&quot; endpoint caches a list for at most 5 minutes (absolute) but refreshes if idle for 30 seconds (sliding). During peak traffic the entry keeps resetting at 30-second intervals and stays hot until the 5-minute ceiling forces a refresh. During off-peak, the 30-second idle window trims unused data from memory without waiting for the full 5 minutes.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A \"top products\" endpoint caches a list for at most 5 minutes (absolute) but refreshes if idle for 30 seconds (sliding). During peak traffic the entry keeps resetting at 30-second intervals and stays hot until the 5-minute ceiling forces a refresh. During off-peak, the 30-second idle window trims unused data from memory without waiting for the full 5 minutes."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eConfusing \u003ccode\u003ePriority\u003c/code\u003e with TTL. A distractor pattern is: &quot;which option makes a cache entry expire sooner — \u003ccode\u003ePriority = Low\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eAbsoluteExpiration = 10s\u003c/code\u003e?&quot; Priority does NOT change expiration time. It only determines eviction order under memory pressure. The \u003ccode\u003eAbsoluteExpiration\u003c/code\u003e setting decides when the entry dies.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Confusing `Priority` with TTL. A distractor pattern is: \"which option makes a cache entry expire sooner — `Priority = Low` or `AbsoluteExpiration = 10s`?\" Priority does NOT change expiration time. It only determines eviction order under memory pressure. The `AbsoluteExpiration` setting decides when the entry dies."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAbsoluteExpiration\u003c/code\u003e = hard deadline. \u003ccode\u003eSlidingExpiration\u003c/code\u003e = idle timeout that resets on access. Combining both gives a capped-and-refreshed window: \u003ccode\u003emin(absolute, idle-since-last-access + sliding)\u003c/code\u003e is when the entry dies. \u003ccode\u003ePriority\u003c/code\u003e is orthogonal — it controls eviction order when memory is tight, not expiration time. For \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e, the options type is \u003ccode\u003eDistributedCacheEntryOptions\u003c/code\u003e with fluent setters (\u003ccode\u003eSetAbsoluteExpiration\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSetSlidingExpiration\u003c/code\u003e); semantics are identical.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`AbsoluteExpiration` = hard deadline. `SlidingExpiration` = idle timeout that resets on access. Combining both gives a capped-and-refreshed window: `min(absolute, idle-since-last-access + sliding)` is when the entry dies. `Priority` is orthogonal — it controls eviction order when memory is tight, not expiration time. For `IDistributedCache`, the options type is `DistributedCacheEntryOptions` with fluent setters (`SetAbsoluteExpiration`, `SetSlidingExpiration`); semantics are identical."}]},{"n":18,"id":"cache-aside-pattern","title":"Cache-aside pattern — GetOrSetAsync + JSON serialization + invalidation","hook":"Check cache, on miss run the fetch, store the result, return.","tags":["cache","pattern","getorset","invalidation"],"module":"Performance & Caching","source":"notes/DataCache_SCRIPT.docx; notes/redis_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §3","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The three steps of cache-aside","text":"The three steps of cache-aside"},{"kind":"p","html":"Given an expensive fetch — a DB query, an external API call, a CPU-heavy computation — the cache-aside pattern interposes a cache between the caller and the source.","text":"Given an expensive fetch — a DB query, an external API call, a CPU-heavy computation — the cache-aside pattern interposes a cache between the caller and the source."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLook up\u003c/strong\u003e the key in the cache.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOn hit\u003c/strong\u003e, return the cached value.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOn miss\u003c/strong\u003e, call the source, store the result, return.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Look up** the key in the cache.\n2. **On hit**, return the cached value.\n3. **On miss**, call the source, store the result, return."},{"kind":"p","html":"Raw \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e shape:","text":"Raw `IMemoryCache` shape:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"if (_cache.TryGetValue\u003cProduct[]\u003e(\"products\", out var cached))\n    return cached!;\n\nvar fresh = await _db.Products.ToArrayAsync();\n_cache.Set(\"products\", fresh,\n    new MemoryCacheEntryOptions { AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5) });\nreturn fresh;"},{"kind":"p","html":"This works but repeats at every call site. The idiomatic .NET helper rolls it into one call:","text":"This works but repeats at every call site. The idiomatic .NET helper rolls it into one call:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var products = await _cache.GetOrCreateAsync(\"products\", entry =\u003e\n{\n    entry.AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5);\n    return FetchFromDbAsync();\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eGetOrCreateAsync\u003c/code\u003e checks cache, runs the factory on miss, stores the result, returns. The factory runs only on miss.","text":"`GetOrCreateAsync` checks cache, runs the factory on miss, stores the result, returns. The factory runs only on miss."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The distributed-cache extension helper","text":"The distributed-cache extension helper"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e works in bytes, so you typically wrap it with a helper that serializes to JSON. The course&#39;s canonical extension:","text":"`IDistributedCache` works in bytes, so you typically wrap it with a helper that serializes to JSON. The course's canonical extension:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public static class DistributedCacheExtensions\n{\n    private static readonly JsonSerializerOptions _json = new()\n    {\n        DefaultIgnoreCondition = JsonIgnoreCondition.WhenWritingNull\n    };\n\n    public static async Task SetAsync\u003cT\u003e(this IDistributedCache cache,\n        string key, T value, DistributedCacheEntryOptions? opts = null)\n    {\n        var bytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(JsonSerializer.Serialize(value, _json));\n        await cache.SetAsync(key, bytes, opts ?? new());\n    }\n\n    public static bool TryGetValue\u003cT\u003e(this IDistributedCache cache,\n        string key, out T? value)\n    {\n        var raw = cache.Get(key);\n        value = default;\n        if (raw is null) return false;\n        value = JsonSerializer.Deserialize\u003cT\u003e(raw, _json);\n        return true;\n    }\n\n    public static async Task\u003cT?\u003e GetOrSetAsync\u003cT\u003e(this IDistributedCache cache,\n        string key, Func\u003cTask\u003cT\u003e\u003e factory, DistributedCacheEntryOptions? opts = null)\n    {\n        if (cache.TryGetValue\u003cT\u003e(key, out var cached) && cached is not null)\n            return cached;\n\n        var value = await factory();\n        if (value is not null)\n        {\n            opts ??= new DistributedCacheEntryOptions()\n                .SetAbsoluteExpiration(TimeSpan.FromHours(1))\n                .SetSlidingExpiration(TimeSpan.FromMinutes(30));\n            await cache.SetAsync(key, value, opts);\n        }\n        return value;\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"A consumer now reads like a single line:","text":"A consumer now reads like a single line:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var games = await _cache.GetOrSetAsync(\n    $\"games:country:{country}\",\n    () =\u003e _db.Games.Where(g =\u003e g.Country == country).ToListAsync(),\n    new DistributedCacheEntryOptions()\n        .SetAbsoluteExpiration(TimeSpan.FromMinutes(20)));"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Invalidation is still your job","text":"Invalidation is still your job"},{"kind":"p","html":"Cache-aside does not know when the source changes. When you write to the DB, you have to invalidate the affected keys:","text":"Cache-aside does not know when the source changes. When you write to the DB, you have to invalidate the affected keys:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public async Task AddGameAsync(Game game)\n{\n    _db.Games.Add(game);\n    await _db.SaveChangesAsync();\n    _cache.Remove(\"games\");                    // parent list\n    _cache.Remove($\"games:country:{game.Country}\"); // specific country\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Miss this step and reads continue to serve stale data until the TTL expires. For &quot;eventually consistent&quot; apps that&#39;s fine; for admin UIs showing the user&#39;s own edit, it looks broken.","text":"Miss this step and reads continue to serve stale data until the TTL expires. For \"eventually consistent\" apps that's fine; for admin UIs showing the user's own edit, it looks broken."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You cache `games:country:France` with a 20-minute TTL. An admin edits a French game via your API. The cached list still shows the old version for 20 minutes. What's the missing call?","a":"The update handler needs to `_cache.Remove(\"games:country:France\")` after `SaveChangesAsync`. Cache-aside relies on the writer invalidating affected keys; without explicit `Remove`, the TTL is the only thing that refreshes the cache."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGetOrSetAsync\u003c/code\u003e one-liner with default 1-hour absolute + 30-minute sliding expiration:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003evar weather = await _cache.GetOrSetAsync(\n    $&quot;weather:{city}&quot;,\n    () =&gt; _weatherApi.GetAsync(city));\n// Absolute: 1h, Sliding: 30m (from helper defaults)\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFirst call fetches from the API. Subsequent calls within 30 minutes return cached. If 31 minutes of idle pass, the sliding timer fires and the next call refetches — unless the 1-hour absolute deadline fires first.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`GetOrSetAsync` one-liner with default 1-hour absolute + 30-minute sliding expiration:\n```cs\nvar weather = await _cache.GetOrSetAsync(\n    $\"weather:{city}\",\n    () =\u003e _weatherApi.GetAsync(city));\n// Absolute: 1h, Sliding: 30m (from helper defaults)\n```\nFirst call fetches from the API. Subsequent calls within 30 minutes return cached. If 31 minutes of idle pass, the sliding timer fires and the next call refetches — unless the 1-hour absolute deadline fires first."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eTryGetValue&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e requires \u003ccode\u003eout var\u003c/code\u003e — it&#39;s an out-parameter, not a return value. A distractor writes \u003ccode\u003eif (_cache.TryGetValue(&quot;key&quot;, product))\u003c/code\u003e and expects the compiler to infer. The correct call is \u003ccode\u003eif (_cache.TryGetValue&lt;T&gt;(&quot;key&quot;, out var product))\u003c/code\u003e. Same shape on \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e when using the extension.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`TryGetValue\u003cT\u003e` requires `out var` — it's an out-parameter, not a return value. A distractor writes `if (_cache.TryGetValue(\"key\", product))` and expects the compiler to infer. The correct call is `if (_cache.TryGetValue\u003cT\u003e(\"key\", out var product))`. Same shape on `IDistributedCache` when using the extension."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eJSON serialization round-tripping loses runtime type info. Caching a \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;Dog&gt;\u003c/code\u003e where \u003ccode\u003eDog : Animal\u003c/code\u003e and deserializing as \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;Animal&gt;\u003c/code\u003e gives you \u003ccode\u003eAnimal\u003c/code\u003e instances without their \u003ccode\u003eDog\u003c/code\u003e specifics. Either cache the concrete type, or add \u003ccode\u003eTypeNameHandling\u003c/code\u003e / serializer settings that preserve type info (at the cost of bigger payloads).\u003c/p\u003e","text":"JSON serialization round-tripping loses runtime type info. Caching a `List\u003cDog\u003e` where `Dog : Animal` and deserializing as `List\u003cAnimal\u003e` gives you `Animal` instances without their `Dog` specifics. Either cache the concrete type, or add `TypeNameHandling` / serializer settings that preserve type info (at the cost of bigger payloads)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eCache-aside = check, miss → fetch → store, return. Use \u003ccode\u003eGetOrCreateAsync\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e or a \u003ccode\u003eGetOrSetAsync&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e extension on \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e for the one-line form. Serialize to JSON bytes for distributed caches. Invalidate by calling \u003ccode\u003eRemove(key)\u003c/code\u003e from every write path that modifies the cached data — TTL alone is not enough for admin UIs.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Cache-aside = check, miss → fetch → store, return. Use `GetOrCreateAsync` on `IMemoryCache` or a `GetOrSetAsync\u003cT\u003e` extension on `IDistributedCache` for the one-line form. Serialize to JSON bytes for distributed caches. Invalidate by calling `Remove(key)` from every write path that modifies the cached data — TTL alone is not enough for admin UIs."}]},{"n":19,"id":"redis-configuration","title":"Redis configuration — Docker, StackExchange.Redis, ConfigurationOptions","hook":"One container, port 6379, one line of Program.cs.","tags":["redis","docker","stackexchange-redis","config"],"module":"Performance & Caching","source":"slides/redis.pptx; notes/redis_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §6","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Spin up Redis on Docker","text":"Spin up Redis on Docker"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"docker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three flags matter. \u003ccode\u003e-d\u003c/code\u003e runs the container detached. \u003ccode\u003e-p 6379:6379\u003c/code\u003e maps the host&#39;s port 6379 to the container&#39;s port 6379 — \u003ccode\u003e6379\u003c/code\u003e is Redis&#39;s conventional port. \u003ccode\u003eredis\u003c/code\u003e is the official image name from Docker Hub.","text":"Three flags matter. `-d` runs the container detached. `-p 6379:6379` maps the host's port 6379 to the container's port 6379 — `6379` is Redis's conventional port. `redis` is the official image name from Docker Hub."},{"kind":"p","html":"Check it&#39;s up:","text":"Check it's up:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"docker ps | grep redis"},{"kind":"p","html":"Connect with the CLI to sanity-check:","text":"Connect with the CLI to sanity-check:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"docker exec -it redis redis-cli\n\u003e SET greeting \"hello\"\nOK\n\u003e GET greeting\n\"hello\"\n\u003e SETEX tempkey 10 \"gone in 10s\"\nOK\n\u003e TTL tempkey\n(integer) 10"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eSETEX\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003eSET\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eEXpiration\u003c/code\u003e — the number is \u003cstrong\u003eseconds\u003c/strong\u003e, not milliseconds. \u003ccode\u003eTTL\u003c/code\u003e returns how many seconds remain. Once expired, \u003ccode\u003eGET\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003e(nil)\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`SETEX` is `SET` + `EXpiration` — the number is **seconds**, not milliseconds. `TTL` returns how many seconds remain. Once expired, `GET` returns `(nil)`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Register Redis as \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Register Redis as `IDistributedCache`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Add the NuGet package:","text":"Add the NuGet package:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis"},{"kind":"p","html":"Wire it in \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Wire it in `Program.cs`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(opts =\u003e\n{\n    opts.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\";\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"That one call registers \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e backed by Redis. Any service that \u003ccode\u003e@inject\u003c/code\u003es or constructor-injects \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e now reads from and writes to your Redis container.","text":"That one call registers `IDistributedCache` backed by Redis. Any service that `@inject`s or constructor-injects `IDistributedCache` now reads from and writes to your Redis container."},{"kind":"p","html":"For production-grade control, swap the shorthand for \u003ccode\u003eConfigurationOptions\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"For production-grade control, swap the shorthand for `ConfigurationOptions`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(opts =\u003e\n{\n    opts.ConfigurationOptions = new StackExchange.Redis.ConfigurationOptions\n    {\n        AbortOnConnectFail = true,\n        EndPoints = { \"localhost:6379\" },\n        Password = builder.Configuration[\"Redis:Password\"],\n        Ssl = true,\n    };\n});"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAbortOnConnectFail = true\u003c/code\u003e forces your app to fail fast if Redis is unreachable at startup. \u003ccode\u003efalse\u003c/code\u003e silently retries in the background — fine for dev, dangerous for prod where you want the container orchestrator to replace a broken app.","text":"`AbortOnConnectFail = true` forces your app to fail fast if Redis is unreachable at startup. `false` silently retries in the background — fine for dev, dangerous for prod where you want the container orchestrator to replace a broken app."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Redis data types (recognition only)","text":"Redis data types (recognition only)"},{"kind":"p","html":"The exam may name-drop Redis data structures. You don&#39;t write code against them directly through \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e (that API is just byte-level keys), but recognize the shapes:","text":"The exam may name-drop Redis data structures. You don't write code against them directly through `IDistributedCache` (that API is just byte-level keys), but recognize the shapes:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eType\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eShape\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eExample use\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eString\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003esingle key → single value\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSET user:42:name &quot;Alice&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHash\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ekey → field-value map\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eHSET user:42 name Alice age 30\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eList\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ekey → ordered list\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eLPUSH feed post1 post2\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSet\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ekey → unique unordered members\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSADD tags sports music\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSorted set\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ekey → scored, ranked members\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eZADD leaderboard 100 player1\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Under Aspire, skip the manual connection string","text":"Under Aspire, skip the manual connection string"},{"kind":"p","html":"If your solution uses \u003ccode\u003e.NET Aspire\u003c/code\u003e, the AppHost registers Redis as a resource and injects the connection string automatically:","text":"If your solution uses `.NET Aspire`, the AppHost registers Redis as a resource and injects the connection string automatically:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// AppHost\nvar cache = builder.AddRedis(\"cache\");\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Api\u003e(\"api\").WithReference(cache);\n\n// Api/Program.cs\nbuilder.AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\");   // reads the injected connection string"},{"kind":"p","html":"No \u003ccode\u003elocalhost:6379\u003c/code\u003e literal, no NuGet reference to \u003ccode\u003eStackExchange.Redis\u003c/code\u003e client — Aspire handles both.","text":"No `localhost:6379` literal, no NuGet reference to `StackExchange.Redis` client — Aspire handles both."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your `Program.cs` has `AddStackExchangeRedisCache(opts =\u003e opts.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\")`. Your app starts and runs, but every cache write gets swallowed — no exception, no data in Redis. What's the most likely cause?","a":"Redis isn't actually running on port 6379. `AbortOnConnectFail` defaults to `false`, so the cache silently no-ops writes. Check with `docker ps`; if Redis is missing, `docker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis`. In production, set `AbortOnConnectFail = true` so this condition crashes at startup."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eInspecting what your app actually wrote to Redis with the CLI:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003edocker exec -it redis redis-cli\n&gt; KEYS games:*\n1) &quot;games:country:France&quot;\n2) &quot;games:country:Japan&quot;\n&gt; TTL games:country:France\n(integer) 842\n&gt; GET games:country:France\n&quot;[{\\&quot;Id\\&quot;:1,\\&quot;Country\\&quot;:\\&quot;France\\&quot;,...}]&quot;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe JSON-serialized list you set from C# is visible as a raw string. Redis Insight (GUI at \u003ca href=\"https://redis.io/insight/\"\u003ehttps://redis.io/insight/\u003c/a\u003e) offers the same view with syntax highlighting.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Inspecting what your app actually wrote to Redis with the CLI:\n```bash\ndocker exec -it redis redis-cli\n\u003e KEYS games:*\n1) \"games:country:France\"\n2) \"games:country:Japan\"\n\u003e TTL games:country:France\n(integer) 842\n\u003e GET games:country:France\n\"[{\\\"Id\\\":1,\\\"Country\\\":\\\"France\\\",...}]\"\n```\nThe JSON-serialized list you set from C# is visible as a raw string. Redis Insight (GUI at \u003chttps://redis.io/insight/\u003e) offers the same view with syntax highlighting."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSETEX destination 10 &quot;Tokyo&quot;\u003c/code\u003e expires in \u003cstrong\u003e10 seconds\u003c/strong\u003e, not 10 milliseconds. Redis TTL commands use seconds by default. The \u003ccode\u003ePSETEX\u003c/code\u003e variant uses milliseconds if you need sub-second precision — rare.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`SETEX destination 10 \"Tokyo\"` expires in **10 seconds**, not 10 milliseconds. Redis TTL commands use seconds by default. The `PSETEX` variant uses milliseconds if you need sub-second precision — rare."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003edocker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis\u003c/code\u003e starts the container on the conventional port. \u003ccode\u003edotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis\u003c/code\u003e plus \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(opts =&gt; opts.Configuration = &quot;localhost:6379&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e registers it as \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e. Under Aspire, use \u003ccode\u003eAddRedis(&quot;cache&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eAddRedisDistributedCache(&quot;cache&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e and skip the connection string. \u003ccode\u003eAbortOnConnectFail = true\u003c/code\u003e prevents silent cache-write swallowing when Redis is missing.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`docker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis` starts the container on the conventional port. `dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis` plus `builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(opts =\u003e opts.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\")` registers it as `IDistributedCache`. Under Aspire, use `AddRedis(\"cache\")` + `AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\")` and skip the connection string. `AbortOnConnectFail = true` prevents silent cache-write swallowing when Redis is missing."}]},{"n":20,"id":"cache-tag-helper","title":"Cache Tag Helper — \u003ccache\u003e fragment caching in Razor","hook":"Wrap a block in `\u003ccache\u003e` and Razor skips re-rendering until the entry expires.","tags":["cache","razor","tag-helper"],"module":"Performance & Caching","source":"notes/Cache_Tag_Helper_SCRIPT.docx; research-cache.md §5","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Declarative fragment caching in a Razor page","text":"Declarative fragment caching in a Razor page"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e&lt;cache&gt;\u003c/code\u003e is a built-in Tag Helper. Wrap it around the piece of a view you want to reuse:","text":"`\u003ccache\u003e` is a built-in Tag Helper. Wrap it around the piece of a view you want to reuse:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"\u003ccache expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)\"\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003eLast rendered: @DateTime.Now\u003c/p\u003e\n    @await Html.PartialAsync(\"_TopProducts\")\n\u003c/cache\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"On first render, Razor evaluates the contents and caches the resulting HTML. Requests over the next 10 minutes skip evaluation entirely — no query, no partial lookup, no C# execution inside the block. The rendered HTML comes back verbatim.","text":"On first render, Razor evaluates the contents and caches the resulting HTML. Requests over the next 10 minutes skip evaluation entirely — no query, no partial lookup, no C# execution inside the block. The rendered HTML comes back verbatim."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The expiration attributes","text":"The expiration attributes"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAttribute\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEffect\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eexpires-after=&quot;@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5)&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAbsolute TTL: expires 5 minutes after first render.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eexpires-on=&quot;@DateTime.Today.AddDays(1)&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAbsolute: expires at a wall-clock moment.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eexpires-sliding=&quot;@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2)&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSliding: resets on each access.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Combine them the same way as \u003ccode\u003eMemoryCacheEntryOptions\u003c/code\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eexpires-after\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eexpires-sliding\u003c/code\u003e together give a capped-and-refreshing window.","text":"Combine them the same way as `MemoryCacheEntryOptions`: `expires-after` + `expires-sliding` together give a capped-and-refreshing window."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003evary-by-*\u003c/code\u003e — separate caches per dimension","text":"`vary-by-*` — separate caches per dimension"},{"kind":"p","html":"A single page rendered for every user, every route, every query string, would flood one cache entry. \u003ccode\u003evary-by-*\u003c/code\u003e attributes create a separate cache key per dimension:","text":"A single page rendered for every user, every route, every query string, would flood one cache entry. `vary-by-*` attributes create a separate cache key per dimension:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"\u003ccache vary-by-user=\"true\" expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)\"\u003e\n    \u003cp\u003eHello, @User.Identity?.Name\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/cache\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each logged-in user gets their own cached greeting. Without \u003ccode\u003evary-by-user\u003c/code\u003e, the first user&#39;s name would render for everyone else.","text":"Each logged-in user gets their own cached greeting. Without `vary-by-user`, the first user's name would render for everyone else."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAttribute\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSeparate cache per\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003evary-by-user=&quot;true&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAuthenticated user identity\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003evary-by-route=&quot;id&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValue of the \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e route parameter\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003evary-by-query=&quot;search&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValue of the \u003ccode\u003esearch\u003c/code\u003e query-string key\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003evary-by-cookie=&quot;SessionId&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValue of the \u003ccode\u003eSessionId\u003c/code\u003e cookie\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003evary-by-header=&quot;User-Agent&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValue of the named HTTP header\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003evary-by=&quot;@Model.Key&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCustom key you compute\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Combine freely:","text":"Combine freely:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"\u003ccache vary-by-user=\"true\" vary-by-route=\"id\" expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5)\"\u003e\n    \u003c!-- one cached fragment per (user, product-id) pair --\u003e\n\u003c/cache\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The load-balancing trap","text":"The load-balancing trap"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e&lt;cache&gt;\u003c/code\u003e uses \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e under the hood. That means the same web-farm problem as raw \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e: each server keeps its own rendered HTML. User A hits Server 1 and triggers cache write; User A&#39;s next request hits Server 2 and sees a fresh render that diverges from what Server 1 cached.","text":"`\u003ccache\u003e` uses `IMemoryCache` under the hood. That means the same web-farm problem as raw `IMemoryCache`: each server keeps its own rendered HTML. User A hits Server 1 and triggers cache write; User A's next request hits Server 2 and sees a fresh render that diverges from what Server 1 cached."},{"kind":"p","html":"There is no straightforward way to back \u003ccode\u003e&lt;cache&gt;\u003c/code\u003e with Redis. Workarounds:","text":"There is no straightforward way to back `\u003ccache\u003e` with Redis. Workarounds:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSticky sessions.\u003c/strong\u003e Route each user to one server.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eShort TTLs.\u003c/strong\u003e Keep the cache short so cross-server drift is brief.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCache at a higher layer.\u003c/strong\u003e Output caching middleware (.NET 7+) or a CDN can cache at the request level across all servers.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Sticky sessions.** Route each user to one server.\n- **Short TTLs.** Keep the cache short so cross-server drift is brief.\n- **Cache at a higher layer.** Output caching middleware (.NET 7+) or a CDN can cache at the request level across all servers."},{"kind":"p","html":"For anything user-facing on a load-balanced deployment, prefer response-level or CDN caching over \u003ccode\u003e&lt;cache&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"For anything user-facing on a load-balanced deployment, prefer response-level or CDN caching over `\u003ccache\u003e`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You wrap a user's profile summary in `\u003ccache vary-by-user=\"true\" expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)\"\u003e`. You deploy to a 3-pod Kubernetes service behind a load balancer. The user reports their name changes every few seconds. Why?","a":"Each pod holds its own `IMemoryCache` for `\u003ccache\u003e` fragments. The load balancer routes the user's requests round-robin across the three pods; each pod either has a stale cached fragment from a prior request or a fresh render — they don't agree. Fix: sticky sessions, or replace `\u003ccache\u003e` with output caching that can share state via Redis."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA product detail page varies its cached main block by route \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e plus user identity, with a 10-minute absolute ceiling and a 2-minute sliding window:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e&lt;cache vary-by-user=&quot;true&quot;\n       vary-by-route=&quot;id&quot;\n       expires-after=&quot;@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)&quot;\n       expires-sliding=&quot;@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2)&quot;&gt;\n    @await Html.PartialAsync(&quot;_ProductDetail&quot;, Model)\n&lt;/cache&gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAn active user sees snappy loads (sliding keeps their fragment hot); an inactive fragment drops after 2 minutes of idle or 10 minutes of age, whichever fires first.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A product detail page varies its cached main block by route `id` plus user identity, with a 10-minute absolute ceiling and a 2-minute sliding window:\n```cs\n\u003ccache vary-by-user=\"true\"\n       vary-by-route=\"id\"\n       expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)\"\n       expires-sliding=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2)\"\u003e\n    @await Html.PartialAsync(\"_ProductDetail\", Model)\n\u003c/cache\u003e\n```\nAn active user sees snappy loads (sliding keeps their fragment hot); an inactive fragment drops after 2 minutes of idle or 10 minutes of age, whichever fires first."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eOmitting \u003ccode\u003evary-by-*\u003c/code\u003e on user-specific content. A cached block with only \u003ccode\u003eexpires-after\u003c/code\u003e produces the same HTML for every visitor — the first user&#39;s data leaks into every subsequent render until the TTL fires. Always ask &quot;does this block depend on the caller?&quot; and add \u003ccode\u003evary-by-user\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003evary-by-route\u003c/code\u003e accordingly.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Omitting `vary-by-*` on user-specific content. A cached block with only `expires-after` produces the same HTML for every visitor — the first user's data leaks into every subsequent render until the TTL fires. Always ask \"does this block depend on the caller?\" and add `vary-by-user` or `vary-by-route` accordingly."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;cache&gt;\u003c/code\u003e wraps any Razor block and skips re-rendering until the entry expires. \u003ccode\u003eexpires-after\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eexpires-on\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eexpires-sliding\u003c/code\u003e control TTL. \u003ccode\u003evary-by-user\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003evary-by-route\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003evary-by-query\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003evary-by-cookie\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003evary-by-header\u003c/code\u003e, and custom \u003ccode\u003evary-by\u003c/code\u003e create per-dimension cache keys. It backs onto \u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e, so it has the same web-farm problem — use sticky sessions or move to output caching / CDN caching for multi-server deployments.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`\u003ccache\u003e` wraps any Razor block and skips re-rendering until the entry expires. `expires-after` / `expires-on` / `expires-sliding` control TTL. `vary-by-user`, `vary-by-route`, `vary-by-query`, `vary-by-cookie`, `vary-by-header`, and custom `vary-by` create per-dimension cache keys. It backs onto `IMemoryCache`, so it has the same web-farm problem — use sticky sessions or move to output caching / CDN caching for multi-server deployments."}]},{"n":21,"id":"taghelper-authoring","title":"Tag Helper authoring — TagHelper base class, ProcessAsync, HtmlTargetElement","hook":"Inherit, decorate, override `ProcessAsync`. HTML attributes map to PascalCase properties.","tags":["tag-helper","razor","asp-net-core"],"module":"Performance & Caching","source":"notes/TagHelpers_SCRIPT.docx; research-taghelpers-blazor.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The three-piece recipe","text":"The three-piece recipe"},{"kind":"p","html":"Custom Tag Helpers let you emit HTML from server-side C#. Three pieces create one:","text":"Custom Tag Helpers let you emit HTML from server-side C#. Three pieces create one:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInherit from \u003ccode\u003eTagHelper\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e (from \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.AspNetCore.Razor.TagHelpers\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDecorate with \u003ccode\u003e[HtmlTargetElement(&quot;name&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — the tag name Razor binds to.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOverride \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync(TagHelperContext, TagHelperOutput)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e (or \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e for synchronous bodies) — the body that emits HTML.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Inherit from `TagHelper`** (from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Razor.TagHelpers`).\n2. **Decorate with `[HtmlTargetElement(\"name\")]`** — the tag name Razor binds to.\n3. **Override `ProcessAsync(TagHelperContext, TagHelperOutput)`** (or `Process` for synchronous bodies) — the body that emits HTML."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Razor.TagHelpers;\n\n[HtmlTargetElement(\"toon\")]\npublic class ToonTagHelper : TagHelper\n{\n    public string? FontFamily { get; set; }\n    public string? FontSize   { get; set; }\n\n    public override async Task ProcessAsync(\n        TagHelperContext context,\n        TagHelperOutput output)\n    {\n        var toons = await FetchToonsAsync();\n        var rows = string.Join(\"\", toons.Select(t =\u003e $\"\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003e{t.Name}\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\"));\n\n        output.TagName = \"table\";                       // rewrite the element\n        output.Content.SetHtmlContent(rows);             // inject inner HTML\n        output.Attributes.SetAttribute(                  // attach a computed style\n            \"style\", $\"font-family:{FontFamily};font-size:{FontSize};\");\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use it in a Razor page:","text":"Use it in a Razor page:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"\u003ctoon font-family=\"arial\" font-size=\"larger\"\u003e\u003c/toon\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"At render time, the tag becomes a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;table&gt;\u003c/code\u003e with your computed rows.","text":"At render time, the tag becomes a `\u003ctable\u003e` with your computed rows."},{"kind":"h2","html":"PascalCase properties ↔ kebab-case attributes","text":"PascalCase properties ↔ kebab-case attributes"},{"kind":"p","html":"Razor auto-translates between C# property names and HTML attribute names. \u003ccode\u003eFontFamily\u003c/code\u003e on the C# side becomes \u003ccode\u003efont-family\u003c/code\u003e on the HTML side. \u003ccode\u003eForegroundColor\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003eforeground-color\u003c/code\u003e. No underscores, no camelCase — always kebab-case in the Razor markup.","text":"Razor auto-translates between C# property names and HTML attribute names. `FontFamily` on the C# side becomes `font-family` on the HTML side. `ForegroundColor` becomes `foreground-color`. No underscores, no camelCase — always kebab-case in the Razor markup."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public string? ForegroundColor { get; set; }   // C#"},{"kind":"code","lang":"html","code":"\u003ctoon foreground-color=\"purple\"\u003e\u003c/toon\u003e        \u003c!-- Razor --\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"This mapping is a one-way derivation, not a config choice. Write your property names in PascalCase; Razor handles the rest.","text":"This mapping is a one-way derivation, not a config choice. Write your property names in PascalCase; Razor handles the rest."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e[HtmlTargetElement]\u003c/code\u003e — target tags or attributes","text":"`[HtmlTargetElement]` — target tags or attributes"},{"kind":"p","html":"The simplest form targets a tag name:","text":"The simplest form targets a tag name:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"[HtmlTargetElement(\"toon\")]          // binds to \u003ctoon ...\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"You can also target an existing tag when a specific attribute is present:","text":"You can also target an existing tag when a specific attribute is present:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"[HtmlTargetElement(\"div\", Attributes = \"toonie\")]  // binds to \u003cdiv toonie ...\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Multiple \u003ccode\u003e[HtmlTargetElement]\u003c/code\u003e attributes stack — one Tag Helper can bind to several patterns.","text":"Multiple `[HtmlTargetElement]` attributes stack — one Tag Helper can bind to several patterns."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e","text":"`ProcessAsync` vs `Process`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Override \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync\u003c/code\u003e when your body awaits anything — an HTTP call, a DB query, file I/O. Override \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e when the body is CPU-only. Mixing them (calling \u003ccode\u003eTask.Run(...)\u003c/code\u003e inside \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e) blocks the rendering thread and can deadlock; async rendering flows through \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync\u003c/code\u003e cleanly.","text":"Override `ProcessAsync` when your body awaits anything — an HTTP call, a DB query, file I/O. Override `Process` when the body is CPU-only. Mixing them (calling `Task.Run(...)` inside `Process`) blocks the rendering thread and can deadlock; async rendering flows through `ProcessAsync` cleanly."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Output manipulation primitives","text":"Output manipulation primitives"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003eTagHelperOutput\u003c/code\u003e object exposes three main knobs:","text":"The `TagHelperOutput` object exposes three main knobs:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMutation\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEffect\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eoutput.TagName = &quot;div&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eChange the rendered tag name. Set \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e to suppress the element.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eoutput.Content.SetHtmlContent(&quot;...&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReplace inner HTML.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eoutput.Content.AppendHtmlContent(&quot;...&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAppend without clearing existing content.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eoutput.Attributes.SetAttribute(&quot;key&quot;, &quot;val&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAdd or replace an HTML attribute.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eoutput.PreContent\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eoutput.PostContent\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInject HTML before / after the element body.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The difference between \u003ccode\u003eSet\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eAppend\u003c/code\u003e matters: \u003ccode\u003eSet\u003c/code\u003e wipes whatever the page author wrote between the open and close tags; \u003ccode\u003eAppend\u003c/code\u003e preserves it.","text":"The difference between `Set` and `Append` matters: `Set` wipes whatever the page author wrote between the open and close tags; `Append` preserves it."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A Tag Helper has a property `public string? BorderColor { get; set; }`. The page author writes `\u003cwidget bordercolor=\"red\"\u003e`. The property stays null. Why?","a":"Razor maps PascalCase to kebab-case — `BorderColor` binds to `border-color`, not `bordercolor`. Rewrite the markup as `\u003cwidget border-color=\"red\"\u003e` and the property populates."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA minimal &quot;environment badge&quot; tag that emits a colored span:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e[HtmlTargetElement(&quot;env-badge&quot;)]\npublic class EnvBadgeTagHelper : TagHelper\n{\n    public string? Name { get; set; }\n    public override void Process(TagHelperContext _, TagHelperOutput output)\n    {\n        output.TagName = &quot;span&quot;;\n        output.Attributes.SetAttribute(\n            &quot;style&quot;, Name == &quot;prod&quot; ? &quot;color:red&quot; : &quot;color:green&quot;);\n        output.Content.SetHtmlContent($&quot;env: {Name}&quot;);\n    }\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;env-badge name=&quot;dev&quot;&gt;&lt;/env-badge&gt;\u003c/code\u003e renders as \u003ccode\u003e&lt;span style=&quot;color:green&quot;&gt;env: dev&lt;/span&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. No async I/O → override \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A minimal \"environment badge\" tag that emits a colored span:\n```cs\n[HtmlTargetElement(\"env-badge\")]\npublic class EnvBadgeTagHelper : TagHelper\n{\n    public string? Name { get; set; }\n    public override void Process(TagHelperContext _, TagHelperOutput output)\n    {\n        output.TagName = \"span\";\n        output.Attributes.SetAttribute(\n            \"style\", Name == \"prod\" ? \"color:red\" : \"color:green\");\n        output.Content.SetHtmlContent($\"env: {Name}\");\n    }\n}\n```\n`\u003cenv-badge name=\"dev\"\u003e\u003c/env-badge\u003e` renders as `\u003cspan style=\"color:green\"\u003eenv: dev\u003c/span\u003e`. No async I/O → override `Process`, not `ProcessAsync`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003eTask.Run(...)\u003c/code\u003e or synchronous blocking inside \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e to call an async API. Razor renders views on a thread pool that starves under blocking calls — the page appears to hang, or throws a deadlock. Override \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync\u003c/code\u003e whenever your helper does anything async.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Using `Task.Run(...)` or synchronous blocking inside `Process` to call an async API. Razor renders views on a thread pool that starves under blocking calls — the page appears to hang, or throws a deadlock. Override `ProcessAsync` whenever your helper does anything async."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eCreate a Tag Helper by inheriting from \u003ccode\u003eTagHelper\u003c/code\u003e, decorating with \u003ccode\u003e[HtmlTargetElement(&quot;tag-name&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e, and overriding \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync(context, output)\u003c/code\u003e. PascalCase properties (\u003ccode\u003eFontFamily\u003c/code\u003e) bind to kebab-case HTML attributes (\u003ccode\u003efont-family\u003c/code\u003e). Use \u003ccode\u003eoutput.TagName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eoutput.Content.SetHtmlContent\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eoutput.Attributes.SetAttribute\u003c/code\u003e to rewrite the rendered element. Pick \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync\u003c/code\u003e for async bodies and \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e for CPU-only.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Create a Tag Helper by inheriting from `TagHelper`, decorating with `[HtmlTargetElement(\"tag-name\")]`, and overriding `ProcessAsync(context, output)`. PascalCase properties (`FontFamily`) bind to kebab-case HTML attributes (`font-family`). Use `output.TagName`, `output.Content.SetHtmlContent`, and `output.Attributes.SetAttribute` to rewrite the rendered element. Pick `ProcessAsync` for async bodies and `Process` for CPU-only."}]},{"n":22,"id":"taghelper-output-registration","title":"Tag Helper output manipulation + registration via _ViewImports","hook":"Register globally in `_ViewImports.cshtml`; manipulate `output` in `Process`.","tags":["tag-helper","razor","view-imports"],"module":"Performance & Caching","source":"notes/TagHelpers_SCRIPT.docx; research-taghelpers-blazor.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e_ViewImports.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e registers Tag Helpers globally","text":"`_ViewImports.cshtml` registers Tag Helpers globally"},{"kind":"p","html":"Tag Helpers are not discovered automatically from assemblies. Each Razor project has a \u003ccode\u003e_ViewImports.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e at the top of \u003ccode\u003ePages/\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eViews/\u003c/code\u003e where registration happens:","text":"Tag Helpers are not discovered automatically from assemblies. Each Razor project has a `_ViewImports.cshtml` at the top of `Pages/` or `Views/` where registration happens:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"@using MyApp\n@namespace MyApp.Pages\n@addTagHelper *, Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers\n@addTagHelper *, MyApp"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two parts per \u003ccode\u003e@addTagHelper\u003c/code\u003e directive:","text":"Two parts per `@addTagHelper` directive:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA glob\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e*\u003c/code\u003e means &quot;every Tag Helper in the assembly,&quot; or a fully qualified type name for a single helper.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAn assembly name\u003c/strong\u003e — the DLL that contains the helpers.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **A glob** — `*` means \"every Tag Helper in the assembly,\" or a fully qualified type name for a single helper.\n2. **An assembly name** — the DLL that contains the helpers."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers\u003c/code\u003e is the built-ins (\u003ccode\u003e&lt;cache&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&lt;environment&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&lt;partial&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003easp-for\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003easp-controller\u003c/code\u003e, etc.). \u003ccode\u003eMyApp\u003c/code\u003e is wherever your custom helpers live — usually the app&#39;s own assembly.","text":"`Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers` is the built-ins (`\u003ccache\u003e`, `\u003cenvironment\u003e`, `\u003cpartial\u003e`, `asp-for`, `asp-controller`, etc.). `MyApp` is wherever your custom helpers live — usually the app's own assembly."},{"kind":"p","html":"Individual \u003ccode\u003e.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e files inherit from \u003ccode\u003e_ViewImports.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e. You do NOT re-register helpers per-page; registration is global by convention.","text":"Individual `.cshtml` files inherit from `_ViewImports.cshtml`. You do NOT re-register helpers per-page; registration is global by convention."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Scoping registrations","text":"Scoping registrations"},{"kind":"p","html":"Drop a \u003ccode\u003e_ViewImports.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e into a subdirectory to scope registrations to pages under that directory:","text":"Drop a `_ViewImports.cshtml` into a subdirectory to scope registrations to pages under that directory:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Pages/\n├── _ViewImports.cshtml          ← global\n├── Admin/\n│   ├── _ViewImports.cshtml      ← additional for admin pages\n│   └── Dashboard.cshtml"},{"kind":"p","html":"The admin \u003ccode\u003eDashboard.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e inherits both files. This pattern is useful when a third-party package adds Tag Helpers you only want in one feature area.","text":"The admin `Dashboard.cshtml` inherits both files. This pattern is useful when a third-party package adds Tag Helpers you only want in one feature area."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e@removeTagHelper\u003c/code\u003e — selectively disable","text":"`@removeTagHelper` — selectively disable"},{"kind":"p","html":"When the global \u003ccode\u003e*, Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers\u003c/code\u003e registration enables a helper you don&#39;t want, remove it by exact name:","text":"When the global `*, Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers` registration enables a helper you don't want, remove it by exact name:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"@removeTagHelper \"Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers.CacheTagHelper, Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers\""},{"kind":"p","html":"Rarely needed, but handy for stripping \u003ccode\u003e&lt;cache&gt;\u003c/code\u003e globally when your team has decided to use output caching middleware instead.","text":"Rarely needed, but handy for stripping `\u003ccache\u003e` globally when your team has decided to use output caching middleware instead."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Shaping output in \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eProcessAsync\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Shaping output in `Process` / `ProcessAsync`"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003eTagHelperOutput\u003c/code\u003e passed into your override is the knob panel. Four main capabilities:","text":"The `TagHelperOutput` passed into your override is the knob panel. Four main capabilities:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRewrite the tag name.\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Rewrite the tag name.**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"output.TagName = \"div\";        // \u003cmytag\u003e → \u003cdiv\u003e\noutput.TagName = null;          // suppress the element entirely; keep its content inline"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eReplace, append, or prepend inner content.\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Replace, append, or prepend inner content.**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"output.Content.SetHtmlContent(\"\u003cp\u003eHi\u003c/p\u003e\");\noutput.Content.AppendHtmlContent(\"\u003cp\u003eMore\u003c/p\u003e\");\noutput.PreContent.SetHtmlContent(\"\u003c!-- begin --\u003e\");\noutput.PostContent.SetHtmlContent(\"\u003c!-- end --\u003e\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eSetHtmlContent\u003c/code\u003e wipes whatever the page author wrote between \u003ccode\u003e&lt;mytag&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&lt;/mytag&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eAppendHtmlContent\u003c/code\u003e preserves it and adds after. \u003ccode\u003ePreContent\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003ePostContent\u003c/code\u003e inject outside the element&#39;s inner HTML but inside the render stream.","text":"`SetHtmlContent` wipes whatever the page author wrote between `\u003cmytag\u003e` and `\u003c/mytag\u003e`. `AppendHtmlContent` preserves it and adds after. `PreContent` / `PostContent` inject outside the element's inner HTML but inside the render stream."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eAdd, replace, or remove attributes.\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Add, replace, or remove attributes.**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"output.Attributes.SetAttribute(\"class\", \"badge badge-warning\");\noutput.Attributes.RemoveAll(\"data-legacy\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSuppress the entire output.\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Suppress the entire output.**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"output.SuppressOutput();        // render nothing"},{"kind":"p","html":"Useful when a conditional property says &quot;don&#39;t show this at all.&quot;","text":"Useful when a conditional property says \"don't show this at all.\""},{"kind":"h2","html":"Distinguishing \u003ccode\u003eContent\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003ePreContent\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003ePostContent\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Distinguishing `Content` from `PreContent` / `PostContent`"},{"kind":"p","html":"Given \u003ccode\u003e&lt;mytag&gt;existing inner&lt;/mytag&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and this override:","text":"Given `\u003cmytag\u003eexisting inner\u003c/mytag\u003e` and this override:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"output.PreContent.SetHtmlContent(\"[pre]\");\noutput.Content.AppendHtmlContent(\"[appended]\");\noutput.PostContent.SetHtmlContent(\"[post]\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"The rendered HTML is \u003ccode\u003e&lt;mytag&gt;[pre]existing inner[appended][post]&lt;/mytag&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — Pre and Post live inside the tag but outside the inner-content area; appended-content adds to existing inner text.","text":"The rendered HTML is `\u003cmytag\u003e[pre]existing inner[appended][post]\u003c/mytag\u003e` — Pre and Post live inside the tag but outside the inner-content area; appended-content adds to existing inner text."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your Tag Helper targets `\u003cwidget\u003e` and overrides `ProcessAsync` with `output.Content.SetHtmlContent(\"\u003cp\u003eNew\u003c/p\u003e\")`. The page has `\u003cwidget\u003e\u003cp\u003eOld\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/widget\u003e`. The rendered output shows only `\u003cwidget\u003e\u003cp\u003eNew\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/widget\u003e` — the `\u003cp\u003eOld\u003c/p\u003e` vanished. What would preserve it?","a":"Swap `SetHtmlContent` for `AppendHtmlContent`. `SetHtmlContent` replaces existing content wholesale; `AppendHtmlContent` keeps the original and adds after. If you want the new content before the existing, use `PreContent.SetHtmlContent` instead."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA helper that renders nothing when a feature flag is off:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e[HtmlTargetElement(&quot;feature-gate&quot;)]\npublic class FeatureGateTagHelper : TagHelper\n{\n    public string? Flag { get; set; }\n    private readonly IFeatureFlags _flags;\n    public FeatureGateTagHelper(IFeatureFlags flags) =&gt; _flags = flags;\n    public override void Process(TagHelperContext _, TagHelperOutput output)\n    {\n        if (!_flags.IsEnabled(Flag!))\n            output.SuppressOutput();\n        else\n            output.TagName = null;   // render children, drop the wrapper tag\n    }\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;feature-gate flag=&quot;new-checkout&quot;&gt;…children…&lt;/feature-gate&gt;\u003c/code\u003e emits the children when enabled, nothing when disabled, and never emits the \u003ccode\u003e&lt;feature-gate&gt;\u003c/code\u003e wrapper tag itself.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A helper that renders nothing when a feature flag is off:\n```cs\n[HtmlTargetElement(\"feature-gate\")]\npublic class FeatureGateTagHelper : TagHelper\n{\n    public string? Flag { get; set; }\n    private readonly IFeatureFlags _flags;\n    public FeatureGateTagHelper(IFeatureFlags flags) =\u003e _flags = flags;\n    public override void Process(TagHelperContext _, TagHelperOutput output)\n    {\n        if (!_flags.IsEnabled(Flag!))\n            output.SuppressOutput();\n        else\n            output.TagName = null;   // render children, drop the wrapper tag\n    }\n}\n```\n`\u003cfeature-gate flag=\"new-checkout\"\u003e…children…\u003c/feature-gate\u003e` emits the children when enabled, nothing when disabled, and never emits the `\u003cfeature-gate\u003e` wrapper tag itself."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eForgetting the \u003ccode\u003e@addTagHelper\u003c/code\u003e line in \u003ccode\u003e_ViewImports.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e. The helper compiles fine in its assembly but Razor treats \u003ccode\u003e&lt;toon&gt;\u003c/code\u003e as an unknown HTML element — rendering literal \u003ccode\u003e&lt;toon&gt;\u003c/code\u003e in the page source. The DI container has nothing to do with Tag Helper discovery; \u003ccode\u003e_ViewImports.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e is the only place Razor looks.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Forgetting the `@addTagHelper` line in `_ViewImports.cshtml`. The helper compiles fine in its assembly but Razor treats `\u003ctoon\u003e` as an unknown HTML element — rendering literal `\u003ctoon\u003e` in the page source. The DI container has nothing to do with Tag Helper discovery; `_ViewImports.cshtml` is the only place Razor looks."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eRegister helpers once per Razor project in \u003ccode\u003e_ViewImports.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e via \u003ccode\u003e@addTagHelper *, AssemblyName\u003c/code\u003e. In the helper itself, shape the result with \u003ccode\u003eoutput.TagName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eoutput.Content\u003c/code\u003e (\u003ccode\u003eSet\u003c/code\u003e replaces, \u003ccode\u003eAppend\u003c/code\u003e preserves), \u003ccode\u003eoutput.PreContent\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eoutput.PostContent\u003c/code\u003e for injections around the body, and \u003ccode\u003eoutput.Attributes.SetAttribute\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eRemoveAll\u003c/code\u003e for attributes. \u003ccode\u003eoutput.SuppressOutput()\u003c/code\u003e removes the element entirely when a condition fails.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Register helpers once per Razor project in `_ViewImports.cshtml` via `@addTagHelper *, AssemblyName`. In the helper itself, shape the result with `output.TagName`, `output.Content` (`Set` replaces, `Append` preserves), `output.PreContent` / `output.PostContent` for injections around the body, and `output.Attributes.SetAttribute` / `RemoveAll` for attributes. `output.SuppressOutput()` removes the element entirely when a condition fails."}]},{"n":23,"id":"localization-resources-cultures","title":"Localization resources + cultures — .resx files, CurrentCulture, providers","hook":"Name the .resx file right; set both cultures; let providers pick.","tags":["i18n","culture","resx"],"module":"Internationalization & Modern UI","source":"slides/asp_core_localization.pptx; notes/razor_pages_localization_SCRIPT.docx; research-localization.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"One \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e file per class per culture","text":"One `.resx` file per class per culture"},{"kind":"p","html":"For a Razor page at \u003ccode\u003ePages/Index.cshtml.cs\u003c/code\u003e (class name \u003ccode\u003eIndexModel\u003c/code\u003e), your French translations live at exactly this path:","text":"For a Razor page at `Pages/Index.cshtml.cs` (class name `IndexModel`), your French translations live at exactly this path:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"Resources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx"},{"kind":"p","html":"The rules:","text":"The rules:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRoot folder\u003c/strong\u003e matches \u003ccode\u003eoptions.ResourcesPath\u003c/code\u003e (conventionally \u003ccode\u003eResources\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSubfolder\u003c/strong\u003e mirrors the class&#39;s folder relative to the project root (\u003ccode\u003ePages/\u003c/code\u003e here).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFilename\u003c/strong\u003e is \u003ccode\u003e&lt;ClassName&gt;.&lt;culture&gt;.resx\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Root folder** matches `options.ResourcesPath` (conventionally `Resources`).\n2. **Subfolder** mirrors the class's folder relative to the project root (`Pages/` here).\n3. **Filename** is `\u003cClassName\u003e.\u003cculture\u003e.resx`."},{"kind":"p","html":"For other conventions:","text":"For other conventions:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA controller \u003ccode\u003eControllers/HomeController.cs\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eResources/Controllers/HomeController.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA shared resource (see the localization-injection lesson) → \u003ccode\u003eResources/SharedResource.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA model with data-annotations → \u003ccode\u003eResources/Models/ContactForm.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- A controller `Controllers/HomeController.cs` → `Resources/Controllers/HomeController.fr.resx`.\n- A shared resource (see the localization-injection lesson) → `Resources/SharedResource.fr.resx`.\n- A model with data-annotations → `Resources/Models/ContactForm.fr.resx`."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e file is XML that stores key → localized-string pairs. The Visual Studio / Rider designer edits them as a two-column grid; VS Code users install the &quot;ResX Editor&quot; extension.","text":"A `.resx` file is XML that stores key → localized-string pairs. The Visual Studio / Rider designer edits them as a two-column grid; VS Code users install the \"ResX Editor\" extension."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Culture codes","text":"Culture codes"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e targets one culture, named by standard BCP-47 tags:","text":"Each `.resx` targets one culture, named by standard BCP-47 tags:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eTag\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMeaning\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003een\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGeneric English\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003efr\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGeneric French\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003een-US\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUS English (regional)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003efr-CA\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCanadian French\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ezh-Hans\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSimplified Chinese\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"ASP.NET Core&#39;s fallback chain: requested culture → parent culture → default. So \u003ccode\u003efr-CA.resx\u003c/code\u003e falls back to \u003ccode\u003efr.resx\u003c/code\u003e, which falls back to the un-suffixed \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e if one exists. Most apps ship \u003ccode\u003een.resx\u003c/code\u003e (or \u003ccode\u003een-US.resx\u003c/code\u003e) as the default and add non-English variants as needed.","text":"ASP.NET Core's fallback chain: requested culture → parent culture → default. So `fr-CA.resx` falls back to `fr.resx`, which falls back to the un-suffixed `.resx` if one exists. Most apps ship `en.resx` (or `en-US.resx`) as the default and add non-English variants as needed."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003eCurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e — not the same","text":"`CurrentCulture` vs `CurrentUICulture` — not the same"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two separate \u003ccode\u003eThread\u003c/code\u003e-scoped values drive localization behaviour:","text":"Two separate `Thread`-scoped values drive localization behaviour:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eProperty\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat it controls\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eThread.CurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDate, number, and currency formatting (\u003ccode\u003e.ToString()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003edecimal.ToString(&quot;C&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e, etc.)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eThread.CurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWhich \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e gets loaded by \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer[...]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Set only \u003ccode\u003eCurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e and your numbers format correctly but your UI strings stay in the default language. Set only \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e and UI strings translate but dates still render in \u003ccode\u003een-US\u003c/code\u003e format. ASP.NET Core&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e middleware sets both together from the detected culture — see the localization-setup lesson.","text":"Set only `CurrentCulture` and your numbers format correctly but your UI strings stay in the default language. Set only `CurrentUICulture` and UI strings translate but dates still render in `en-US` format. ASP.NET Core's `UseRequestLocalization()` middleware sets both together from the detected culture — see the localization-setup lesson."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Culture providers — who picks the culture","text":"Culture providers — who picks the culture"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eRequestLocalizationMiddleware\u003c/code\u003e runs three providers in a strict order. First match wins:","text":"`RequestLocalizationMiddleware` runs three providers in a strict order. First match wins:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eQueryStringRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e?culture=fr\u003c/code\u003e in the URL. Highest priority; useful for testing and for deep links to specific languages.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCookieRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — reads \u003ccode\u003e.AspNetCore.Culture\u003c/code\u003e cookie. This is how persistent user selection works (see the switcher UI in localization-setup).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAcceptLanguageHeaderRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — reads the browser&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eAccept-Language\u003c/code\u003e header. Automatic, zero UI required.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **`QueryStringRequestCultureProvider`** — `?culture=fr` in the URL. Highest priority; useful for testing and for deep links to specific languages.\n2. **`CookieRequestCultureProvider`** — reads `.AspNetCore.Culture` cookie. This is how persistent user selection works (see the switcher UI in localization-setup).\n3. **`AcceptLanguageHeaderRequestCultureProvider`** — reads the browser's `Accept-Language` header. Automatic, zero UI required."},{"kind":"p","html":"Order is configurable via \u003ccode\u003eoptions.RequestCultureProviders\u003c/code\u003e if you want the header to beat the cookie. Default order is the one above.","text":"Order is configurable via `options.RequestCultureProviders` if you want the header to beat the cookie. Default order is the one above."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A page's `IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e[\"Welcome\"]` returns the literal string `\"Welcome\"` even though `Resources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx` contains a `Welcome` key translated to `\"Bienvenue\"`. What two independent misconfigurations could cause this?","a":"(1) The user's detected culture isn't French — maybe `?culture=fr` isn't set, no cookie exists, and the `Accept-Language` header is `en-US`. (2) `UseRequestLocalization()` middleware is missing from `Program.cs`, so no provider runs and `CurrentUICulture` stays at the default. Fix either / both."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eResource-file layout for a course website supporting English and French:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-text\"\u003eResources/\n├── Pages/\n│   ├── IndexModel.fr.resx\n│   └── CoursesModel.fr.resx\n├── Controllers/\n│   └── HomeController.fr.resx\n├── Models/\n│   └── EnrollForm.fr.resx\n└── SharedResource.fr.resx\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eEnglish uses the default un-suffixed \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e (or a parallel \u003ccode\u003e.en.resx\u003c/code\u003e set). Adding German later means copying the file tree and swapping \u003ccode\u003e.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e for \u003ccode\u003e.de.resx\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Resource-file layout for a course website supporting English and French:\n```text\nResources/\n├── Pages/\n│   ├── IndexModel.fr.resx\n│   └── CoursesModel.fr.resx\n├── Controllers/\n│   └── HomeController.fr.resx\n├── Models/\n│   └── EnrollForm.fr.resx\n└── SharedResource.fr.resx\n```\nEnglish uses the default un-suffixed `.resx` (or a parallel `.en.resx` set). Adding German later means copying the file tree and swapping `.fr.resx` for `.de.resx`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eNaming a resource file \u003ccode\u003eResources/IndexModel.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e (no \u003ccode\u003ePages/\u003c/code\u003e subfolder) for a class in \u003ccode\u003ePages/Index.cshtml.cs\u003c/code\u003e. The file exists, the build succeeds, but \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;IndexModel&gt;\u003c/code\u003e looks in \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e and finds nothing — the indexer returns the key unchanged. Directory structure under \u003ccode\u003eResources/\u003c/code\u003e must mirror the class&#39;s folder.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Naming a resource file `Resources/IndexModel.fr.resx` (no `Pages/` subfolder) for a class in `Pages/Index.cshtml.cs`. The file exists, the build succeeds, but `IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e` looks in `Resources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx` and finds nothing — the indexer returns the key unchanged. Directory structure under `Resources/` must mirror the class's folder."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eOne \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e per class per culture, at \u003ccode\u003eResources/&lt;folder&gt;/&lt;ClassName&gt;.&lt;culture&gt;.resx\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eCurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e controls formatting; \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e controls which \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e loads — set both. Culture providers run in order QueryString → Cookie → AcceptLanguageHeader; first match wins. If a lookup returns the key verbatim, check the file path AND whether the middleware actually detected your target culture.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"One `.resx` per class per culture, at `Resources/\u003cfolder\u003e/\u003cClassName\u003e.\u003cculture\u003e.resx`. `CurrentCulture` controls formatting; `CurrentUICulture` controls which `.resx` loads — set both. Culture providers run in order QueryString → Cookie → AcceptLanguageHeader; first match wins. If a lookup returns the key verbatim, check the file path AND whether the middleware actually detected your target culture."}]},{"n":24,"id":"localization-setup","title":"Localization setup — AddLocalization, AddViewLocalization, UseRequestLocalization","hook":"Three registrations in Program.cs; one middleware call. Skip any and localization silently fails.","tags":["i18n","middleware","program-cs"],"module":"Internationalization & Modern UI","source":"notes/razor_pages_localization_SCRIPT.docx; research-localization.md §3","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The five-line localization boilerplate","text":"The five-line localization boilerplate"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every ASP.NET Core app that localizes anything needs this in \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Every ASP.NET Core app that localizes anything needs this in `Program.cs`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\n// 1. Register localization services + where resource files live\nbuilder.Services.AddLocalization(opts =\u003e opts.ResourcesPath = \"Resources\");\n\n// 2. Declare supported cultures + default\nbuilder.Services.Configure\u003cRequestLocalizationOptions\u003e(opts =\u003e\n{\n    var supported = new[]\n    {\n        new CultureInfo(\"en\"),\n        new CultureInfo(\"fr\"),\n        new CultureInfo(\"de\"),\n    };\n    opts.DefaultRequestCulture = new RequestCulture(\"en\");\n    opts.SupportedCultures      = supported;   // formatting (CurrentCulture)\n    opts.SupportedUICultures    = supported;   // resource-file picks (CurrentUICulture)\n});\n\n// 3. Turn on view + data-annotation localization\nbuilder.Services.AddMvc()\n    .AddViewLocalization()\n    .AddDataAnnotationsLocalization();\n\nvar app = builder.Build();\n\n// 4. Apply detected culture to each request\napp.UseRequestLocalization();\n\napp.MapRazorPages();\napp.Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Five registrations, one middleware call. Skip any one and the chain falls silently.","text":"Five registrations, one middleware call. Skip any one and the chain falls silently."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What each line does","text":"What each line does"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddLocalization\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e registers \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, and the underlying factory. \u003ccode\u003eResourcesPath\u003c/code\u003e is the root folder for \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e files.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eConfigure&lt;RequestLocalizationOptions&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e declares which cultures the app is willing to serve and the fallback. \u003ccode\u003eSupportedCultures\u003c/code\u003e sets the allowed values for \u003ccode\u003eCurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e (formatting); \u003ccode\u003eSupportedUICultures\u003c/code\u003e sets allowed values for \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e (which \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddViewLocalization\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e wires up \u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e so you can \u003ccode\u003e@inject\u003c/code\u003e it in \u003ccode\u003e.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e files.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddDataAnnotationsLocalization\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e translates validation attributes like \u003ccode\u003e[Required(ErrorMessage = &quot;FieldRequired&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e through \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eapp.UseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e is the middleware that actually runs the culture providers on each request and sets \u003ccode\u003eThread.CurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e accordingly.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **`AddLocalization`** registers `IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e`, `IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e`, and the underlying factory. `ResourcesPath` is the root folder for `.resx` files.\n- **`Configure\u003cRequestLocalizationOptions\u003e`** declares which cultures the app is willing to serve and the fallback. `SupportedCultures` sets the allowed values for `CurrentCulture` (formatting); `SupportedUICultures` sets allowed values for `CurrentUICulture` (which `.resx`).\n- **`AddViewLocalization`** wires up `IViewLocalizer` so you can `@inject` it in `.cshtml` files.\n- **`AddDataAnnotationsLocalization`** translates validation attributes like `[Required(ErrorMessage = \"FieldRequired\")]` through `IStringLocalizer`.\n- **`app.UseRequestLocalization()`** is the middleware that actually runs the culture providers on each request and sets `Thread.CurrentCulture` + `CurrentUICulture` accordingly."},{"kind":"p","html":"Register the services but forget \u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization\u003c/code\u003e and you get a silent no-op: every request uses the default culture, and any user-selected language is ignored.","text":"Register the services but forget `UseRequestLocalization` and you get a silent no-op: every request uses the default culture, and any user-selected language is ignored."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Middleware ordering matters","text":"Middleware ordering matters"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization\u003c/code\u003e must run \u003cstrong\u003ebefore\u003c/strong\u003e any middleware or endpoint that reads localized content. The typical order:","text":"`UseRequestLocalization` must run **before** any middleware or endpoint that reads localized content. The typical order:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"app.UseRequestLocalization();   // 1. detect culture\napp.UseStaticFiles();            // 2. static content\napp.UseRouting();                // 3. endpoint matching\napp.UseAuthorization();          // 4. auth\napp.MapRazorPages();             // 5. endpoints"},{"kind":"p","html":"Putting \u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization\u003c/code\u003e after \u003ccode\u003eUseRouting\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eUseEndpoints\u003c/code\u003e causes endpoint handlers to run with the default culture even when the user&#39;s preferred culture was detectable.","text":"Putting `UseRequestLocalization` after `UseRouting` or `UseEndpoints` causes endpoint handlers to run with the default culture even when the user's preferred culture was detectable."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Explicit options + middleware","text":"Explicit options + middleware"},{"kind":"p","html":"The simple \u003ccode\u003eapp.UseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e call reads options from DI and applies them. If you need to manipulate options at middleware time (e.g. swap providers) you can pass them explicitly:","text":"The simple `app.UseRequestLocalization()` call reads options from DI and applies them. If you need to manipulate options at middleware time (e.g. swap providers) you can pass them explicitly:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using (var scope = app.Services.CreateScope())\n{\n    var opts = scope.ServiceProvider\n        .GetRequiredService\u003cIOptions\u003cRequestLocalizationOptions\u003e\u003e()\n        .Value;\n    app.UseRequestLocalization(opts);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Same effect; more boilerplate. Use the explicit form only when you need it.","text":"Same effect; more boilerplate. Use the explicit form only when you need it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Culture-switcher handler","text":"Culture-switcher handler"},{"kind":"p","html":"The UI for letting a user switch language is covered in the practice file and \u003ccode\u003elocalization-injection\u003c/code\u003e lesson. The core handler is a \u003ccode\u003ePOST\u003c/code\u003e that writes the \u003ccode\u003e.AspNetCore.Culture\u003c/code\u003e cookie:","text":"The UI for letting a user switch language is covered in the practice file and `localization-injection` lesson. The core handler is a `POST` that writes the `.AspNetCore.Culture` cookie:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public IActionResult OnPost(string culture, string returnUrl)\n{\n    Response.Cookies.Append(\n        CookieRequestCultureProvider.DefaultCookieName,\n        CookieRequestCultureProvider.MakeCookieValue(new RequestCulture(culture)),\n        new CookieOptions { Expires = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow.AddYears(1) });\n\n    return LocalRedirect(returnUrl);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eCookieRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e will pick this up on subsequent requests, because the cookie provider is registered by \u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e by default.","text":"`CookieRequestCultureProvider` will pick this up on subsequent requests, because the cookie provider is registered by `UseRequestLocalization()` by default."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your app has `AddLocalization`, `Configure\u003cRequestLocalizationOptions\u003e`, and `AddViewLocalization` in `Program.cs`. Users report language is never switching. What's the single most likely missing line?","a":"`app.UseRequestLocalization()`. Without the middleware call, no provider runs, `CurrentCulture` / `CurrentUICulture` never get set from the request, and the app behaves as if every user preferred the default culture. The symptoms are exactly \"nothing localizes no matter what I do.\""},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe minimum viable localization boot — trimmed to the three absolute essentials for a single-language-switch demo:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003evar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.Services.AddLocalization(o =&gt; o.ResourcesPath = &quot;Resources&quot;);\nbuilder.Services.Configure&lt;RequestLocalizationOptions&gt;(o =&gt;\n{\n    o.DefaultRequestCulture = new RequestCulture(&quot;en&quot;);\n    o.SupportedCultures   = new[] { new CultureInfo(&quot;en&quot;), new CultureInfo(&quot;fr&quot;) };\n    o.SupportedUICultures = o.SupportedCultures;\n});\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorPages().AddViewLocalization();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.UseRequestLocalization();\napp.MapRazorPages();\napp.Run();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWith a matching pair of \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.en.resx\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e, appending \u003ccode\u003e?culture=fr\u003c/code\u003e to any page now flips it to French.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The minimum viable localization boot — trimmed to the three absolute essentials for a single-language-switch demo:\n```cs\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.Services.AddLocalization(o =\u003e o.ResourcesPath = \"Resources\");\nbuilder.Services.Configure\u003cRequestLocalizationOptions\u003e(o =\u003e\n{\n    o.DefaultRequestCulture = new RequestCulture(\"en\");\n    o.SupportedCultures   = new[] { new CultureInfo(\"en\"), new CultureInfo(\"fr\") };\n    o.SupportedUICultures = o.SupportedCultures;\n});\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorPages().AddViewLocalization();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.UseRequestLocalization();\napp.MapRazorPages();\napp.Run();\n```\nWith a matching pair of `Resources/Pages/IndexModel.en.resx` and `Resources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx`, appending `?culture=fr` to any page now flips it to French."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003eAddLocalization\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003eAddViewLocalization\u003c/code\u003e in a Razor Pages app. \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;PageModel&gt;\u003c/code\u003e works in code-behind, but \u003ccode\u003e@inject IViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e fails at runtime with &quot;no service registered.&quot; Always pair them when views need to localize directly.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Calling `AddLocalization` without `AddViewLocalization` in a Razor Pages app. `IStringLocalizer\u003cPageModel\u003e` works in code-behind, but `@inject IViewLocalizer` in `.cshtml` fails at runtime with \"no service registered.\" Always pair them when views need to localize directly."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eRegister \u003ccode\u003eAddLocalization\u003c/code\u003e (with \u003ccode\u003eResourcesPath\u003c/code\u003e), configure \u003ccode\u003eRequestLocalizationOptions\u003c/code\u003e (SupportedCultures + SupportedUICultures + DefaultRequestCulture), call \u003ccode\u003eAddViewLocalization\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eAddDataAnnotationsLocalization\u003c/code\u003e if you need them, and — critically — call \u003ccode\u003eapp.UseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e early in the middleware pipeline. Skipping the middleware is the most common reason localization silently does nothing.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Register `AddLocalization` (with `ResourcesPath`), configure `RequestLocalizationOptions` (SupportedCultures + SupportedUICultures + DefaultRequestCulture), call `AddViewLocalization` and `AddDataAnnotationsLocalization` if you need them, and — critically — call `app.UseRequestLocalization()` early in the middleware pipeline. Skipping the middleware is the most common reason localization silently does nothing."}]},{"n":25,"id":"localization-injection","title":"Localizer injection — IStringLocalizer, IHtmlLocalizer, IViewLocalizer, shared resources","hook":"Three localizer types, three injection sites. Pick by what you render.","tags":["i18n","di","istringlocalizer","iviewlocalizer"],"module":"Internationalization & Modern UI","source":"notes/razor_pages_localization_SCRIPT.docx; research-localization.md §2, §5","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Three localizer interfaces for three render surfaces","text":"Three localizer interfaces for three render surfaces"},{"kind":"p","html":".NET ships three localizer types. They differ in where you inject them and what kind of content they return.","text":".NET ships three localizer types. They differ in where you inject them and what kind of content they return."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eInterface\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhere\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eReturns\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eUse when\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAny DI-aware class (PageModel, Controller, Service)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePlain text\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRendering a string into a variable or \u003ccode\u003eViewData\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAny DI-aware class\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMarked-safe HTML\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eThe translation contains markup (anchor tags, \u003ccode\u003e&lt;strong&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, etc.)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e views directly via \u003ccode\u003e@inject\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePlain text\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRendering straight from markup without routing through the PageModel\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"All three use the same indexer syntax: \u003ccode\u003elocalizer[&quot;Key&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e, optionally \u003ccode\u003elocalizer[&quot;Key&quot;, arg1, arg2]\u003c/code\u003e for positional string-format substitutions.","text":"All three use the same indexer syntax: `localizer[\"Key\"]`, optionally `localizer[\"Key\", arg1, arg2]` for positional string-format substitutions."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e in a PageModel","text":"`IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` in a PageModel"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class IndexModel : PageModel\n{\n    private readonly IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e _localizer;\n\n    public IndexModel(IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e localizer)\n        =\u003e _localizer = localizer;\n\n    public void OnGet()\n    {\n        ViewData[\"Message\"] = _localizer[\"Message\"];\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The generic parameter \u003ccode\u003e&lt;IndexModel&gt;\u003c/code\u003e drives two things: which resource file to load (the name maps to \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.&lt;culture&gt;.resx\u003c/code\u003e) and which service registration to pick in DI. Always generic; never a plain \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e unless you want the shared-resource pattern below.","text":"The generic parameter `\u003cIndexModel\u003e` drives two things: which resource file to load (the name maps to `Resources/Pages/IndexModel.\u003cculture\u003e.resx`) and which service registration to pick in DI. Always generic; never a plain `IStringLocalizer` unless you want the shared-resource pattern below."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e inline in a \u003ccode\u003e.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e","text":"`IViewLocalizer` inline in a `.cshtml`"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"@page\n@inject IViewLocalizer Localizer\n@model IndexModel\n\n\u003ch1\u003e@Localizer[\"Welcome\"]\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e@Localizer[\"Intro\"]\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The implicit generic parameter is the type of the \u003ccode\u003e.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e file&#39;s generated class — which maps to the same resource file as \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;IndexModel&gt;\u003c/code\u003e would. Use \u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e when the string is only ever rendered directly in markup; use \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e when code-behind needs the string.","text":"The implicit generic parameter is the type of the `.cshtml` file's generated class — which maps to the same resource file as `IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e` would. Use `IViewLocalizer` when the string is only ever rendered directly in markup; use `IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` when code-behind needs the string."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for HTML-bearing translations","text":"`IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` for HTML-bearing translations"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class IndexModel : PageModel\n{\n    private readonly IHtmlLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e _html;\n\n    public IndexModel(IHtmlLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e html) =\u003e _html = html;\n\n    public IHtmlContent Learn() =\u003e _html[\"LearnMore\"];\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"With \u003ccode\u003eLearnMore\u003c/code\u003e in the \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e set to \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Read &lt;a href=\\&quot;/docs\\&quot;&gt;the docs&lt;/a&gt;&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e returns an \u003ccode\u003eIHtmlContent\u003c/code\u003e that renders the anchor verbatim. \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e would HTML-encode the angle brackets so the user sees the raw HTML source — not what you want.","text":"With `LearnMore` in the `.resx` set to `\"Read \u003ca href=\\\"/docs\\\"\u003ethe docs\u003c/a\u003e\"`, `IHtmlLocalizer` returns an `IHtmlContent` that renders the anchor verbatim. `IStringLocalizer` would HTML-encode the angle brackets so the user sees the raw HTML source — not what you want."},{"kind":"p","html":"Rule of thumb: if the translated string contains any \u003ccode\u003e&lt;\u003c/code\u003e character that should be interpreted as markup, use \u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e. Otherwise use \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Rule of thumb: if the translated string contains any `\u003c` character that should be interpreted as markup, use `IHtmlLocalizer`. Otherwise use `IStringLocalizer`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Shared resources for strings used everywhere","text":"Shared resources for strings used everywhere"},{"kind":"p","html":"Strings like navigation labels, footer copyright, or common button text appear on many pages. Duplicating translations across every per-page \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e is tedious and error-prone. The shared-resources pattern uses one empty marker class plus a service:","text":"Strings like navigation labels, footer copyright, or common button text appear on many pages. Duplicating translations across every per-page `.resx` is tedious and error-prone. The shared-resources pattern uses one empty marker class plus a service:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// Marker class — the \"type\" whose resource file holds shared strings.\nnamespace MyApp;\npublic class SharedResource { }"},{"kind":"p","html":"Create \u003ccode\u003eResources/SharedResource.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e (no subfolder — the marker is at the root namespace).","text":"Create `Resources/SharedResource.fr.resx` (no subfolder — the marker is at the root namespace)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Register a service:","text":"Register a service:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class SharedLocalizer\n{\n    private readonly IStringLocalizer _inner;\n\n    public SharedLocalizer(IStringLocalizerFactory factory)\n    {\n        var assembly = typeof(SharedResource).Assembly.GetName();\n        _inner = factory.Create(nameof(SharedResource), assembly.Name!);\n    }\n\n    public string Get(string key) =\u003e _inner[key];\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Register and inject:","text":"Register and inject:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// Program.cs\nbuilder.Services.AddSingleton\u003cSharedLocalizer\u003e();\n\n// Razor page\n@inject SharedLocalizer Shared\n\u003cfooter\u003e© @DateTime.Now.Year — @Shared.Get(\"CompanyName\")\u003c/footer\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Strings translated once; visible everywhere.","text":"Strings translated once; visible everywhere."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Arguments and formatting","text":"Arguments and formatting"},{"kind":"p","html":"All three localizers accept positional args:","text":"All three localizers accept positional args:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"_localizer[\"GreetUser\", userName]\n// .resx value: \"Hello, {0}!\"\n// Renders: \"Hello, Alice!\" (en) / \"Bonjour, Alice !\" (fr)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Use this instead of string concatenation so translators can reorder \u003ccode\u003e{0}\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e{1}\u003c/code\u003e in languages with different word order.","text":"Use this instead of string concatenation so translators can reorder `{0}` and `{1}` in languages with different word order."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You add `IViewLocalizer Localizer` to a `.cshtml` file and get a runtime error: \"no service for type `IViewLocalizer` has been registered.\" Services and middleware are configured. What's missing?","a":"`AddViewLocalization()` wasn't called on the MVC / Razor Pages builder. `AddLocalization` alone registers `IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` but not `IViewLocalizer`. Add `.AddViewLocalization()` to the `AddMvc()` or `AddRazorPages()` chain."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA three-page site with per-page strings (via \u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e) and shared navigation (via \u003ccode\u003eSharedLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e):\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e@page\n@inject IViewLocalizer PageL\n@inject SharedLocalizer Shared\n@model IndexModel\n&lt;nav&gt;\n    &lt;a href=&quot;/&quot;&gt;@Shared.Get(&quot;NavHome&quot;)&lt;/a&gt;\n    &lt;a href=&quot;/Courses&quot;&gt;@Shared.Get(&quot;NavCourses&quot;)&lt;/a&gt;\n&lt;/nav&gt;\n&lt;h1&gt;@PageL[&quot;Welcome&quot;]&lt;/h1&gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe nav labels come from \u003ccode\u003eResources/SharedResource.&lt;culture&gt;.resx\u003c/code\u003e; the welcome comes from \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.&lt;culture&gt;.resx\u003c/code\u003e. Each translator owns a scoped file set.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A three-page site with per-page strings (via `IViewLocalizer`) and shared navigation (via `SharedLocalizer`):\n```cs\n@page\n@inject IViewLocalizer PageL\n@inject SharedLocalizer Shared\n@model IndexModel\n\u003cnav\u003e\n    \u003ca href=\"/\"\u003e@Shared.Get(\"NavHome\")\u003c/a\u003e\n    \u003ca href=\"/Courses\"\u003e@Shared.Get(\"NavCourses\")\u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/nav\u003e\n\u003ch1\u003e@PageL[\"Welcome\"]\u003c/h1\u003e\n```\nThe nav labels come from `Resources/SharedResource.\u003cculture\u003e.resx`; the welcome comes from `Resources/Pages/IndexModel.\u003cculture\u003e.resx`. Each translator owns a scoped file set."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e to render a translation that contains HTML markup. The indexer returns a \u003ccode\u003eLocalizedString\u003c/code\u003e whose \u003ccode\u003eValue\u003c/code\u003e gets HTML-encoded when rendered in Razor, so \u003ccode\u003e&quot;&lt;a href=\\&quot;/\\&quot;&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;&quot;\u003c/code\u003e shows up as literal \u003ccode\u003e&lt;a href=&quot;/&quot;&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;\u003c/code\u003e text. Either use \u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e or wrap the value with \u003ccode\u003e@Html.Raw(...)\u003c/code\u003e (riskier — you lose XSS protection).\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Using `IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` to render a translation that contains HTML markup. The indexer returns a `LocalizedString` whose `Value` gets HTML-encoded when rendered in Razor, so `\"\u003ca href=\\\"/\\\"\u003eHome\u003c/a\u003e\"` shows up as literal `\u003ca href=\"/\"\u003eHome\u003c/a\u003e` text. Either use `IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` or wrap the value with `@Html.Raw(...)` (riskier — you lose XSS protection)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for code-behind plain text; \u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for code-behind HTML content; \u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e for direct \u003ccode\u003e.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e use via \u003ccode\u003e@inject\u003c/code\u003e. Shared strings get a \u003ccode\u003eSharedResource\u003c/code\u003e marker class plus a singleton service using \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizerFactory.Create(nameof(SharedResource), assemblyName)\u003c/code\u003e. Indexer \u003ccode\u003elocalizer[&quot;Key&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e is the same across all three; positional args \u003ccode\u003e[&quot;Key&quot;, val1, val2]\u003c/code\u003e fill \u003ccode\u003e{0}\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e{1}\u003c/code\u003e placeholders in the \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e value.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` for code-behind plain text; `IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` for code-behind HTML content; `IViewLocalizer` for direct `.cshtml` use via `@inject`. Shared strings get a `SharedResource` marker class plus a singleton service using `IStringLocalizerFactory.Create(nameof(SharedResource), assemblyName)`. Indexer `localizer[\"Key\"]` is the same across all three; positional args `[\"Key\", val1, val2]` fill `{0}` / `{1}` placeholders in the `.resx` value."}]},{"n":26,"id":"blazor-quickgrid","title":"Blazor QuickGrid — PropertyColumn, TemplateColumn, PaginationState, sorting, filtering","hook":"Bind an IQueryable, pick a column type per purpose, and wire pagination with PaginationState.","tags":["blazor","ui","quickgrid"],"module":"Internationalization & Modern UI","source":"notes/BlazorServer_QuickGrid.docx; notes/BlazorWasm_QuickGrid.docx; Labs/W07 QuickGrid/; research-taghelpers-blazor.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"One grid, three column types","text":"One grid, three column types"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eQuickGrid\u003c/code\u003e is Microsoft&#39;s data-grid component shipped in \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid\u003c/code\u003e (.NET 8+). A minimal grid binding to an \u003ccode\u003eIQueryable&lt;Student&gt;\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"`QuickGrid` is Microsoft's data-grid component shipped in `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid` (.NET 8+). A minimal grid binding to an `IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"@page \"/students\"\n@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid\n@rendermode InteractiveServer\n\n\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@_students\" Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.LastName)\"  Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n    \u003cTemplateColumn Title=\"Full name\" SortBy=\"@_sortByFull\"\u003e\n        \u003cdiv\u003e@context.FirstName @context.LastName\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/TemplateColumn\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\n\u003cPaginator State=\"@_pagination\" /\u003e\n\n@code {\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e _students = Student.GetStudents();\n    private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 10 };\n    private GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e _sortByFull =\n        GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e.ByAscending(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\n                         .ThenAscending(s =\u003e s.LastName);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three ingredients:","text":"Three ingredients:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;QuickGrid Items=&quot;@_students&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — the data source. Must be \u003ccode\u003eIQueryable&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for server-side filtering / paging. An \u003ccode\u003eIEnumerable&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e works but pulls everything into memory first.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eColumns\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e&lt;PropertyColumn Property=&quot;@(x =&gt; x.Field)&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for straight property binding, or \u003ccode\u003e&lt;TemplateColumn&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for custom render logic.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePagination\u003c/strong\u003e — bind \u003ccode\u003e&lt;QuickGrid Pagination=&quot;@_pagination&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e plus a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;Paginator State=&quot;@_pagination&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e component. Declare \u003ccode\u003ePaginationState\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e@code\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **`\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@_students\"\u003e`** — the data source. Must be `IQueryable\u003cT\u003e` for server-side filtering / paging. An `IEnumerable\u003cT\u003e` works but pulls everything into memory first.\n2. **Columns** — `\u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(x =\u003e x.Field)\"\u003e` for straight property binding, or `\u003cTemplateColumn\u003e` for custom render logic.\n3. **Pagination** — bind `\u003cQuickGrid Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e` plus a `\u003cPaginator State=\"@_pagination\"\u003e` component. Declare `PaginationState` in `@code`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003ePropertyColumn\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e","text":"`PropertyColumn` vs `TemplateColumn`"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePropertyColumn\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e\u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBinding\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eProperty=&quot;@(x =&gt; x.Field)&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFree-form render fragment using \u003ccode\u003e@context\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSortability\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSortable=&quot;true&quot;\u003c/code\u003e sorts by the bound expression automatically\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRequires \u003ccode\u003eSortBy=&quot;@someGridSort&quot;\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003eSortable\u003c/code\u003e alone does nothing\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUse when\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOne property, no custom markup\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCustom layout, multi-property display, computed value\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e&#39;s sort quirk trips people up. Without \u003ccode\u003eSortBy\u003c/code\u003e, the column header renders as plain text — no click, no arrow, no sort. The \u003ccode\u003eGridSort&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e object is built fluently:","text":"`TemplateColumn`'s sort quirk trips people up. Without `SortBy`, the column header renders as plain text — no click, no arrow, no sort. The `GridSort\u003cT\u003e` object is built fluently:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"private GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e _sortByName =\n    GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e.ByAscending(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\n                     .ThenAscending(s =\u003e s.LastName);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Multiple \u003ccode\u003e.ThenAscending\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e.ThenDescending\u003c/code\u003e calls chain to produce multi-key sort.","text":"Multiple `.ThenAscending` / `.ThenDescending` calls chain to produce multi-key sort."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Pagination","text":"Pagination"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ePaginationState\u003c/code\u003e tracks the current page and page size:","text":"`PaginationState` tracks the current page and page size:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 10 };"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e&lt;Paginator State=&quot;@_pagination&quot; /&gt;\u003c/code\u003e renders the first/prev/next/last controls and updates \u003ccode\u003eCurrentPageIndex\u003c/code\u003e when clicked. \u003ccode\u003eQuickGrid\u003c/code\u003e watches the state object and re-renders the right page&#39;s data.","text":"`\u003cPaginator State=\"@_pagination\" /\u003e` renders the first/prev/next/last controls and updates `CurrentPageIndex` when clicked. `QuickGrid` watches the state object and re-renders the right page's data."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Live filter with \u003ccode\u003eIQueryable\u003c/code\u003e","text":"Live filter with `IQueryable`"},{"kind":"p","html":"A text input that filters in real time is a few lines:","text":"A text input that filters in real time is a few lines:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"\u003cinput @bind=\"_filter\" @bind:event=\"oninput\" placeholder=\"Search...\" /\u003e\n\n\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@FilteredStudents\" Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\n@code {\n    private string _filter = string.Empty;\n\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e FilteredStudents =\u003e\n        string.IsNullOrEmpty(_filter)\n            ? _students\n            : _students.Where(s =\u003e\n                s.FirstName.Contains(_filter, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two mechanics matter:","text":"Two mechanics matter:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@bind:event=&quot;oninput&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — updates \u003ccode\u003e_filter\u003c/code\u003e on each keystroke. The default \u003ccode\u003e@bind\u003c/code\u003e listens for \u003ccode\u003eonchange\u003c/code\u003e, which fires only on focus loss — not what you want for live filtering.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eKeep the return type \u003ccode\u003eIQueryable&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Calling \u003ccode\u003e.ToList()\u003c/code\u003e pulls the whole set into memory and defeats EF Core&#39;s ability to translate the filter into a SQL \u003ccode\u003eWHERE\u003c/code\u003e clause.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **`@bind:event=\"oninput\"`** — updates `_filter` on each keystroke. The default `@bind` listens for `onchange`, which fires only on focus loss — not what you want for live filtering.\n2. **Keep the return type `IQueryable\u003cT\u003e`.** Calling `.ToList()` pulls the whole set into memory and defeats EF Core's ability to translate the filter into a SQL `WHERE` clause."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Render mode","text":"Render mode"},{"kind":"p","html":"QuickGrid is interactive — sorting, paging, filtering all trigger re-renders. The page hosting it must declare an interactive render mode:","text":"QuickGrid is interactive — sorting, paging, filtering all trigger re-renders. The page hosting it must declare an interactive render mode:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"@rendermode InteractiveServer"},{"kind":"p","html":"Or \u003ccode\u003eInteractiveWebAssembly\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eInteractiveAuto\u003c/code\u003e. A static-server-rendered page shows the initial grid but clicks on sort headers and pager buttons do nothing because the component has no runtime behind it.","text":"Or `InteractiveWebAssembly` / `InteractiveAuto`. A static-server-rendered page shows the initial grid but clicks on sort headers and pager buttons do nothing because the component has no runtime behind it."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your `\u003cTemplateColumn Title=\"City\" Sortable=\"true\"\u003e` renders correctly but the column header doesn't sort when clicked. Why, and what's the fix?","a":"`TemplateColumn` ignores `Sortable=\"true\"`. It needs an explicit `SortBy=\"@GridSort\u003cT\u003e.ByAscending(x =\u003e x.City)\"`. `PropertyColumn` supports `Sortable=\"true\"` because it already knows which property to sort by; `TemplateColumn` has no implicit sort key."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003ePagination-plus-filter combined on a student list:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e&lt;input @bind=&quot;_filter&quot; @bind:event=&quot;oninput&quot; placeholder=&quot;Filter...&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;QuickGrid Items=&quot;@Filtered&quot; Pagination=&quot;@_pagination&quot;&gt;\n    &lt;PropertyColumn Property=&quot;@(s =&gt; s.Id)&quot;        Sortable=&quot;true&quot; /&gt;\n    &lt;PropertyColumn Property=&quot;@(s =&gt; s.FirstName)&quot; Sortable=&quot;true&quot; /&gt;\n    &lt;PropertyColumn Property=&quot;@(s =&gt; s.LastName)&quot;  Sortable=&quot;true&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;/QuickGrid&gt;\n&lt;Paginator State=&quot;@_pagination&quot; /&gt;\n@code {\n    private IQueryable&lt;Student&gt; _students = Student.GetStudents();\n    private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };\n    private string _filter = &quot;&quot;;\n    private IQueryable&lt;Student&gt; Filtered =&gt;\n        string.IsNullOrEmpty(_filter)\n            ? _students\n            : _students.Where(s =&gt; s.LastName.Contains(_filter));\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTyping in the input filters every keystroke; the paginator always reflects the filtered count.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Pagination-plus-filter combined on a student list:\n```cs\n\u003cinput @bind=\"_filter\" @bind:event=\"oninput\" placeholder=\"Filter...\" /\u003e\n\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@Filtered\" Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.Id)\"        Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.LastName)\"  Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\u003cPaginator State=\"@_pagination\" /\u003e\n@code {\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e _students = Student.GetStudents();\n    private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };\n    private string _filter = \"\";\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e Filtered =\u003e\n        string.IsNullOrEmpty(_filter)\n            ? _students\n            : _students.Where(s =\u003e s.LastName.Contains(_filter));\n}\n```\nTyping in the input filters every keystroke; the paginator always reflects the filtered count."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003e@bind=&quot;_filter&quot;\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003e@bind:event=&quot;oninput&quot;\u003c/code\u003e on the filter input. The filter only updates when the input loses focus, so users type, see no change, and conclude the filter is broken. Always pair live-filter inputs with \u003ccode\u003e@bind:event=&quot;oninput&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Using `@bind=\"_filter\"` without `@bind:event=\"oninput\"` on the filter input. The filter only updates when the input loses focus, so users type, see no change, and conclude the filter is broken. Always pair live-filter inputs with `@bind:event=\"oninput\"`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eBind a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;QuickGrid Items=&quot;IQueryable&lt;T&gt;&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and declare a \u003ccode\u003ePaginationState\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e@code\u003c/code\u003e. Use \u003ccode\u003e&lt;PropertyColumn Property=&quot;...&quot; Sortable=&quot;true&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for simple columns and \u003ccode\u003e&lt;TemplateColumn Title=&quot;...&quot; SortBy=&quot;@gridSort&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for custom markup — \u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e needs \u003ccode\u003eSortBy\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003eSortable\u003c/code\u003e. A text input with \u003ccode\u003e@bind=&quot;_filter&quot; @bind:event=&quot;oninput&quot;\u003c/code\u003e plus a computed \u003ccode\u003eIQueryable\u003c/code\u003e property gives live filter. The hosting page must declare \u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveServer\u003c/code\u003e (or another interactive mode) for any of this to work.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Bind a `\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"IQueryable\u003cT\u003e\"\u003e` and declare a `PaginationState` in `@code`. Use `\u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"...\" Sortable=\"true\"\u003e` for simple columns and `\u003cTemplateColumn Title=\"...\" SortBy=\"@gridSort\"\u003e` for custom markup — `TemplateColumn` needs `SortBy`, not `Sortable`. A text input with `@bind=\"_filter\" @bind:event=\"oninput\"` plus a computed `IQueryable` property gives live filter. The hosting page must declare `@rendermode InteractiveServer` (or another interactive mode) for any of this to work."}]},{"n":27,"id":"file-based-app-basics","title":"File-based .NET apps — single .cs file, no csproj, `dotnet run file.cs`","hook":"Drop a `.cs` file, run it. No project, no build folder.","tags":["dotnet-10","scripting","file-based"],"module":".NET 10 Scripts & Reporting","source":"slides/file-based-apps.pptx; notes/file-based-apps.docx; research-file-based.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"One file, one command","text":"One file, one command"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e.NET 10\u003c/code\u003e lets you run a standalone \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e file without ever creating a \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e. Save this as \u003ccode\u003eHelloDevs.cs\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"`.NET 10` lets you run a standalone `.cs` file without ever creating a `.csproj`. Save this as `HelloDevs.cs`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"Console.WriteLine(\"Hello Devs\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"Then run:","text":"Then run:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"dotnet run HelloDevs.cs"},{"kind":"p","html":"The CLI detects the \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e argument, generates an implicit project context, compiles the file in memory, and executes it. Compilation artifacts are cached under \u003ccode\u003e~/.dotnet/runfile/\u003c/code\u003e (macOS / Linux) or \u003ccode\u003e%USERPROFILE%\\.dotnet\\runfile\\\u003c/code\u003e (Windows), keyed by file hash + content hash so subsequent runs are fast.","text":"The CLI detects the `.cs` argument, generates an implicit project context, compiles the file in memory, and executes it. Compilation artifacts are cached under `~/.dotnet/runfile/` (macOS / Linux) or `%USERPROFILE%\\.dotnet\\runfile\\` (Windows), keyed by file hash + content hash so subsequent runs are fast."},{"kind":"p","html":"No \u003ccode\u003ebin/\u003c/code\u003e, no \u003ccode\u003eobj/\u003c/code\u003e, no \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e. Just one file.","text":"No `bin/`, no `obj/`, no `.csproj`. Just one file."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Top-level statements + implicit usings","text":"Top-level statements + implicit usings"},{"kind":"p","html":"File-based apps skip the \u003ccode\u003eProgram\u003c/code\u003e class + \u003ccode\u003eMain\u003c/code\u003e ceremony. Code at file scope IS \u003ccode\u003eMain\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"File-based apps skip the `Program` class + `Main` ceremony. Code at file scope IS `Main`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"Console.WriteLine(args.Length \u003e 0 ? args[0] : \"World\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"Several namespaces are imported implicitly: \u003ccode\u003eSystem\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Collections.Generic\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Linq\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Text\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Threading.Tasks\u003c/code\u003e. You can write \u003ccode\u003eConsole.WriteLine\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;int&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, or \u003ccode\u003eforeach (var x in arr.Where(p))\u003c/code\u003e without any \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e directives.","text":"Several namespaces are imported implicitly: `System`, `System.Collections.Generic`, `System.Linq`, `System.Text`, `System.Threading.Tasks`. You can write `Console.WriteLine`, `List\u003cint\u003e`, or `foreach (var x in arr.Where(p))` without any `using` directives."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Command-line arguments","text":"Command-line arguments"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eargs\u003c/code\u003e is a regular \u003ccode\u003estring[]\u003c/code\u003e in scope at the top level:","text":"`args` is a regular `string[]` in scope at the top level:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// greet.cs\nvar name = args.Length \u003e 0 ? args[0] : \"World\";\nConsole.WriteLine($\"Hello, {name}!\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"Invoke with a \u003ccode\u003e--\u003c/code\u003e separator so the CLI knows which args belong to your script vs \u003ccode\u003edotnet run\u003c/code\u003e itself:","text":"Invoke with a `--` separator so the CLI knows which args belong to your script vs `dotnet run` itself:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"dotnet run greet.cs -- Kevin\n# → Hello, Kevin!"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e--\u003c/code\u003e is not optional when you pass arguments. Without it the CLI interprets your \u003ccode\u003eKevin\u003c/code\u003e as a flag to itself and you get &quot;Hello, World!&quot;.","text":"The `--` is not optional when you pass arguments. Without it the CLI interprets your `Kevin` as a flag to itself and you get \"Hello, World!\"."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When file-based apps are (and aren&#39;t) the right tool","text":"When file-based apps are (and aren't) the right tool"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRight fit:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Right fit:**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOne-off utilities — data massaging, log grepping, quick prototypes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTeaching examples — no project plumbing to distract from the concept.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eInline web APIs (see \u003ccode\u003efile-based-app-web\u003c/code\u003e lesson).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eScripts that need a NuGet package without ceremony (see \u003ccode\u003efile-based-app-directives\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- One-off utilities — data massaging, log grepping, quick prototypes.\n- Teaching examples — no project plumbing to distract from the concept.\n- Inline web APIs (see `file-based-app-web` lesson).\n- Scripts that need a NuGet package without ceremony (see `file-based-app-directives`)."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eWrong fit:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Wrong fit:**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMulti-file projects — no way to reference a sibling \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e from another \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e without converting to a project.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAnything that needs a full project structure (unit test suites, complex build steps, code analyzers).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLong-lived services where deployment tooling expects a \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Multi-file projects — no way to reference a sibling `.cs` from another `.cs` without converting to a project.\n- Anything that needs a full project structure (unit test suites, complex build steps, code analyzers).\n- Long-lived services where deployment tooling expects a `.csproj`."},{"kind":"p","html":"When the single-file approach outgrows its use case, convert to a traditional project:","text":"When the single-file approach outgrows its use case, convert to a traditional project:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"dotnet project convert HelloDevs.cs -o HelloDevsProject"},{"kind":"p","html":"The command creates a folder with the \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e, moves the \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e into it, and preserves any \u003ccode\u003e#:\u003c/code\u003e directives as the project&#39;s equivalent settings (see \u003ccode\u003efile-based-app-directives\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"The command creates a folder with the `.csproj`, moves the `.cs` into it, and preserves any `#:` directives as the project's equivalent settings (see `file-based-app-directives`)."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You run `dotnet run greet.cs Kevin` and see `Hello, World!` rather than `Hello, Kevin!`. What did you forget?","a":"The `--` separator. `dotnet run greet.cs Kevin` passes `Kevin` to `dotnet`, not to your script. The correct invocation is `dotnet run greet.cs -- Kevin` — everything after `--` becomes `args` inside your `.cs`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA three-line utility that reads stdin and prints line counts, with no project overhead:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e// count.cs\nvar lines = Console.In.ReadToEnd().Split(&#39;\\n&#39;);\nConsole.WriteLine($&quot;Lines: {lines.Length}&quot;);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRun: \u003ccode\u003ecat some-file.txt | dotnet run count.cs\u003c/code\u003e. No \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e, no \u003ccode\u003ebin/\u003c/code\u003e, no setup — the CLI caches the compiled binary under \u003ccode\u003e~/.dotnet/runfile/\u003c/code\u003e for subsequent invocations.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A three-line utility that reads stdin and prints line counts, with no project overhead:\n```cs\n// count.cs\nvar lines = Console.In.ReadToEnd().Split('\\n');\nConsole.WriteLine($\"Lines: {lines.Length}\");\n```\nRun: `cat some-file.txt | dotnet run count.cs`. No `.csproj`, no `bin/`, no setup — the CLI caches the compiled binary under `~/.dotnet/runfile/` for subsequent invocations."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e.NET versions before 10 do NOT fully support the file-based flow. On .NET 8 or 9, \u003ccode\u003edotnet run file.cs\u003c/code\u003e either errors or requires a different shim. The course targets .NET 10; verify with \u003ccode\u003edotnet --version\u003c/code\u003e if a script silently fails.\u003c/p\u003e","text":".NET versions before 10 do NOT fully support the file-based flow. On .NET 8 or 9, `dotnet run file.cs` either errors or requires a different shim. The course targets .NET 10; verify with `dotnet --version` if a script silently fails."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003edotnet run file.cs\u003c/code\u003e compiles and runs a single \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e file without a project. Top-level statements replace \u003ccode\u003eclass Program { static void Main }\u003c/code\u003e. Implicit usings cover \u003ccode\u003eSystem\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Linq\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Collections.Generic\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Text\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Threading.Tasks\u003c/code\u003e. Pass CLI args with \u003ccode\u003edotnet run file.cs -- arg1 arg2\u003c/code\u003e. Use \u003ccode\u003edotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder\u003c/code\u003e to graduate to a traditional project when single-file stops fitting.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`dotnet run file.cs` compiles and runs a single `.cs` file without a project. Top-level statements replace `class Program { static void Main }`. Implicit usings cover `System`, `System.Linq`, `System.Collections.Generic`, `System.Text`, and `System.Threading.Tasks`. Pass CLI args with `dotnet run file.cs -- arg1 arg2`. Use `dotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder` to graduate to a traditional project when single-file stops fitting."}]},{"n":28,"id":"file-based-app-directives","title":"File-based app `#:` directives — package, property, sdk, project","hook":"Four directives put NuGet, MSBuild, SDK, and project refs inline. No space after the colon.","tags":["dotnet-10","scripting","directives"],"module":".NET 10 Scripts & Reporting","source":"notes/file-based-apps.docx; research-file-based.md §2.4","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"The four \u003ccode\u003e#:\u003c/code\u003e directives","text":"The four `#:` directives"},{"kind":"p","html":"File-based apps declare build-time metadata through four directives. All four share the same shape: \u003ccode\u003e#:&lt;kind&gt; &lt;value&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — the \u003ccode\u003e#\u003c/code\u003e immediately followed by \u003ccode\u003e:\u003c/code\u003e followed immediately by the directive name, no space. A space after the colon is a syntax error and a common exam distractor.","text":"File-based apps declare build-time metadata through four directives. All four share the same shape: `#:\u003ckind\u003e \u003cvalue\u003e` — the `#` immediately followed by `:` followed immediately by the directive name, no space. A space after the colon is a syntax error and a common exam distractor."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDirective\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:package\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAdd a NuGet package dependency\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:property\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSet an MSBuild property (e.g. \u003ccode\u003eTargetFramework\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:sdk\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSwitch SDK (default is console; \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e for web APIs)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:project\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReference a local \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Directives go at the top of the file, above any \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e or code.","text":"Directives go at the top of the file, above any `using` or code."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e#:package\u003c/code\u003e","text":"`#:package`"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1\n\nusing Spectre.Console;\n\nvar table = new Table();\ntable.AddColumn(\"City\");\ntable.AddRow(\"New York\");\nAnsiConsole.Write(table);"},{"kind":"p","html":"Format: \u003ccode\u003e#:package &lt;PackageName&gt;@&lt;Version&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. The CLI downloads the package on first run, caches it under \u003ccode\u003e~/.dotnet/runfile/\u003c/code\u003e, and resolves references automatically. Subsequent runs use the cache.","text":"Format: `#:package \u003cPackageName\u003e@\u003cVersion\u003e`. The CLI downloads the package on first run, caches it under `~/.dotnet/runfile/`, and resolves references automatically. Subsequent runs use the cache."},{"kind":"p","html":"Omit the \u003ccode\u003e@version\u003c/code\u003e and you get the latest stable version — fine for quick exploration, risky for anything you want to reproduce weeks later.","text":"Omit the `@version` and you get the latest stable version — fine for quick exploration, risky for anything you want to reproduce weeks later."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e#:property\u003c/code\u003e","text":"`#:property`"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"#:property TargetFramework=net10.0\n#:property Nullable=enable\n#:property LangVersion=preview\n\nConsole.WriteLine($\"Running on: {Environment.Version}\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"Format: \u003ccode\u003e#:property &lt;Name&gt;=&lt;Value&gt;\u003c/code\u003e (the \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e matters; no spaces around it).","text":"Format: `#:property \u003cName\u003e=\u003cValue\u003e` (the `=` matters; no spaces around it)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Common properties:","text":"Common properties:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eTargetFramework=net10.0\u003c/code\u003e — pin the .NET version.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eNullable=enable\u003c/code\u003e — turn on nullable reference types.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eLangVersion=preview\u003c/code\u003e — allow not-yet-stabilized C# language features.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `TargetFramework=net10.0` — pin the .NET version.\n- `Nullable=enable` — turn on nullable reference types.\n- `LangVersion=preview` — allow not-yet-stabilized C# language features."},{"kind":"p","html":"You can stack multiple \u003ccode\u003e#:property\u003c/code\u003e lines.","text":"You can stack multiple `#:property` lines."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e#:sdk\u003c/code\u003e","text":"`#:sdk`"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\n#:package Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@10.0.0\n\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.Services.AddOpenApi();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapGet(\"/\", () =\u003e \"Hello from a file-based web app!\");\napp.Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Format: \u003ccode\u003e#:sdk &lt;SdkName&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Three SDKs matter for 4870:","text":"Format: `#:sdk \u003cSdkName\u003e`. Three SDKs matter for 4870:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.NET.Sdk\u003c/code\u003e — default console app (no directive needed).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e — ASP.NET Core / minimal APIs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.NET.Sdk.BlazorWebAssembly\u003c/code\u003e — Blazor WASM (out of scope but good to recognize).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `Microsoft.NET.Sdk` — default console app (no directive needed).\n- `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` — ASP.NET Core / minimal APIs.\n- `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.BlazorWebAssembly` — Blazor WASM (out of scope but good to recognize)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Without \u003ccode\u003e#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e, calls like \u003ccode\u003eWebApplication.CreateBuilder(args)\u003c/code\u003e fail to resolve because the default SDK doesn&#39;t include ASP.NET Core types.","text":"Without `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web`, calls like `WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args)` fail to resolve because the default SDK doesn't include ASP.NET Core types."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e#:project\u003c/code\u003e","text":"`#:project`"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"#:project ./MyLibrary/MyLibrary.csproj\n\nusing MyLibrary;\n\nvar person = new Person { FirstName = \"John\", LastName = \"Doe\" };\nConsole.WriteLine($\"{person.FirstName} {person.LastName}\");"},{"kind":"p","html":"Format: \u003ccode\u003e#:project &lt;relative-path-to-.csproj&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Adds a project reference — the file-based script can now use types from \u003ccode\u003eMyLibrary\u003c/code\u003e. Useful when you have a shared library project and want a one-off script that consumes it.","text":"Format: `#:project \u003crelative-path-to-.csproj\u003e`. Adds a project reference — the file-based script can now use types from `MyLibrary`. Useful when you have a shared library project and want a one-off script that consumes it."},{"kind":"p","html":"The reverse (a \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e referencing a file-based \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e) is not supported — file-based apps cannot be consumed as dependencies. Convert them to projects first with \u003ccode\u003edotnet project convert\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The reverse (a `.csproj` referencing a file-based `.cs`) is not supported — file-based apps cannot be consumed as dependencies. Convert them to projects first with `dotnet project convert`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A classmate's `app.cs` has `#: package Spectre.Console@0.49.1` at the top. The script fails with a parser error on that line. What's the fix?","a":"Remove the space after the colon. The correct form is `#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1` — `#:` + directive name with nothing between them. The spaced form is a classic exam distractor and not a legal syntax."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA full minimal web API in one file, using three directives stacked:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\n#:package Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@10.0.0\n#:property Nullable=enable\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.Services.AddOpenApi();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapOpenApi();\napp.MapGet(&quot;/&quot;, () =&gt; &quot;Hello file-based web!&quot;);\napp.Run();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRun with \u003ccode\u003edotnet run api.cs\u003c/code\u003e. The SDK swap turns a console script into an ASP.NET Core web host.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A full minimal web API in one file, using three directives stacked:\n```cs\n#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\n#:package Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@10.0.0\n#:property Nullable=enable\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.Services.AddOpenApi();\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapOpenApi();\napp.MapGet(\"/\", () =\u003e \"Hello file-based web!\");\napp.Run();\n```\nRun with `dotnet run api.cs`. The SDK swap turns a console script into an ASP.NET Core web host."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:package\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e#:property\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e#:sdk\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e#:project\u003c/code\u003e are all case-sensitive and have NO space after the colon. Writing \u003ccode\u003e#: package\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e#:Package\u003c/code\u003e, or \u003ccode\u003e#: sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e all fail. Each \u003ccode\u003e#:\u003c/code\u003e directive must sit on its own line — you cannot combine two directives on one line with a separator.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`#:package`, `#:property`, `#:sdk`, `#:project` are all case-sensitive and have NO space after the colon. Writing `#: package`, `#:Package`, or `#: sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` all fail. Each `#:` directive must sit on its own line — you cannot combine two directives on one line with a separator."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eFour directives drive file-based-app build metadata: \u003ccode\u003e#:package PackageName@version\u003c/code\u003e for NuGet, \u003ccode\u003e#:property Name=Value\u003c/code\u003e for MSBuild properties, \u003ccode\u003e#:sdk SdkName\u003c/code\u003e for SDK selection, \u003ccode\u003e#:project ./Path/To.csproj\u003c/code\u003e for project references. No space after \u003ccode\u003e#:\u003c/code\u003e. Stack as many as you need at the top of the file — the CLI parses them before compilation.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Four directives drive file-based-app build metadata: `#:package PackageName@version` for NuGet, `#:property Name=Value` for MSBuild properties, `#:sdk SdkName` for SDK selection, `#:project ./Path/To.csproj` for project references. No space after `#:`. Stack as many as you need at the top of the file — the CLI parses them before compilation."}]},{"n":29,"id":"file-based-app-web","title":"File-based web apps — `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` plus minimal API","hook":"Swap the SDK, add one line of ASP.NET Core, run.","tags":["dotnet-10","scripting","web","minimal-api"],"module":".NET 10 Scripts & Reporting","source":"notes/file-based-apps.docx; research-file-based.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"A web API in one \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e file","text":"A web API in one `.cs` file"},{"kind":"p","html":"The default file-based-app SDK (\u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.NET.Sdk\u003c/code\u003e) produces a console app. ASP.NET Core types like \u003ccode\u003eWebApplication\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eWebApplicationBuilder\u003c/code\u003e live in the web SDK, so you swap the SDK with \u003ccode\u003e#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"The default file-based-app SDK (`Microsoft.NET.Sdk`) produces a console app. ASP.NET Core types like `WebApplication` and `WebApplicationBuilder` live in the web SDK, so you swap the SDK with `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\n\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nvar app = builder.Build();\n\napp.MapGet(\"/\", () =\u003e \"Hello from a file-based web API\");\napp.MapGet(\"/time\", () =\u003e new { now = DateTime.UtcNow });\n\napp.Run();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Save as \u003ccode\u003eapi.cs\u003c/code\u003e, then:","text":"Save as `api.cs`, then:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"dotnet run api.cs"},{"kind":"p","html":"The CLI picks up the \u003ccode\u003e#:sdk\u003c/code\u003e directive, installs the web SDK behind the scenes, compiles the file, and runs the app on a dev port (typically \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:5000\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003ehttps://localhost:5001\u003c/code\u003e). Two endpoints, zero project files.","text":"The CLI picks up the `#:sdk` directive, installs the web SDK behind the scenes, compiles the file, and runs the app on a dev port (typically `http://localhost:5000` / `https://localhost:5001`). Two endpoints, zero project files."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Adding packages on top","text":"Adding packages on top"},{"kind":"p","html":"Most real web APIs pull in a few NuGet packages. Stack them with \u003ccode\u003e#:package\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Most real web APIs pull in a few NuGet packages. Stack them with `#:package`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\n#:package Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@10.0.0\n#:package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.InMemory@10.0.0\n\nusing Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;\n\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nbuilder.Services.AddDbContext\u003cAppDb\u003e(opts =\u003e opts.UseInMemoryDatabase(\"demo\"));\nbuilder.Services.AddOpenApi();\n\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapOpenApi();\napp.MapGet(\"/widgets\", (AppDb db) =\u003e db.Widgets.ToList());\n\napp.Run();\n\nclass AppDb(DbContextOptions\u003cAppDb\u003e opts) : DbContext(opts)\n{\n    public DbSet\u003cWidget\u003e Widgets =\u003e Set\u003cWidget\u003e();\n}\nrecord Widget(int Id, string Name);"},{"kind":"p","html":"The file now includes OpenAPI docs, an in-memory EF Core DbContext, a \u003ccode\u003eGET /widgets\u003c/code\u003e endpoint, and a couple of nested types (\u003ccode\u003eAppDb\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eWidget\u003c/code\u003e). Still one file.","text":"The file now includes OpenAPI docs, an in-memory EF Core DbContext, a `GET /widgets` endpoint, and a couple of nested types (`AppDb`, `Widget`). Still one file."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When to graduate to a project","text":"When to graduate to a project"},{"kind":"p","html":"Single-file web apps stop fitting as soon as you want:","text":"Single-file web apps stop fitting as soon as you want:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMultiple physical files (separate controllers, services).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA test project that references it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDeployment pipelines that expect a \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eContainer images with structured layer caching.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Multiple physical files (separate controllers, services).\n- A test project that references it.\n- Deployment pipelines that expect a `.csproj`.\n- Container images with structured layer caching."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003edotnet project convert api.cs -o ApiProject\u003c/code\u003e creates a proper ASP.NET Core project, moves the \u003ccode\u003e.cs\u003c/code\u003e content into \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e, and preserves each \u003ccode\u003e#:\u003c/code\u003e directive as the right MSBuild equivalent (\u003ccode\u003e&lt;Sdk&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&lt;PackageReference&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&lt;PropertyGroup&gt;\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"`dotnet project convert api.cs -o ApiProject` creates a proper ASP.NET Core project, moves the `.cs` content into `Program.cs`, and preserves each `#:` directive as the right MSBuild equivalent (`\u003cSdk\u003e`, `\u003cPackageReference\u003e`, `\u003cPropertyGroup\u003e`)."},{"kind":"p","html":"The file-based form earns its keep for demos, one-off utilities, and exploratory hacking. Anything destined for production should be a real project from the start.","text":"The file-based form earns its keep for demos, one-off utilities, and exploratory hacking. Anything destined for production should be a real project from the start."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You have `var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);` at the top of `api.cs` but `dotnet run api.cs` fails with `The name 'WebApplication' does not exist in the current context`. What's missing?","a":"`#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` — the first line. The default console SDK doesn't include ASP.NET Core types. Swapping to the web SDK pulls `WebApplication`, routing, middleware, and everything else into the implicit references."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA 10-line REST API exposing an in-memory cart:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\nvar cart = new List&lt;string&gt;();\nvar app = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build();\napp.MapGet(&quot;/cart&quot;,            () =&gt; cart);\napp.MapPost(&quot;/cart/{item}&quot;,    (string item) =&gt; { cart.Add(item); return Results.Ok(cart); });\napp.MapDelete(&quot;/cart&quot;,         () =&gt; { cart.Clear(); return Results.NoContent(); });\napp.Run();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRun with \u003ccode\u003edotnet run cart.cs\u003c/code\u003e. Add a fourth \u003ccode\u003eMapPut\u003c/code\u003e if you want to replace items. Every endpoint is a lambda; routing, JSON serialization, and DI all work out of the box because \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e wires them in.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A 10-line REST API exposing an in-memory cart:\n```cs\n#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\nvar cart = new List\u003cstring\u003e();\nvar app = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build();\napp.MapGet(\"/cart\",            () =\u003e cart);\napp.MapPost(\"/cart/{item}\",    (string item) =\u003e { cart.Add(item); return Results.Ok(cart); });\napp.MapDelete(\"/cart\",         () =\u003e { cart.Clear(); return Results.NoContent(); });\napp.Run();\n```\nRun with `dotnet run cart.cs`. Add a fourth `MapPut` if you want to replace items. Every endpoint is a lambda; routing, JSON serialization, and DI all work out of the box because `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` wires them in."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eForgetting \u003ccode\u003e#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e while trying to call \u003ccode\u003eWebApplication.CreateBuilder\u003c/code\u003e. The error message is compiler-level (&quot;type or namespace &#39;WebApplication&#39; not found&quot;) rather than runtime, so it&#39;s easy to assume a wrong \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e — but \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e alone can&#39;t import types that aren&#39;t in the referenced SDK.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Forgetting `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` while trying to call `WebApplication.CreateBuilder`. The error message is compiler-level (\"type or namespace 'WebApplication' not found\") rather than runtime, so it's easy to assume a wrong `using` — but `using` alone can't import types that aren't in the referenced SDK."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e switches a file-based app from console mode to ASP.NET Core. After that, \u003ccode\u003eWebApplication.CreateBuilder(args)\u003c/code\u003e plus \u003ccode\u003eapp.MapGet/Post/Put/Delete(...)\u003c/code\u003e produces a full minimal-API web server from one file. Stack \u003ccode\u003e#:package\u003c/code\u003e directives for additional NuGet dependencies (OpenAPI, EF Core, etc.). Graduate to a real project with \u003ccode\u003edotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder\u003c/code\u003e when the single-file model stops fitting.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` switches a file-based app from console mode to ASP.NET Core. After that, `WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args)` plus `app.MapGet/Post/Put/Delete(...)` produces a full minimal-API web server from one file. Stack `#:package` directives for additional NuGet dependencies (OpenAPI, EF Core, etc.). Graduate to a real project with `dotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder` when the single-file model stops fitting."}]},{"n":30,"id":"excel-export","title":"Excel export with ClosedXML — 1-based cells, FileResult, XLSX MIME","hook":"New workbook, add a worksheet, fill cells, save to MemoryStream, return as FileResult.","tags":["excel","closedxml","report"],"module":".NET 10 Scripts & Reporting","source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/; research-excel-pdf-chart.md §3","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Five steps to an \u003ccode\u003e.xlsx\u003c/code\u003e download","text":"Five steps to an `.xlsx` download"},{"kind":"p","html":"Given the NuGet package \u003ccode\u003eClosedXML\u003c/code\u003e (v0.105.0 in the course solution), a Razor Page handler can emit an Excel file in about 20 lines:","text":"Given the NuGet package `ClosedXML` (v0.105.0 in the course solution), a Razor Page handler can emit an Excel file in about 20 lines:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using ClosedXML.Excel;\nusing System.IO;\n\npublic FileResult OnGet()\n{\n    var games = Game.GetGames();\n\n    using var workbook = new XLWorkbook();\n    IXLWorksheet sheet  = workbook.Worksheets.Add(\"Games\");\n\n    // 1. Headers\n    sheet.Cell(1, 1).Value = \"Game ID\";\n    sheet.Cell(1, 2).Value = \"Year\";\n    sheet.Cell(1, 3).Value = \"Continent\";\n\n    // 2. Header styling\n    IXLRange header = sheet.Range(sheet.Cell(1, 1).Address, sheet.Cell(1, 3).Address);\n    header.Style.Fill.SetBackgroundColor(XLColor.Almond);\n    header.Style.Font.Bold = true;\n\n    // 3. Data rows\n    int row = 1;\n    foreach (var g in games)\n    {\n        row++;\n        sheet.Cell(row, 1).Value = g.GameId;\n        sheet.Cell(row, 2).Value = g.Year;\n        sheet.Cell(row, 3).Value = g.Continent;\n    }\n\n    // 4. Write to a MemoryStream\n    using var stream = new MemoryStream();\n    workbook.SaveAs(stream);\n    var bytes = stream.ToArray();\n\n    // 5. Return as FileResult\n    return File(\n        bytes,\n        \"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet\",\n        $\"Games_{DateTime.Now:yyyyMMdd}.xlsx\");\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Five moving parts:","text":"Five moving parts:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eXLWorkbook()\u003c/code\u003e creates an in-memory workbook. \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e disposes it after.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eWorksheets.Add(&quot;Games&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e adds a named sheet.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCell(row, col)\u003c/code\u003e is \u003cstrong\u003e1-based\u003c/strong\u003e, not 0-based — \u003ccode\u003eCell(1, 1)\u003c/code\u003e is the top-left cell. \u003ccode\u003eRange(cellA, cellB)\u003c/code\u003e selects rectangular regions for bulk styling.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSaveAs(stream)\u003c/code\u003e writes the workbook into a \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003estream.ToArray()\u003c/code\u003e gives the byte array.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eFile(bytes, mimeType, filename)\u003c/code\u003e returns a \u003ccode\u003eFileResult\u003c/code\u003e — ASP.NET Core serves the file as a download with the supplied filename.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. `XLWorkbook()` creates an in-memory workbook. `using` disposes it after.\n2. `Worksheets.Add(\"Games\")` adds a named sheet.\n3. `Cell(row, col)` is **1-based**, not 0-based — `Cell(1, 1)` is the top-left cell. `Range(cellA, cellB)` selects rectangular regions for bulk styling.\n4. `SaveAs(stream)` writes the workbook into a `MemoryStream`; `stream.ToArray()` gives the byte array.\n5. `File(bytes, mimeType, filename)` returns a `FileResult` — ASP.NET Core serves the file as a download with the supplied filename."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The MIME type matters","text":"The MIME type matters"},{"kind":"p","html":"Excel&#39;s MIME type is a mouthful: \u003ccode\u003eapplication/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet\u003c/code\u003e. Getting this wrong — e.g. \u003ccode\u003eapplication/excel\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eapplication/vnd.ms-excel\u003c/code\u003e (which is the old \u003ccode\u003e.xls\u003c/code\u003e binary format) — confuses browsers, which may either download without an extension or open the wrong app. Stick with the exact OpenXML string.","text":"Excel's MIME type is a mouthful: `application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet`. Getting this wrong — e.g. `application/excel` or `application/vnd.ms-excel` (which is the old `.xls` binary format) — confuses browsers, which may either download without an extension or open the wrong app. Stick with the exact OpenXML string."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Styling the output","text":"Styling the output"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eClosedXML\u003c/code\u003e exposes the full Excel styling model through fluent setters:","text":"`ClosedXML` exposes the full Excel styling model through fluent setters:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"sheet.Cell(1, 1).Style.Fill.BackgroundColor = XLColor.Almond;\nsheet.Cell(1, 1).Style.Font.Bold = true;\nsheet.Cell(1, 1).Style.Alignment.Horizontal = XLAlignmentHorizontalValues.Center;\n\nsheet.Columns().AdjustToContents();  // auto-fit column widths"},{"kind":"p","html":"Autofit is common for exported reports so users don&#39;t land on a sheet whose columns are all 8 characters wide. Call after filling data, before saving.","text":"Autofit is common for exported reports so users don't land on a sheet whose columns are all 8 characters wide. Call after filling data, before saving."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Row-and-column mental model","text":"Row-and-column mental model"},{"kind":"p","html":"ClosedXML&#39;s 1-based indexing matches how Excel&#39;s UI labels cells. \u003ccode\u003eCell(5, 3)\u003c/code\u003e is row 5 column 3 — displayed as \u003ccode\u003eC5\u003c/code\u003e in Excel. When you&#39;re used to \u003ccode\u003eint[,]\u003c/code\u003e in C# where \u003ccode\u003earr[0, 0]\u003c/code\u003e is the first element, flipping to 1-based causes subtle off-by-one bugs. A safe pattern: start your data loop at \u003ccode\u003erow = 1\u003c/code\u003e and pre-increment with \u003ccode\u003erow++\u003c/code\u003e before each data write, so row 2 is the first data row (row 1 is headers).","text":"ClosedXML's 1-based indexing matches how Excel's UI labels cells. `Cell(5, 3)` is row 5 column 3 — displayed as `C5` in Excel. When you're used to `int[,]` in C# where `arr[0, 0]` is the first element, flipping to 1-based causes subtle off-by-one bugs. A safe pattern: start your data loop at `row = 1` and pre-increment with `row++` before each data write, so row 2 is the first data row (row 1 is headers)."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Users report that downloaded Excel files sometimes have a trailing blank row, and the totals formula breaks when they add rows. Looking at your handler, you see `for (int i = 0; i \u003c games.Count; i++) sheet.Cell(i, 1).Value = games[i].Name;`. What is wrong?","a":"The loop starts at `i = 0`, but ClosedXML cells are 1-based — `sheet.Cell(0, 1)` is invalid or silently skipped. The first actual write lands in row 1, overwriting the headers. Start the loop at `i = 1` and write to `sheet.Cell(i + 1, 1)`, or pre-increment a separate `row` counter starting at 1 (for the header) and incrementing before each data write."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA minimal export handler that just dumps a \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;Player&gt;\u003c/code\u003e to Excel:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003epublic FileResult OnGet()\n{\n    using var wb = new XLWorkbook();\n    var sheet = wb.Worksheets.Add(&quot;Players&quot;);\n    sheet.Cell(1, 1).Value = &quot;Name&quot;;\n    sheet.Cell(1, 2).Value = &quot;Score&quot;;\n    int row = 2;\n    foreach (var p in Player.All())\n    {\n        sheet.Cell(row, 1).Value = p.Name;\n        sheet.Cell(row, 2).Value = p.Score;\n        row++;\n    }\n    using var ms = new MemoryStream();\n    wb.SaveAs(ms);\n    return File(ms.ToArray(),\n                &quot;application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet&quot;,\n                &quot;players.xlsx&quot;);\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e15 lines, including styling-free data dump. Add \u003ccode\u003esheet.Columns().AdjustToContents()\u003c/code\u003e before \u003ccode\u003eSaveAs\u003c/code\u003e to auto-fit columns.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A minimal export handler that just dumps a `List\u003cPlayer\u003e` to Excel:\n```cs\npublic FileResult OnGet()\n{\n    using var wb = new XLWorkbook();\n    var sheet = wb.Worksheets.Add(\"Players\");\n    sheet.Cell(1, 1).Value = \"Name\";\n    sheet.Cell(1, 2).Value = \"Score\";\n    int row = 2;\n    foreach (var p in Player.All())\n    {\n        sheet.Cell(row, 1).Value = p.Name;\n        sheet.Cell(row, 2).Value = p.Score;\n        row++;\n    }\n    using var ms = new MemoryStream();\n    wb.SaveAs(ms);\n    return File(ms.ToArray(),\n                \"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet\",\n                \"players.xlsx\");\n}\n```\n15 lines, including styling-free data dump. Add `sheet.Columns().AdjustToContents()` before `SaveAs` to auto-fit columns."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eTreating \u003ccode\u003eCell(row, col)\u003c/code\u003e as 0-based like C# arrays. Excel and ClosedXML both use 1-based indexing — \u003ccode\u003eCell(1, 1)\u003c/code\u003e is A1. Writing to \u003ccode\u003eCell(0, 0)\u003c/code\u003e either throws or silently targets an invalid address. If your first data row is row 2 (because row 1 is headers), your loop counter starts at 2, not 0 or 1.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Treating `Cell(row, col)` as 0-based like C# arrays. Excel and ClosedXML both use 1-based indexing — `Cell(1, 1)` is A1. Writing to `Cell(0, 0)` either throws or silently targets an invalid address. If your first data row is row 2 (because row 1 is headers), your loop counter starts at 2, not 0 or 1."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eInstall \u003ccode\u003eClosedXML\u003c/code\u003e, open an \u003ccode\u003eXLWorkbook()\u003c/code\u003e inside a \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e, add a named worksheet, fill cells with 1-based indexing, save to a \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e, and return \u003ccode\u003eFile(bytes, &quot;application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet&quot;, &quot;name.xlsx&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e. Use \u003ccode\u003eRange(start, end).Style\u003c/code\u003e for bulk styling and \u003ccode\u003eColumns().AdjustToContents()\u003c/code\u003e to auto-fit column widths before saving.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Install `ClosedXML`, open an `XLWorkbook()` inside a `using`, add a named worksheet, fill cells with 1-based indexing, save to a `MemoryStream`, and return `File(bytes, \"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet\", \"name.xlsx\")`. Use `Range(start, end).Style` for bulk styling and `Columns().AdjustToContents()` to auto-fit column widths before saving."}]},{"n":31,"id":"pdf-export","title":"PDF export with iText 7 — PdfWriter → PdfDocument → Document, FileStreamResult","hook":"Two NuGet packages, four constructors, one rule: reset MemoryStream.Position before returning.","tags":["pdf","itext7","report"],"module":".NET 10 Scripts & Reporting","source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/; research-excel-pdf-chart.md §3","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Two packages, not one","text":"Two packages, not one"},{"kind":"p","html":"iText 7 generates PDFs but does not ship a full crypto stack on its own. You need both packages:","text":"iText 7 generates PDFs but does not ship a full crypto stack on its own. You need both packages:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"xml","code":"\u003cPackageReference Include=\"itext7\" Version=\"9.6.0\" /\u003e\n\u003cPackageReference Include=\"itext.bouncy-castle-adapter\" Version=\"9.6.0\" /\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Forgetting the \u003ccode\u003ebouncy-castle-adapter\u003c/code\u003e produces a runtime \u003ccode\u003eNoClassDefFound\u003c/code\u003e-style error the first time iText tries to sign or hash anything — not a build error, so the mistake sneaks through local dev. Add both packages from day one.","text":"Forgetting the `bouncy-castle-adapter` produces a runtime `NoClassDefFound`-style error the first time iText tries to sign or hash anything — not a build error, so the mistake sneaks through local dev. Add both packages from day one."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Four constructors in order","text":"Four constructors in order"},{"kind":"p","html":"The iText 7 pipeline stacks four types, each wrapping the previous one:","text":"The iText 7 pipeline stacks four types, each wrapping the previous one:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using iText.Kernel.Pdf;\nusing iText.Layout;\nusing iText.Layout.Element;\nusing iText.Kernel.Geom;\nusing iText.Kernel.Colors;\n\npublic async Task\u003cIActionResult\u003e OnGet()\n{\n    var ms = new MemoryStream();\n\n    var writer   = new PdfWriter(ms);                   // stream sink\n    var pdfDoc   = new PdfDocument(writer);              // PDF structure\n    var document = new Document(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false);  // layout engine\n\n    writer.SetCloseStream(false);                        // keep MemoryStream open\n\n    // ...add content...\n\n    document.Close();\n    ms.Position = 0;                                      // CRITICAL: rewind before returning\n\n    return new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\")\n    {\n        FileDownloadName = $\"Report_{DateTime.Now:yyyyMMdd}.pdf\"\n    };\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each layer does one job:","text":"Each layer does one job:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePdfWriter\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — writes bytes to a stream (often a \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePdfDocument\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — PDF file structure (pages, cross-reference table, metadata).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDocument\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — high-level layout (paragraphs, tables, line separators).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eSetCloseStream(false)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — tells \u003ccode\u003ePdfWriter\u003c/code\u003e not to close the \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e when \u003ccode\u003edocument.Close()\u003c/code\u003e runs. You need the stream to stay open so you can return it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **`PdfWriter`** — writes bytes to a stream (often a `MemoryStream`).\n- **`PdfDocument`** — PDF file structure (pages, cross-reference table, metadata).\n- **`Document`** — high-level layout (paragraphs, tables, line separators).\n- **`SetCloseStream(false)`** — tells `PdfWriter` not to close the `MemoryStream` when `document.Close()` runs. You need the stream to stay open so you can return it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Adding content","text":"Adding content"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eDocument.Add(...)\u003c/code\u003e accepts any \u003ccode\u003eIBlockElement\u003c/code\u003e. The most common ones:","text":"`Document.Add(...)` accepts any `IBlockElement`. The most common ones:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"document.Add(new Paragraph(\"Report Title\")\n    .SetTextAlignment(iText.Layout.Properties.TextAlignment.CENTER)\n    .SetFontSize(20));\n\ndocument.Add(new LineSeparator(new SolidLine()));\n\nvar table = new Table(3);\ntable.AddCell(new Cell(1, 1)\n    .SetBackgroundColor(ColorConstants.LIGHT_GRAY)\n    .Add(new Paragraph(\"Column 1\")));\n// ... data rows ...\ndocument.Add(table);"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eTable(3)\u003c/code\u003e is a three-column table; each \u003ccode\u003eAddCell\u003c/code\u003e fills the next cell left-to-right, wrapping to a new row when the row fills up.","text":"`Table(3)` is a three-column table; each `AddCell` fills the next cell left-to-right, wrapping to a new row when the row fills up."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Page numbers","text":"Page numbers"},{"kind":"p","html":"Add page numbers after content is laid out, because you need to know how many pages the PDF has:","text":"Add page numbers after content is laid out, because you need to know how many pages the PDF has:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"int total = pdfDoc.GetNumberOfPages();\nfor (int i = 1; i \u003c= total; i++)\n{\n    document.ShowTextAligned(\n        new Paragraph($\"Page {i} of {total}\"),\n        559, 806, i,\n        iText.Layout.Properties.TextAlignment.RIGHT,\n        iText.Layout.Properties.VerticalAlignment.TOP,\n        0);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The magic numbers \u003ccode\u003e559, 806\u003c/code\u003e are X/Y coordinates in points on an A4 page (595 × 842 points). \u003ccode\u003e559, 806\u003c/code\u003e lands the text near the top-right corner. Adjust if your page size or margins differ.","text":"The magic numbers `559, 806` are X/Y coordinates in points on an A4 page (595 × 842 points). `559, 806` lands the text near the top-right corner. Adjust if your page size or margins differ."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream.Position = 0\u003c/code\u003e trap","text":"The `MemoryStream.Position = 0` trap"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ePdfWriter\u003c/code\u003e writes bytes into the \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e, advancing its position to the end. If you return the stream as-is to \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e, ASP.NET Core reads from the current position to the end — which is empty. The client downloads a zero-byte file.","text":"`PdfWriter` writes bytes into the `MemoryStream`, advancing its position to the end. If you return the stream as-is to `FileStreamResult`, ASP.NET Core reads from the current position to the end — which is empty. The client downloads a zero-byte file."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eAlways set \u003ccode\u003ems.Position = 0\u003c/code\u003e before returning.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e then reads from the beginning.","text":"**Always set `ms.Position = 0` before returning.** `FileStreamResult` then reads from the beginning."},{"kind":"p","html":"An alternative: skip \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e and use \u003ccode\u003eFile(ms.ToArray(), &quot;application/pdf&quot;, &quot;name.pdf&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e.ToArray()\u003c/code\u003e materializes the stream and the position is irrelevant. For large PDFs the stream form saves memory; for small ones either works.","text":"An alternative: skip `FileStreamResult` and use `File(ms.ToArray(), \"application/pdf\", \"name.pdf\")`. `.ToArray()` materializes the stream and the position is irrelevant. For large PDFs the stream form saves memory; for small ones either works."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your handler compiles, runs, and returns a `.pdf` file. Users open it and see a zero-byte file (\"document is empty or corrupted\"). The handler is correct up to `new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\")`. What's missing?","a":"`ms.Position = 0` before constructing the `FileStreamResult`. After writing, the MemoryStream's position is at the end — `FileStreamResult` reads from current position, finds zero bytes, delivers an empty file. Rewinding fixes it. Alternatively, use `File(ms.ToArray(), \"application/pdf\", \"name.pdf\")` which is position-insensitive."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eMinimal PDF export with one title + one table:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003epublic IActionResult OnGet()\n{\n    var ms = new MemoryStream();\n    var writer = new PdfWriter(ms);\n    var doc    = new Document(new PdfDocument(writer), PageSize.A4, false);\n    writer.SetCloseStream(false);\n    doc.Add(new Paragraph(&quot;Players&quot;)\n        .SetTextAlignment(iText.Layout.Properties.TextAlignment.CENTER)\n        .SetFontSize(18));\n    var table = new Table(2);\n    table.AddCell(&quot;Name&quot;).AddCell(&quot;Score&quot;);\n    foreach (var p in Player.All())\n    {\n        table.AddCell(p.Name);\n        table.AddCell(p.Score.ToString());\n    }\n    doc.Add(table);\n    doc.Close();\n    ms.Position = 0;\n    return new FileStreamResult(ms, &quot;application/pdf&quot;)\n    {\n        FileDownloadName = &quot;players.pdf&quot;\n    };\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eEvery layer is present: MemoryStream → PdfWriter → PdfDocument → Document → add elements → close → rewind → return.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Minimal PDF export with one title + one table:\n```cs\npublic IActionResult OnGet()\n{\n    var ms = new MemoryStream();\n    var writer = new PdfWriter(ms);\n    var doc    = new Document(new PdfDocument(writer), PageSize.A4, false);\n    writer.SetCloseStream(false);\n    doc.Add(new Paragraph(\"Players\")\n        .SetTextAlignment(iText.Layout.Properties.TextAlignment.CENTER)\n        .SetFontSize(18));\n    var table = new Table(2);\n    table.AddCell(\"Name\").AddCell(\"Score\");\n    foreach (var p in Player.All())\n    {\n        table.AddCell(p.Name);\n        table.AddCell(p.Score.ToString());\n    }\n    doc.Add(table);\n    doc.Close();\n    ms.Position = 0;\n    return new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\")\n    {\n        FileDownloadName = \"players.pdf\"\n    };\n}\n```\nEvery layer is present: MemoryStream → PdfWriter → PdfDocument → Document → add elements → close → rewind → return."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eInstalling only \u003ccode\u003eitext7\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003eitext.bouncy-castle-adapter\u003c/code\u003e. The project compiles fine. Runtime crashes when iText tries to hash or sign — typically while embedding fonts or producing encrypted output. Add both packages together; don&#39;t wait for the first crash to notice.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Installing only `itext7` without `itext.bouncy-castle-adapter`. The project compiles fine. Runtime crashes when iText tries to hash or sign — typically while embedding fonts or producing encrypted output. Add both packages together; don't wait for the first crash to notice."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eInstall both \u003ccode\u003eitext7\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eitext.bouncy-castle-adapter\u003c/code\u003e. Build a \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e, wrap it in \u003ccode\u003ePdfWriter\u003c/code\u003e, wrap that in \u003ccode\u003ePdfDocument\u003c/code\u003e, wrap that in \u003ccode\u003eDocument(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false)\u003c/code\u003e, and call \u003ccode\u003ewriter.SetCloseStream(false)\u003c/code\u003e. Add content with \u003ccode\u003eDocument.Add(new Paragraph(...))\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eDocument.Add(new Table(cols))\u003c/code\u003e. Add page numbers in a post-layout loop using \u003ccode\u003epdfDoc.GetNumberOfPages()\u003c/code\u003e. Call \u003ccode\u003edocument.Close()\u003c/code\u003e, then \u003ccode\u003ems.Position = 0\u003c/code\u003e, then return \u003ccode\u003enew FileStreamResult(ms, &quot;application/pdf&quot;) { FileDownloadName = &quot;name.pdf&quot; }\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Install both `itext7` and `itext.bouncy-castle-adapter`. Build a `MemoryStream`, wrap it in `PdfWriter`, wrap that in `PdfDocument`, wrap that in `Document(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false)`, and call `writer.SetCloseStream(false)`. Add content with `Document.Add(new Paragraph(...))` and `Document.Add(new Table(cols))`. Add page numbers in a post-layout loop using `pdfDoc.GetNumberOfPages()`. Call `document.Close()`, then `ms.Position = 0`, then return `new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\") { FileDownloadName = \"name.pdf\" }`."}]},{"n":32,"id":"chart-rendering","title":"Chart.js in Razor — CDN script, Razor data injection, pie chart config","hook":"Server computes the data; Razor writes it into JS arrays; Chart.js renders on the canvas.","tags":["chart","chart-js","razor"],"module":".NET 10 Scripts & Reporting","source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/; research-excel-pdf-chart.md §3","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Chart.js renders client-side","text":"Chart.js renders client-side"},{"kind":"p","html":"Unlike Excel and PDF exports, chart rendering happens in the browser. The server computes the numbers, Razor writes them into a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script&gt;\u003c/code\u003e block, and Chart.js draws on a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;canvas&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Unlike Excel and PDF exports, chart rendering happens in the browser. The server computes the numbers, Razor writes them into a `\u003cscript\u003e` block, and Chart.js draws on a `\u003ccanvas\u003e`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Three pieces:","text":"Three pieces:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA \u003ccode\u003e&lt;canvas&gt;\u003c/code\u003e element with an \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe Chart.js library (loaded from a CDN).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script&gt;\u003c/code\u003e block that constructs the chart, referencing the canvas and the data.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. A `\u003ccanvas\u003e` element with an `id`.\n2. The Chart.js library (loaded from a CDN).\n3. A `\u003cscript\u003e` block that constructs the chart, referencing the canvas and the data."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Skeleton page","text":"Skeleton page"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"@page\n@model IndexModel\n\n\u003ch4\u003eGames by Continent\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv class=\"chart-container\"\u003e\n    \u003ccanvas id=\"pie-chart\" width=\"400\" height=\"400\"\u003e\u003c/canvas\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cscript src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js\"\u003e\u003c/script\u003e\n\n\u003cscript\u003e\n    const Counts     = [];\n    const Continents = [];\n\n    @foreach (var item in Model.ChartData)\n    {\n        @:Counts.push(@item.Count);\n        @:Continents.push('@item.Name');\n    }\n\n    const ctx = document.getElementById('pie-chart');\n\n    new Chart(ctx, {\n        type: 'pie',\n        data: {\n            labels: Continents,\n            datasets: [{\n                label: 'Games',\n                data: Counts,\n                backgroundColor: [\n                    'rgba(255, 99, 132, 0.7)',\n                    'rgba(54, 162, 235, 0.7)',\n                    'rgba(255, 206, 86, 0.7)',\n                    'rgba(75, 192, 192, 0.7)',\n                    'rgba(153, 102, 255, 0.7)'\n                ]\n            }]\n        }\n    });\n\u003c/script\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e Razor directive","text":"The `@:` Razor directive"},{"kind":"p","html":"Inside a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script&gt;\u003c/code\u003e block, Razor treats everything as JavaScript text. \u003ccode\u003e@\u003c/code\u003e alone is ambiguous because the browser&#39;s JS also uses \u003ccode\u003e@\u003c/code\u003e (or might, in edge cases). The \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e directive forces Razor to treat a whole line as mixed Razor-plus-HTML (or in this case, Razor-plus-JS):","text":"Inside a `\u003cscript\u003e` block, Razor treats everything as JavaScript text. `@` alone is ambiguous because the browser's JS also uses `@` (or might, in edge cases). The `@:` directive forces Razor to treat a whole line as mixed Razor-plus-HTML (or in this case, Razor-plus-JS):"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"@foreach (var item in Model.ChartData)\n{\n    @:Counts.push(@item.Count);\n    @:Continents.push('@item.Name');\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each \u003ccode\u003e@:Counts.push(@item.Count);\u003c/code\u003e produces a literal JS line like \u003ccode\u003eCounts.push(42);\u003c/code\u003e per iteration. The inner \u003ccode\u003e@item.Count\u003c/code\u003e evaluates a Razor expression; the \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e at the start says &quot;render this line of JS with Razor substitutions.&quot;","text":"Each `@:Counts.push(@item.Count);` produces a literal JS line like `Counts.push(42);` per iteration. The inner `@item.Count` evaluates a Razor expression; the `@:` at the start says \"render this line of JS with Razor substitutions.\""},{"kind":"h2","html":"The \u003ccode\u003enew Chart(ctx, config)\u003c/code\u003e constructor","text":"The `new Chart(ctx, config)` constructor"},{"kind":"p","html":"Chart.js v3+ takes two arguments:","text":"Chart.js v3+ takes two arguments:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ectx\u003c/code\u003e — the canvas element (or its 2D context, but the element is accepted as a shorthand).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003econfig\u003c/code\u003e — a JS object with \u003ccode\u003etype\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003edata\u003c/code\u003e, and optional \u003ccode\u003eoptions\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `ctx` — the canvas element (or its 2D context, but the element is accepted as a shorthand).\n- `config` — a JS object with `type`, `data`, and optional `options`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003etype\u003c/code\u003e selects the chart shape. \u003ccode\u003e&#39;pie&#39;\u003c/code\u003e for the course example; Chart.js also supports \u003ccode\u003e&#39;bar&#39;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&#39;line&#39;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&#39;doughnut&#39;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&#39;radar&#39;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&#39;scatter&#39;\u003c/code\u003e, and a few others.","text":"`type` selects the chart shape. `'pie'` for the course example; Chart.js also supports `'bar'`, `'line'`, `'doughnut'`, `'radar'`, `'scatter'`, and a few others."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003edata\u003c/code\u003e has \u003ccode\u003elabels\u003c/code\u003e (array of strings) and \u003ccode\u003edatasets\u003c/code\u003e (array of dataset objects). Each dataset has its own \u003ccode\u003elabel\u003c/code\u003e (shown in tooltips), \u003ccode\u003edata\u003c/code\u003e (the numeric values aligned with \u003ccode\u003elabels\u003c/code\u003e), and styling like \u003ccode\u003ebackgroundColor\u003c/code\u003e. For pie charts, \u003ccode\u003ebackgroundColor\u003c/code\u003e is an array so each slice gets its own color.","text":"`data` has `labels` (array of strings) and `datasets` (array of dataset objects). Each dataset has its own `label` (shown in tooltips), `data` (the numeric values aligned with `labels`), and styling like `backgroundColor`. For pie charts, `backgroundColor` is an array so each slice gets its own color."},{"kind":"h2","html":"No server-side rendering option","text":"No server-side rendering option"},{"kind":"p","html":"Chart.js runs only in the browser — there is no &quot;server-rendered PNG&quot; fallback in the course toolkit. If you need a server-generated chart (e.g. embedded in a PDF), you use a different library like \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Office.Interop.Graph\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eSkiaSharp\u003c/code\u003e, both out of scope for 4870.","text":"Chart.js runs only in the browser — there is no \"server-rendered PNG\" fallback in the course toolkit. If you need a server-generated chart (e.g. embedded in a PDF), you use a different library like `Microsoft.Office.Interop.Graph` or `SkiaSharp`, both out of scope for 4870."},{"kind":"p","html":"The corollary: the \u003ccode\u003e&lt;canvas&gt;\u003c/code\u003e is empty until client-side JS runs. Users who load the page with JavaScript disabled see nothing where the chart should be. Add a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;noscript&gt;\u003c/code\u003e fallback with the raw numbers if that matters.","text":"The corollary: the `\u003ccanvas\u003e` is empty until client-side JS runs. Users who load the page with JavaScript disabled see nothing where the chart should be. Add a `\u003cnoscript\u003e` fallback with the raw numbers if that matters."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You render a pie chart that shows up fine on first load but \"flashes\" empty for a second before the slices appear. What's the sequence and is anything wrong?","a":"The sequence is correct: the server sends HTML with the canvas + `\u003cscript\u003e` block, the browser fetches `chart.min.js` from the CDN, JS executes, Chart.js draws. The flash is the time between HTML paint and script execution. Nothing is broken — to improve perceived latency, move the `\u003cscript src=\"...chart.min.js\"\u003e` into `\u003chead\u003e` with `defer` so it downloads in parallel with the page."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA minimal bar chart of top 5 score leaders:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e&lt;canvas id=&quot;scores&quot; width=&quot;500&quot; height=&quot;300&quot;&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;\n&lt;script src=&quot;https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n    const names  = [];\n    const scores = [];\n    @foreach (var p in Model.Top5)\n    {\n        @:names.push(&#39;@p.Name&#39;);\n        @:scores.push(@p.Score);\n    }\n    new Chart(document.getElementById(&#39;scores&#39;), {\n        type: &#39;bar&#39;,\n        data: {\n            labels: names,\n            datasets: [{ label: &#39;Score&#39;, data: scores }]\n        }\n    });\n&lt;/script&gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSame pattern as the pie: \u003ccode\u003etype: &#39;bar&#39;\u003c/code\u003e changes the rendering, \u003ccode\u003elabels\u003c/code\u003e pair with \u003ccode\u003edata\u003c/code\u003e element-wise.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A minimal bar chart of top 5 score leaders:\n```cs\n\u003ccanvas id=\"scores\" width=\"500\" height=\"300\"\u003e\u003c/canvas\u003e\n\u003cscript src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js\"\u003e\u003c/script\u003e\n\u003cscript\u003e\n    const names  = [];\n    const scores = [];\n    @foreach (var p in Model.Top5)\n    {\n        @:names.push('@p.Name');\n        @:scores.push(@p.Score);\n    }\n    new Chart(document.getElementById('scores'), {\n        type: 'bar',\n        data: {\n            labels: names,\n            datasets: [{ label: 'Score', data: scores }]\n        }\n    });\n\u003c/script\u003e\n```\nSame pattern as the pie: `type: 'bar'` changes the rendering, `labels` pair with `data` element-wise."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eWriting \u003ccode\u003eCount.push(&quot;@item.Name&quot;);\u003c/code\u003e inside a plain JavaScript block without \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e. Razor tries to interpret the whole line and throws a compile error, or (worse) produces a malformed \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script&gt;\u003c/code\u003e that breaks the whole page&#39;s JS. Use \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e for lines that mix JS and Razor expressions.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Writing `Count.push(\"@item.Name\");` inside a plain JavaScript block without `@:`. Razor tries to interpret the whole line and throws a compile error, or (worse) produces a malformed `\u003cscript\u003e` that breaks the whole page's JS. Use `@:` for lines that mix JS and Razor expressions."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eChart.js renders client-side from a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;canvas&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Load the library from \u003ccode\u003ehttps://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js\u003c/code\u003e. Use Razor&#39;s \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e directive to inject per-iteration \u003ccode\u003edata.push(...)\u003c/code\u003e calls. Construct with \u003ccode\u003enew Chart(ctx, { type: &#39;pie&#39; | &#39;bar&#39; | &#39;line&#39;, data: { labels, datasets } })\u003c/code\u003e. No server-rendered fallback — if the user&#39;s browser has JS disabled, the chart doesn&#39;t appear.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Chart.js renders client-side from a `\u003ccanvas\u003e`. Load the library from `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js`. Use Razor's `@:` directive to inject per-iteration `data.push(...)` calls. Construct with `new Chart(ctx, { type: 'pie' | 'bar' | 'line', data: { labels, datasets } })`. No server-rendered fallback — if the user's browser has JS disabled, the chart doesn't appear."}]},{"n":33,"id":"tdd-cycle","title":"TDD cycle — Red, Green, Refactor + three Laws of TDD","hook":"Write the failing test first. Write the minimum code to pass. Refactor once green.","tags":["tdd","discipline","red-green-refactor"],"module":"Testing Discipline","source":"slides/TDD_xunit.pptx; notes/TDD_xunit_SCRIPT.docx; research-tdd.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Three phases on repeat","text":"Three phases on repeat"},{"kind":"p","html":"Test-Driven Development builds features in a tight loop:","text":"Test-Driven Development builds features in a tight loop:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRed\u003c/strong\u003e — Write a failing test that describes the next tiny requirement. The feature doesn&#39;t exist yet, so the test fails immediately. A failing test on a feature you haven&#39;t written is confirmation that your testing infrastructure works.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGreen\u003c/strong\u003e — Write the \u003cem\u003eminimum\u003c/em\u003e production code that makes the test pass. No extras, no &quot;while I&#39;m here&quot; improvements. If the ugliest shortcut would pass the test, that&#39;s the answer — refactoring comes next.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRefactor\u003c/strong\u003e — With the test green, clean up the code. Rename variables, extract helpers, remove duplication. Run the test after every change. You never refactor with a failing test on the table.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Red** — Write a failing test that describes the next tiny requirement. The feature doesn't exist yet, so the test fails immediately. A failing test on a feature you haven't written is confirmation that your testing infrastructure works.\n2. **Green** — Write the *minimum* production code that makes the test pass. No extras, no \"while I'm here\" improvements. If the ugliest shortcut would pass the test, that's the answer — refactoring comes next.\n3. **Refactor** — With the test green, clean up the code. Rename variables, extract helpers, remove duplication. Run the test after every change. You never refactor with a failing test on the table."},{"kind":"p","html":"Repeat. Every new requirement is a new Red-Green-Refactor cycle.","text":"Repeat. Every new requirement is a new Red-Green-Refactor cycle."},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"   ┌──► Red  ─► Green ─► Refactor ──┐\n   │                                │\n   └─────────── repeat ─────────────┘"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Why write the test first","text":"Why write the test first"},{"kind":"p","html":"Writing a test first forces you to decide the public shape before the implementation: what&#39;s the class called, what&#39;s the method signature, what types do inputs and outputs take? These decisions are expensive to change once production code exists. By making the decision through a test, you get interface-level design for free.","text":"Writing a test first forces you to decide the public shape before the implementation: what's the class called, what's the method signature, what types do inputs and outputs take? These decisions are expensive to change once production code exists. By making the decision through a test, you get interface-level design for free."},{"kind":"p","html":"It also guarantees the test can actually fail. A test written after the code often passes on the first run — but you haven&#39;t proven the test would catch a regression. The Red phase removes that ambiguity.","text":"It also guarantees the test can actually fail. A test written after the code often passes on the first run — but you haven't proven the test would catch a regression. The Red phase removes that ambiguity."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Robert C. Martin&#39;s Three Laws","text":"Robert C. Martin's Three Laws"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou are not allowed to write any production code unless it is to make a failing test pass.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou are not allowed to write any more of a unit test than is sufficient to make it fail\u003c/strong\u003e (compilation failures count).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou are not allowed to write any more production code than is sufficient to make the currently failing test pass.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **You are not allowed to write any production code unless it is to make a failing test pass.**\n2. **You are not allowed to write any more of a unit test than is sufficient to make it fail** (compilation failures count).\n3. **You are not allowed to write any more production code than is sufficient to make the currently failing test pass.**"},{"kind":"p","html":"The three laws sound absolute because they are. Strict TDD practitioners follow them to the letter. Looser interpretations treat them as directional guidance — the spirit is &quot;test-first, minimum-viable, continuously green.&quot; Either way, the three laws distinguish TDD from &quot;I write tests, just not first.&quot;","text":"The three laws sound absolute because they are. Strict TDD practitioners follow them to the letter. Looser interpretations treat them as directional guidance — the spirit is \"test-first, minimum-viable, continuously green.\" Either way, the three laws distinguish TDD from \"I write tests, just not first.\""},{"kind":"h2","html":"The FizzBuzz worked example","text":"The FizzBuzz worked example"},{"kind":"p","html":"FizzBuzz: given an integer, return \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Fizz&quot;\u003c/code\u003e if divisible by 3, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Buzz&quot;\u003c/code\u003e if divisible by 5, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;FizzBuzz&quot;\u003c/code\u003e if divisible by both, otherwise the integer as a string.","text":"FizzBuzz: given an integer, return `\"Fizz\"` if divisible by 3, `\"Buzz\"` if divisible by 5, `\"FizzBuzz\"` if divisible by both, otherwise the integer as a string."},{"kind":"p","html":"Following TDD strictly, here&#39;s the first cycle:","text":"Following TDD strictly, here's the first cycle:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// Red: write the failing test.\n[Fact]\npublic void Given2Result2()\n{\n    var fb = new FizzBuzz();\n    Assert.Equal(\"2\", fb.GetResult(2));\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Compile error: no \u003ccode\u003eFizzBuzz\u003c/code\u003e class. That&#39;s a &quot;test failure&quot; by Law 2. Create the class + method with the smallest possible body:","text":"Compile error: no `FizzBuzz` class. That's a \"test failure\" by Law 2. Create the class + method with the smallest possible body:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// Green: minimum code to make the test pass.\npublic class FizzBuzz\n{\n    public string GetResult(int n) =\u003e n.ToString();\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Test passes. No refactor needed yet.","text":"Test passes. No refactor needed yet."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// Red: next test.\n[Fact]\npublic void Given3ResultFizz()\n{\n    var fb = new FizzBuzz();\n    Assert.Equal(\"Fizz\", fb.GetResult(3));\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Test fails — \u003ccode\u003eGetResult(3)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003e&quot;3&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Fizz&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Update:","text":"Test fails — `GetResult(3)` returns `\"3\"`, not `\"Fizz\"`. Update:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"// Green: minimum to pass BOTH tests.\npublic string GetResult(int n)\n    =\u003e n % 3 == 0 ? \"Fizz\" : n.ToString();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Both tests green. Continue the cycle: add a test for 5 → Buzz, then 15 → FizzBuzz, then refactor the if/else pile into a clean form when duplication emerges.","text":"Both tests green. Continue the cycle: add a test for 5 → Buzz, then 15 → FizzBuzz, then refactor the if/else pile into a clean form when duplication emerges."},{"kind":"p","html":"The point isn&#39;t that TDD delivers clever code. It&#39;s that every line of production code exists because a failing test demanded it.","text":"The point isn't that TDD delivers clever code. It's that every line of production code exists because a failing test demanded it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When TDD hurts","text":"When TDD hurts"},{"kind":"p","html":"Not every scenario benefits from test-first. Exploratory spikes (&quot;does this library even support what I need?&quot;) move faster when you prototype first and test-harness the viable result. UI tweaks, prototyping, and research code are commonly written without TDD — the test-first discipline gets in the way when the goal is learning.","text":"Not every scenario benefits from test-first. Exploratory spikes (\"does this library even support what I need?\") move faster when you prototype first and test-harness the viable result. UI tweaks, prototyping, and research code are commonly written without TDD — the test-first discipline gets in the way when the goal is learning."},{"kind":"p","html":"For production business logic, algorithms, and anything where a regression is expensive, TDD shines.","text":"For production business logic, algorithms, and anything where a regression is expensive, TDD shines."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You're adding a `Discount.Calculate(order)` method. You write `Discount.Calculate` first (eyeballing the logic), then write a test. The test passes on the first run. Which TDD phase did you skip and what's the risk?","a":"You skipped the **Red** phase. You never proved the test can fail — it may be tautological (checking something the code trivially satisfies) or have a wrong assertion. The fix next time: write the test with a specific expected value BEFORE writing any `Discount.Calculate` body. Watch it fail; then implement."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA full one-cycle demo of TDD:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e// 1. Red — test fails; Calculator doesn&#39;t exist.\n[Fact]\npublic void Add_TwoPlusTwo_Returns4()\n{\n    Assert.Equal(4, new Calculator().Add(2, 2));\n}\n// 2. Green — minimum code to pass.\npublic class Calculator { public int Add(int a, int b) =&gt; a + b; }\n// 3. Refactor — nothing to clean up yet. Move to next Red.\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","text":"A full one-cycle demo of TDD:\n```cs\n// 1. Red — test fails; Calculator doesn't exist.\n[Fact]\npublic void Add_TwoPlusTwo_Returns4()\n{\n    Assert.Equal(4, new Calculator().Add(2, 2));\n}\n// 2. Green — minimum code to pass.\npublic class Calculator { public int Add(int a, int b) =\u003e a + b; }\n// 3. Refactor — nothing to clean up yet. Move to next Red.\n```"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e&quot;I&#39;ll write the test right after I write the code&quot; is not TDD. Retrofit tests often pass on first run without you ever seeing them fail, which means the test might be wrong and you&#39;d never know. The three Laws exist specifically to prevent this class of false-confidence. Strict TDD means committing to Red → Green → Refactor, in that order, every time.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"\"I'll write the test right after I write the code\" is not TDD. Retrofit tests often pass on first run without you ever seeing them fail, which means the test might be wrong and you'd never know. The three Laws exist specifically to prevent this class of false-confidence. Strict TDD means committing to Red → Green → Refactor, in that order, every time."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eTDD is Red → Green → Refactor: write a failing test, write the minimum code to pass it, then clean up without breaking it. Robert Martin&#39;s three Laws enforce test-first discipline: no production code without a failing test; no more test than needed to fail; no more production code than needed to pass. The discipline pays off in design quality and regression safety; it&#39;s overkill for spikes and prototypes.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"TDD is Red → Green → Refactor: write a failing test, write the minimum code to pass it, then clean up without breaking it. Robert Martin's three Laws enforce test-first discipline: no production code without a failing test; no more test than needed to fail; no more production code than needed to pass. The discipline pays off in design quality and regression safety; it's overkill for spikes and prototypes."}]},{"n":34,"id":"xunit-attributes-assertions","title":"xUnit — [Fact], [Theory], [InlineData], Assert.Equal, AAA","hook":"One attribute per test method, one Assert per logical check, expected-actual order matters.","tags":["tdd","xunit","assert"],"module":"Testing Discipline","source":"slides/TDD_xunit.pptx; notes/TDD_xunit_SCRIPT.docx; research-tdd.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e[Fact]\u003c/code\u003e for single-scenario tests","text":"`[Fact]` for single-scenario tests"},{"kind":"p","html":"xUnit&#39;s most common attribute. A \u003ccode\u003e[Fact]\u003c/code\u003e method has no parameters and runs once:","text":"xUnit's most common attribute. A `[Fact]` method has no parameters and runs once:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"using Xunit;\n\npublic class CalculatorTests\n{\n    [Fact]\n    public void Add_TwoPlusTwo_ReturnsFour()\n    {\n        var calc = new Calculator();\n        int result = calc.Add(2, 2);\n        Assert.Equal(4, result);\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"The test class itself needs no attribute in xUnit — the framework discovers any class containing test methods. Each \u003ccode\u003e[Fact]\u003c/code\u003e produces one entry in the test-runner output.","text":"The test class itself needs no attribute in xUnit — the framework discovers any class containing test methods. Each `[Fact]` produces one entry in the test-runner output."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003e[Theory]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[InlineData]\u003c/code\u003e for parameterized tests","text":"`[Theory]` + `[InlineData]` for parameterized tests"},{"kind":"p","html":"When one conceptual test has multiple input sets, use \u003ccode\u003e[Theory]\u003c/code\u003e + one or more data attributes:","text":"When one conceptual test has multiple input sets, use `[Theory]` + one or more data attributes:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"[Theory]\n[InlineData(1, 2, 3)]\n[InlineData(0, 0, 0)]\n[InlineData(-1, 1, 0)]\n[InlineData(int.MaxValue, 0, int.MaxValue)]\npublic void Add_Variants_ReturnsCorrectSum(int a, int b, int expected)\n{\n    var calc = new Calculator();\n    Assert.Equal(expected, calc.Add(a, b));\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each \u003ccode\u003e[InlineData(...)]\u003c/code\u003e triggers one execution. Four data rows = four runs of the same method body. Each run shows up separately in the test report, so a single failing row doesn&#39;t obscure the passing rows.","text":"Each `[InlineData(...)]` triggers one execution. Four data rows = four runs of the same method body. Each run shows up separately in the test report, so a single failing row doesn't obscure the passing rows."},{"kind":"p","html":"For larger or more complex data, use \u003ccode\u003e[MemberData(nameof(MethodReturningIEnumerable))]\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e[ClassData(typeof(DataProviderClass))]\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e[InlineData]\u003c/code\u003e is fine for small cases; member/class data is better once the parameters need computation or exceed a few lines.","text":"For larger or more complex data, use `[MemberData(nameof(MethodReturningIEnumerable))]` or `[ClassData(typeof(DataProviderClass))]`. `[InlineData]` is fine for small cases; member/class data is better once the parameters need computation or exceed a few lines."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Arrange / Act / Assert (AAA)","text":"Arrange / Act / Assert (AAA)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every test has three sections — by convention arranged top-to-bottom with or without comments:","text":"Every test has three sections — by convention arranged top-to-bottom with or without comments:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"[Fact]\npublic void Add_NegativeAndPositive_ReturnsSum()\n{\n    // Arrange\n    var calc = new Calculator();\n\n    // Act\n    int result = calc.Add(-5, 10);\n\n    // Assert\n    Assert.Equal(5, result);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eArrange\u003c/strong\u003e sets up the inputs and any dependencies (mocks, doubles, fixtures). \u003cstrong\u003eAct\u003c/strong\u003e performs the single operation under test. \u003cstrong\u003eAssert\u003c/strong\u003e verifies the result. Keeping them separate makes tests readable and makes failures easy to diagnose — you can tell whether arrangement, action, or expectation went wrong just by glancing at which block the stack trace points to.","text":"**Arrange** sets up the inputs and any dependencies (mocks, doubles, fixtures). **Act** performs the single operation under test. **Assert** verifies the result. Keeping them separate makes tests readable and makes failures easy to diagnose — you can tell whether arrangement, action, or expectation went wrong just by glancing at which block the stack trace points to."},{"kind":"p","html":"One test, one conceptual assertion. If you find yourself writing three different \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Equal\u003c/code\u003e calls checking unrelated properties, consider splitting into three tests.","text":"One test, one conceptual assertion. If you find yourself writing three different `Assert.Equal` calls checking unrelated properties, consider splitting into three tests."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Assertion family","text":"Assertion family"},{"kind":"p","html":"xUnit&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eAssert\u003c/code\u003e class exposes matchers for the common cases:","text":"xUnit's `Assert` class exposes matchers for the common cases:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAssertion\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Equal(expected, actual)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValue equality. Works for primitives, strings, collections (content-wise).\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.NotEqual(expected, actual)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eThe opposite.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.True(bool)\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eAssert.False(bool)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBoolean checks.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Null(object)\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eAssert.NotNull(object)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNull checks.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Throws&lt;T&gt;(() =&gt; action())\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExpects the lambda to throw \u003ccode\u003eT\u003c/code\u003e. Returns the thrown instance for further assertions.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.InRange(value, low, high)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValue between two bounds.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Contains(expected, collection)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMembership.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.IsType&lt;T&gt;(object)\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eAssert.IsAssignableFrom&lt;T&gt;(object)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExact type / subtype check.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Same(expected, actual)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReference equality. Different from \u003ccode\u003eEqual\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The first two arguments of \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Equal(expected, actual)\u003c/code\u003e matter. Expected first, actual second. Reversing produces failure messages like &quot;Expected 5, Actual 4&quot; that lie — you&#39;ll chase the wrong value. The compiler doesn&#39;t enforce the order; your discipline does.","text":"The first two arguments of `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` matter. Expected first, actual second. Reversing produces failure messages like \"Expected 5, Actual 4\" that lie — you'll chase the wrong value. The compiler doesn't enforce the order; your discipline does."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Exception testing","text":"Exception testing"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"[Fact]\npublic void Divide_ByZero_Throws()\n{\n    var calc = new Calculator();\n    var ex = Assert.Throws\u003cDivideByZeroException\u003e(() =\u003e calc.Divide(10, 0));\n    Assert.Contains(\"zero\", ex.Message);\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Throws&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e returns the exception instance, letting you assert on its \u003ccode\u003eMessage\u003c/code\u003e or custom properties. The test fails if the lambda doesn&#39;t throw \u003ccode\u003eT\u003c/code\u003e (or throws a more-derived type — use \u003ccode\u003eAssert.ThrowsAny&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e when derived exceptions are acceptable).","text":"`Assert.Throws\u003cT\u003e` returns the exception instance, letting you assert on its `Message` or custom properties. The test fails if the lambda doesn't throw `T` (or throws a more-derived type — use `Assert.ThrowsAny\u003cT\u003e` when derived exceptions are acceptable)."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A coworker's failing test reports \"Expected: 4, but was: 5\". You look at the code and see `calc.Add(2, 2)` should return 4. Clicking through, the `Assert.Equal` call is `Assert.Equal(actualResult, 4);`. What's the subtle problem and what does the message really mean?","a":"The arguments are swapped. `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` is the correct order; this call has `actualResult` as the first arg and `4` as the second. The \"Expected: 4\" in the failure message is really the actual value of `actualResult`, and \"but was: 5\" is really the expected value 4 — so the failure message is misleading. The underlying math is correct; the test infrastructure is lying because of the argument swap. Fix: always put expected first."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eCombining \u003ccode\u003e[Theory]\u003c/code\u003e, exception assertions, and AAA in one test file:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003epublic class RoleManagerTests\n{\n    [Theory]\n    [InlineData(null)]\n    [InlineData(&quot;&quot;)]\n    [InlineData(&quot;   &quot;)]\n    public void Assign_EmptyRoleName_Throws(string roleName)\n    {\n        // Arrange\n        var mgr = new RoleManager();\n        // Act + Assert (exception cases: act and assert fold together)\n        Assert.Throws&lt;ArgumentException&gt;(() =&gt; mgr.Assign(&quot;alice&quot;, roleName));\n    }\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThree runs, one method body. The exception case is the canonical example where Act and Assert are one call (\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Throws(...)\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Combining `[Theory]`, exception assertions, and AAA in one test file:\n```cs\npublic class RoleManagerTests\n{\n    [Theory]\n    [InlineData(null)]\n    [InlineData(\"\")]\n    [InlineData(\"   \")]\n    public void Assign_EmptyRoleName_Throws(string roleName)\n    {\n        // Arrange\n        var mgr = new RoleManager();\n        // Act + Assert (exception cases: act and assert fold together)\n        Assert.Throws\u003cArgumentException\u003e(() =\u003e mgr.Assign(\"alice\", roleName));\n    }\n}\n```\nThree runs, one method body. The exception case is the canonical example where Act and Assert are one call (`Assert.Throws(...)`)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Equal(actual, expected)\u003c/code\u003e with arguments swapped compiles fine and fails only on the test actually failing — at which point the error message blames the wrong value. The convention (expected first) is consistent across MSTest, NUnit, and xUnit, so cross-framework muscle memory applies. Code-review tests for argument order every time.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`Assert.Equal(actual, expected)` with arguments swapped compiles fine and fails only on the test actually failing — at which point the error message blames the wrong value. The convention (expected first) is consistent across MSTest, NUnit, and xUnit, so cross-framework muscle memory applies. Code-review tests for argument order every time."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[Fact]\u003c/code\u003e for one-run tests, \u003ccode\u003e[Theory]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[InlineData]\u003c/code\u003e for parameterized tests. Arrange-Act-Assert inside every test body. \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Equal(expected, actual)\u003c/code\u003e — expected always first. Exception tests use \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Throws&lt;T&gt;(() =&gt; action())\u003c/code\u003e, which returns the exception for further assertions. The compiler does not check argument order; your discipline does.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`[Fact]` for one-run tests, `[Theory]` + `[InlineData]` for parameterized tests. Arrange-Act-Assert inside every test body. `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` — expected always first. Exception tests use `Assert.Throws\u003cT\u003e(() =\u003e action())`, which returns the exception for further assertions. The compiler does not check argument order; your discipline does."}]},{"n":35,"id":"xunit-fixtures-lifecycle","title":"xUnit lifecycle — constructor + IDisposable, IClassFixture, ICollectionFixture","hook":"Constructor runs before every test. IClassFixture shares expensive setup across a class. ICollectionFixture shares across multiple classes.","tags":["tdd","xunit","fixture","lifecycle"],"module":"Testing Discipline","source":"notes/TDD_xunit_SCRIPT.docx; research-tdd.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"One test class per test — by default","text":"One test class per test — by default"},{"kind":"p","html":"xUnit creates a fresh instance of the test class for every \u003ccode\u003e[Fact]\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e[Theory]\u003c/code\u003e execution. That means:","text":"xUnit creates a fresh instance of the test class for every `[Fact]` or `[Theory]` execution. That means:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe \u003cstrong\u003econstructor\u003c/strong\u003e runs before each test (think of it as xUnit&#39;s \u003ccode\u003e[SetUp]\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIf the class implements \u003ccode\u003eIDisposable\u003c/code\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDispose()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e runs after each test (think of it as xUnit&#39;s \u003ccode\u003e[TearDown]\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNo test sees state left over from another test. Each run is independent.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- The **constructor** runs before each test (think of it as xUnit's `[SetUp]`).\n- If the class implements `IDisposable`, **`Dispose()`** runs after each test (think of it as xUnit's `[TearDown]`).\n- No test sees state left over from another test. Each run is independent."},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class CalculatorTests : IDisposable\n{\n    private readonly Calculator _calc;\n\n    public CalculatorTests()              // runs before EACH test\n    {\n        _calc = new Calculator();\n    }\n\n    [Fact]\n    public void Add_Works() =\u003e Assert.Equal(5, _calc.Add(2, 3));\n\n    [Fact]\n    public void Subtract_Works() =\u003e Assert.Equal(1, _calc.Subtract(3, 2));\n\n    public void Dispose()                  // runs after EACH test\n    {\n        // cleanup if needed\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"This is different from older frameworks (NUnit, MSTest) that use \u003ccode\u003e[SetUp]\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e[TearDown]\u003c/code\u003e attribute-decorated methods. xUnit relies on standard C# object lifecycle — no attribute, no hidden convention.","text":"This is different from older frameworks (NUnit, MSTest) that use `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` attribute-decorated methods. xUnit relies on standard C# object lifecycle — no attribute, no hidden convention."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — share across a test class","text":"`IClassFixture\u003cT\u003e` — share across a test class"},{"kind":"p","html":"Sometimes setup is expensive — spinning up a \u003ccode\u003eDbContext\u003c/code\u003e, starting an in-memory server, loading a large file. Running that cost before every test makes the test suite slow. \u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e shares one instance across every test in one class:","text":"Sometimes setup is expensive — spinning up a `DbContext`, starting an in-memory server, loading a large file. Running that cost before every test makes the test suite slow. `IClassFixture\u003cT\u003e` shares one instance across every test in one class:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"public class DbFixture : IDisposable\n{\n    public MyDbContext Db { get; } = new MyDbContext(...);\n    public DbFixture() { /* seed data */ }\n    public void Dispose() =\u003e Db.Dispose();\n}\n\npublic class UserServiceTests : IClassFixture\u003cDbFixture\u003e\n{\n    private readonly DbFixture _fixture;\n\n    public UserServiceTests(DbFixture fixture)     // xUnit injects the shared instance\n        =\u003e _fixture = fixture;\n\n    [Fact]\n    public void FindUser_Exists() { /* use _fixture.Db */ }\n\n    [Fact]\n    public void FindUser_Missing() { /* use _fixture.Db */ }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"xUnit creates the \u003ccode\u003eDbFixture\u003c/code\u003e once, injects it into every test class instance via the constructor, and disposes it after all tests in the class finish. Each \u003ccode\u003e[Fact]\u003c/code\u003e still runs in its own \u003ccode\u003eUserServiceTests\u003c/code\u003e instance — \u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture\u003c/code\u003e shares the fixture, not the test class.","text":"xUnit creates the `DbFixture` once, injects it into every test class instance via the constructor, and disposes it after all tests in the class finish. Each `[Fact]` still runs in its own `UserServiceTests` instance — `IClassFixture` shares the fixture, not the test class."},{"kind":"h2","html":"\u003ccode\u003eICollectionFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — share across multiple classes","text":"`ICollectionFixture\u003cT\u003e` — share across multiple classes"},{"kind":"p","html":"When multiple test classes need the same shared state (e.g. one expensive resource serving several test suites), use \u003ccode\u003eICollectionFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e plus \u003ccode\u003e[CollectionDefinition]\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e[Collection]\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"When multiple test classes need the same shared state (e.g. one expensive resource serving several test suites), use `ICollectionFixture\u003cT\u003e` plus `[CollectionDefinition]` and `[Collection]`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"cs","code":"[CollectionDefinition(\"DbCollection\")]\npublic class DbCollection : ICollectionFixture\u003cDbFixture\u003e { }\n\n[Collection(\"DbCollection\")]\npublic class UserServiceTests { /* ... */ }\n\n[Collection(\"DbCollection\")]\npublic class OrderServiceTests { /* ... */ }"},{"kind":"p","html":"One \u003ccode\u003eDbFixture\u003c/code\u003e instance is shared across \u003ccode\u003eUserServiceTests\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eOrderServiceTests\u003c/code\u003e, and any other class in the \u003ccode\u003e&quot;DbCollection&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. Runs get serialized within the collection (xUnit parallelizes across collections but not within), so &quot;shared&quot; doesn&#39;t race.","text":"One `DbFixture` instance is shared across `UserServiceTests`, `OrderServiceTests`, and any other class in the `\"DbCollection\"`. Runs get serialized within the collection (xUnit parallelizes across collections but not within), so \"shared\" doesn't race."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Parallelization defaults","text":"Parallelization defaults"},{"kind":"p","html":"By default, xUnit runs \u003cstrong\u003etests within one class serially\u003c/strong\u003e and \u003cstrong\u003eclasses in different classes in parallel\u003c/strong\u003e. A class using \u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eICollectionFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e follows the same rule, but the shared fixture is not re-created — it&#39;s instantiated once.","text":"By default, xUnit runs **tests within one class serially** and **classes in different classes in parallel**. A class using `IClassFixture\u003cT\u003e` or `ICollectionFixture\u003cT\u003e` follows the same rule, but the shared fixture is not re-created — it's instantiated once."},{"kind":"p","html":"Opt into full parallelization or opt out of parallelization via \u003ccode\u003e[assembly: CollectionBehavior(...)]\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eAssemblyInfo.cs\u003c/code\u003e or an \u003ccode\u003exunit.runner.json\u003c/code\u003e file. Rarely needed; the defaults are sensible for most suites.","text":"Opt into full parallelization or opt out of parallelization via `[assembly: CollectionBehavior(...)]` in `AssemblyInfo.cs` or an `xunit.runner.json` file. Rarely needed; the defaults are sensible for most suites."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When to reach for a fixture","text":"When to reach for a fixture"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eScenario\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eUse\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIndependent unit of logic, no setup cost\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePlain class; no fixture\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExpensive setup (DB, HttpClient, server) shared by one class&#39;s tests\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExpensive setup shared by multiple test classes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eICollectionFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[Collection]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStatic reference data (list of 100 country codes)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStatic field in the test class; not a fixture\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Fixtures trade isolation for speed. Use them only when the setup is genuinely expensive. An in-memory \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;int&gt;\u003c/code\u003e does not warrant a fixture.","text":"Fixtures trade isolation for speed. Use them only when the setup is genuinely expensive. An in-memory `List\u003cint\u003e` does not warrant a fixture."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You add a new `[Fact]` to an existing test class. The test passes on your machine but fails in CI, complaining that a database row it expects isn't present. You didn't change anything else. What's the most likely lifecycle reason?","a":"Another test in the same class (or a sibling class in the same collection) previously modified shared state through the fixture. Because xUnit reuses the fixture across tests, one test's writes persist into subsequent tests. Fix options: make the fixture's `DbContext` reset between tests (add cleanup to `Dispose` on the test class itself), or move the affected tests to their own collection so their state stays isolated."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003eA test class that shares a seeded in-memory DB across its tests via \u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture\u003c/code\u003e:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003epublic class SeededDbFixture : IDisposable\n{\n    public MyDb Db { get; } = new MyDb(new DbContextOptionsBuilder&lt;MyDb&gt;()\n        .UseInMemoryDatabase($&quot;test-{Guid.NewGuid()}&quot;).Options);\n    public SeededDbFixture()\n    {\n        Db.Users.AddRange(new User(&quot;Alice&quot;), new User(&quot;Bob&quot;));\n        Db.SaveChanges();\n    }\n    public void Dispose() =&gt; Db.Dispose();\n}\npublic class UserQueryTests : IClassFixture&lt;SeededDbFixture&gt;\n{\n    private readonly SeededDbFixture _fx;\n    public UserQueryTests(SeededDbFixture fx) =&gt; _fx = fx;\n    [Fact] public void FindAlice() =&gt; Assert.NotNull(_fx.Db.Users.Find(1));\n    [Fact] public void CountUsers() =&gt; Assert.Equal(2, _fx.Db.Users.Count());\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSeeding runs once per class; each test sees the pre-populated DB without paying setup cost.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A test class that shares a seeded in-memory DB across its tests via `IClassFixture`:\n```cs\npublic class SeededDbFixture : IDisposable\n{\n    public MyDb Db { get; } = new MyDb(new DbContextOptionsBuilder\u003cMyDb\u003e()\n        .UseInMemoryDatabase($\"test-{Guid.NewGuid()}\").Options);\n    public SeededDbFixture()\n    {\n        Db.Users.AddRange(new User(\"Alice\"), new User(\"Bob\"));\n        Db.SaveChanges();\n    }\n    public void Dispose() =\u003e Db.Dispose();\n}\npublic class UserQueryTests : IClassFixture\u003cSeededDbFixture\u003e\n{\n    private readonly SeededDbFixture _fx;\n    public UserQueryTests(SeededDbFixture fx) =\u003e _fx = fx;\n    [Fact] public void FindAlice() =\u003e Assert.NotNull(_fx.Db.Users.Find(1));\n    [Fact] public void CountUsers() =\u003e Assert.Equal(2, _fx.Db.Users.Count());\n}\n```\nSeeding runs once per class; each test sees the pre-populated DB without paying setup cost."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for a resource whose tests mutate it. The fixture is shared — if \u003ccode\u003eTestA\u003c/code\u003e adds a user and \u003ccode\u003eTestB\u003c/code\u003e counts users, \u003ccode\u003eTestB\u003c/code\u003e&#39;s result depends on whether \u003ccode\u003eTestA\u003c/code\u003e ran first. xUnit does NOT guarantee test order. Use a fixture only when tests treat it as read-only, or reset state in the test class&#39;s own \u003ccode\u003eIDisposable.Dispose\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Using `IClassFixture\u003cT\u003e` for a resource whose tests mutate it. The fixture is shared — if `TestA` adds a user and `TestB` counts users, `TestB`'s result depends on whether `TestA` ran first. xUnit does NOT guarantee test order. Use a fixture only when tests treat it as read-only, or reset state in the test class's own `IDisposable.Dispose`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eConstructor runs before each test; \u003ccode\u003eDispose\u003c/code\u003e (when implementing \u003ccode\u003eIDisposable\u003c/code\u003e) runs after. \u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e shares one expensive setup instance across all tests in one class. \u003ccode\u003eICollectionFixture&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[CollectionDefinition]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[Collection(&quot;Name&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e shares across multiple classes. Tests inside one class (or one collection) run serially; different classes run in parallel by default. Reach for a fixture only when setup cost justifies it — keep plain tests simple.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Constructor runs before each test; `Dispose` (when implementing `IDisposable`) runs after. `IClassFixture\u003cT\u003e` shares one expensive setup instance across all tests in one class. `ICollectionFixture\u003cT\u003e` + `[CollectionDefinition]` + `[Collection(\"Name\")]` shares across multiple classes. Tests inside one class (or one collection) run serially; different classes run in parallel by default. Reach for a fixture only when setup cost justifies it — keep plain tests simple."}]}],"practice":[{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":1,"id":"ai-agent-wire-up-console","title":"Wire a single-tool MAF agent in a console app","lang":"csharp","tags":["ai","maf","agent","tools","console"],"source":"Assignment 2 (variant — console-only MAF agent registering one tool via AIFunctionFactory.Create, simpler than A2's full-stack AI-integrated Blazor)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e for a console app that uses the Microsoft Agent Framework (MAF) to answer weather questions with one tool.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRequirements:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eStart from an existing \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient chatClient\u003c/code\u003e (assume it is already constructed against GitHub Models).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDefine a static C# method \u003ccode\u003eWeatherService.GetWeatherForCity(string city)\u003c/code\u003e that returns a plain string like \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Vancouver: 8C, rainy&quot;\u003c/code\u003e for any input.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRegister that method as an \u003ccode\u003eAITool\u003c/code\u003e using \u003ccode\u003eAIFunctionFactory.Create\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003ename: &quot;GetWeatherForCity&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and a description the LLM can read.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBuild a \u003ccode\u003eChatClientAgent\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e.AsAIAgent(...)\u003c/code\u003e, passing the tool in the \u003ccode\u003etools:\u003c/code\u003e array plus an \u003ccode\u003einstructions:\u003c/code\u003e string and a \u003ccode\u003ename:\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate an \u003ccode\u003eAgentSession\u003c/code\u003e once via \u003ccode\u003eawait agent.CreateSessionAsync()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLoop: read a line from the console, call \u003ccode\u003eagent.RunAsync(input, session)\u003c/code\u003e, and print the \u003ccode\u003e.Text\u003c/code\u003e property.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDo not use \u003ccode\u003eChatHistory\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e.AsAgent()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eagent.Invoke()\u003c/code\u003e, or \u003ccode\u003eAITool.Register()\u003c/code\u003e — none exist in MAF.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"using Microsoft.Agents.AI;\nusing Microsoft.Extensions.AI;\n\npublic static class WeatherService\n{\n    public static string GetWeatherForCity(string city)\n    {\n        // TODO: return a stub string like \"Vancouver: 8C, rainy\"\n        throw new NotImplementedException();\n    }\n}\n\npublic class Program\n{\n    public static async Task Main(string[] args)\n    {\n        IChatClient chatClient = BuildChatClient(); // assume provided\n\n        // TODO 1: wrap WeatherService.GetWeatherForCity as an AITool using AIFunctionFactory.Create.\n        // TODO 2: build the agent with chatClient.AsAIAgent(name, instructions, tools).\n        // TODO 3: create an AgentSession with await agent.CreateSessionAsync().\n        // TODO 4: loop — read input, call agent.RunAsync(input, session), print response.Text.\n    }\n\n    private static IChatClient BuildChatClient() =\u003e throw new NotImplementedException();\n}","solution":"using Microsoft.Agents.AI;\nusing Microsoft.Extensions.AI;\n\npublic static class WeatherService\n{\n    public static string GetWeatherForCity(string city)\n    {\n        return $\"{city}: 8C, rainy\";\n    }\n}\n\npublic class Program\n{\n    public static async Task Main(string[] args)\n    {\n        IChatClient chatClient = BuildChatClient();\n\n        AITool weatherTool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(\n            WeatherService.GetWeatherForCity,\n            name: \"GetWeatherForCity\",\n            description: \"Get the current weather summary for a given city name.\");\n\n        AIAgent agent = chatClient.AsAIAgent(\n            name: \"WeatherAgent\",\n            instructions: \"You answer weather questions. Call GetWeatherForCity whenever the user asks about a city's weather.\",\n            tools: [weatherTool]);\n\n        var session = await agent.CreateSessionAsync();\n\n        while (true)\n        {\n            Console.Write(\"User \u003e \");\n            string? input = Console.ReadLine();\n            if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(input)) continue;\n\n            var response = await agent.RunAsync(input, session);\n            Console.WriteLine(response.Text);\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static IChatClient BuildChatClient() =\u003e throw new NotImplementedException();\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe LLM decides when to call \u003ccode\u003eGetWeatherForCity\u003c/code\u003e based on the description string. That is the entire function-calling contract — the description is metadata the model reads, not a comment for humans.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA common wrong approach: build a \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;ChatMessage&gt; history\u003c/code\u003e and append each user and assistant message manually, passing the list into every \u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e call. That is the raw \u003ccode\u003eIChatClient\u003c/code\u003e pattern. MAF agents use \u003ccode\u003eAgentSession\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003eawait agent.CreateSessionAsync()\u003c/code\u003e; passing both a manual \u003ccode\u003eChatHistory\u003c/code\u003e and a session duplicates state.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA second wrong approach: register the method with \u003ccode\u003eAITool.Register(WeatherService.GetWeatherForCity)\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003echatClient.AsAgent(...)\u003c/code\u003e. Neither compiles — MAF ships \u003ccode\u003eAIFunctionFactory.Create\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e.AsAIAgent()\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e.AsAgent()\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eAITool.Register()\u003c/code\u003e are documented exam distractors.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA third wrong approach: call \u003ccode\u003eagent.Invoke(input)\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ekernel.InvokeAsync(...)\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eInvoke\u003c/code\u003e is Semantic Kernel vocabulary; MAF agents expose \u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e (buffered) and \u003ccode\u003eRunStreamingAsync\u003c/code\u003e (token-by-token). Mixing the two SDKs&#39; verbs on the same object does not interop.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":2,"id":"grpc-crud-student","title":"Implement InsertStudent on a gRPC service","lang":"cs","tags":["grpc","server","asp-net-core","ef-core"],"source":"Labs/W09 gRPC/ Q5 (variant — implement a single InsertStudent override plus its DI setup, simpler than the full 4-method CRUD in the lab)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eComplete the \u003ccode\u003eStudentsService\u003c/code\u003e class below so that \u003ccode\u003eInsertStudent\u003c/code\u003e persists the request into the \u003ccode\u003eSchoolDbContext\u003c/code\u003e, saves changes, and returns a \u003ccode\u003eReply\u003c/code\u003e whose \u003ccode\u003eIsOk\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003etrue\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eResult\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Inserted&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e service and messages already exist and generate \u003ccode\u003eStudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eStudentModel\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eReply\u003c/code\u003e for you.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"public class StudentsService : StudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase\n{\n    private readonly SchoolDbContext _context;\n\n    public StudentsService(SchoolDbContext context) =\u003e _context = context;\n\n    public override Task\u003cReply\u003e InsertStudent(\n        StudentModel request,\n        ServerCallContext context)\n    {\n        // TODO: add a new Student to _context.Students based on request,\n        // save changes, and return a successful Reply.\n        throw new NotImplementedException();\n    }\n}","solution":"public class StudentsService : StudentRemote.StudentRemoteBase\n{\n    private readonly SchoolDbContext _context;\n\n    public StudentsService(SchoolDbContext context) =\u003e _context = context;\n\n    public override async Task\u003cReply\u003e InsertStudent(\n        StudentModel request,\n        ServerCallContext context)\n    {\n        _context.Students!.Add(new Student\n        {\n            FirstName = request.FirstName,\n            LastName  = request.LastName,\n            School    = request.School\n        });\n\n        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();\n\n        return new Reply { Result = \"Inserted\", IsOk = true };\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe override takes \u003ccode\u003eStudentModel\u003c/code\u003e (the request) plus \u003ccode\u003eServerCallContext\u003c/code\u003e and returns \u003ccode\u003eTask&lt;Reply&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Because \u003ccode\u003eSaveChangesAsync\u003c/code\u003e is awaited, the method must be declared \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e — the compiler will flag any \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e method that returns \u003ccode\u003eTask.FromResult(...)\u003c/code\u003e or a non-awaited value.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReturning \u003ccode\u003eTask.FromResult(new Reply { … })\u003c/code\u003e while still calling \u003ccode\u003eSaveChanges()\u003c/code\u003e synchronously.\u003c/strong\u003e The student ends up persisted, but the method blocks the gRPC thread pool for the duration of the write. Under concurrent load this throttles unrelated requests. Always prefer \u003ccode\u003easync\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eSaveChangesAsync\u003c/code\u003e when any I/O happens.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting \u003ccode\u003eoverride\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Without it the method does not replace the base-class virtual method; the generated base&#39;s default throws \u003ccode\u003eUNIMPLEMENTED\u003c/code\u003e when the client calls \u003ccode\u003eInsertStudentAsync\u003c/code\u003e. The code compiles and the service starts successfully, which makes this trap especially sharp.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMapping \u003ccode\u003erequest.StudentId\u003c/code\u003e into the new \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The database auto-generates the primary key. Forcing a specific \u003ccode\u003eStudentId\u003c/code\u003e from the client either collides with existing rows or overrides the sequence unexpectedly — return \u003ccode\u003eInserted\u003c/code\u003e but tell the client the generated id, if anything.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":3,"id":"grpc-client-di","title":"Register a gRPC client in Program.cs","lang":"cs","tags":["grpc","client","di","asp-net-core"],"source":"Labs/W09 gRPC/ Q1 (variant — register a single ToonRemoteClient against localhost:5099, simpler than the lab's multi-client Aspire AppHost wiring)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eComplete the \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e snippet below so that the \u003ccode\u003eToonRemote.ToonRemoteClient\u003c/code\u003e (generated from \u003ccode\u003eProtos\\toon.proto\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eGrpcServices=&quot;Client&quot;\u003c/code\u003e) is registered in the DI container, pointing at \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:5099\u003c/code\u003e. Assume \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Net.ClientFactory\u003c/code\u003e is already added as a NuGet package.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\n// TODO: register ToonRemote.ToonRemoteClient in the DI container,\n// pointing at http://localhost:5099 so that any component can @inject it.\n\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorComponents()\n    .AddInteractiveServerComponents();\n\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapRazorComponents\u003cApp\u003e()\n   .AddInteractiveServerRenderMode();\napp.Run();","solution":"var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nbuilder.Services.AddGrpcClient\u003cToonRemote.ToonRemoteClient\u003e(opts =\u003e\n{\n    opts.Address = new Uri(\"http://localhost:5099\");\n});\n\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorComponents()\n    .AddInteractiveServerComponents();\n\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.MapRazorComponents\u003cApp\u003e()\n   .AddInteractiveServerRenderMode();\napp.Run();","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddGrpcClient&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e registers a typed gRPC client with the factory. The factory manages channel lifetime so every injection of \u003ccode\u003eToonRemote.ToonRemoteClient\u003c/code\u003e reuses the same pooled HTTP/2 connection. The \u003ccode\u003eopts.Address\u003c/code\u003e assignment is the only per-client configuration you typically need; additional options (timeouts, interceptors) chain off the returned \u003ccode\u003eIHttpClientBuilder\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003enew GrpcChannel.ForAddress(...)\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e and passing it to \u003ccode\u003eAddSingleton\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e You end up with a hand-rolled channel that bypasses the factory — no resilience handlers, no OpenTelemetry hooks, no service discovery. Under Aspire, this also misses out on \u003ccode\u003ehttp://backend/\u003c/code\u003e name resolution.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting the NuGet package reference to \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Net.ClientFactory\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The extension method does not exist without it, so \u003ccode\u003eAddGrpcClient&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e fails to compile.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHardcoding \u003ccode\u003elocalhost:5099\u003c/code\u003e into the deployed app.\u003c/strong\u003e In a local-only demo this is fine; once the service runs elsewhere (Aspire, Docker Compose, Kubernetes), replace the literal with \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.Configuration[&quot;Services:Toon:Address&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e or an Aspire logical name like \u003ccode\u003ehttp://toon\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":4,"id":"grpc-blazor-inject","title":"Call a gRPC service from a Blazor component","lang":"cs","tags":["grpc","blazor","interactive-server"],"source":"Labs/W09 gRPC/ Q2 (variant — inject StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient into a Blazor page, call GetStudentInfoAsync, render the result, simpler single-call version of the lab's full CRUD UI)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eComplete the Blazor component \u003ccode\u003eStudentLookup.razor\u003c/code\u003e so that it injects the gRPC client (already registered in \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e), calls \u003ccode\u003eGetStudentInfoAsync(new StudentLookupModel { StudentId = 3 })\u003c/code\u003e when the page initializes, and renders the returned \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e. Set the render mode explicitly so the async call runs. Assume the \u003ccode\u003e.proto\u003c/code\u003e has been compiled and \u003ccode\u003eStudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eStudentLookupModel\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eStudentModel\u003c/code\u003e are available.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"@page \"/student-lookup\"\n@using Grpc.Net.Client\n\n// TODO: set the render mode and inject the gRPC client.\n\n\u003ch1\u003eStudent lookup\u003c/h1\u003e\n\n@if (_student is null)\n{\n    \u003cp\u003eLoading…\u003c/p\u003e\n}\nelse\n{\n    \u003cp\u003eFound: @_student.FirstName @_student.LastName\u003c/p\u003e\n}\n\n@code {\n    private StudentModel? _student;\n\n    protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()\n    {\n        // TODO: call GetStudentInfoAsync on the injected client and\n        // assign the result to _student.\n    }\n}","solution":"@page \"/student-lookup\"\n@rendermode InteractiveServer\n@inject StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient _grpcClient\n\n\u003ch1\u003eStudent lookup\u003c/h1\u003e\n\n@if (_student is null)\n{\n    \u003cp\u003eLoading…\u003c/p\u003e\n}\nelse\n{\n    \u003cp\u003eFound: @_student.FirstName @_student.LastName\u003c/p\u003e\n}\n\n@code {\n    private StudentModel? _student;\n\n    protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()\n    {\n        _student = await _grpcClient.GetStudentInfoAsync(\n            new StudentLookupModel { StudentId = 3 });\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThree directives carry the weight. \u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveServer\u003c/code\u003e keeps the component alive after the initial render so the awaited gRPC call can complete and trigger a re-render. \u003ccode\u003e@inject StudentRemote.StudentRemoteClient _grpcClient\u003c/code\u003e pulls the typed stub from DI — the stub was registered in \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e via \u003ccode\u003eAddGrpcClient&lt;T&gt;()\u003c/code\u003e. The call itself uses the \u003ccode\u003eAsync\u003c/code\u003e suffix (\u003ccode\u003eGetStudentInfoAsync\u003c/code\u003e), not the blocking form, which is the only form safe to await in an async method.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting \u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveServer\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Under static server rendering, \u003ccode\u003eOnInitializedAsync\u003c/code\u003e still runs once, but any post-render updates never reach the client — the page shows &quot;Loading…&quot; forever because the component was torn down before the awaited task completed.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003e_grpcClient.GetStudentInfo(...).Result\u003c/code\u003e to &quot;simplify&quot; the async flow.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e.Result\u003c/code\u003e blocks the SignalR circuit thread and can deadlock under load. Always await the \u003ccode\u003eAsync\u003c/code\u003e form inside an async method.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInjecting \u003ccode\u003eGrpcChannel\u003c/code\u003e and constructing the client inside \u003ccode\u003eOnInitializedAsync\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e This works but throws away the factory&#39;s channel pooling. Once DI registration is in place, inject the typed client directly.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":5,"id":"aspire-wire-grpc-backend","title":"Wire a gRPC backend into an Aspire AppHost","lang":"cs","tags":["aspire","grpc","apphost"],"source":"Labs/W09 gRPC/ Q4 (variant — single-backend + single-frontend orchestration with WithReference + WaitFor, simpler than the lab's full multi-service CRUD)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou have two projects in your solution: \u003ccode\u003eStudentsGrpcApi\u003c/code\u003e (a gRPC backend) and \u003ccode\u003eStudentsBlazor\u003c/code\u003e (a Blazor Server frontend). The AppHost project already has \u003ccode\u003e&lt;ProjectReference&gt;\u003c/code\u003e to both. Fill in \u003ccode\u003eAppHost/Program.cs\u003c/code\u003e so Aspire starts the backend first, waits for it to report healthy, then starts the frontend with the backend&#39;s URL injected as an environment variable.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\n// TODO: register the gRPC backend under the logical name \"backend\".\n// Then register the Blazor frontend under \"frontend\" so it waits for\n// the backend and receives its URL via service discovery.\n\nbuilder.Build().Run();","solution":"var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nvar backend = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.StudentsGrpcApi\u003e(\"backend\");\n\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.StudentsBlazor\u003e(\"frontend\")\n    .WithReference(backend)\n    .WaitFor(backend);\n\nbuilder.Build().Run();","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddProject&lt;Projects.StudentsGrpcApi&gt;(&quot;backend&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e both launches the backend and assigns it the logical name \u003ccode\u003ebackend\u003c/code\u003e. The frontend&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eWithReference(backend)\u003c/code\u003e injects an environment variable (something like \u003ccode\u003eservices__backend__http__0\u003c/code\u003e) that the frontend&#39;s service-discovery handler reads whenever the app resolves \u003ccode\u003ehttp://backend/\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eWaitFor(backend)\u003c/code\u003e prevents the frontend from starting until the backend passes its \u003ccode\u003e/health\u003c/code\u003e check — without this, the first gRPC calls fire against a server that hasn&#39;t finished booting.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHardcoding \u003ccode\u003eopts.Address = new Uri(&quot;http://localhost:5099&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e in the frontend&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e and skipping \u003ccode\u003eWithReference\u003c/code\u003e in the AppHost.\u003c/strong\u003e It works in local dev but loses every benefit of Aspire — no dynamic port allocation, no environment-specific overrides, no dashboard telemetry. The right move is \u003ccode\u003eopts.Address = new Uri(&quot;http://backend&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e on the client plus \u003ccode\u003eWithReference\u003c/code\u003e in the AppHost.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting \u003ccode\u003eWaitFor(backend)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The frontend can boot, be reachable, and issue its first gRPC call before the backend has finished migrations or health checks. The failure reads as a network error; the real cause is ordering.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e in the AppHost.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults\u003c/code\u003e belongs in each individual service&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e. Putting it in the AppHost is a boot-break — the orchestrator tries to register OpenTelemetry and health checks on itself and fails.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":6,"id":"aspire-multi-project-a2","title":"Orchestrate an Assignment-2-style multi-project stack","lang":"cs","tags":["aspire","apphost","sql-server"],"source":"Assignment 2 (variant — WebAPI + Server-Blazor admin + Client-Blazor public against one SQL Server, simpler than A2's full-stack which also adds AI integration and role-based auth)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eAssignment 2&#39;s architecture: one WebAPI (the data tier), one Server-Blazor project (admin site for authors + admins), one Client-Blazor WASM project (public-facing reader). All three share one SQL Server database named \u003ccode\u003ecms\u003c/code\u003e. Write the AppHost \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e that wires this up: the API depends on the database; both Blazor sites depend on the API.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\n// TODO: register SQL Server + a database called \"cms\".\n// TODO: register the WebAPI under \"api\" with the database injected.\n// TODO: register the Server-Blazor admin site and the Client-Blazor\n// public site, both depending on the api.\n\nbuilder.Build().Run();","solution":"var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nvar db = builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\")\n                .AddDatabase(\"cms\");\n\nvar api = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Cms_Api\u003e(\"api\")\n    .WithReference(db)\n    .WaitFor(db);\n\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Cms_Admin\u003e(\"admin\")\n    .WithReference(api)\n    .WaitFor(api);\n\nbuilder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Cms_Public\u003e(\"public\")\n    .WithReference(api)\n    .WaitFor(api);\n\nbuilder.Build().Run();","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe dependency graph is explicit: \u003ccode\u003edb → api → (admin, public)\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eAddSqlServer(&quot;sql&quot;).AddDatabase(&quot;cms&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e gives the API a connection string via \u003ccode\u003eConnectionStrings__cms\u003c/code\u003e. The API&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/code\u003e calls \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.AddSqlServerDbContext&lt;CmsDbContext&gt;(&quot;cms&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e and EF Core picks up the injected value — no \u003ccode\u003eappsettings.json\u003c/code\u003e edits per environment. Each Blazor project reaches the API as \u003ccode\u003ehttp://api/\u003c/code\u003e; the admin site uses that for admin-only endpoints, the public site uses it for anonymous reads.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRegistering two separate databases, one for admin and one for public.\u003c/strong\u003e A2 explicitly requires a shared database so content authored in admin appears on the public site. Registering \u003ccode\u003eAddDatabase(&quot;admin-cms&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eAddDatabase(&quot;public-cms&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e produces two isolated SQL Server databases that never sync.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSkipping \u003ccode\u003eWaitFor(api)\u003c/code\u003e on the Blazor projects.\u003c/strong\u003e Both sites launch, hit the API on first render, and fail because the API hasn&#39;t finished EF migrations yet. The user sees a spinner or an error; the root cause is startup-order, not code.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAdding AI integration at the AppHost level via \u003ccode\u003eWithEnvironment(&quot;OPENAI_KEY&quot;, ...)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e A2 does require AI, but AI config belongs inside each service that needs it — via that service&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eappsettings.json\u003c/code\u003e or its own \u003ccode\u003eWithEnvironment\u003c/code\u003e call in AppHost scoped to one project, not leaked as a global env var. Scoping secrets to the service that uses them limits blast radius.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":7,"id":"quickgrid-pagination","title":"Paginate a Blazor QuickGrid to 15 rows per page","lang":"cs","tags":["blazor","quickgrid","pagination"],"source":"Labs/W07 QuickGrid/ Q1 (variant — pure pagination wiring, no filter or sort, simpler than the lab's combined Q1+Q2+Q3)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou have a Blazor Server page with an \u003ccode\u003eIQueryable&lt;Student&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;QuickGrid&gt;\u003c/code\u003e already bound to it. The grid currently shows every row. Add pagination so the grid displays 15 rows per page, with a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;Paginator&gt;\u003c/code\u003e control under the grid that lets the user move through pages.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"@page \"/students\"\n@rendermode InteractiveServer\n@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid\n\n\u003ch1\u003eStudents\u003c/h1\u003e\n\n\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@_students\"\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.Id)\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.LastName)\" /\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\n@* TODO: add a \u003cPaginator\u003e component under the grid. *@\n\n@code {\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e _students = Student.GetStudents();\n\n    // TODO: declare a PaginationState set to 15 items per page\n    //       and wire it into the QuickGrid via its Pagination attribute.\n}","solution":"@page \"/students\"\n@rendermode InteractiveServer\n@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid\n\n\u003ch1\u003eStudents\u003c/h1\u003e\n\n\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@_students\" Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.Id)\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.LastName)\" /\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\n\u003cPaginator State=\"@_pagination\" /\u003e\n\n@code {\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e _students = Student.GetStudents();\n    private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePaginationState\u003c/code\u003e is a stateful object that tracks \u003ccode\u003eCurrentPageIndex\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eItemsPerPage\u003c/code\u003e. Binding the QuickGrid&#39;s \u003ccode\u003ePagination\u003c/code\u003e attribute to it tells the grid which slice of \u003ccode\u003eItems\u003c/code\u003e to render. The \u003ccode\u003e&lt;Paginator&gt;\u003c/code\u003e component reads and writes the same state object; clicks on first/prev/next/last mutate \u003ccode\u003eCurrentPageIndex\u003c/code\u003e, which QuickGrid watches and re-renders on.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBoth components must bind to the \u003cstrong\u003esame\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ePaginationState\u003c/code\u003e instance — they coordinate through shared state, not events.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDeclaring \u003ccode\u003ePaginationState\u003c/code\u003e as a local variable inside a method.\u003c/strong\u003e Each render creates a fresh instance, so page navigation never advances. The state must be a \u003ccode\u003e@code\u003c/code\u003e-block field so it survives component re-renders.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003e.ToList()\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003e_students\u003c/code\u003e before binding.\u003c/strong\u003e QuickGrid paginates in .NET over the materialized list, losing EF Core&#39;s ability to issue \u003ccode\u003eOFFSET / FETCH\u003c/code\u003e at the database. For large tables this loads every row into memory on every page change.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting \u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveServer\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The initial render produces a grid and a paginator, but clicks on the paginator do nothing because there&#39;s no client-side runtime. A static-server-rendered page can display data but cannot respond to interaction.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":8,"id":"quickgrid-filter","title":"Live filter a Blazor QuickGrid by last name","lang":"cs","tags":["blazor","quickgrid","filter"],"source":"Labs/W07 QuickGrid/ Q2 (variant — filter by last name only, simpler than the lab's multi-keyword matcher that searches multiple fields)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eExtend the students grid so that a text input above the grid live-filters the displayed rows by \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e. The filter is case-insensitive and updates on every keystroke. When the input is empty, the grid shows every student.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"@page \"/students\"\n@rendermode InteractiveServer\n@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid\n\n\u003ch1\u003eStudents\u003c/h1\u003e\n\n@* TODO: add a text input bound to a filter field. *@\n\n\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@_students\" Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.LastName)\"  Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\n\u003cPaginator State=\"@_pagination\" /\u003e\n\n@code {\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e _students = Student.GetStudents();\n    private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };\n\n    // TODO: add a filter field and a computed IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e\n    //       that filters by LastName.Contains(filter, case-insensitive).\n    //       Bind Items=\"@Filtered\" instead of \"@_students\".\n}","solution":"@page \"/students\"\n@rendermode InteractiveServer\n@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid\n\n\u003ch1\u003eStudents\u003c/h1\u003e\n\n\u003cinput @bind=\"_filter\" @bind:event=\"oninput\" placeholder=\"Filter last name...\" /\u003e\n\n\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@Filtered\" Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.LastName)\"  Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\n\u003cPaginator State=\"@_pagination\" /\u003e\n\n@code {\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e _students = Student.GetStudents();\n    private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };\n    private string _filter = string.Empty;\n\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e Filtered =\u003e\n        string.IsNullOrEmpty(_filter)\n            ? _students\n            : _students.Where(s =\u003e\n                s.LastName.Contains(_filter, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@bind=&quot;_filter&quot;\u003c/code\u003e round-trips the input value into the \u003ccode\u003e_filter\u003c/code\u003e field. \u003ccode\u003e@bind:event=&quot;oninput&quot;\u003c/code\u003e changes the update trigger from the default \u003ccode\u003eonchange\u003c/code\u003e (fires on focus loss) to \u003ccode\u003eoninput\u003c/code\u003e (fires on every keystroke) — without that change, users see no filtering until they tab out of the input.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003eFiltered\u003c/code\u003e property is a computed \u003ccode\u003eIQueryable&lt;Student&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Each re-render re-evaluates it and the grid sees a new source; QuickGrid handles the diff internally.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003e@bind\u003c/code\u003e without \u003ccode\u003e@bind:event=&quot;oninput&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The filter only kicks in when the input loses focus — functional but non-obvious for users who expect instant feedback.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMaterializing to \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003e.ToList()\u003c/code\u003e inside \u003ccode\u003eFiltered\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e That destroys IQueryable and forces EF Core to pull the entire student table into memory on every keystroke. Keep the expression as IQueryable so the database does the work.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003eStateHasChanged()\u003c/code\u003e manually after setting \u003ccode\u003e_filter\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e@bind\u003c/code\u003e already triggers a re-render; manual calls are redundant and sometimes mask ordering bugs where the filter value updates after the grid has already started rendering.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":9,"id":"quickgrid-sort","title":"Sort a TemplateColumn in Blazor QuickGrid","lang":"cs","tags":["blazor","quickgrid","sort","gridsort"],"source":"Labs/W07 QuickGrid/ Q3 (variant — a single multi-key sortable TemplateColumn, simpler than the lab's combined sort-across-all-columns exercise)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eReplace the separate \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e \u003ccode\u003ePropertyColumn\u003c/code\u003es with one \u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e titled &quot;Full name&quot; that renders \u003ccode\u003e&quot;@context.FirstName @context.LastName&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. The column must be sortable by the user — clicking the header sorts by \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e first, then by \u003ccode\u003eFirstName\u003c/code\u003e as a tie-breaker.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@_students\" Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.FirstName)\" Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n    \u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(s =\u003e s.LastName)\"  Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\n@code {\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e _students = Student.GetStudents();\n    private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };\n\n    // TODO: declare a GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e that sorts by LastName then FirstName.\n    // TODO: replace the two PropertyColumns with one TemplateColumn\n    //       that renders full name and is sortable via the GridSort.\n}","solution":"\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@_students\" Pagination=\"@_pagination\"\u003e\n    \u003cTemplateColumn Title=\"Full name\" SortBy=\"@_sortByFull\"\u003e\n        \u003cdiv\u003e@context.FirstName @context.LastName\u003c/div\u003e\n    \u003c/TemplateColumn\u003e\n\u003c/QuickGrid\u003e\n\n@code {\n    private IQueryable\u003cStudent\u003e _students = Student.GetStudents();\n    private PaginationState _pagination = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };\n\n    private GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e _sortByFull =\n        GridSort\u003cStudent\u003e.ByAscending(s =\u003e s.LastName)\n                         .ThenAscending(s =\u003e s.FirstName);\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e renders arbitrary markup using the \u003ccode\u003e@context\u003c/code\u003e variable (the current row&#39;s data item). Because the template can reference any combination of properties, QuickGrid cannot infer a sort key — you must supply one via \u003ccode\u003eSortBy\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eGridSort&lt;Student&gt;\u003c/code\u003e builds the expression fluently. \u003ccode\u003eByAscending(s =&gt; s.LastName)\u003c/code\u003e picks the primary key; \u003ccode\u003eThenAscending(s =&gt; s.FirstName)\u003c/code\u003e tie-breaks ties on \u003ccode\u003eLastName\u003c/code\u003e. Chain more \u003ccode\u003e.ThenAscending\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e.ThenDescending\u003c/code\u003e calls for additional tie-breakers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSetting \u003ccode\u003eSortable=&quot;true&quot;\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn\u003c/code\u003e instead of supplying \u003ccode\u003eSortBy\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The header shows no sort arrow because QuickGrid has no key. Remove \u003ccode\u003eSortable\u003c/code\u003e and add \u003ccode\u003eSortBy=&quot;@_sortByFull&quot;\u003c/code\u003e instead.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBuilding the \u003ccode\u003eGridSort&lt;Student&gt;\u003c/code\u003e inside the markup.\u003c/strong\u003e Each render creates a fresh sort object; QuickGrid compares by reference and treats every render as &quot;sort changed,&quot; producing excess work. Declare the field once in \u003ccode\u003e@code\u003c/code\u003e and reuse.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSorting on a computed property inside the template\u003c/strong\u003e — e.g. \u003ccode\u003ex =&gt; $&quot;{x.FirstName} {x.LastName}&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. EF Core cannot translate a formatted string into SQL, so the sort either falls back to in-memory (loading every row) or throws. Use the two underlying properties with \u003ccode\u003eThenAscending\u003c/code\u003e chaining instead.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":10,"id":"localization-add-culture","title":"Register French as a supported culture in Program.cs","lang":"cs","tags":["i18n","program-cs","request-localization"],"source":"Labs/W10 Localization/ Q1 (variant — adding one additional culture to an English-only app, simpler than the lab which added four cultures plus a switcher)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou have an existing Razor Pages app that currently only supports English. Add French as a supported culture so that \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e loads French \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e files when \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003efr\u003c/code\u003e. Use \u003ccode\u003eResources/\u003c/code\u003e as the resource root. English must remain the default.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\n// TODO: register localization services with ResourcesPath = \"Resources\".\n// TODO: configure RequestLocalizationOptions for English and French,\n//       with English as the default.\n\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorPages()\n    .AddViewLocalization();\n\nvar app = builder.Build();\n\n// TODO: enable UseRequestLocalization middleware.\n\napp.MapRazorPages();\napp.Run();","solution":"using System.Globalization;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Localization;\n\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n\nbuilder.Services.AddLocalization(opts =\u003e opts.ResourcesPath = \"Resources\");\n\nbuilder.Services.Configure\u003cRequestLocalizationOptions\u003e(opts =\u003e\n{\n    var supported = new[]\n    {\n        new CultureInfo(\"en\"),\n        new CultureInfo(\"fr\"),\n    };\n    opts.DefaultRequestCulture = new RequestCulture(\"en\");\n    opts.SupportedCultures     = supported;\n    opts.SupportedUICultures   = supported;\n});\n\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorPages()\n    .AddViewLocalization();\n\nvar app = builder.Build();\n\napp.UseRequestLocalization();\n\napp.MapRazorPages();\napp.Run();","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThree service registrations plus one middleware call are the minimum to flip a single-language app into a multi-culture app.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddLocalization(opts =&gt; opts.ResourcesPath = &quot;Resources&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e tells the framework where \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e files live. \u003ccode\u003eRequestLocalizationOptions.SupportedCultures\u003c/code\u003e sets which values \u003ccode\u003eThread.CurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e (formatting) may take; \u003ccode\u003eSupportedUICultures\u003c/code\u003e sets which values \u003ccode\u003eThread.CurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e (resource lookup) may take. Both must be set, typically to the same list, or you end up with a half-localized page.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eapp.UseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e is the middleware that runs the registered culture providers on each request and applies the result. Without it, the options are configured but nothing executes them.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting \u003ccode\u003eapp.UseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Services are registered, resource files exist, but no request ever has its culture set from the providers. \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;[&quot;Key&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e always returns the English value.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSetting \u003ccode\u003eSupportedCultures\u003c/code\u003e but not \u003ccode\u003eSupportedUICultures\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Numbers format in French, but strings stay in English because \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e never changes from the default. Always set both.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eImporting \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Globalization\u003c/code\u003e but omitting \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.AspNetCore.Localization\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eCultureInfo\u003c/code\u003e comes from the first namespace, but \u003ccode\u003eRequestCulture\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eCookieRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e come from the second. The code compiles only when both are imported.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"applied","n":11,"id":"localization-switcher-ui","title":"Build a culture-switcher dropdown that persists the user's choice","tags":["i18n","ui","cookie"],"source":"Labs/W10 Localization/ Q2 (variant — a single switcher in a partial that POSTs to one handler, simpler than the lab's multi-partial + multi-handler breakdown)","problem_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou have an app with \u003ccode\u003eAddLocalization\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eRequestLocalizationOptions\u003c/code\u003e declaring \u003ccode\u003een\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003efr\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e middleware all in place. Now add a language-selector UI:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA \u003ccode\u003e&lt;select&gt;\u003c/code\u003e dropdown in the footer showing every supported culture (the user can click to change).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSelecting a culture POSTs to a handler that writes the \u003ccode\u003e.AspNetCore.Culture\u003c/code\u003e cookie and redirects back to the page the user was on.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe chosen culture persists across browser restarts (cookie \u003ccode\u003eExpires\u003c/code\u003e = 1 year).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe URL displayed is irrelevant; the switcher must work regardless of the current route. Describe the markup and the handler code, then trace what happens on the first reload after switching.\u003c/p\u003e","walkthrough_html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBuild the cultureItems list.\u003c/strong\u003e In a shared partial \u003ccode\u003e_SelectLanguagePartial.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e, inject \u003ccode\u003eIOptions&lt;RequestLocalizationOptions&gt;\u003c/code\u003e to read the declared \u003ccode\u003eSupportedUICultures\u003c/code\u003e. Convert each to a \u003ccode\u003eSelectListItem\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eValue = c.Name\u003c/code\u003e (e.g. \u003ccode\u003e&quot;fr&quot;\u003c/code\u003e) and \u003ccode\u003eText = c.DisplayName\u003c/code\u003e (e.g. \u003ccode\u003e&quot;French (France)&quot;\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRender the form.\u003c/strong\u003e Use a Razor form that POSTs to an \u003ccode\u003eOnPost\u003c/code\u003e handler on the current page:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cshtml\"\u003e@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Localization\n@inject IOptions&lt;RequestLocalizationOptions&gt; LocOpts\n\n@{\n    var current = Context.Features.Get&lt;IRequestCultureFeature&gt;();\n    var items = LocOpts.Value.SupportedUICultures!\n        .Select(c =&gt; new SelectListItem { Value = c.Name, Text = c.DisplayName })\n        .ToList();\n}\n\n&lt;form asp-page=&quot;/Index&quot; method=&quot;post&quot;&gt;\n    &lt;select name=&quot;culture&quot;\n            onchange=&quot;this.form.submit();&quot;\n            asp-for=&quot;@current!.RequestCulture.UICulture.Name&quot;\n            asp-items=&quot;items&quot;&gt;\n    &lt;/select&gt;\n    &lt;input type=&quot;hidden&quot; name=&quot;returnUrl&quot; value=&quot;@Context.Request.Path&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;/form&gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWrite the \u003ccode\u003eOnPost\u003c/code\u003e handler.\u003c/strong\u003e In the PageModel:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003epublic IActionResult OnPost(string culture, string returnUrl)\n{\n    Response.Cookies.Append(\n        CookieRequestCultureProvider.DefaultCookieName,\n        CookieRequestCultureProvider.MakeCookieValue(new RequestCulture(culture)),\n        new CookieOptions { Expires = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow.AddYears(1) });\n\n    return LocalRedirect(returnUrl);\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eDefaultCookieName\u003c/code\u003e is the built-in value \u003ccode\u003e.AspNetCore.Culture\u003c/code\u003e that \u003ccode\u003eCookieRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e looks for. \u003ccode\u003eMakeCookieValue\u003c/code\u003e formats the string exactly the way the provider expects (\u003ccode\u003ec=&lt;culture&gt;|uic=&lt;uiculture&gt;\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrace the first reload.\u003c/strong\u003e The user selects \u003ccode\u003efr\u003c/code\u003e and the form submits. The handler writes \u003ccode\u003e.AspNetCore.Culture=c=fr|uic=fr\u003c/code\u003e as a cookie with a 1-year expiry, then \u003ccode\u003eLocalRedirect\u003c/code\u003es back to the same page. On the redirected GET, \u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization\u003c/code\u003e runs its providers in order: \u003ccode\u003eQueryStringRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e finds nothing (no \u003ccode\u003e?culture=\u003c/code\u003e), \u003ccode\u003eCookieRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e reads \u003ccode\u003e.AspNetCore.Culture=c=fr|uic=fr\u003c/code\u003e and returns \u003ccode\u003efr\u003c/code\u003e, so \u003ccode\u003eThread.CurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e both become \u003ccode\u003efr\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e now returns French values; dates and numbers format in French.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","common_wrong_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNot passing \u003ccode\u003ereturnUrl\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eLocalRedirect(&quot;/&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e hard-codes the home page, so switching languages on any deep page bounces the user back to the top. Pass the current path as a hidden field and redirect there instead.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003eRedirect(returnUrl)\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003eLocalRedirect(returnUrl)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eRedirect\u003c/code\u003e accepts any URL, including external ones, which opens an open-redirect vulnerability if \u003ccode\u003ereturnUrl\u003c/code\u003e comes from user input. \u003ccode\u003eLocalRedirect\u003c/code\u003e rejects absolute URLs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSetting the cookie without \u003ccode\u003eCookieOptions.Expires\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Without an expiry the cookie becomes a session cookie that disappears when the browser closes. Users expect a persistent language choice — always set \u003ccode\u003eExpires\u003c/code\u003e at least months out.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003eCookieRequestCultureProvider.MakeCookieValue(new RequestCulture(culture, culture))\u003c/code\u003e redundantly.\u003c/strong\u003e The single-arg form already sets both \u003ccode\u003eCulture\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eUICulture\u003c/code\u003e. Adding the second arg only differs when you deliberately want dates in one locale and UI strings in another — rarely desired.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","why_html":"\u003cp\u003ePersistent language selection requires coordination between three moving parts: the UI (dropdown with \u003ccode\u003eonchange=&quot;this.form.submit();&quot;\u003c/code\u003e), the server handler (cookie write + \u003ccode\u003eLocalRedirect\u003c/code\u003e), and the middleware pipeline (\u003ccode\u003eCookieRequestCultureProvider\u003c/code\u003e reading \u003ccode\u003e.AspNetCore.Culture\u003c/code\u003e on subsequent requests). The cookie format is non-negotiable — the provider knows exactly which name and value shape to look for. The year-long expiry makes the choice survive browser restarts; the \u003ccode\u003eLocalRedirect\u003c/code\u003e keeps users on the page they were viewing; and the whole mechanism works on every page without per-page handler code because the form POSTs to a single \u003ccode\u003eOnPost(culture, returnUrl)\u003c/code\u003e method that sits on a base PageModel or on a dedicated \u003ccode\u003e/LanguageSwitcher\u003c/code\u003e handler.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":12,"id":"localization-translate-page","title":"Translate a Razor page's PageModel + view strings","lang":"cs","tags":["i18n","di","istringlocalizer","iviewlocalizer"],"source":"Labs/W10 Localization/ Q3 (variant — translate exactly two strings on one page, simpler than the lab's full-site string pass)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eAn \u003ccode\u003eIndex.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e page has two strings that need translation: a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;h1&gt;\u003c/code\u003e welcome heading rendered directly in markup, and a \u003ccode\u003e&lt;p&gt;\u003c/code\u003e message whose text is set in the PageModel via \u003ccode\u003eViewData[&quot;Message&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e. The page already has \u003ccode\u003e@inject IViewLocalizer Localizer\u003c/code\u003e available and the PageModel already constructor-injects \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;IndexModel&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Replace the hardcoded English strings with localized lookups that pick up translations from \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.&lt;culture&gt;.resx\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"// Pages/Index.cshtml.cs\npublic class IndexModel : PageModel\n{\n    private readonly IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e _localizer;\n\n    public IndexModel(IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e localizer)\n        =\u003e _localizer = localizer;\n\n    public void OnGet()\n    {\n        // TODO: replace the hardcoded English with a localized lookup\n        //       using the key \"Message\".\n        ViewData[\"Message\"] = \"This is the message.\";\n    }\n}\n\n// Pages/Index.cshtml\n@page\n@inject IViewLocalizer Localizer\n@model IndexModel\n\n// TODO: replace the hardcoded \"Welcome\" with a localized lookup\n//       using the key \"Welcome\".\n\u003ch1\u003eWelcome\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e@ViewData[\"Message\"]\u003c/p\u003e","solution":"// Pages/Index.cshtml.cs\npublic class IndexModel : PageModel\n{\n    private readonly IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e _localizer;\n\n    public IndexModel(IStringLocalizer\u003cIndexModel\u003e localizer)\n        =\u003e _localizer = localizer;\n\n    public void OnGet()\n    {\n        ViewData[\"Message\"] = _localizer[\"Message\"];\n    }\n}\n\n// Pages/Index.cshtml\n@page\n@inject IViewLocalizer Localizer\n@model IndexModel\n\n\u003ch1\u003e@Localizer[\"Welcome\"]\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e@ViewData[\"Message\"]\u003c/p\u003e","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou also need two resource files, \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.en.resx\u003c/code\u003e (or no-suffix default) with keys \u003ccode\u003eWelcome → Welcome\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eMessage → This is the message.\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e with \u003ccode\u003eWelcome → Bienvenue\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eMessage → Ceci est le message.\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe view uses \u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e for strings rendered directly from markup; the PageModel uses \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;IndexModel&gt;\u003c/code\u003e for strings that are computed in code and passed through \u003ccode\u003eViewData\u003c/code\u003e. Both resolve against the same resource file — \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.&lt;culture&gt;.resx\u003c/code\u003e — because the generic type parameter on \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;IndexModel&gt;\u003c/code\u003e and the implicit type parameter on \u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e (the view&#39;s generated class) map to the same .resx naming path.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe indexer \u003ccode\u003e_localizer[&quot;Key&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eLocalizer[&quot;Key&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e does three things in sequence: look up the current \u003ccode\u003eCultureInfo\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003eThread.CurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e, find the matching \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e file (falling back through the parent-culture chain), read the key. If the key isn&#39;t present in any \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e, the indexer returns the key itself as a literal string — so a missing translation shows up as &quot;Welcome&quot; instead of &quot;Bienvenue&quot; rather than blowing up.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003e@Html.Raw(Localizer[&quot;Welcome&quot;])\u003c/code\u003e unnecessarily.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e returns a \u003ccode\u003eLocalizedHtmlString\u003c/code\u003e that Razor already knows how to render. \u003ccode\u003e@Html.Raw\u003c/code\u003e is only needed when you want to bypass HTML encoding, which matters for \u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e content (not \u003ccode\u003eIViewLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInjecting \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer\u003c/code\u003e (non-generic) into the PageModel.\u003c/strong\u003e Without the \u003ccode\u003e&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e parameter, DI can&#39;t decide which resource file to target. The correct injection is \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;IndexModel&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePutting the .resx file at \u003ccode\u003eResources/IndexModel.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e (missing the \u003ccode\u003ePages/\u003c/code\u003e subfolder).\u003c/strong\u003e Directory layout under \u003ccode\u003eResources/\u003c/code\u003e must mirror the class location. With the wrong path the file is invisible to the localizer, which silently falls back to the default culture or returns the key.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":13,"id":"filebased-json-read","title":"Deserialize students.json in a file-based app","lang":"cs","tags":["dotnet-10","file-based","json","deserialize"],"source":"Labs/W11 File Based C# Apps/ Q1 (variant — deserialize one JSON file into a typed list and print the count, simpler than the lab's multi-field filter)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eGiven a file \u003ccode\u003estudents.json\u003c/code\u003e (a JSON array of \u003ccode\u003e{ name, school, dob, gender }\u003c/code\u003e objects) in the current directory, write a file-based C# app (\u003ccode\u003ereadStudents.cs\u003c/code\u003e) that:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReads the file with \u003ccode\u003eFile.ReadAllText\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDeserializes it into a \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;Student&gt;\u003c/code\u003e using \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Text.Json\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePrints \u003ccode\u003eLoaded N students.\u003c/code\u003e where N is the count.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUse a \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e record declared below the top-level code.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"// readStudents.cs\n\n// TODO: read students.json, deserialize into a List\u003cStudent\u003e,\n//       and print the count.\n\npublic record Student(string Name, string School, string Dob, string Gender);","solution":"// readStudents.cs\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar json = File.ReadAllText(\"students.json\");\nvar students = JsonSerializer.Deserialize\u003cList\u003cStudent\u003e\u003e(\n    json,\n    new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true });\n\nConsole.WriteLine($\"Loaded {students?.Count ?? 0} students.\");\n\npublic record Student(string Name, string School, string Dob, string Gender);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThree file-based-app idioms show up. First, top-level statements replace \u003ccode\u003eMain\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003eFile.ReadAllText(...)\u003c/code\u003e runs at the top of the file. Second, implicit usings cover \u003ccode\u003eSystem.IO\u003c/code\u003e (for \u003ccode\u003eFile\u003c/code\u003e) and \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Collections.Generic\u003c/code\u003e (for \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e), so no \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e directives are needed for those. \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Text.Json\u003c/code\u003e is NOT implicit, so it needs an explicit \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e. Third, type declarations (the \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e record) live below top-level statements — the compiler rewrites the file so top-level code goes into an implicit \u003ccode\u003eMain\u003c/code\u003e and type declarations are compiled as peers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003ePropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true\u003c/code\u003e lets your PascalCase C# record match typical camelCase JSON. Without it, deserialization returns a list where every property is null.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRun with \u003ccode\u003edotnet run readStudents.cs\u003c/code\u003e. Output: \u003ccode\u003eLoaded 6 students.\u003c/code\u003e (or whatever the file contains).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDeclaring \u003ccode\u003eStudent\u003c/code\u003e above the top-level code.\u003c/strong\u003e The compiler requires type declarations after top-level statements. Moving the record to the top of the file produces a compilation error.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting \u003ccode\u003ePropertyNameCaseInsensitive\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e JSON like \u003ccode\u003e{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Alice&quot;}\u003c/code\u003e won&#39;t bind to a property \u003ccode\u003eName\u003c/code\u003e by default — properties come out as their default values (null for strings). Case-insensitive matching bridges the case convention gap.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003eargs[0]\u003c/code\u003e as the filename without a fallback.\u003c/strong\u003e If the script is invoked without args (\u003ccode\u003edotnet run readStudents.cs\u003c/code\u003e), \u003ccode\u003eargs[0]\u003c/code\u003e throws IndexOutOfRange. Hardcode the filename or guard with \u003ccode\u003eargs.Length &gt; 0\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":14,"id":"filebased-filter","title":"Filter a deserialized list by keyword (case-insensitive)","lang":"cs","tags":["dotnet-10","file-based","linq","filter"],"source":"Labs/W11 File Based C# Apps/ Q2 (variant — filter by Name substring only, simpler than the lab which searched Name OR School OR Dob OR Gender)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eExtend the previous script (\u003ccode\u003ereadStudents.cs\u003c/code\u003e) to accept a \u003ccode\u003ekeyword\u003c/code\u003e command-line argument. Filter the loaded \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;Student&gt;\u003c/code\u003e to rows where the \u003ccode\u003eName\u003c/code\u003e property contains the keyword (case-insensitive). Print each matching student&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eName\u003c/code\u003e. If no keyword is supplied, print every student.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"// readStudents.cs\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar json = File.ReadAllText(\"students.json\");\nvar students = JsonSerializer.Deserialize\u003cList\u003cStudent\u003e\u003e(\n    json,\n    new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true }) ?? new();\n\n// TODO: read an optional keyword from args and filter students by Name.\n// TODO: print each matching student's Name on its own line.\n\npublic record Student(string Name, string School, string Dob, string Gender);","solution":"// readStudents.cs\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar json = File.ReadAllText(\"students.json\");\nvar students = JsonSerializer.Deserialize\u003cList\u003cStudent\u003e\u003e(\n    json,\n    new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true }) ?? new();\n\nvar keyword = args.Length \u003e 0 ? args[0] : null;\n\nvar matches = keyword is null\n    ? students\n    : students.Where(s =\u003e s.Name.Contains(keyword, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));\n\nforeach (var s in matches)\n    Console.WriteLine(s.Name);\n\npublic record Student(string Name, string School, string Dob, string Gender);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eargs\u003c/code\u003e is available at the top level in every file-based app. The ternary \u003ccode\u003eargs.Length &gt; 0 ? args[0] : null\u003c/code\u003e defaults gracefully when the user invokes \u003ccode\u003edotnet run readStudents.cs -- \u003c/code\u003e without a value. \u003ccode\u003estring.Contains(..., StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase)\u003c/code\u003e is the .NET 5+ overload that skips \u003ccode\u003e.ToLower()\u003c/code\u003e allocations and normalizes consistently across cultures.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eInvoke with \u003ccode\u003edotnet run readStudents.cs -- alice\u003c/code\u003e. Without the \u003ccode\u003e--\u003c/code\u003e, the CLI consumes \u003ccode\u003ealice\u003c/code\u003e as its own argument and your script sees empty \u003ccode\u003eargs\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003e.ToLower()\u003c/code\u003e on both sides of the comparison.\u003c/strong\u003e It works but allocates a new string per row — fine for a script, expensive in a hot loop. \u003ccode\u003eStringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase\u003c/code\u003e avoids the allocation.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting the \u003ccode\u003e--\u003c/code\u003e when running.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003edotnet run readStudents.cs alice\u003c/code\u003e hands \u003ccode\u003ealice\u003c/code\u003e to the CLI (which ignores it silently or errors). Everything after \u003ccode\u003e--\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003eargs\u003c/code\u003e inside the script.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReturning the filtered query as \u003ccode\u003eIEnumerable\u003c/code\u003e and enumerating it twice.\u003c/strong\u003e LINQ queries are lazy — iterating a \u003ccode\u003eWhere\u003c/code\u003e result twice re-evaluates the predicate per row. For small data it doesn&#39;t matter; for large data, materialize with \u003ccode\u003e.ToList()\u003c/code\u003e once.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":15,"id":"filebased-spectre-table","title":"Render results as a Spectre.Console table using #:package","lang":"cs","tags":["dotnet-10","file-based","directive","spectre-console"],"source":"Labs/W11 File Based C# Apps/ Q3 (variant — single-column rendered table of names, simpler than the lab which rendered a multi-column Spectre table with borders, colors, and title)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eReplace the plain \u003ccode\u003eConsole.WriteLine(s.Name)\u003c/code\u003e output in the filter script with a bordered Spectre.Console table. The table has one column titled &quot;Name&quot; and one row per matching student. Declare the package dependency inline via \u003ccode\u003e#:package\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"// filterStudents.cs\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\n// TODO: declare a #:package directive for Spectre.Console.\n// TODO: import Spectre.Console.\n\nvar json = File.ReadAllText(\"students.json\");\nvar students = JsonSerializer.Deserialize\u003cList\u003cStudent\u003e\u003e(\n    json,\n    new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true }) ?? new();\n\nvar keyword = args.Length \u003e 0 ? args[0] : null;\nvar matches = keyword is null\n    ? students\n    : students.Where(s =\u003e s.Name.Contains(keyword, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));\n\n// TODO: render matches as a bordered Spectre table with one \"Name\" column.\nforeach (var s in matches)\n    Console.WriteLine(s.Name);\n\npublic record Student(string Name, string School, string Dob, string Gender);","solution":"// filterStudents.cs\n#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1\n\nusing System.Text.Json;\nusing Spectre.Console;\n\nvar json = File.ReadAllText(\"students.json\");\nvar students = JsonSerializer.Deserialize\u003cList\u003cStudent\u003e\u003e(\n    json,\n    new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true }) ?? new();\n\nvar keyword = args.Length \u003e 0 ? args[0] : null;\nvar matches = keyword is null\n    ? students\n    : students.Where(s =\u003e s.Name.Contains(keyword, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));\n\nvar table = new Table();\ntable.Border = TableBorder.Rounded;\ntable.AddColumn(\"Name\");\n\nforeach (var s in matches)\n    table.AddRow(s.Name);\n\nAnsiConsole.Write(table);\n\npublic record Student(string Name, string School, string Dob, string Gender);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1\u003c/code\u003e is the entire package-management story for this script — the CLI downloads Spectre.Console on first run and caches it in \u003ccode\u003e~/.dotnet/runfile/\u003c/code\u003e. No NuGet restore, no \u003ccode\u003e.csproj\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAnsiConsole.Write(table)\u003c/code\u003e is the Spectre pattern for rendering. Spectre tables support borders (\u003ccode\u003eTableBorder.Rounded\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eHeavy\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eDouble\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eNone\u003c/code\u003e), column alignment, styled text (\u003ccode\u003e[green]Name[/]\u003c/code\u003e), and cell colors — all out of scope for this practice but easy additions.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#: package Spectre.Console@0.49.1\u003c/code\u003e (space after the colon).\u003c/strong\u003e Syntax error. The directive name must sit flush against \u003ccode\u003e#:\u003c/code\u003e. The spaced form is the single most-tested exam distractor.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting the version pin (\u003ccode\u003e@0.49.1\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/strong\u003e The CLI pulls the latest version on first run, which may subtly change the API between sessions. Pinning a version makes the script reproducible across machines and months.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCalling \u003ccode\u003eConsole.WriteLine(table)\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003eAnsiConsole.Write(table)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Spectre tables don&#39;t have a meaningful \u003ccode\u003eToString()\u003c/code\u003e — you see \u003ccode\u003eSpectre.Console.Table\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003eAnsiConsole.Write\u003c/code\u003e drives the actual rendering with ANSI escape codes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":16,"id":"filebased-cli-args","title":"Accept keyword from command-line args in a file-based app","lang":"cs","tags":["dotnet-10","file-based","cli","args"],"source":"Labs/W11 File Based C# Apps/ Q4 (variant — default to \"medicine\" keyword when no arg given, matching the lab's start.sh default behavior)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eModify the filter script so that when \u003ccode\u003edotnet run filterStudents.cs -- &lt;keyword&gt;\u003c/code\u003e is invoked with no keyword, the script defaults to \u003ccode\u003e&quot;medicine&quot;\u003c/code\u003e (matching the lab&#39;s \u003ccode\u003estart.sh\u003c/code\u003e convention) instead of listing every student. When a keyword IS supplied, use it.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ePrint the effective keyword on the first line: \u003ccode\u003eFiltering by: &lt;keyword&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"// filterStudents.cs\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar json = File.ReadAllText(\"students.json\");\nvar students = JsonSerializer.Deserialize\u003cList\u003cStudent\u003e\u003e(\n    json,\n    new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true }) ?? new();\n\n// TODO: determine the effective keyword — use args[0] if given,\n//       otherwise default to \"medicine\".\n// TODO: print \"Filtering by: \u003ckeyword\u003e\".\n// TODO: filter by Name OR School containing the keyword.\nforeach (var s in students)\n    Console.WriteLine(s.Name);\n\npublic record Student(string Name, string School, string Dob, string Gender);","solution":"// filterStudents.cs\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar json = File.ReadAllText(\"students.json\");\nvar students = JsonSerializer.Deserialize\u003cList\u003cStudent\u003e\u003e(\n    json,\n    new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true }) ?? new();\n\nvar keyword = args.Length \u003e 0 ? args[0] : \"medicine\";\nConsole.WriteLine($\"Filtering by: {keyword}\");\n\nvar matches = students.Where(s =\u003e\n    s.Name.Contains(keyword, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase) ||\n    s.School.Contains(keyword, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));\n\nforeach (var s in matches)\n    Console.WriteLine($\"  {s.Name} ({s.School})\");\n\npublic record Student(string Name, string School, string Dob, string Gender);","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe default-value pattern \u003ccode\u003eargs.Length &gt; 0 ? args[0] : &quot;medicine&quot;\u003c/code\u003e mirrors what the lab&#39;s \u003ccode\u003estart.sh\u003c/code\u003e does: if the user doesn&#39;t type a keyword, apply a sensible default. This is common in CLI tools — a zero-arg run should still do something useful rather than listing everything or erroring.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eExtending the predicate to search both \u003ccode\u003eName\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eSchool\u003c/code\u003e is a single \u003ccode\u003e||\u003c/code\u003e between two \u003ccode\u003e.Contains(...)\u003c/code\u003e calls. With more than two fields, a helper method keeps the lambda readable.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRun examples:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003edotnet run filterStudents.cs\u003c/code\u003e → keyword = \u003ccode\u003e&quot;medicine&quot;\u003c/code\u003e (default).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003edotnet run filterStudents.cs -- alice\u003c/code\u003e → keyword = \u003ccode\u003e&quot;alice&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003edotnet run filterStudents.cs -- &quot;St. Mary&quot;\u003c/code\u003e → keyword = \u003ccode\u003e&quot;St. Mary&quot;\u003c/code\u003e (quotes keep the space).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eChecking \u003ccode\u003eargs.Length &gt;= 0\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Always true. The predicate must be \u003ccode\u003e&gt; 0\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e== 1\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAccessing \u003ccode\u003eargs[0]\u003c/code\u003e without a length guard.\u003c/strong\u003e If the user runs with no args, \u003ccode\u003eargs[0]\u003c/code\u003e throws \u003ccode\u003eIndexOutOfRangeException\u003c/code\u003e. The ternary is the idiomatic fix.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDefaulting to \u003ccode\u003estring.Empty\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003enull\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Empty-string \u003ccode\u003eContains\u003c/code\u003e matches everything (every string contains the empty string), so the filter returns the full list — technically not wrong but hides the intent. Using a real default like \u003ccode\u003e&quot;medicine&quot;\u003c/code\u003e makes the zero-arg behavior match the lab&#39;s scripted demo.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":17,"id":"xlsx-export","title":"Export a list to Excel via ClosedXML","lang":"cs","tags":["excel","closedxml","file-result","razor-pages"],"source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/ Q2 (variant — two-column player export, simpler than the lab's multi-column FIFA game table with styling)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eOn a Razor Page handler \u003ccode\u003eOnGet\u003c/code\u003e, produce an Excel download named \u003ccode\u003eplayers.xlsx\u003c/code\u003e containing two columns — \u003ccode\u003eName\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eScore\u003c/code\u003e — with one row per entry in \u003ccode\u003ePlayer.All()\u003c/code\u003e. Style the header row with a light-gray fill. Return the result as a \u003ccode\u003eFileResult\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"using ClosedXML.Excel;\nusing System.IO;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.RazorPages;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;\n\npublic class PlayersModel : PageModel\n{\n    public FileResult OnGet()\n    {\n        // TODO: build an XLWorkbook, add a \"Players\" worksheet,\n        //       write headers + data, style the header row with a gray fill,\n        //       save to a MemoryStream, and return as FileResult\n        //       with filename \"players.xlsx\".\n        throw new NotImplementedException();\n    }\n}","solution":"using ClosedXML.Excel;\nusing System.IO;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.RazorPages;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;\n\npublic class PlayersModel : PageModel\n{\n    public FileResult OnGet()\n    {\n        using var workbook = new XLWorkbook();\n        var sheet = workbook.Worksheets.Add(\"Players\");\n\n        sheet.Cell(1, 1).Value = \"Name\";\n        sheet.Cell(1, 2).Value = \"Score\";\n\n        var header = sheet.Range(sheet.Cell(1, 1).Address, sheet.Cell(1, 2).Address);\n        header.Style.Fill.SetBackgroundColor(XLColor.LightGray);\n        header.Style.Font.Bold = true;\n\n        int row = 2;\n        foreach (var p in Player.All())\n        {\n            sheet.Cell(row, 1).Value = p.Name;\n            sheet.Cell(row, 2).Value = p.Score;\n            row++;\n        }\n\n        sheet.Columns().AdjustToContents();\n\n        using var ms = new MemoryStream();\n        workbook.SaveAs(ms);\n\n        return File(\n            ms.ToArray(),\n            \"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet\",\n            \"players.xlsx\");\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eFive steps — open workbook, add sheet, write headers (row 1) and data (row 2 upward), style the header range, save to a \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e, return a \u003ccode\u003eFileResult\u003c/code\u003e. The header range is styled as a group via \u003ccode\u003eIXLRange.Style\u003c/code\u003e; per-cell styling would work but repeats the Fill + Bold setup per column.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003esheet.Columns().AdjustToContents()\u003c/code\u003e auto-fits column widths after data is written. Without it, the downloaded file opens with every column at the default ~8-character width, forcing the user to drag column dividers before the data is readable.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe MIME type \u003ccode\u003eapplication/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet\u003c/code\u003e is the exact OpenXML spreadsheet identifier. \u003ccode\u003eapplication/excel\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eapplication/vnd.ms-excel\u003c/code\u003e target different formats (or don&#39;t exist) and cause browsers to save the file without a proper extension.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStarting the data loop at \u003ccode\u003erow = 1\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Row 1 is the header; data starts at row 2. Starting at 1 overwrites the headers with the first player&#39;s name.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003esheet.Cell(0, 0)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e ClosedXML cells are 1-based. \u003ccode\u003eCell(0, 0)\u003c/code\u003e either throws or is silently ignored, so the first header never appears.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReturning \u003ccode\u003eFile(ms, mime, name)\u003c/code\u003e with an unclosed \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e on the MemoryStream.\u003c/strong\u003e When using \u003ccode\u003eFile(stream, ...)\u003c/code\u003e, the framework reads from the stream asynchronously — a \u003ccode\u003eusing\u003c/code\u003e disposes the stream before the read completes and the response body is empty. Either return \u003ccode\u003ems.ToArray()\u003c/code\u003e (no stream lifetime issue) or let the framework dispose the stream.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":18,"id":"pdf-players-export","title":"Export a list to PDF via iText 7","lang":"cs","tags":["pdf","itext7","file-stream-result","razor-pages"],"source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/ Q3 (variant — single 'Players' table without page numbering, simpler than the lab's multi-table report with centered title + per-page footer)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eOn a Razor Page handler, produce a PDF download named \u003ccode\u003eplayers.pdf\u003c/code\u003e containing a centered title &quot;Players&quot; followed by a two-column table (\u003ccode\u003eName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eScore\u003c/code\u003e) with one row per entry in \u003ccode\u003ePlayer.All()\u003c/code\u003e. Return the result as a \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e. Assume both \u003ccode\u003eitext7\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eitext.bouncy-castle-adapter\u003c/code\u003e NuGet packages are installed.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"using iText.Kernel.Geom;\nusing iText.Kernel.Pdf;\nusing iText.Layout;\nusing iText.Layout.Element;\nusing iText.Layout.Properties;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.RazorPages;\nusing System.IO;\n\npublic class PdfReportModel : PageModel\n{\n    public IActionResult OnGet()\n    {\n        // TODO: create a MemoryStream, wrap in PdfWriter → PdfDocument → Document.\n        // TODO: call writer.SetCloseStream(false).\n        // TODO: add a centered \"Players\" title, then a 2-column table\n        //       with headers and one row per Player.All().\n        // TODO: close the Document, rewind the stream, return as FileStreamResult.\n        throw new NotImplementedException();\n    }\n}","solution":"using iText.Kernel.Geom;\nusing iText.Kernel.Pdf;\nusing iText.Layout;\nusing iText.Layout.Element;\nusing iText.Layout.Properties;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.RazorPages;\nusing System.IO;\n\npublic class PdfReportModel : PageModel\n{\n    public IActionResult OnGet()\n    {\n        var ms = new MemoryStream();\n\n        var writer = new PdfWriter(ms);\n        var pdfDoc = new PdfDocument(writer);\n        var doc    = new Document(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false);\n        writer.SetCloseStream(false);\n\n        doc.Add(new Paragraph(\"Players\")\n            .SetTextAlignment(TextAlignment.CENTER)\n            .SetFontSize(20));\n\n        var table = new Table(2);\n        table.AddCell(new Cell().Add(new Paragraph(\"Name\")));\n        table.AddCell(new Cell().Add(new Paragraph(\"Score\")));\n\n        foreach (var p in Player.All())\n        {\n            table.AddCell(new Cell().Add(new Paragraph(p.Name)));\n            table.AddCell(new Cell().Add(new Paragraph(p.Score.ToString())));\n        }\n\n        doc.Add(table);\n        doc.Close();\n        ms.Position = 0;\n\n        return new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\")\n        {\n            FileDownloadName = \"players.pdf\"\n        };\n    }\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThe iText pipeline is four layers: \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ePdfWriter(ms)\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ePdfDocument(writer)\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eDocument(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false)\u003c/code\u003e. Each layer wraps the previous. \u003ccode\u003eSetCloseStream(false)\u003c/code\u003e keeps the \u003ccode\u003eMemoryStream\u003c/code\u003e open after \u003ccode\u003edoc.Close()\u003c/code\u003e so you can read it into the response.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003enew Table(2)\u003c/code\u003e creates a two-column table. \u003ccode\u003eAddCell\u003c/code\u003e fills the next cell left-to-right, wrapping to a new row when the count hits \u003ccode\u003e2 * N\u003c/code\u003e. Each \u003ccode\u003eCell\u003c/code\u003e wraps a \u003ccode\u003eParagraph\u003c/code\u003e for text content; you could also style fills, borders, and alignment per cell.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe three-line finish is the whole trap: \u003ccode\u003edoc.Close()\u003c/code\u003e writes the final PDF bytes; \u003ccode\u003ems.Position = 0\u003c/code\u003e rewinds to the start (without it, \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e reads from the end and serves an empty file); \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e produces the response with the correct filename.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting \u003ccode\u003ems.Position = 0\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The MemoryStream&#39;s cursor is at the end after writing. \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e reads from the current position, finds nothing, and the browser downloads a 0-byte PDF labelled &quot;Document is empty or corrupted.&quot;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSkipping \u003ccode\u003ewriter.SetCloseStream(false)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Default behavior closes the underlying stream when the Document closes. Subsequent attempts to read from \u003ccode\u003ems\u003c/code\u003e throw \u003ccode\u003eObjectDisposedException\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInstalling only \u003ccode\u003eitext7\u003c/code\u003e and not \u003ccode\u003eitext.bouncy-castle-adapter\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Compilation succeeds; runtime throws when iText tries to hash or sign content. Install both packages together.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":19,"id":"chartjs-pie","title":"Render a Chart.js pie chart from Razor data","lang":"cs","tags":["chart","chart-js","razor","pie"],"source":"Labs/W13 Excel, PDF, Chart cocktail/ Q4 (variant — render a single pie chart of games-per-continent, simpler than the lab which stacked pie + bar charts on one page with explicit CSS)","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eOn a Razor Page whose \u003ccode\u003eModel.ChartData\u003c/code\u003e is an \u003ccode\u003eIEnumerable&lt;(string Name, int Count)&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, render a Chart.js pie chart. Each slice corresponds to one tuple — the label comes from \u003ccode\u003eName\u003c/code\u003e, the value from \u003ccode\u003eCount\u003c/code\u003e. Load Chart.js from the course CDN URL.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"@page\n@model IndexModel\n\n\u003ch4\u003eGames by Continent\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n@* TODO: add a \u003ccanvas\u003e with id=\"pie-chart\". *@\n\n@* TODO: load Chart.js from the CDN:\n         https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js *@\n\n@* TODO: in a \u003cscript\u003e block, build JS arrays `labels` and `counts`\n         by looping over Model.ChartData with @: directives, then\n         call `new Chart(ctx, { type: 'pie', data: { labels, datasets: [{ data: counts }] } })`. *@","solution":"@page\n@model IndexModel\n\n\u003ch4\u003eGames by Continent\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003ccanvas id=\"pie-chart\" width=\"400\" height=\"400\"\u003e\u003c/canvas\u003e\n\n\u003cscript src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js\"\u003e\u003c/script\u003e\n\n\u003cscript\u003e\n    const labels = [];\n    const counts = [];\n\n    @foreach (var item in Model.ChartData)\n    {\n        @:labels.push('@item.Name');\n        @:counts.push(@item.Count);\n    }\n\n    const ctx = document.getElementById('pie-chart');\n\n    new Chart(ctx, {\n        type: 'pie',\n        data: {\n            labels: labels,\n            datasets: [{\n                label: 'Games',\n                data: counts,\n                backgroundColor: [\n                    'rgba(255, 99, 132, 0.7)',\n                    'rgba(54, 162, 235, 0.7)',\n                    'rgba(255, 206, 86, 0.7)',\n                    'rgba(75, 192, 192, 0.7)',\n                    'rgba(153, 102, 255, 0.7)'\n                ]\n            }]\n        }\n    });\n\u003c/script\u003e","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eThree moving pieces get the chart on screen. The \u003ccode\u003e&lt;canvas&gt;\u003c/code\u003e element receives the drawing; \u003ccode\u003edocument.getElementById(&#39;pie-chart&#39;)\u003c/code\u003e fetches the reference Chart.js needs. The Chart.js \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script src&gt;\u003c/code\u003e must load before the chart-construction \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — keeping both inside \u003ccode\u003e&lt;body&gt;\u003c/code\u003e in order is simplest.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003e@foreach (...)\u003c/code\u003e block builds the JavaScript data arrays by interpolating each tuple&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eName\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eCount\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e@:labels.push(...)\u003c/code\u003e is Razor&#39;s &quot;mixed line&quot; directive — it tells Razor to treat the line as literal output with \u003ccode\u003e@\u003c/code\u003e-expression substitutions. Without \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e, Razor tries to parse the whole line as C# and errors out (or, worse, produces malformed JS).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003enew Chart(ctx, config)\u003c/code\u003e is the library entry point. \u003ccode\u003etype: &#39;pie&#39;\u003c/code\u003e selects the shape; \u003ccode\u003edata.labels\u003c/code\u003e aligns 1:1 with \u003ccode\u003edata.datasets[0].data\u003c/code\u003e — index \u003ccode\u003ei\u003c/code\u003e of one array corresponds to index \u003ccode\u003ei\u003c/code\u003e of the other.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCommon wrong approaches:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOmitting the \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e directive inside the \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script&gt;\u003c/code\u003e block.\u003c/strong\u003e Razor tries to parse \u003ccode\u003elabels.push(...)\u003c/code\u003e as C# and fails, or emits broken JS. \u003ccode\u003e@:\u003c/code\u003e is the signal to Razor that this line mixes JS with \u003ccode\u003e@\u003c/code\u003e-expressions.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePlacing the Chart.js \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script src&gt;\u003c/code\u003e AFTER the construction \u003ccode\u003e&lt;script&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e JavaScript executes top-to-bottom. If the construction block runs before Chart.js has loaded, \u003ccode\u003eChart is not defined\u003c/code\u003e appears in the console and the canvas stays blank.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing fewer colors in \u003ccode\u003ebackgroundColor\u003c/code\u003e than data points.\u003c/strong\u003e Chart.js recycles colors in order, so slices beyond the 5th color repeat the first. For a small fixed dataset this is fine; for variable-length data, compute colors programmatically or use Chart.js plugins for palettes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"}],"cheatSheet":{"blocks":[{"heading":"Exam meta","body_md":"- 2026-04-24 · 10:30–11:30 · SE12-327 · 80 marks / 60 min\n- 60 MCQ + 10 match + 1 coding\n- Allowed: one hand-written 8.5\" × 11\" sheet, both sides","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e2026-04-24 · 10:30–11:30 · SE12-327 · 80 marks / 60 min\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e60 MCQ + 10 match + 1 coding\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAllowed: one hand-written 8.5&quot; × 11&quot; sheet, both sides\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"AI — Semantic Kernel, MAF, Ollama, cloud models","body_md":"- **Packages**: `Microsoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI --prerelease` (MAF+OpenAI) · `OllamaSharp` · `Microsoft.SemanticKernel` · `Microsoft.Extensions.AI 10.4.0`\n- **MAF agent**: `var agent = chatClient.AsAIAgent(name, instructions, tools);` — `.AsAgent()` does NOT exist\n- **MAF tool**: `AIFunctionFactory.Create(method, name: \"N\", description: \"D\")` returns `AITool`\n- **MAF call**: `await agent.RunAsync(input, session)` or `agent.RunStreamingAsync(...)` — NOT `agent.Invoke(...)`\n- **Multi-turn**: `var session = await agent.CreateSessionAsync();`\n- **Ollama**: `new OllamaApiClient(new Uri(\"http://localhost:11434/\"), \"phi3\")` — HTTP, port 11434, no auth\n- **GitHub Models**: `new ChatClient(model, new AzureKeyCredential(token), new OpenAIClientOptions { Endpoint = new Uri(\"https://models.github.ai/inference\") })` — HTTPS, `/inference` path, model name `\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"`\n- **Semantic Kernel**: `new KernelBuilder().AddOpenAIChatCompletion(...).Build()` → `Kernel` · `kernel.InvokeAsync(...)` (not `Execute`) · `[KernelFunction]` (not `[SkillFunction]`) · plugins: `kernel.ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory(dir)` or `.ImportPluginFromType\u003cT\u003e()`\n- **Template var**: `{{$variableName}}` in `skprompt.txt`\n- **Chat**: `ChatMessage(ChatRole.User, content)` + `List\u003cChatMessage\u003e`; stream with `await foreach (var u in chatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync(history))`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePackages\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Agents.AI.OpenAI --prerelease\u003c/code\u003e (MAF+OpenAI) · \u003ccode\u003eOllamaSharp\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.SemanticKernel\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Extensions.AI 10.4.0\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMAF agent\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003evar agent = chatClient.AsAIAgent(name, instructions, tools);\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e.AsAgent()\u003c/code\u003e does NOT exist\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMAF tool\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eAIFunctionFactory.Create(method, name: &quot;N&quot;, description: &quot;D&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e returns \u003ccode\u003eAITool\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMAF call\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eawait agent.RunAsync(input, session)\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eagent.RunStreamingAsync(...)\u003c/code\u003e — NOT \u003ccode\u003eagent.Invoke(...)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMulti-turn\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003evar session = await agent.CreateSessionAsync();\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOllama\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003enew OllamaApiClient(new Uri(&quot;http://localhost:11434/&quot;), &quot;phi3&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e — HTTP, port 11434, no auth\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGitHub Models\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003enew ChatClient(model, new AzureKeyCredential(token), new OpenAIClientOptions { Endpoint = new Uri(&quot;https://models.github.ai/inference&quot;) })\u003c/code\u003e — HTTPS, \u003ccode\u003e/inference\u003c/code\u003e path, model name \u003ccode\u003e&quot;openai/gpt-4o-mini&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSemantic Kernel\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003enew KernelBuilder().AddOpenAIChatCompletion(...).Build()\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eKernel\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003ekernel.InvokeAsync(...)\u003c/code\u003e (not \u003ccode\u003eExecute\u003c/code\u003e) · \u003ccode\u003e[KernelFunction]\u003c/code\u003e (not \u003ccode\u003e[SkillFunction]\u003c/code\u003e) · plugins: \u003ccode\u003ekernel.ImportPluginFromPromptDirectory(dir)\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e.ImportPluginFromType&lt;T&gt;()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTemplate var\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e{{$variableName}}\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003eskprompt.txt\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eChat\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eChatMessage(ChatRole.User, content)\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eList&lt;ChatMessage&gt;\u003c/code\u003e; stream with \u003ccode\u003eawait foreach (var u in chatClient.GetStreamingResponseAsync(history))\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"ML.NET","body_md":"- **7-step pipeline**:\n  1. `var ml = new MLContext(seed: 0);`\n  2. `IDataView data = ml.Data.LoadFromTextFile\u003cT\u003e(path, hasHeader: true, separatorChar: ',');`\n  3. `var pipe = ml.Transforms.CopyColumns(\"Label\", \"FareAmount\")`\n  4. `  .Append(ml.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(\"VendorIdEncoded\", \"VendorId\"))`\n  5. `  .Append(ml.Transforms.Concatenate(\"Features\", \"VendorIdEncoded\", \"TripDistance\"))`\n  6. `  .Append(ml.Regression.Trainers.FastTree());`\n  7. `ITransformer model = pipe.Fit(data);`\n- **Evaluate**: `var metrics = ml.Regression.Evaluate(model.Transform(testData), \"Label\", \"Score\");` — reads `metrics.RSquared` and `metrics.RootMeanSquaredError`\n- **Predict**: `var engine = ml.Model.CreatePredictionEngine\u003cTIn, TOut\u003e(model); var p = engine.Predict(input);`\n- **Save/Load**: `ml.Model.Save(model, data.Schema, \"model.zip\");` / `ml.Model.Load(\"model.zip\", out var schema);`\n- **Output class**: `[ColumnName(\"Score\")] public float FareAmount;`\n- **[LoadColumn(N)]** is 0-based; names `\"Label\"` and `\"Features\"` are hardcoded\n- **AutoML CLI**: `mlnet regression --dataset train.csv --label-col 6 --train-time 60`\n- **Namespace trap**: `Regression` vs `BinaryClassification` vs `MulticlassClassification` — pick by task","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e7-step pipeline\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003evar ml = new MLContext(seed: 0);\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIDataView data = ml.Data.LoadFromTextFile&lt;T&gt;(path, hasHeader: true, separatorChar: &#39;,&#39;);\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003evar pipe = ml.Transforms.CopyColumns(&quot;Label&quot;, &quot;FareAmount&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e  .Append(ml.Transforms.Categorical.OneHotEncoding(&quot;VendorIdEncoded&quot;, &quot;VendorId&quot;))\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e  .Append(ml.Transforms.Concatenate(&quot;Features&quot;, &quot;VendorIdEncoded&quot;, &quot;TripDistance&quot;))\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e  .Append(ml.Regression.Trainers.FastTree());\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eITransformer model = pipe.Fit(data);\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEvaluate\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003evar metrics = ml.Regression.Evaluate(model.Transform(testData), &quot;Label&quot;, &quot;Score&quot;);\u003c/code\u003e — reads \u003ccode\u003emetrics.RSquared\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003emetrics.RootMeanSquaredError\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePredict\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003evar engine = ml.Model.CreatePredictionEngine&lt;TIn, TOut&gt;(model); var p = engine.Predict(input);\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSave/Load\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eml.Model.Save(model, data.Schema, &quot;model.zip&quot;);\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eml.Model.Load(&quot;model.zip&quot;, out var schema);\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOutput class\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e[ColumnName(&quot;Score&quot;)] public float FareAmount;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e[LoadColumn(N)]\u003c/strong\u003e is 0-based; names \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e are hardcoded\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAutoML CLI\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003emlnet regression --dataset train.csv --label-col 6 --train-time 60\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNamespace trap\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eRegression\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003eBinaryClassification\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003eMulticlassClassification\u003c/code\u003e — pick by task\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Cache / Redis","body_md":"- **Register**:\n  - Memory: `builder.Services.AddMemoryCache();`\n  - Redis: `builder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(o =\u003e o.Configuration = \"localhost:6379\");` (package `Microsoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis`)\n- **IMemoryCache fails in web farms** — use `IDistributedCache` or sticky sessions\n- **Expiration**: `new MemoryCacheEntryOptions { AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10), SlidingExpiration = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2), Priority = CacheItemPriority.High };`\n  - Combined: expires at `min(absolute, idle+sliding)`\n  - Priority ≠ expiration time; controls eviction under memory pressure only\n- **TryGetValue**: `if (_cache.TryGetValue\u003cT\u003e(k, out var v)) { ... }` — needs `out`\n- **GetOrCreateAsync**: `await _cache.GetOrCreateAsync(k, entry =\u003e { entry.AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5); return FetchAsync(); });`\n- **Invalidate on write**: `_cache.Remove(key);` after `SaveChangesAsync()`\n- **Docker Redis**: `docker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis`\n- **Redis CLI**: `SETEX key 10 \"val\"` (seconds) · `GET key` · `DEL key` · `TTL key`\n- **Cache Tag Helper**: `\u003ccache vary-by-user=\"true\" vary-by-route=\"id\" expires-after=\"@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)\"\u003e...\u003c/cache\u003e` — backs onto IMemoryCache (same farm trap)\n- **vary-by-***: `user`, `route`, `query`, `cookie`, `header`, custom `vary-by=\"@Model.Key\"`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRegister\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMemory: \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.Services.AddMemoryCache();\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRedis: \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.Services.AddStackExchangeRedisCache(o =&gt; o.Configuration = &quot;localhost:6379&quot;);\u003c/code\u003e (package \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.Extensions.Caching.StackExchangeRedis\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIMemoryCache fails in web farms\u003c/strong\u003e — use \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e or sticky sessions\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExpiration\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003enew MemoryCacheEntryOptions { AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10), SlidingExpiration = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2), Priority = CacheItemPriority.High };\u003c/code\u003e\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCombined: expires at \u003ccode\u003emin(absolute, idle+sliding)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePriority ≠ expiration time; controls eviction under memory pressure only\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTryGetValue\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eif (_cache.TryGetValue&lt;T&gt;(k, out var v)) { ... }\u003c/code\u003e — needs \u003ccode\u003eout\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGetOrCreateAsync\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eawait _cache.GetOrCreateAsync(k, entry =&gt; { entry.AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5); return FetchAsync(); });\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInvalidate on write\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e_cache.Remove(key);\u003c/code\u003e after \u003ccode\u003eSaveChangesAsync()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDocker Redis\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003edocker run --name redis -d -p 6379:6379 redis\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRedis CLI\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eSETEX key 10 &quot;val&quot;\u003c/code\u003e (seconds) · \u003ccode\u003eGET key\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eDEL key\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eTTL key\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCache Tag Helper\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e&lt;cache vary-by-user=&quot;true&quot; vary-by-route=&quot;id&quot; expires-after=&quot;@TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10)&quot;&gt;...&lt;/cache&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — backs onto IMemoryCache (same farm trap)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003evary-by-\u003c/strong\u003e*: \u003ccode\u003euser\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eroute\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003equery\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecookie\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eheader\u003c/code\u003e, custom \u003ccode\u003evary-by=&quot;@Model.Key&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"File-based apps","body_md":"- **Run**: `dotnet run file.cs` · `dotnet run file.cs -- arg1 arg2` (`--` separator required)\n- **Cache**: `~/.dotnet/runfile/` (macOS/Linux) · `%USERPROFILE%\\.dotnet\\runfile\\` (Windows)\n- **Directives (no space after colon)**:\n  - `#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1`\n  - `#:property TargetFramework=net10.0` / `Nullable=enable` / `LangVersion=preview`\n  - `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` (for web APIs)\n  - `#:project ./Lib/Lib.csproj` (reference a project)\n- **Implicit usings**: `System`, `System.Linq`, `System.Collections.Generic`, `System.Text`, `System.Threading.Tasks` (NOT `System.Text.Json`)\n- **Top-level statements**: file body runs as `Main`; type declarations go AFTER the code\n- **Convert**: `dotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder`\n- **Minimal web**: `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` then `var app = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build(); app.MapGet(\"/\", () =\u003e \"hi\"); app.Run();`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRun\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003edotnet run file.cs\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003edotnet run file.cs -- arg1 arg2\u003c/code\u003e (\u003ccode\u003e--\u003c/code\u003e separator required)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCache\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e~/.dotnet/runfile/\u003c/code\u003e (macOS/Linux) · \u003ccode\u003e%USERPROFILE%\\.dotnet\\runfile\\\u003c/code\u003e (Windows)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDirectives (no space after colon)\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:package Spectre.Console@0.49.1\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:property TargetFramework=net10.0\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eNullable=enable\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003eLangVersion=preview\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e (for web APIs)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:project ./Lib/Lib.csproj\u003c/code\u003e (reference a project)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eImplicit usings\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eSystem\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Linq\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Collections.Generic\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Text\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Threading.Tasks\u003c/code\u003e (NOT \u003ccode\u003eSystem.Text.Json\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTop-level statements\u003c/strong\u003e: file body runs as \u003ccode\u003eMain\u003c/code\u003e; type declarations go AFTER the code\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConvert\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003edotnet project convert file.cs -o Folder\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMinimal web\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web\u003c/code\u003e then \u003ccode\u003evar app = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args).Build(); app.MapGet(&quot;/&quot;, () =&gt; &quot;hi&quot;); app.Run();\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"gRPC","body_md":"- **Packages**: `Grpc.Tools` (build), `Google.Protobuf`, `Grpc.Net.Client` (client), `Grpc.Net.ClientFactory` (DI)\n- **.proto** (proto3):\n  - `syntax = \"proto3\";` · `option csharp_namespace = \"NS\";`\n  - `service Foo { rpc Bar (Req) returns (Resp); }`\n  - `message Req { int32 id = 1; string name = 2; }`\n  - Field tags 1–15 = 1 byte; 16+ = 2 bytes; PERMANENT (`reserved 2;` when removed)\n  - `repeated T` = list; unset proto3 scalars = zero-values (NO null)\n- **.csproj**: `\u003cProtobuf Include=\"Protos\\foo.proto\" GrpcServices=\"Server|Client|Both\" /\u003e`\n- **Server**:\n  ```cs\n  public class FooService : FooRemote.FooRemoteBase {\n    public override Task\u003cResp\u003e Bar(Req r, ServerCallContext ctx) =\u003e Task.FromResult(new Resp { ... });\n  }\n  ```\n  Register: `builder.Services.AddGrpc(); app.MapGrpcService\u003cFooService\u003e();`\n- **Client**:\n  - Raw: `using var ch = GrpcChannel.ForAddress(\"http://localhost:5099\"); var c = new FooRemote.FooRemoteClient(ch); var r = await c.BarAsync(req);`\n  - DI: `builder.Services.AddGrpcClient\u003cFooRemote.FooRemoteClient\u003e(o =\u003e o.Address = new Uri(\"http://backend\"));` then `@inject FooRemote.FooRemoteClient _c`\n- **Blazor host**: `@rendermode InteractiveServer` required for async calls","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePackages\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Tools\u003c/code\u003e (build), \u003ccode\u003eGoogle.Protobuf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Net.Client\u003c/code\u003e (client), \u003ccode\u003eGrpc.Net.ClientFactory\u003c/code\u003e (DI)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e.proto\u003c/strong\u003e (proto3):\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003esyntax = &quot;proto3&quot;;\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eoption csharp_namespace = &quot;NS&quot;;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eservice Foo { rpc Bar (Req) returns (Resp); }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003emessage Req { int32 id = 1; string name = 2; }\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eField tags 1–15 = 1 byte; 16+ = 2 bytes; PERMANENT (\u003ccode\u003ereserved 2;\u003c/code\u003e when removed)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003erepeated T\u003c/code\u003e = list; unset proto3 scalars = zero-values (NO null)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e.csproj\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e&lt;Protobuf Include=&quot;Protos\\foo.proto&quot; GrpcServices=&quot;Server|Client|Both&quot; /&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eServer\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003epublic class FooService : FooRemote.FooRemoteBase {\n  public override Task&lt;Resp&gt; Bar(Req r, ServerCallContext ctx) =&gt; Task.FromResult(new Resp { ... });\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\nRegister: \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.Services.AddGrpc(); app.MapGrpcService&lt;FooService&gt;();\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eClient\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRaw: \u003ccode\u003eusing var ch = GrpcChannel.ForAddress(&quot;http://localhost:5099&quot;); var c = new FooRemote.FooRemoteClient(ch); var r = await c.BarAsync(req);\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDI: \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.Services.AddGrpcClient&lt;FooRemote.FooRemoteClient&gt;(o =&gt; o.Address = new Uri(&quot;http://backend&quot;));\u003c/code\u003e then \u003ccode\u003e@inject FooRemote.FooRemoteClient _c\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBlazor host\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveServer\u003c/code\u003e required for async calls\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"TDD — xUnit","body_md":"- **Cycle**: Red (failing test) → Green (minimum code) → Refactor (clean up with tests green)\n- **3 Laws**: (1) no prod code without a failing test · (2) no more test than needed to fail · (3) no more prod code than needed to pass\n- **Attributes**:\n  - `[Fact]` — one run\n  - `[Theory]` + `[InlineData(...)]` — one run per InlineData\n  - `[Theory]` + `[MemberData(nameof(Provider))]` — data from static member\n- **Body pattern**: Arrange / Act / Assert\n- **Assertions**: `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` (expected FIRST) · `Assert.NotEqual` · `Assert.True/False` · `Assert.Null/NotNull` · `Assert.Throws\u003cT\u003e(() =\u003e action)` returns exception · `Assert.InRange(v, low, high)` · `Assert.Contains(item, collection)` · `Assert.Same(a, b)` (reference)\n- **Lifecycle**: constructor runs before EACH test; `IDisposable.Dispose()` runs after. No `[Setup]`/`[TearDown]` attributes.\n- **Fixtures**:\n  - `IClassFixture\u003cTFixture\u003e` — share one fixture across one class's tests\n  - `ICollectionFixture\u003cTFixture\u003e` + `[CollectionDefinition(\"X\")]` + `[Collection(\"X\")]` — share across multiple classes\n- **Commands**: `dotnet new xunit -n Tests` · `dotnet add reference` · `dotnet test`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCycle\u003c/strong\u003e: Red (failing test) → Green (minimum code) → Refactor (clean up with tests green)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e3 Laws\u003c/strong\u003e: (1) no prod code without a failing test · (2) no more test than needed to fail · (3) no more prod code than needed to pass\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAttributes\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[Fact]\u003c/code\u003e — one run\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[Theory]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[InlineData(...)]\u003c/code\u003e — one run per InlineData\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[Theory]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[MemberData(nameof(Provider))]\u003c/code\u003e — data from static member\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBody pattern\u003c/strong\u003e: Arrange / Act / Assert\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAssertions\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Equal(expected, actual)\u003c/code\u003e (expected FIRST) · \u003ccode\u003eAssert.NotEqual\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eAssert.True/False\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Null/NotNull\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Throws&lt;T&gt;(() =&gt; action)\u003c/code\u003e returns exception · \u003ccode\u003eAssert.InRange(v, low, high)\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Contains(item, collection)\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003eAssert.Same(a, b)\u003c/code\u003e (reference)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLifecycle\u003c/strong\u003e: constructor runs before EACH test; \u003ccode\u003eIDisposable.Dispose()\u003c/code\u003e runs after. No \u003ccode\u003e[Setup]\u003c/code\u003e/\u003ccode\u003e[TearDown]\u003c/code\u003e attributes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFixtures\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIClassFixture&lt;TFixture&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — share one fixture across one class&#39;s tests\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eICollectionFixture&lt;TFixture&gt;\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[CollectionDefinition(&quot;X&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e[Collection(&quot;X&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e — share across multiple classes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommands\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003edotnet new xunit -n Tests\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003edotnet add reference\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003edotnet test\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":".NET Aspire","body_md":"- **AppHost Program.cs**:\n  ```cs\n  var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n  var db = builder.AddSqlServer(\"sql\").AddDatabase(\"cms\");\n  var cache = builder.AddRedis(\"cache\");\n  var api = builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Api\u003e(\"api\").WithReference(db).WithReference(cache).WaitFor(db);\n  builder.AddProject\u003cProjects.Web\u003e(\"web\").WithReference(api).WaitFor(api);\n  builder.Build().Run();\n  ```\n- **`AddProject\u003cProjects.X\u003e(\"name\")`** — logical name for service discovery (`http://name`)\n- **`WithReference`** — injects connection info into consumer as env-var\n- **`WaitFor`** — delays startup until dependency reports healthy\n- **Service's Program.cs**: `builder.AddServiceDefaults();` + `app.MapDefaultEndpoints();` — NEVER in AppHost\n- **ServiceDefaults installs**: service discovery · OpenTelemetry · `/health` (readiness, all checks pass) + `/alive` (liveness, \"live\" tagged only) · HttpClient resilience\n- **Typed consumers**: `builder.AddSqlServerDbContext\u003cCmsDb\u003e(\"cms\");` · `builder.AddRedisDistributedCache(\"cache\");`\n- **Run**: `cd AppHost && dotnet watch` · dashboard on `http://localhost:15888`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAppHost Program.cs\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003evar builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nvar db = builder.AddSqlServer(&quot;sql&quot;).AddDatabase(&quot;cms&quot;);\nvar cache = builder.AddRedis(&quot;cache&quot;);\nvar api = builder.AddProject&lt;Projects.Api&gt;(&quot;api&quot;).WithReference(db).WithReference(cache).WaitFor(db);\nbuilder.AddProject&lt;Projects.Web&gt;(&quot;web&quot;).WithReference(api).WaitFor(api);\nbuilder.Build().Run();\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddProject&lt;Projects.X&gt;(&quot;name&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — logical name for service discovery (\u003ccode\u003ehttp://name\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eWithReference\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — injects connection info into consumer as env-var\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eWaitFor\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — delays startup until dependency reports healthy\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eService&#39;s Program.cs\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.AddServiceDefaults();\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eapp.MapDefaultEndpoints();\u003c/code\u003e — NEVER in AppHost\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eServiceDefaults installs\u003c/strong\u003e: service discovery · OpenTelemetry · \u003ccode\u003e/health\u003c/code\u003e (readiness, all checks pass) + \u003ccode\u003e/alive\u003c/code\u003e (liveness, &quot;live&quot; tagged only) · HttpClient resilience\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTyped consumers\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.AddSqlServerDbContext&lt;CmsDb&gt;(&quot;cms&quot;);\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003ebuilder.AddRedisDistributedCache(&quot;cache&quot;);\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRun\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ecd AppHost &amp;&amp; dotnet watch\u003c/code\u003e · dashboard on \u003ccode\u003ehttp://localhost:15888\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Localization","body_md":"- **Program.cs**:\n  ```cs\n  builder.Services.AddLocalization(o =\u003e o.ResourcesPath = \"Resources\");\n  builder.Services.Configure\u003cRequestLocalizationOptions\u003e(o =\u003e {\n    var sup = new[] { new CultureInfo(\"en\"), new CultureInfo(\"fr\") };\n    o.DefaultRequestCulture = new RequestCulture(\"en\");\n    o.SupportedCultures = sup;\n    o.SupportedUICultures = sup;\n  });\n  builder.Services.AddRazorPages().AddViewLocalization();\n  // Later:\n  app.UseRequestLocalization();   // ESSENTIAL — silent failure without it\n  ```\n- **Resource path**: `Resources/\u003cfolder\u003e/\u003cClassName\u003e.\u003cculture\u003e.resx` — for `Pages/Index.cshtml.cs` (class `IndexModel`) → `Resources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx`\n- **Shared**: empty class `SharedResource` + `Resources/SharedResource.fr.resx` + service using `IStringLocalizerFactory.Create(nameof(SharedResource), assemblyName)`\n- **Inject**:\n  - Code-behind text: `IStringLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` · `localizer[\"Key\"]`\n  - Code-behind HTML: `IHtmlLocalizer\u003cT\u003e` (no XSS encoding)\n  - View: `@inject IViewLocalizer Localizer` then `@Localizer[\"Key\"]`\n- **CurrentCulture** = formatting (dates/numbers); **CurrentUICulture** = which .resx loads. SET BOTH.\n- **Providers (order)**: QueryString (`?culture=fr`) → Cookie (`.AspNetCore.Culture`) → Accept-Language header\n- **Switch cookie**: `Response.Cookies.Append(CookieRequestCultureProvider.DefaultCookieName, CookieRequestCultureProvider.MakeCookieValue(new RequestCulture(culture)), new CookieOptions { Expires = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow.AddYears(1) });`\n- **Positional args**: `localizer[\"Greet\", name]` → `.resx` `\"Hello, {0}!\"`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProgram.cs\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003ebuilder.Services.AddLocalization(o =&gt; o.ResourcesPath = &quot;Resources&quot;);\nbuilder.Services.Configure&lt;RequestLocalizationOptions&gt;(o =&gt; {\n  var sup = new[] { new CultureInfo(&quot;en&quot;), new CultureInfo(&quot;fr&quot;) };\n  o.DefaultRequestCulture = new RequestCulture(&quot;en&quot;);\n  o.SupportedCultures = sup;\n  o.SupportedUICultures = sup;\n});\nbuilder.Services.AddRazorPages().AddViewLocalization();\n// Later:\napp.UseRequestLocalization();   // ESSENTIAL — silent failure without it\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eResource path\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eResources/&lt;folder&gt;/&lt;ClassName&gt;.&lt;culture&gt;.resx\u003c/code\u003e — for \u003ccode\u003ePages/Index.cshtml.cs\u003c/code\u003e (class \u003ccode\u003eIndexModel\u003c/code\u003e) → \u003ccode\u003eResources/Pages/IndexModel.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eShared\u003c/strong\u003e: empty class \u003ccode\u003eSharedResource\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eResources/SharedResource.fr.resx\u003c/code\u003e + service using \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizerFactory.Create(nameof(SharedResource), assemblyName)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInject\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCode-behind text: \u003ccode\u003eIStringLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e · \u003ccode\u003elocalizer[&quot;Key&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCode-behind HTML: \u003ccode\u003eIHtmlLocalizer&lt;T&gt;\u003c/code\u003e (no XSS encoding)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eView: \u003ccode\u003e@inject IViewLocalizer Localizer\u003c/code\u003e then \u003ccode\u003e@Localizer[&quot;Key&quot;]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCurrentCulture\u003c/strong\u003e = formatting (dates/numbers); \u003cstrong\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/strong\u003e = which .resx loads. SET BOTH.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProviders (order)\u003c/strong\u003e: QueryString (\u003ccode\u003e?culture=fr\u003c/code\u003e) → Cookie (\u003ccode\u003e.AspNetCore.Culture\u003c/code\u003e) → Accept-Language header\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSwitch cookie\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eResponse.Cookies.Append(CookieRequestCultureProvider.DefaultCookieName, CookieRequestCultureProvider.MakeCookieValue(new RequestCulture(culture)), new CookieOptions { Expires = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow.AddYears(1) });\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePositional args\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003elocalizer[&quot;Greet&quot;, name]\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e.resx\u003c/code\u003e \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Hello, {0}!&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Tag Helpers","body_md":"- **Custom**:\n  ```cs\n  [HtmlTargetElement(\"toon\")]\n  public class ToonTagHelper : TagHelper {\n    public string? FontFamily { get; set; }   // kebab-case: font-family\n    public override async Task ProcessAsync(TagHelperContext ctx, TagHelperOutput output) {\n      output.TagName = \"div\";\n      output.Content.SetHtmlContent(\"\u003cp\u003eHi\u003c/p\u003e\");     // Set replaces; Append preserves\n      output.Attributes.SetAttribute(\"style\", \"color:red\");\n      // output.SuppressOutput(); to render nothing\n    }\n  }\n  ```\n- **Register in `_ViewImports.cshtml`**: `@addTagHelper *, Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers` (built-ins) · `@addTagHelper *, MyApp` (custom)\n- **PascalCase ↔ kebab-case**: `FontFamily` ↔ `font-family`\n- **`[HtmlTargetElement(\"tag\")]`** or `[HtmlTargetElement(\"div\", Attributes = \"toonie\")]` (stack multiple)\n- **Process vs ProcessAsync**: async for awaiting; sync `Process` for CPU-only\n- **Output manipulation**: `TagName`, `Content.SetHtmlContent/AppendHtmlContent`, `PreContent`, `PostContent`, `Attributes.SetAttribute/RemoveAll`, `SuppressOutput()`","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCustom\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003e[HtmlTargetElement(&quot;toon&quot;)]\npublic class ToonTagHelper : TagHelper {\n  public string? FontFamily { get; set; }   // kebab-case: font-family\n  public override async Task ProcessAsync(TagHelperContext ctx, TagHelperOutput output) {\n    output.TagName = &quot;div&quot;;\n    output.Content.SetHtmlContent(&quot;&lt;p&gt;Hi&lt;/p&gt;&quot;);     // Set replaces; Append preserves\n    output.Attributes.SetAttribute(&quot;style&quot;, &quot;color:red&quot;);\n    // output.SuppressOutput(); to render nothing\n  }\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRegister in \u003ccode\u003e_ViewImports.cshtml\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e@addTagHelper *, Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.TagHelpers\u003c/code\u003e (built-ins) · \u003ccode\u003e@addTagHelper *, MyApp\u003c/code\u003e (custom)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePascalCase ↔ kebab-case\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eFontFamily\u003c/code\u003e ↔ \u003ccode\u003efont-family\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[HtmlTargetElement(&quot;tag&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e[HtmlTargetElement(&quot;div&quot;, Attributes = &quot;toonie&quot;)]\u003c/code\u003e (stack multiple)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProcess vs ProcessAsync\u003c/strong\u003e: async for awaiting; sync \u003ccode\u003eProcess\u003c/code\u003e for CPU-only\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOutput manipulation\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eTagName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eContent.SetHtmlContent/AppendHtmlContent\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ePreContent\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ePostContent\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eAttributes.SetAttribute/RemoveAll\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eSuppressOutput()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Blazor QuickGrid","body_md":"- Package: `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid`\n- `@rendermode InteractiveServer` (or WebAssembly/Auto) required\n- `\u003cQuickGrid Items=\"@iqueryable\" Pagination=\"@paginationState\"\u003e`\n  - `\u003cPropertyColumn Property=\"@(x =\u003e x.Name)\" Sortable=\"true\" /\u003e` — sort works out of the box\n  - `\u003cTemplateColumn Title=\"Full\" SortBy=\"@sortExpr\"\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e@context.First @context.Last\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/TemplateColumn\u003e` — needs `SortBy`, not `Sortable`\n- `private PaginationState _p = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };` + `\u003cPaginator State=\"@_p\" /\u003e`\n- Multi-key sort: `GridSort\u003cT\u003e.ByAscending(x =\u003e x.A).ThenAscending(x =\u003e x.B)`\n- Live filter: `\u003cinput @bind=\"_filter\" @bind:event=\"oninput\" /\u003e` + computed `IQueryable` property","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePackage: \u003ccode\u003eMicrosoft.AspNetCore.Components.QuickGrid\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@rendermode InteractiveServer\u003c/code\u003e (or WebAssembly/Auto) required\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;QuickGrid Items=&quot;@iqueryable&quot; Pagination=&quot;@paginationState&quot;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;PropertyColumn Property=&quot;@(x =&gt; x.Name)&quot; Sortable=&quot;true&quot; /&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — sort works out of the box\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;TemplateColumn Title=&quot;Full&quot; SortBy=&quot;@sortExpr&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;@context.First @context.Last&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/TemplateColumn&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — needs \u003ccode\u003eSortBy\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003eSortable\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eprivate PaginationState _p = new() { ItemsPerPage = 15 };\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e&lt;Paginator State=&quot;@_p&quot; /&gt;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMulti-key sort: \u003ccode\u003eGridSort&lt;T&gt;.ByAscending(x =&gt; x.A).ThenAscending(x =&gt; x.B)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLive filter: \u003ccode\u003e&lt;input @bind=&quot;_filter&quot; @bind:event=&quot;oninput&quot; /&gt;\u003c/code\u003e + computed \u003ccode\u003eIQueryable\u003c/code\u003e property\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Excel / PDF / Chart","body_md":"- **Excel (ClosedXML)**:\n  ```cs\n  using var wb = new XLWorkbook();\n  var sheet = wb.Worksheets.Add(\"Games\");\n  sheet.Cell(1, 1).Value = \"Name\";      // 1-BASED indexing\n  int r = 2; foreach (var x in data) { sheet.Cell(r, 1).Value = x.Name; r++; }\n  sheet.Columns().AdjustToContents();\n  using var ms = new MemoryStream();\n  wb.SaveAs(ms);\n  return File(ms.ToArray(), \"application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet\", \"export.xlsx\");\n  ```\n- **PDF (iText 7 + `itext.bouncy-castle-adapter`)**:\n  ```cs\n  var ms = new MemoryStream();\n  var writer = new PdfWriter(ms);\n  var pdfDoc = new PdfDocument(writer);\n  var doc = new Document(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false);\n  writer.SetCloseStream(false);\n  doc.Add(new Paragraph(\"Title\").SetTextAlignment(TextAlignment.CENTER).SetFontSize(20));\n  var table = new Table(2);\n  foreach (var x in data) { table.AddCell(x.Name); table.AddCell(x.Score.ToString()); }\n  doc.Add(table);\n  doc.Close();\n  ms.Position = 0;   // CRITICAL\n  return new FileStreamResult(ms, \"application/pdf\") { FileDownloadName = \"r.pdf\" };\n  ```\n- **Chart.js** (client-side only):\n  ```html\n  \u003ccanvas id=\"c\" width=\"400\" height=\"400\"\u003e\u003c/canvas\u003e\n  \u003cscript src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js\"\u003e\u003c/script\u003e\n  \u003cscript\u003e\n    const labels = []; const counts = [];\n    @foreach (var x in Model.Data) { @:labels.push('@x.Name'); @:counts.push(@x.Count); }\n    new Chart(document.getElementById('c'), { type: 'pie', data: { labels, datasets: [{ data: counts, backgroundColor: [...] }] } });\n  \u003c/script\u003e\n  ```","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExcel (ClosedXML)\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003eusing var wb = new XLWorkbook();\nvar sheet = wb.Worksheets.Add(&quot;Games&quot;);\nsheet.Cell(1, 1).Value = &quot;Name&quot;;      // 1-BASED indexing\nint r = 2; foreach (var x in data) { sheet.Cell(r, 1).Value = x.Name; r++; }\nsheet.Columns().AdjustToContents();\nusing var ms = new MemoryStream();\nwb.SaveAs(ms);\nreturn File(ms.ToArray(), &quot;application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet&quot;, &quot;export.xlsx&quot;);\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePDF (iText 7 + \u003ccode\u003eitext.bouncy-castle-adapter\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-cs\"\u003evar ms = new MemoryStream();\nvar writer = new PdfWriter(ms);\nvar pdfDoc = new PdfDocument(writer);\nvar doc = new Document(pdfDoc, PageSize.A4, false);\nwriter.SetCloseStream(false);\ndoc.Add(new Paragraph(&quot;Title&quot;).SetTextAlignment(TextAlignment.CENTER).SetFontSize(20));\nvar table = new Table(2);\nforeach (var x in data) { table.AddCell(x.Name); table.AddCell(x.Score.ToString()); }\ndoc.Add(table);\ndoc.Close();\nms.Position = 0;   // CRITICAL\nreturn new FileStreamResult(ms, &quot;application/pdf&quot;) { FileDownloadName = &quot;r.pdf&quot; };\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eChart.js\u003c/strong\u003e (client-side only):\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-html\"\u003e&lt;canvas id=&quot;c&quot; width=&quot;400&quot; height=&quot;400&quot;&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;\n&lt;script src=&quot;https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@3.9.1/dist/chart.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n  const labels = []; const counts = [];\n  @foreach (var x in Model.Data) { @:labels.push(&#39;@x.Name&#39;); @:counts.push(@x.Count); }\n  new Chart(document.getElementById(&#39;c&#39;), { type: &#39;pie&#39;, data: { labels, datasets: [{ data: counts, backgroundColor: [...] }] } });\n&lt;/script&gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Final-hour triage","body_md":"- **`#:package` NOT `#: package`** — no space after colon\n- **`.AsAIAgent()` NOT `.AsAgent()`** · **`RunAsync` NOT `Invoke`** · **`InvokeAsync` NOT `Execute`** (SK)\n- **Ollama HTTP :11434 · GitHub HTTPS /inference**\n- **`ITransformer` from `Fit()` NOT `IDataView`**\n- **Column names `\"Label\"` and `\"Features\"` are hardcoded in ML.NET**\n- **`[LoadColumn(N)]` is 0-based; ClosedXML `Cell(r,c)` is 1-based**\n- **MemoryStream `Position = 0` before `FileStreamResult`** (PDF export)\n- **`Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` — expected FIRST**\n- **`AddServiceDefaults()` in each service, NOT AppHost**\n- **`IMemoryCache` fails in web farms; use `IDistributedCache`**\n- **`TemplateColumn SortBy=`, PropertyColumn `Sortable=\"true\"`**\n- **`CurrentCulture` (formatting) and `CurrentUICulture` (resources) — set BOTH**\n- **`UseRequestLocalization()` middleware or localization silently no-ops**\n- **iText needs `itext.bouncy-castle-adapter` package alongside `itext7`**\n- **Every cards/lessons/practice file must have `source:`**","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e#:package\u003c/code\u003e NOT \u003ccode\u003e#: package\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — no space after colon\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e.AsAIAgent()\u003c/code\u003e NOT \u003ccode\u003e.AsAgent()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e · \u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRunAsync\u003c/code\u003e NOT \u003ccode\u003eInvoke\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e · \u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eInvokeAsync\u003c/code\u003e NOT \u003ccode\u003eExecute\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e (SK)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOllama HTTP :11434 · GitHub HTTPS /inference\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eITransformer\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003eFit()\u003c/code\u003e NOT \u003ccode\u003eIDataView\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eColumn names \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Label&quot;\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e&quot;Features&quot;\u003c/code\u003e are hardcoded in ML.NET\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[LoadColumn(N)]\u003c/code\u003e is 0-based; ClosedXML \u003ccode\u003eCell(r,c)\u003c/code\u003e is 1-based\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMemoryStream \u003ccode\u003ePosition = 0\u003c/code\u003e before \u003ccode\u003eFileStreamResult\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e (PDF export)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAssert.Equal(expected, actual)\u003c/code\u003e — expected FIRST\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAddServiceDefaults()\u003c/code\u003e in each service, NOT AppHost\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eIMemoryCache\u003c/code\u003e fails in web farms; use \u003ccode\u003eIDistributedCache\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eTemplateColumn SortBy=\u003c/code\u003e, PropertyColumn \u003ccode\u003eSortable=&quot;true&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eCurrentCulture\u003c/code\u003e (formatting) and \u003ccode\u003eCurrentUICulture\u003c/code\u003e (resources) — set BOTH\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eUseRequestLocalization()\u003c/code\u003e middleware or localization silently no-ops\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eiText needs \u003ccode\u003eitext.bouncy-castle-adapter\u003c/code\u003e package alongside \u003ccode\u003eitext7\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEvery cards/lessons/practice file must have \u003ccode\u003esource:\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"}]}};
